II. THE CENTRAL NERVOUS SYSTEM (CNS) \
\
The central nervous system (CNS) consists of the spinal cord and brain, with sensory \
(afferent) neurons carrying information into the CNS, and motor (efferent) neurons \
carrying information away from the CNS to muscles and glands. \
\
A. THE SPINAL CORD \
\
The spinal cord is divided into four regions. The cervical or neck region includes vertebrae \
C1 through C7. The thoracic or chest region includes vertebrae T1 through T12. The \
lumbar or back region includes vertebrae L1 through L5. Finally, the sacral region includes \
the S1 vertebra. When the spinal cord is damaged, muscles served by sections of the spinal \
cord below the damaged area do not function normally, and paralysis may result. \
\
Severing the spinal cord anywhere between C1 and C5 results in paralysis in all four limbs \
termed quadriplegia ("quad" means four and "plegia" means paralysis). \
\
Paraplegia refers to paralysis in the legs only. Severing the spinal cord at C6 or C7 results \
in both paraplegia and partial paralysis of the arms. Severing the spinal cord at TI or below \
results in paraplegia only. \
\
Incomplete severing of the spinal cord may result in muscle weakness, termed paresis, \
rather than full paralysis. Strokes can also cause paresis. \
\
Even when the spinal cord is damaged, many reflexes still remain intact (e.g., the knee jerk \
reflex). A male who is paralyzed can therefore achieve an erection (a reflex). He may even \
be able to ejaculate and experience sensations of orgasm. \
\
\
 \
\
