B. THE BRAIN \
\
The brain is the control center for all voluntary and most involuntary behavior. The major \
divisions of the brain are: the cerebrum, consisting of the cerebral cortex and subcortical \
areas; the cerebellum; and the brain stem. \
\
B1. THE CEREBRUM \
\
The cerebrum is involved with complex thought, perception, and action. The outer layer of \
the cerebrum is the cerebral cortex and the inside layer contains the subcortical areas. The \
cerebrum can be compared to an orange: the cortex is like the rind of the orange and the \
subcortical areas are like the fruit of the orange. \
\
>THE CEREBRAL CORTEX The cerebral cortex, the outside surface of the brain, is at \
birth the least developed part of the brain. It is, however, more developed in humans than \
in other animals. The surface of the cerebral cortex is highly convoluted with folds (gyri). \
These folds allow for expansion of the cortical surface area without increasing the size of \
the brain. \
\
  THE HEMISPHERES The cerebral cortex is divided into halves, the left and right \
  hemispheres, which are connected with a thick band of nerve fibers, the corpus \
  callosum. \
\
  The left hemisphere controls the right side of the body, while the right hemisphere \
  controls the left side of the body. Although the two hemispheres appear to be mirror \
  images of one another, there are important distinctions in their respective functions. \
\
     THE LEFT HEMISPHERE The left hemisphere is dominant in about 97% of all \
     people. Dominance refers to control over language, which includes reading, \
     writing. speaking, spelling, naming, as well as motor control. About 90% of the \
     population is right handed, and almost all right-handers are left hemisphere \
     dominant; of the 10% of the population that is left-handed, most of them (about \
     75% - 80%) are also left hemisphere dominant. The left hemisphere is also involved \
     in verbal memory, as well as in thinking that is rational, analytical, logical, and \
     abstract. \
\
     For most people damage to the left hemisphere may result in aphasia (speech \
     disorder), other language problems (e.g., agraphia, anomia), apraxia (motor \
     disorder), and/or difficulties with the right side of the body. \
\
\
\
