\
The hallmark of cerebellar disease is ataxia, defined as a lack of coordination of voluntary \
movements in the absence of weakness or sensory loss. Symptoms of cerebellar damage \
may appear as problems with posture, gait, incorrect timing in the activation of muscles, \
disequilibrium, vertigo, inability to reach out and grab objects, difficulty making rapid \
movements, or problems coordinating fine movements. \
\
HINT: Think of "taxi" as movement (although this is not the correct etymology, it's a good \
memory aid). \
\
B3. THE BRAIN STEM \
\
The brain stem lies below the subcortical regions and in front of the cerebellum. It is the \
most primitive part of the brain and is an extension of the spinal cord. Of the 12 cranial \
nerves, 10 begin in the brain stem. The major brain stem areas are the pons, medulla, and \
reticular formation. \
\
>THE PONS AND THE MEDULLA The pons, the upper portion of the brain stem, and \
the medulla, found at the bottom of the brain stem just above the spinal cord, are involved \
in sleep (including initiation of REM sleep), respiration, movement, and cardiovascular \
activity. Damage to the medulla or pons can lead to failure of bodily functions and death. \
\
Cranial nerve XII, the hypoglossal nerve, originates in the medulla; damage to this nerve \
can cause problems with articulation similar to those seen in Broca's aphasia. \
\
>THE RETICULAR FORMATION The reticular formation is a set of interconnected \
nuclei in the brainstem, especially important in awareness, attention, and sleep. Part of the \
reticular formation, the reticular activating system (RAS), projects to the thalamus. The \
RAS is involved in the sleep-wake cycle, serves as a filter for incoming sensory \
information, and mediates alertness. \
\
