               2.2 NEURONS AND THE \
              NEUROTRANSMITTERS \
\
I. NEURONS \
\
All behavior results from neuronal activity. Each neuron (nerve cell) is a tiny information \
processing system with thousands of connections for receiving and sending electrical and \
chemical signals to other neurons. Neurons, the cells of the brain and spinal cord, \
communicate with each other, with glands, muscles, and other body organs by releasing \
minute amounts of chemical neurotransmitters. \
\
>PARTS OF A NEURON Each neuron contains three parts: dendrites, the cell body or \
soma, and an axon. Dendrites receive information from other neurons by capturing \
neurotransmitters released into the synaptic cleft (space between the neurons) at their \
receptor sites. A neuron may have hundreds or thousands of dendrites. The cell body, or \
soma, integrates information from the dendrites. The soma contains the nucleus, which \
regulates all cell activity and controls hereditary characteristics (e.g., DNA). Finally, the \
axon is a tube-like structure that transmits information. \
\
>ACTION POTENTIAL The action potential plays a vital role in cell-to-cell \
communication. At rest, the outside of the cell contains an excess of sodium ions (Na+), \
 while the inside of the cell contains an excess of potassium ions (K+). The neuron's axon \
is especially sensitive to changes in the electrical charge of its membrane. When a stimulus \
 of sufficient charge reaches a resting neuron, sodium (Na+) outside the cell membrane \
rushes into the cell, creating an action potential (an electrochemical impulse). Potassium \
(K+) then moves outside the cell. The action potential travels the entire length of the axon \
to the boutons (terminal buttons), releasing neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft \
(synapse), the small space separating neurons. \
\
Some of the released neurotransmitters cross the synaptic cleft and bind to receptor sites \
on dendrites of adjacent neurons, thus continuing the chain of communication. In addition \
to this process, reuptake occurs. Neurotransmitters in the synaptic cleft are taken up by the \
pre-synaptic neuron's terminal buttons and therefore never reach the adjoining neuron. \
\
>ALL OR NONE PRINCIPLE The phenomenon that guides neuronal firing is the \
"all or none principle," according to which a neuron, if sufficiently stimulated, will fire to \
