its fullest extent; if it is not sufficiently stimulated, it will not fire at all. In other words, \
the neuron either fires or doesn't fire. It doesn't fire more strongly or less strongly in \
response to the strength of the stimulation. After firing, there is an absolute refractory \
period, during which the neuron cannot fire, regardless of the strength of stimulation. A \
relative refractory period then follows during which only very intense stimulation will \
cause firing. During the refractory period Na+ and K+ are returned to their original sides, \
with Na+ on the outside and K+ on the inside. \
\
II. THE NEUROTRANSMITTERS \
\
The neurotransmitters are broadly divided into two categories: the classical \
neurotransmitters (the basic ones) and the peptide neurotransmitters. The term agonist is \
applied to any substance that enhances the effect of the neurotransmitter, while antagonist \
refers to any substance that inhibits the neurotransmitter effect. Neurotransmitters are also \
classified as either excitatory (e.g., acetylcholine, norepinephrine, glutamate), if they \
increase the likelihood of an action potential, or as inhibitory (e.g., GABA, endorphins), \
if they decrease the likelihood of an action potential. \
\
A. THE CLASSICAL NEUROTRANSMITTERS \
\
The classical neurotransmitters include acetylcholine, the catecholamines (dopamine, \
norepinephrine), serotonin, and the amino acids. \
\
>ACETYLCHOLINE    (Ach) Acetylcholine is one of the most common \
neurotransmitters. Ach is involved in two significant functions: voluntary movement, and \
memory and cognition. In terms of voluntary movement, it is believed that the poison of \
the black widow spider, which causes paralysis, directly affects acetylcholine. Ach is also \
particularly prevalent in the hippocampus, which is responsible for the consolidation of \
long term memory. Significant deficiencies in Ach are observed in Alzheimer's disease. \
\
>THE CATECHOLAMINES The principle catecholamines found in the nervous system \
are dopamine (DA) and norepinephrine (NE). These neurotransmitters are synthesized \
from dietary tyrosine and phenylalanine. \
\
