     antagonism of the novel antipsychotics that reduces the symptoms of psychosis. It \
     has also been found that a deficit in DA transmission at D1 receptors in the \
     prefrontal cortex (PFC) might be implicated in the cognitive impairments and \
     negative symptoms of schizophrenia. \
\
     By contrast, Parkinson's Disease involves a degeneration of neurons in the \
     substantia nigra. As a result, there is a decrease in the dopamine available in the \
     basal ganglia (the group of nerve cells that includes the substantia nigra). L-Dopa \
     (Levodopa), which is a precursor to dopamine, is used to treat the movement \
     components of Parkinson's. \
\
     NOREPINEPHRINE (NE) Norepinephrine, also called noradrenalin, is \
     significantly involved in mood. Depression is associated with a relative deficiency \
     of norepinephrine, while mania is associated with a relative norepinephrine excess. \
\
     Norepinephrine plays a role in pain perception as well as sleep. Norepinephrine is \
     also released as a hormone into the bloodstream, where it causes blood vessels to \
     contract and heart rate to increase. \
\
>SEROTONIN Serotonin (5-HT) is significantly involved in mood, sleep. appetite, \
aggression, sexual activity, and pain perception. Serotonin is produced by dietary \
modification of tryptophan. Dysregulation of serotonin has been associated with suicidality \
and impulsivity. Deficiencies in serotonin are implicated in mood disorders. Levels of \
norepinephrine play a role in whether the mood disorder is expressed as mania (too much \
norepinephrine) or depression (too little norepinephrine). Thus, low serotonin and low \
norepinephrine are linked to depression; low serotonin and high norepinephrine are linked \
to mania. \
\
>THE AMINO ACIDS The amino acids include GABA, Glycine and Glutamate. \
\
     GABA (GAMMA-AMINOBUTYRIC ACID) AND GLYCINE. GABA and \
     glycine are major inhibitory neurotransmitters in the CNS, and they have a calming \
