           2.3 ENDOCRINE DISORDERS \
\
Disruption of endocrine functioning can result in a variety of medical conditions, many of \
which have accompanying psychological symptoms. The pituitary is considered the \
master endocrine gland, as it releases hormones that activate other endocrine glands. The \
pituitary itself is regulated by the hypothalamus. \
\
I. THYROID DISORDERS \
\
The thyroid gland controls metabolism through secretion of the hormone thyroxin. \
\
>HYPERTHYROIDISM Hyperthyroidism (excessive secretion of thyroxin) results in \
weight loss despite increased appetite, heat sensitivity, sweating, diarrhea, tremor and \
palpitations, fatigue, agitated depression, insomnia, impaired memory and judgment, and \
can even involve hallucinations and delusions. The most common form of hyperthyroidism \
is Grave's disease. \
\
>HYPOTHYROIDISM    Hypothyroidism (undersecretion of thyroxin) results in \
unexplained weight gain, sluggishness, fatigue, impaired memory and intellectual \
functioning, and sensitivity to cold. \
\
HINT: Thyroid disorders are one of the first medical disorders to suspect when there are \
psychiatric symptoms. Hyperthyroidism will most likely mimic anxiety or a manic episode. \
Hypothyroidism will most likely mimic depression. \
\
II. DIABETES \
\
The pancreas produces and secretes insulin, which regulates blood sugar levels. Diabetes \
develops when the pancreas does not produce insulin (Type I Diabetes), when the body \
develops a resistance to insulin (Type II Diabetes) or may develop during pregnancy \
(Gestational Diabetes). \
\
The hallmark of diabetes is hyperglycemia (excessive glucose or blood sugar levels). The \
classic symptoms are the "Three P's": polyuria (increased urination), polydipsia (increased \
thirst), and polyphagia (increased appetite). One of the challenges of diabetes management \
\
\
\
