\
is attaining tight blood sugar control. Medications used to treat diabetes carry the risk of \
lowering blood sugar levels too much, resulting in hypoglycemia (low blood sugar). \
Symptoms of hypoglycemia include nervousness, irritability, trembling, cold sweats, \
fatigue, rapid heart rate, hunger, headache, and confusion. \
\
>TYPE I DIABETES or Insulin Dependent Diabetes Mellitus (IDDM), previously called \
Juvenile Onset, usually develops before the age of 30 and requires life-long insulin \
injections. Children with Type I Diabetes generally do well managing their diabetic \
regimen (e.g., diet, injections), but tend to become non-compliant or erratic in compliance \
when they become adolescents. \
\
>TYPE II DIABETES or Non-Insulin Dependent Diabetes Mellitus (NIDDM). \
previously called Adult Onset, can sometimes be controlled by diet and exercise alone. \
Most often, however, diabetics require oral medications or even insulin injections. Obesity \
and a sedentary lifestyle are major risk factors for developing this disease. The dramatic \
increase in Type II Diabetes among children has been attributed to rising rates of childhood \
obesity and inactivity. African Americans and Hispanics have a much higher risk of \
developing Type II Diabetes than other ethnic groups. \
\
>GESTATIONAL DIABETES Gestational Diabetes occurs when pregnant women \
without a previous diagnosis of diabetes develop a high blood glucose level. It may precede \
development of Type II Diabetes. Gestational diabetes occurs in 1 to 3 percent of all \
pregnancies. \
\
III. OTHER ENDOCRINE DISORDERS \
\
>HYPOPITUITARISM & HYPERPITUITARISM Hypopituitarism (undersecretion \
of pituitary growth hormones) can cause dwarfism and pubertal delay in children. In adults, \
it can cause gonadal failure (e.g., impotence, infertility), as well as a host of other disorders \
(e.g., hypothyroidism, diabetes, adrenocortical insufficiency). Hyperpituitarism \
(oversection of pituitary growth hormone) involves startling skeletal overgrowth resulting \
in gigantism or acromegaly. \
\
>ADDISON'S DISEASE & CUSHING'S DISEASE The adrenal cortex secretes \
corticosteroids that are involved in the use of energy resources, the inhibition of antibody \
formation, and inflammation. Addison's Disease results from undersecretion of \
corticosteroids, or adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms include apathy, weakness, irritability, \
depression, and gastrointestinal disturbance. Cushing's Disease results from oversecretion \
