           2.4 COGNITIVE DISORDERS \
\
I. COGNITIVE SYMPTOMS ASSOCIATED WITH \
STROKE, TRAUMA, BRAIN TUMORS, AND \
NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDERS \
\
The impact of a stroke, trauma, or a brain tumor depends on the size, specific location \
(cortical or subcortical region), and cerebral hemisphere affected. \
\
>APHASIA Aphasia refers to the loss of language abilities due to damage (also called \
lesions) in the brain. The specific location of the lesion determines the nature of the \
language disruption. Most people (about 97% of the population) are left hemisphere \
dominant, meaning that the left hemisphere controls language. There are several common \
subtypes of aphasia. \
\
     BROCA'S APHASIA Broca's aphasia results from lesions to the dominant (left) \
     frontal lobe. The hallmark of this aphasia is a severe problem with speech \
     production and articulation (dysarthria), making speech slow and effortful. People \
     with Broca's aphasia speak in short phrases punctuated by lengthy pauses. Their \
     speech has a telegraphic quality, in which articles (the, an, a), conjunctions, and \
     other small words are omitted. For example: "Walk dog ... dog .. . park." \
     Comprehension is mostly intact, but some comprehension problems may exist (e.g., \
     understanding passive grammatical constructions). Other problems include \
     difficulty with word finding, naming objects, and repeating verbal phrases. People \
     with Broca's aphasia are aware of their difficulties. One way to remember this \
     aphasia is to think of it as "broken (Broca) or choppy speech." Broca's aphasia is \
     considered an expressive or motor aphasia. \
\
     WERNICKE'S APHASIA   Wernicke's aphasia results from lesions in the \
     dominant (left) temporal lobe. People with Wernicke's aphasia have no language \
     comprehension. They cannot follow verbal commands or repeat phrases. They \
     speak fluently, but what they're saying is complete nonsense (think of the phrase \
     "garbage in, garbage out"). Interestingly, they are unaware of their problem \
     (anosognosia) and expect others to be able to understand them. Wernicke's is \
     considered a receptive or sensory aphasia. \
\
\
 \
\
                                     Section 2 - Biological: Cognitive Disorders \
\
     CONDUCTION APHASIA Conduction aphasia is relatively rare, and results \
     from a lesion to the connecting pathway between the expressive and receptive \
     speech areas. People with conduction aphasia have intact language comprehension. \
     speak fluently, but are unable to repeat verbal phrases. They resemble people with \
     Wernicke's aphasias in that they speak fluently but make no sense. However, unlike \
     people with Wernicke's aphasia, they are able to execute verbal commands because \
     they can still comprehend language. \
\
     GLOBAL APHASIA A global aphasia results from widespread damage to much \
     of the language regions of the cortex. Most language functions are impaired, \
     including fluency, comprehension, repetition, and naming. \
\
     ANOMIC APHASIA An anomic aphasia is characterized by problems recalling \
     words or names. The person may speak in a roundabout way (circumlocution) and \
     resort to descriptions to express a certain word for which they can't remember the \
     name. It is thought that anomia results from damage to the parietal or temporal lobe. \
\
     TRANSCORTICAL APHASIA   A transcortical aphasia is caused by damage \
     outside of the main language regions. There are three types of transcortical aphasias \
     - transcortical motor aphasia, transcortical sensory aphasia, and transcortical mixed \
     aphasia. They are similar to Broca's, Wernicke's, and global aphasia respectively, \
     except that the ability to repeat words, phrases, and sentences remains intact. For \
     example, in a transcortical motor aphasia, the person cannot spontaneously say "I \
     am thirsty." However, the person could repeat the phrase "I am thirsty" with ease. \
\
>APRAXIA Apraxia refers to the inability to carry out voluntary or purposeful motor \
movements, even though there are no motor or sensory deficits. The person understands \
and is willing to perform the movements; the person simply cannot execute the act. There \
are many different types of apraxias. Examples include difficulty carrying out a specific \
motor command voluntarily (e.g .. "scratch your nose") while being able to involuntarily \
perform this action with ease (e.g., scratching one's nose if it itches); inability to carry out \
a complex task in sequence (e.g., putting on one's socks before one's shoes); no longer \
being able to perform a learned task when given the necessary objects (e.g., when given a \
screwdriver, the person tries to write with it); difficulty planning and coordinating the \
movements necessary for speech (apraxia of speech); and difficulty drawing, copying, or \
constructing simple figures (constructional apraxia). It is believed that apraxia is caused by \
a lesion in the neural pathways of the brain that contain the learned patterns of movement; \
apraxia most likely results from damage to the parietal or frontal lobes. \
\
\
\
