\
>AGNOSIA Agnosia is the loss of ability to recognize a specific sensory stimulus, such \
as objects, people, sounds, shapes, or smells. The specific sense is not defective nor is there \
any significant memory loss. Agnosia is caused by damage in the parietal, temporal or \
occipital regions. \
\
     PROSOPAGNOSIA Prosopagnosia refers to the inability to recognize a familiar \
     face. A person with prosopagnosia usually has both a retrograde problem (the \
     inability to recognize the faces of previously known individuals) and an anterograde \
     problem (the inability to learn new faces). Prosopagnosia occurs in spite of normal \
     or near-normal visual perception and intact alertness, attention, intelligence, and \
     language. It is thought to be due to injury to the areas of the visual association \
     cortex. \
\
     ANOSOGNOSIA Anosognosia is defined as the lack of awareness of a disability, \
     or the lack of awareness of the nature of one's illness. For example, people with \
     Wernicke's typically don't recognize that they are speaking gibberish or they \
     attribute their speech problem to some other cause, such as a long-standing learning \
     disorder. Anosognosia usually stems from deficits in the frontal or parietal lobes. \
\
>AGRAPHIA Agraphia refers to the partial or complete loss of ability to write. Patients \
may evidence problems with letter formation, spelling, word selection, grammar or spatial \
arrangement. Agraphia may result from left hemisphere damage in any of a variety of areas \
including the frontal, temporal or parietal lobes. \
\
>ALEXIA Alexia, also called word-blindness, refers to the loss of the ability to read \
and/or comprehend the meaning of written or printed words and sentences. The most \
common cause of alexia is a stroke to the dominant (left) hemisphere. \
\
>AMNESIA Amnesia refers to partial or total memory loss. \
\
     RETROGRADE AMNESIA    Retrograde amnesia involves the loss of pre- \
     existing memories. Retrograde amnesia is usually temporally graded, which means \
     that recent memories are much more affected in comparison with remote memories. \
     Typically, episodic memory (memory for autobiographical information) is more \
     severely affected than semantic memory (memory for factual information and \
     general knowledge of the world). The extent of retrograde amnesia can be relatively \
     short and encompass only one or two years, or it can be more extensive and cover \
     decades. Even in situations in which retrograde amnesia is extensive, memories for \
     the facts and events of childhood and adolescence are typically intact. \
\
\
 \
\
                                     Section 2 - Biological: Cognitive Disorders \
\
     ANTEROGRADE AMNESIA Anterograde amnesia refers to the loss of ability \
     to form new memories. A person suffering from anterograde amnesia will forget \
     new information, new people, or new events within a few seconds because the \
     information does not transfer from short-term memory to long-term memory. \
\
>ONE-SIDED NEGLECT One-sided (hemispatial) neglect most often results from a \
stroke in the right hemisphere. Such individuals with right-sided brain damage often fail to \
be aware of objects to their left (the contralateral or opposite side of the brain damage). \
They may eat from only the right side of a plate, write only on the right side of a page, and \
shave or put make-up only on the non-neglected right (same side or ipsilateral) side of their \
face. Patients may forget to dress the left side of the body and walk into furniture or objects \
on the left. \
\
II. NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDERS \
\
Neurocognitive disorders (NCDs) include delirium, as well as major NCDs, mild NCDs. \
and their subtypes (e.g., due to Alzheimer's disease, due to traumatic brain injury). The \
term dementia is subsumed under major neurocognitive disorder. While dementia is still \
used for disorders involving degenerative processes typically in older adults (e.g., \
Alzheimer's), neurocognitive disorder is preferred for conditions affecting younger \
persons (e.g., impairment secondary to traumatic brain injury or HIV infection). The major \
NCD definition is also broad in that individuals with a decline in a single domain can \
receive the diagnosis (e.g., what used to be an amnestic disorder is now a major NCD). \
Less severe levels of cognitive impairment are diagnosed as a mild neurocognitive \
disorder. \
\
The criteria for the neurocognitive disorders include a decline in one or more of six \
cognitive domains: complex attention (sustained attention, divided attention, processing \
speed); executive function (planning, decision-making, responding to feedback, mental \
flexibility); learning and memory (immediate memory, recent memory, remote memory); \
expressive and receptive language (naming, word finding, grammar, comprehension); \
perceptual-motor (visual perception, visuo-constructional, perceptual-motor, praxis, \
gnosis); and social cognition (recognition of emotions, theory of mind). \
\
The distinction between mild and major NCD is based on the extent to which the cognitive \
symptoms interfere with daily functioning. If the "cognitive deficits interfere with \
independence in everyday activities," the diagnosis should be major cognitive disorder. If \
the deficits don't interfere with independence, the diagnosis should be mild cognitive \
\
\
\
                                     Section 2 - Biological: Cognitive Disorders \
\
disorder. Note that the distinction between major and mild cognitive disorder is not based \
on how many cognitive domains are affected nor on which domains are affected. \
\
Whether major or mild, the cause of a neurocognitive disorder (NCD) should always be \
specified as part of the diagnosis. Specifiers include whether due to: Alzheimer's disease, \
vascular disease, Lewy body disease, multiple etiologies, Parkinson's disease, \
Huntington's disease, frontotemporal lobar degeneration, HIV infection, prion disease \
(e.g., Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease), another medical condition, traumatic brain injury, \
substance/medication use, or unspecified. \
\
A. DELIRIUM \
\
The hallmark of delirium is a disturbance in attention and awareness (e.g., reduced \
orientation to the environment). The onset is rapid (hours to days) and the course tends to \
be fluctuating. Additionally, delirium includes a cognitive disturbance (e.g., memory \
problems, disorientation, language difficulties, visuospatial abilities, or perceptual \
disturbance). Delirium is only diagnosed when there is evidence that the symptoms have a \
physiological cause (i.e., a general medical condition, infection, substance intoxication, or \
substance withdrawal). Delirium is sometimes to referred to as an acute confusional state. \
\
In contrast with major or minor NCD, delirium has an acute onset and fluctuating course, \
and is usually reversible. Sometimes, delirium can be superimposed upon a major \
neurocognitive disorder (e.g., major NCD due to Alzheimer's disease, with delirium). \
\
Delirium may occur at any age, but it is most common with older adults. The most common \
causes of delirium are drugs/medications and infections. \
\
Once delirium is diagnosed or suspected, the underlying cause must be identified and \
targeted. Additionally, reorientation techniques or memory cues such as a calendar, a clock, \
and family photos may be helpful. The environment should be stable, quiet, and well lit. \
The most common medications used to manage delirium are antipsychotics (e.g., Haldol). \
Benzodiazepines often are used to manage withdrawal delirium. \
\
B. ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE (AD) \
\
Alzheimer's disease (AD) is the most commonly occurring major NCD, accounting for up \
to 80% of all cases of major NCD. Estimates are that between 5.2 and 5.4 million people \
in the U.S. (1 in 8 over the age of 65) have AD. The prevalence of AD increases with age; \
\
\
