\
less than 2% of people ages 65-69, 5% of those age 71-79, 24% of those age 80-89, and \
37% of those age 90 and over have AD. Alzheimer's disease is more prevalent in women, \
because on average women live longer than men. \
\
Early clinical symptoms of AD include memory problems (e.g., difficulty remembering \
names, recent events, what one was about to do, misplacing things), as well as apathy and \
depression. Later symptoms include disorientation, confusion, problems with judgment, \
behavior changes, and gait and motor problems. As the disease progresses, people need \
help with basic activities of daily living (e.g., bathing, dressing, eating). In the final stages \
of AD, patients lose their ability to communicate, fail to recognize loved ones, and become \
bedridden. \
\
Hallmark abnormalities of AD include amyloid plaques (deposits of protein fragment \
beta-amyloid) and neurofibrillary tangles (twisted strands of the protein tau). There is also \
evidence of neuronal damage and death throughout the cortex and within brain structures, \
especially the hippocampus (associated with memory) and amygdala (associated with \
aggression). Patients with AD evidence a significant decrease in the level of the neuro- \
transmitter acetylcholine (ACh), involved in learning and memory. \
\
In 2011, the National Institute on Aging (NIA) and the Alzheimer's Association \
recommended new diagnostic criteria and guidelines for AD. Specifically, they identified \
three stages of Alzheimer's disease: 1) pre-clinical Alzheimer's disease (biomarkers \
indicate early disease, but no symptoms are present), 2) mild cognitive impairment or MCI \
due to Alzheimer's disease (mild but noticeable changes in thinking that do not affect the \
person's ability to carry out daily activities), and 3) dementia due to Alzheimer's disease. \
Alzheimer's is now thought to be a disease that begins up to 20 years before the \
development of symptoms. \
\
Until recently, diagnosis of AD could only be definitively made or confirmed based on \
histopathological evidence found on biopsy or autopsy. New research shows that an agent \
called Amyvid (florbetapir) can help diagnose Alzheimer's by sticking to beta amyloid \
clumps and emitting radioactivity, which can then be picked up by a PET scan. Proton MR \
spectroscopy is also being used to detect abnormalities in several brain metabolites that \
may be biomarkers of future Alzheimer's disease. \
\
Although the etiology of AD remains unclear, there is some evidence for a genetic \
component. Individuals with a first-degree relative with Alzheimer's are more likely to \
develop the disease than those who do not have a first-degree relative with Alzheimer's. \
\
\
\
                                     Section 2 - Biological: Cognitive Disorders \
\
Alzheimer's is a progressive disease. It is considered cortical in nature, with memory, \
language, and praxis most affected. Two principles of AD management are to support \
caregivers and treat what is treatable (without aggravating existing symptoms). The most \
common caregivers for Alzheimer's patients are their adult children. A variety of drugs, \
such as Aricept (donepezil) and Cognex (tacrine) appear to result in modest, albeit \
temporary improvements in cognitive functioning (e.g., 3 - 4 points on the Folstein Mini \
Mental State). Currently there is no treatment that slows or stops AD. Research is actively \
looking at developing "disease modifying" treatments. \
\
C. MAJOR VASCULAR NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER \
\
Major vascular NCD is the second most common major NCD, and accounts for 10-15% of \
all cases of major NCD in older adults. Major vascular NCD is twice as common in males \
as females. It results from numerous small cerebrovascular accidents (CVAs) or strokes. \
The location of the brain injury (microscopic bleeding and blood vessel blockage) \
determines how the person's functioning is affected. \
\
Initial symptoms of vascular NCD include impaired judgment or ability to make plans, as \
opposed to the memory loss more often associated with the beginnings of Alzheimer's. \
Onset is typically abrupt, with a course frequently described as "step-wise" to indicate that \
there are plateaus followed by further degeneration. \
\
Half of those diagnosed with major vascular NCD die within two to three years of \
diagnosis, and age of onset is usually younger than in Alzheimer's. Although no \
medications can reverse the effects of a stroke, aspirin, anticoagulants, and \
antihypertensives can reduce the likelihood of a future stroke. \
\
D. MAJOR NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER WITH LEWY \
BODIES \
\
Major NCD with Lewy bodies involves abnormal aggregations (clumps) of the protein \
alpha-synuclein (also found in Parkinson's Disease). Symptoms of major NCD with Lewy \
bodies are similar to Alzheimer's, but typically also include visual hallucinations, sleep \
disturbances, and muscle rigidity or other parkinsonian movement features (e.g., shuffling \
gait). \
\
\
 \
\
                                     Section 2 - Biological: Cognitive Disorders \
\
E. MAJOR NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER DUE TO \
MULTIPLE ETIOLOGIES \
\
Major NCD due to multiple etiologies most commonly involves Alzheimer's disease co- \
occurring with another NCD, such as vascular disease or Lewy bodies. Recent research \
suggests that major NCD due to multiple etiologies is more common than previously \
thought. \
\
F. PARKINSON'S DISEASE \
\
Parkinson's disease (PD) is primarily considered a movement disorder marked by tremor, \
rigidity, bradykinesia (slowed initiation of movement), and shuffling gait. Sufferers also \
frequently exhibit various neuropsychiatric symptoms, such as depression or a \
neurocognitive disorder. Estimates of the prevalence rates of depression in patients with \
PD vary considerably, from less than 25% to 75%. Some research suggests that symptoms \
of depression may precede the motor symptoms of PD by several years. As PD progresses, \
neurocognitive symptoms are quite common, with a prevalence rate of major NCD due to \
Parkinson's disease of up to 40% in PD patients. Major NCD due to Parkinson's disease is \
generally considered to be sub-cortical, affecting speed of processing and executive \
functions (planning, organizing, sequencing). \
\
The incidence of PD is about one-tenth that of Alzheimer's. Abnormalities found in PD \
include alpha-synuclein aggregates (also found in neurocognitive disorder with Lewy \
bodies) that begin in the substantia nigra, a section of the basal ganglia. The basal ganglia \
are involved in regulating voluntary movement. The aggregates are thought to cause \
degeneration of the nerve cells that produce dopamine. L-Dopa (Levodopa), which is a \
precursor to dopamine, is used to treat the movement components of Parkinson's. \
Unfortunately, it does not alter the progression of the disease nor decrease symptoms of \
the major neurocognitive disorder. \
\
G. HUNTINGTON'S DISEASE (CHOREA) \
\
Huntington's disease is a fatal condition that results from an autosomal-dominant gene. \
Symptoms gradually become apparent between 30 and 50 years of age. Earliest symptoms \
are typically non-specific changes in personality and mood, such as irritability. apathy, or \
disinhibition. All patients with Huntington's disease experience a progressively \
deteriorating major NCD (memory loss and lack of reasoning) that slowly develops along \
with psychological symptoms. The choreiform movements (frequent, discrete, brisk \
