jerking movements of the pelvis, trunk, and limbs), athetosis (slow writhing movements), \
as well as facial grimaces may begin up to 10 years after the onset of the disease. \
\
Huntington's disease involves the basal ganglia, specifically the caudate nucleus and \
putamen. The motor symptoms of the disease are thought to result from a significant \
reduction of acetylcholine and GABA, which in turn triggers an excess of dopamine. \
\
Genetic counseling is an important intervention for people with a family history of \
Huntington's. A child whose parent has the gene for Huntington's has a 50% chance of \
getting Huntington's. \
\
H. MAJOR FRONTOTEMPORAL NEUROCOGNITIVE \
DISORDER \
\
Major frontotemporal NCD (frontotemporal lobar degeneration) is an umbrella term used \
to describe a diverse group of rare disorders that primarily affect the frontal and temporal \
lobes of the brain. Typical symptoms include changes in personality and behavior (e.g., \
problems with judgment, explosive temper, disinhibition and poor impulse control, \
impaired insight) and difficulty with language. Pick's disease and progressive supranuclear \
palsy are both major frontotemporal NCDs. \
\
I. MAJOR NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER DUE TO HIV \
INFECTION \
\
In the U.S. more than one million people are living with HIV. HIV infects vital cells of the \
immune system. Prior to the advent of highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART), major \
NCD was a common source of morbidity and mortality in HIV-infected patients. \
\
Major NCD due to HIV infection is also referred to as AIDS dementia complex (ADC). \
The symptoms of ADC include cognitive, motor, and behavioral/mood changes. The \
cognitive symptoms include memory problems (although long-term memory frequently \
remains intact), difficulty with attention and concentration, and language difficulties. \
Motor problems commonly include weakness, lack of coordination, unsteady gait, and \
jerky eye movements. Behavioral/mood changes include apathy, withdrawal, lack of \
motivation, personality changes, inappropriate affect, mood swings, and even \
hallucinations. \
\
\
