\
J. CREUTZFELDT-JAKOB DISEASE \
\
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) is a rare, degenerative, fatal brain disorder, thought to \
result from an infectious misfolded protein (prion) that triggers other proteins throughout \
the brain to misfold and thus malfunction. CJD results in a rapidly progressive major NCD \
(due to prion diseae), with problems with muscular coordination, personality changes. \
impaired orientation, memory, judgment, and thinking, as well as problems with vision. \
The average duration of the disease from onset of symptoms to death is four to six months. \
A variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease is believed to be caused by consumption of products \
from cattle affected by mad cow disease. \
\
K. HYDROCEPHALUS \
\
Hydrocephalus involves a pathological accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) in the \
brain's ventricles, causing increased intracranial pressure. Hydrocephalus can be caused \
by either over-production or malabsorption of CSF, with malabsorption being far more \
common. In addition to causing problems of urinary incontinence and unsteady gait, \
hydrocephalus can lead to a neurocognitive disorder. Hydrocephalus can sometimes be \
corrected, and symptoms reversed, with the surgical installation of a shunt in the brain to \
drain excess fluid. \
\
L. NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER DUE TO \
TRAUMATIC BRAIN INJURY \
\
Neurocognitive disorder due to traumatic brain injury involves a NCD that results directly \
from the pathophysiological consequence of head trauma. The nature and extent of the \
cognitive impairment and other behavioral disturbances depends upon the location and \
extent of the brain injury. In many cases, posttraumatic amnesia is present, as well as some \
degree of persisting memory impairment and some disturbance of executive functioning. \
Other symptoms may include problems with attention, difficulty regulating mood (e.g .. \
irritability, anxiety, depression or affective lability), aggression, apathy, or other changes \
in personality. \
\
Head trauma is the leading cause of brain injury in children and young adults. Head traumas \
can stem from either closed-head or open-head injuries. \
\
>CLOSED-HEAD INJURIES In closed-head injuries, the skull is not pierced or cracked. \
A loss of consciousness frequently results. The two most common subtypes are \
concussions and contusions. \
\
\
\
