\
     CONCUSSIONS Concussions, the most common head injury, result from a blow \
     to the head, hard enough to cause temporary neural dysfunction, but not hard \
     enough to cause a cerebral contusion (bruising). Concussions may cause a short- \
     term loss of consciousness as well as both anterograde amnesia (inability to \
     remember new information) and retrograde amnesia (loss of memory for \
     information acquired prior to the injury). With concussions, retrograde amnesia \
     typically includes amnesia for events just before the injury and the incident itself. \
     rather than for remote events. Brain injuries from concussions are microscopic, \
     widespread, and tend to cause functional (rather than structural) damage. \
\
     Postconcussion syndrome is a constellation of somatic and psychological \
     symptoms including headache, dizziness, fatigue, diminished concentration, \
     memory deficit, irritability, anxiety, insomnia, hypochondriacal concern, \
     hypersensitivity to noise, hypersensitivity to light (photophobia). The most \
     common symptoms are irritability, fatigue, headache, and dizziness. Generally, the \
     psychological symptoms heal in about the same period of time that the physical \
     injuries do. \
\
     CONTUSIONS Cerebral contusions (bruises) are more serious than concussions, \
     and result from a severe blow to the head that leads to bleeding and bruising of the \
     brain. The bruising typically occurs in a coup-countrecoup fashion, meaning that \
     there is bruising beneath the point of impact (coup) as well as on the opposite side \
     of the brain (countercoup). Cerebral swelling is also common and is potentially life- \
     threatening. Contusions are localized, macroscopic, and tend to cause structural \
     damage. The site of the coup or countercoup is frequently the frontal or temporal \
     lobes. Frontal lobe syndrome is characterized by a lack of foresight and concern, \
     problems with executive functioning, irresponsibility, and a loss of insight. \
     Temporal lobe syndrome is characterized by irritability and hostility. \
\
>OPEN-HEAD INJURIES   Open-head injuries (e.g., gunshot wounds) involve \
penetration of the skull. Many people who have open head injuries do not lose \
consciousness. Neurological signs are often highly specific, with the effects of the injuries \
resembling the surgical removal of a small area of the cortex. \
\
>RECOVERY FROM HEAD TRAUMA Although it is frequently stated that recovery \
from head trauma may continue for two to three years, the bulk of cognitive recovery \
occurs within the first six to nine months. Recovery of memory functions is typically \
slower than recovery of general intelligence. Additionally, the final level of memory \
performance is lower than for other cognitive functions. \
\
\
 \
\
