\
People with head trauma frequently suffer from retrograde amnesia, the inability to \
remember events that occurred prior to the trauma. As they recover their memory, they \
first remember more remote events and slowly remember events coming closer and closer \
to the event of the trauma. For example, the person first remembers what occurred ten years \
ago, then three years ago, then one year ago, then several months ago, etc. Frequently, \
memory is never regained for what happened just prior to the injury and for the traumatic \
incident itself. It is believed that the head injury disrupts the process of memory \
consolidation. \
\
M. SUBSTANCE/MEDICATION-INDUCED MAJOR \
NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER \
\
In a substance/medication-induced major NCD, the impairment persists beyond \
intoxication and withdrawal. Korsakoff's syndrome is a common cause of alcohol- \
induced major NCD, amnestic-confabulatory type. Korsakoff's results from chronic \
thiamin (Vitamin B1) deficiency associated with longstanding alcohol abuse. The most \
significant problem associated with Korsakoff's is anterograde amnesia, difficulty forming \
new memories. Korsakoff's patients also suffer from retrograde amnesia. While retrieval \
of recent memories is most impaired, Korsakoff patients also have difficulty retrieving \
more remote memories. Confabulation, the replacement of a gap in the patient's memory \
with false information the patient believes to be true, is common. Other hallmarks of \
Korsakoff's include lack of insight, limited spontaneous conversation, problems with \
executive functioning, disorientation, apathy, and labile irritability. \
\
N. PSEUDODEMENTIA \
\
Pseudodementia occurs in older people who are depressed and exhibit cognitive \
impairments resembling a neurocognitive disorder. Depressive symptoms in older people \
often include mild cognitive dysfunction: slower processing speed, difficulties in \
concentration and attention, psychomotor retardation, and easily giving up on difficult \
items when tested. A key distinguishing feature between people with pseudodementia and \
those with a NCD, is that patients with pseudodementia tend to complain about their \
memory loss while those with a NCD tend to lack insight into their condition and often \
deny memory loss. Additionally, people with pseudodementia regain mental function after \
the depression is treated, while those with a NCD do not. \
