I. PAIN \
\
According to Melzak and Wall's (1965) gate control theory, sensations of pain are not \
directly related to activation of pain receptors, but rather they are mediated by neural gates \
in the spinal cord that allow these signals to continue on to the brain. Pressure stimulation \
tends to close the gates, which is why rubbing a hurt area may often relieve pain. \
Psychological factors, such as attitudes (cognitions) and moods, also significantly affect \
the gates. In particular, depression and bereavement may open neural gates and increase \
experiences of pain. \
\
Distinctions are commonly made between acute and chronic pain. Acute pain begins \
suddenly and is usually triggered by a clearly defined cause (e.g., an injury, surgery, burns \
or cuts, broken bones). Acute pain resolves with the healing of its underlying cause. \
Chronic pain persists despite the fact that the injury has healed. Chronic pain affects \
people both physically and emotionally. Physical effects may include tense muscles. \
limited mobility, and lack of energy. Emotional effects may include depression, anger, and \
anxiety. Common chronic pain complaints include headache, low back pain, cancer pain, \
arthritis pain, and neuropathic pain (shooting and burning pain, tingling and numbness, \
brought about by nerve damage). \
\
Chronic pain is a considered to be a multi-factorial process, largely affected by neural \
memories of previous pain. According to the centralization of pain theory, sensitization \
to pain occurs when the brain is exposed to repeated pain signals or nerve stimulation. As \
a result of neural plasticity (the brain's ability to change in response to one's experience), \
neurons develop a memory for responding to pain signals. Repeated or frequent stimulation \
results in a stronger brain memory; the brain responds more quickly when exposed to the \
same signals in the future, with a lowered pain threshold and a stronger pain response. \
Once central sensitization occurs, it also takes larger and larger doses of analgesics, \
typically opiates, to overcome it. Some practitioners argue that preemptive analgesia \
(treatment before pain progresses) may decrease or even prevent neural plasticity, and that \
pain should be treated early and aggressively. \
\
Historically, the recommendation for management of chronic pain has been to provide \
opiate pain medications on a time-contingent (e.g., on a fixed interval schedule) rather than \
