II. SLEEP \
\
There are two main types of sleep: Non-Rapid Eye Movement (NREM) Sleep and Rapid \
Eye Movement (REM) Sleep. Brain waves differ depending on a person's state of alertness, \
relaxation, and depth of sleep. Beta waves characterize states of alertness and attention. \
Alpha waves are present during relaxation. \
\
HINT: Beta waves mean you beta be alert. Alpha waves mean you're saying "aaah." \
\
The sleep cycle is divided into four NREM stages followed by REM sleep. REM sleep is \
sometimes referred to as Stage 5 sleep. \
\
     STAGE 1 Stage 1 is a brief transitional stage between wakefulness and sleep, the \
     lightest stage of sleep. In Stage 1 theta waves predominate. \
\
     STAGE 2 In Stage 2, the brain produces bursts of rapid, rhythmic brain wave \
     activity known as sleep spindles. Body temperature starts to decrease and heart rate \
     begins to slow. \
\
     STAGES 3 AND 4 Stages 3 and 4 are characterized by delta waves. Stage 3 is a \
     transitional period between light and very deep sleep, whereas Stage 4 is deep sleep. \
     Heart rate and respiration are slowed, but muscles maintain tone. \
\
     REM SLEEP REM sleep (Stage 5 sleep) is characterized by rapid eye movement, \
     increased respiration rate, and increased brain activity. REM sleep is also \
     considered paradoxical sleep; while the brain and other body systems become more \
     active, muscles become more relaxed. Most dreaming occurs during REM sleep. \
\
The stages of sleep alternate throughout the night. The deeper stages become less frequent \
in the second half of the night and REM sleep becomes more prominent. As people age the \
percentage of time spent in REM sleep decreases. For example, the time spent in REM \
sleep for newborns is 50%. For five-year-olds, it's about 20 - 25%, and for older adults, \
it's only 18%. \
\
\
\
