\
If awakened during non-REM sleep, people report having a dream only 30% of the time. \
Non-REM dreams typically seem "normal" and logical. If awakened during REM sleep, \
most people report having a dream, which is typically bizarre and illogical. Overall, non- \
REM sleep appears to have a physically restorative function, whereas REM sleep appears \
to have a psychologically restorative function. \
\
Sleep deprivation has many negative effects. It significantly impairs memory. \
concentration, and decision-making; disrupts the body's metabolism; and increases stress \
hormones. Long-term sleep deprivation also increases the risk of automobile accidents. \
Dream deprivation (caused by waking subjects repeatedly during REM periods) results in \
REM-rebound. \
\
III. SEIZURES \
\
A seizure is a sudden disruption of the brain's normal electrical activity. Seizures are short \
lived (lasting from a few seconds to a few minutes) and stop on their own without medical \
help. Seizures always involve altered consciousness and/or other neurological and \
behavioral manifestations. Seizures are classified as either generalized or partial. \
\
>GENERALIZED SEIZURES Generalized seizures, by definition, affect the entire brain \
and always involve loss of consciousness. The two most common generalized seizures are \
tonic clonic seizures and absence seizures. \
\
   & TONIC CLONIC SEIZURES Tonic clonic seizures (also called grand mal \
     seizures) start with sudden loss of consciousness and tonic activity (stiffening) \
     followed by clonic activity (rhythmic jerking caused by alternating muscle \
     contractions and relaxation). After such seizures, people typically experience \
     headache, confusion, fatigue, and amnesia for the seizure. \
\
     ABSENCE SEIZURES Absence seizures (or petit mal seizures), occur most \
     frequently in children, usually beginning before the age of five. These seizures last \
     from one to 30 seconds and begin with a brief change in level of consciousness. \
     followed by blinking or rolling of the eyes, a blank stare, and slight mouth \
     movements, such as twitching. The person appears to be daydreaming. Posture is \
     retained and pre-seizure activity is returned to without difficulty. \
\
>PARTIAL SEIZURES Partial seizures involve an electrical disturbance that is limited \
to a specific area of one cerebral hemisphere. Partial seizures are classified into simple \
