partial seizures (in which consciousness or awareness is retained) and complex partial \
seizures (in which consciousness is impaired or lost). \
\
     SIMPLE PARTIAL SEIZURES In simple partial seizures there are electrical \
     abnormalities in a focal area of the brain only, which may include any of the lobes. \
     Symptoms may be motor (e.g., twitching), autonomic (e.g., racing heart), sensory \
     (e.g., abnormal smells), or psychological (e.g., fear, deja-vu). The person remains \
     conscious during the seizure and can later describe it in detail. Jacksonian \
     seizures, a type of simple partial frontal lobe seizure, are characterized by an \
     initially localized motor seizure, with a spread of abnormal activity to adjacent \
     brain areas. For example, the seizure may start with a finger and then slowly march \
     upwards to the whole hand and arm. \
\
     COMPLEX PARTIAL SEIZURES Complex partial seizures always involve \
     impairment of awareness/consciousness. Automatisms very commonly occur \
     during the seizure. Automatisms are involuntary, purposeless behaviors such as lip \
     smacking, repeating nonsense phrases, fidgeting, and aimless walking. Complex \
     partial seizures are frequently preceded by an aura, such as a familiar feeling (deja \
     vu), nausea, heat or tingling, or distortion of sensory perceptions. Complex partial \
     seizures are most commonly a manifestation of temporal lobe epilepsy. \
\
IV. ELECTROCONVULSIVE THERAPY (ECT) \
\
Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is a procedure in which electric currents are passed \
through the brain, deliberately triggering a brief seizure that can immediately reverse \
symptoms of certain mental illnesses. In spite of the controversy that has historically \
surrounded ECT, it is now generally considered a safe and effective treatment. ECT is most \
widely used for certain patients with severe depression (especially with suicidality or \
psychotic symptoms). It is also used for patients with treatment-resistant bipolar disorder, \
acute psychosis, or catatonia. ECT has been found to help up to 85% of patients who are \
medication resistant. Additionally, ECT provides very rapid relief; many patients respond \
after the first or second treatment. \
\
Memory loss is one of the most significant concerns of ECT. Immediately following ECT. \
the person may be confused and disoriented for up to 45 minutes. In addition to the \
immediate effects of the procedure, patients commonly experience both anterograde and \
retrograde amnesia. Anterograde amnesia (difficulty creating new memories) typically \
resolves a few weeks after treatment. Retrograde amnesia tends to take longer to resolve. \
\
\
\
