\
Most patients experience some permanent loss of memory for events that occurred during \
the treatment period and for events that occurred a few days to a few weeks beforehand. \
The risk of severe and long-lasting memory loss is uncommon. \
\
Bilateral ECT causes greater memory impairment than unilateral ECT. While some \
practitioners think unilateral ECT is less effective than bilateral ECT, others have argued \
that if the dose of electricity is adequate, unilateral ECT is as effective as bilateral ECT, \
with fewer adverse effects. \
\
V. TESTS OF BRAIN FUNCTION & STRUCTURE \
\
Tests of brain function and structure include the EEG, PET and SPECT scan, the MRI, \
fMRI, and MR spectroscopy, and the CT scan. \
\
>EEG (ELECTROENCEPHALOGRAM) An EEG uses electrodes attached to the scalp \
to measure electrical activity in the cortex. EEG results show changes in brain activity that \
aid in diagnosis of brain conditions, especially seizure disorders. An EEG is the preferred \
method of localizing the source of a seizure during the event. \
\
>PET AND SPECT SCANS Both the PET (positron emission tomography) scan and \
SPECT (single-photon emission computerized tomography) scan are nuclear imaging \
techniques, used to demonstrate activity or functioning of the brain and other organs. A \
small amount of radioactive material is injected into a vein, inhaled, or swallowed. These \
scans measure metabolism and blood flow, which helps detect abnormalities. For example, \
cancers show up as brighter spots on PET/SPECT scans because cancer cells have a higher \
metabolism rate than normal cells. \
\
>MRI, IMRI, & MR SPECTROSCOPY MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) uses a \
magnetic field and radio waves to create detailed images of the structure of the brain, as \
well as other organs and tissues of the body. MRI is the most frequently used imaging test \
of the brain, and it can pick up scars or lesions indicating damage to specific regions. The \
fMRI (functional MRI) examines brain activity and functioning. In an fMRI, the MRI \
machine is specially configured to detect how the blood flows within the brain during a \
specific task. The parts of the brain that are involved or active during a task have more \
blood flow and show up as bright colors on the scan images. MR spectroscopy is used to \
detect metabolic changes in the brain that may be consistent with certain disease processes. \
\
>CT SCAN (COMPUTERIZED TOMOGRAPHY) The CT scan is a test of structure. \
It combines a series of X-ray views taken from many different angles and computer \
