VI. HEADACHES \
\
Primary headaches include tension, migraine, and cluster headaches. They are considered \
primary in that they are not caused by an underlying structural problem in the head or neck \
(e.g., a tumor, bleeding in the brain, encephalitis). \
\
>TENSION HEADACHES Tension headaches are the most common type of headache. \
They are characterized by a feeling of band-like tightness, ache, or pressure around the \
head. The pain, which is bilateral, is typically dull and steady. The headache is not \
associated with an aura, nausea, vomiting, or sensitivity to light and sound. Most people \
can function normally, despite the headache. Tension headaches occur more commonly \
among women than men. \
\
>MIGRAINE HEADACHES Migraines are the second most common type of headache. \
They commonly involve unilateral (bilateral on occasion) throbbing pain, of moderate to \
severe intensity. The pain interferes with or is worsened by normal physical activity. \
Associated features include nausea and/or vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. \
About 15% - 20% of people experience an aura (e.g., visual distortion, hand numbness) \
prior to the headache. Ocular/retinal migraines involve visual disturbances such as flashing \
or bright lights, floating geometric shapes, scotomata (blind spots), or loss of peripheral \
vision. \
\
>CLUSTER HEADACHES Cluster headaches are recurring headaches that occur in \
groups or cycles over a period of days or weeks, followed by remissions that can last days \
or weeks. They appear suddenly and are characterized by severe, debilitating pain on one \
side of the head, often accompanied by a watery eye and nasal congestion or a runny nose \
on the same side of the face. Cluster headaches are rare, affecting 0.1% of the population \
(1 in 1,000 people). These headaches are more frequent in men. \
\
VII. SYNESTHESIA \
\
Synesthesia is a perceptual condition of mixed sensations. It occurs when a stimulus in one \
sensory modality (e.g., vision) involuntarily elicits a sensation/experience in another \
modality (e.g. olfaction); or a perception of a form (e.g., a letter or number) induces a \
