VIII. GENERAL ADAPTATION SYNDROME (GAS) \
\
Hans Selye developed a model of response to long-term stress that he called the General \
Adaptation Syndrome (GAS). GAS consists of three stages: alarm, resistance, and \
exhaustion. \
\
>ALARM During the alarm stage, the body mobilizes resources to cope with stress ("fight \
or flight response") by activating the sympathetic nervous system and releasing stress \
hormones including cortisol and adrenaline. While the body is highly alert, this initial \
response can lower immune functioning and decrease resistance to illness. Physical \
symptoms may include headaches, fatigue, and diarrhea. \
\
>RESISTANCE In the resistance stage, the alarm reaction subsides and the body adapts \
to the stressor. The person may experience a level of resistance to illness above normal. \
\
>EXHAUSTION   During the exhaustion phase, which occurs in response to chronic, \
unremitting stress, the body's resources are exhausted and immunity is greatly lowered. \
Unless a way of reducing stress is found, there can be significant loss of health and in \
extreme cases even death. \
\
IX. HEALTH BELIEF MODEL \
\
Rosenstock's health belief model is multicausal, positing that in addition to psychosocial \
factors (e.g., demographic characteristics, peer pressure), there are six constructs that \
predict health behavior. These include perceived susceptibility to disease, perceived \
seriousness of the disease, perceived benefits of preventative action, perceived barriers to \
preventative action, cues to action (e.g., media information), and self-efficacy (confidence \
in one's ability to take action). This model has been widely applied to designing \
interventions to change habitual unhealthy behaviors, such as being sedentary, smoking, or \
overeating, and to encourage healthy habits such as exercise and good nutrition. \
