I. OVERVIEW \
\
Schizophrenia is characterized by positive symptoms (e.g., hallucinations, delusions, \
disorganized thinking), negative symptoms (e.g., affective flattening, lack of motivation, \
poverty of speech, etc.), and cognitive symptoms (e.g., poor executive functioning, trouble \
focusing and paying attention, problems with working memory). These symptoms \
frequently limit functional capacity and reduce quality of life. \
\
The first-generation typical antipsychotic drugs, available since the mid-1950s, have a long \
history of effectiveness in reducing positive symptoms. However, they are only minimally \
effective for the negative and cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Second generation \
atypical antipsychotics were introduced in the 1990s. Initially, these medications were \
viewed as a breakthrough in the treatment of negative symptoms. However, in practice, \
this has not been the case. Results of recent large-scale research studies indicate that \
atypical antipsychotics appear to be no more effective than typical antipsychotics, nor are \
they associated with better cognitive or social outcomes. The side effects of the atypical \
antipsychotics are generally less severe. \
\
II. PRESUMED MECHANISM OF ACTION \
\
All antipsychotics are to some extent dopamine D2 antagonists, which means that they \
lower ("antagonize") the levels of the neurotransmitter dopamine in the brain by blocking \
postsynaptic dopamine receptors. \
\
III. DISORDERS TREATED WITH ANTIPSYCHOTICS \
\
>SCHIZOPHRENIA Antipsychotics are the medication of choice for the treatment of \
schizophrenia. They are generally effective in reducing positive symptoms of \
schizophrenia. However, they do not appear to significantly affect the negative and \
cognitive symptoms of the disorder. \
\
>OTHER PSYCHOTIC DISORDERS   Antipsychotics are commonly used to treat \
psychotic disorders other than schizophrenia, including delusional disorder, brief psychotic \
disorder, and schizoaffective disorder. \
\
>BIPOLAR DISORDER Atypical antipsychotics medications are sometimes used in \
conjunction with mood stabilizers or antidepressants to treat manic episodes of bipolar \
disorder. \
\
\
 \
\
                                       Section 2 - Biological: Antipsychotics \
\
>OTHER CLINICAL USES   Antipsychotics are also used to manage delirium, \
Tourette's disorder, and autism spectrum disorder (to decrease oppositional behavior. \
emotional lability, and irritability). They are also sometimes used as an adjunct in the \
treatment of PTSD and major depressive disorder. While antipsychotics have been used in \
the treatment of neurocognitive disorders, the FDA has determined that death rates are \
higher for elderly patients with neurocognitive disorders when taking antipsychotics. \
\
IV. SIDE EFFECTS \
\
The antipsychotics differ somewhat in their side effect profiles. Common side effects when \
starting any antipsychotic medication include sedation and drowsiness, as well as \
orthostatic hypotension (dizziness when standing up). Both the typical and atypical \
antipsychotics may cause anticholinergic side effects. Weight gain and sexual dysfunction \
may also occur. For the typical antipsychotics (especially Haldol, Prolixin, and Trilafon, \
which are higher potency), the most significant side effects are the extrapyramidal \
symptoms (EPS). All of the antipsychotics can potentially cause tardive dyskinesia, \
although the risk is reduced with atypical antipsychotics. In contrast, the atypical \
antipsychotics carry a higher risk of metabolic adverse effects. The atypical antipsychotic \
Clozaril (clozapine) is associated with an increased risk of agranulocytosis. \
\
>ANTICHOLINERGIC EFFECTS Anticholinergic effects include dry mouth (the most \
common anticholinergic effect), constipation, urinary hesitancy or retention, blurred \
vision, dry eyes, photophobia (sensitivity to light), nasal congestion, confusion, and \
decreased memory. These side effects typically diminish but do not completely disappear \
within the first month of antipsychotic use. These symptoms can be remembered because \
they mostly deal with "drying out" or "holding in." \
\
>EXTRAPYRAMIDAL SYMPTOMS (EPS)   Extrapyramidal symptoms (EPS) are \
movement-related symptoms, some of which are the most disturbing and damaging side \
effects of the antipsychotics. EPS symptoms may be managed through the use of \
anticholinergic agents (ACAs), such as Cogentin (benztropine) and Artane (trihexy- \
phenidyl). A significant advantage of the atypical antipsychotics is that they are far less \
likely to cause EPS. \
\
EPS symptoms include dystonia (acute and painful muscle spasms), parkinsonism (a \
mask-like face, shuffling gait, drooling, resting tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia), and \
akathisia (an unpleasant, restless feeling particularly in the legs). Akathisia is both \
extremely common and distressing, and is associated with premature treatment \
termination. \
\
\
\
