\
>TARDIVE DYSKINESIA (TD) Tardive dyskinesia (TD) most commonly involves \
abnormal movements of the lips, tongue, and jaw (e.g., lip smacking, grimacing, chewing, \
rolling and protruding the tongue), and may involve the trunk or arms as well. TD generally \
occurs after a relatively long period of treatment (e.g., a year or more). There is a \
significantly higher risk of developing TD when taking typical antipsychotics; 20% to 40% \
of patients treated with typical antipsychotics eventually develop TD. While TD is not \
dangerous, it may be stigmatizing; people with TD are often considered weird. \
\
Tardive dyskinesia is best treated through prevention, such as monitoring patients regularly \
for tardive-like symptoms and re-assessing patients every six months to see if medications \
can be discontinued, or dosages reduced. Occasionally, the symptoms only emerge after \
medications have been terminated or dosages have been lowered. There is no established \
treatment for TD. Paradoxically, antipsychotics themselves represent a short-term \
treatment for TD. In two-thirds of all patients, an increase in antipsychotics resulted in a \
clinically significant, albeit temporary, reduction in TD symptoms. Anticholinergic agents \
usually exacerbate tardive dyskinesia. \
\
Tardive dyskinesia may be reversible. About 50% of the patients who develop tardive \
dyskinesia experience a full remission of symptoms after antipsychotics have been stopped. \
\
>METABOLIC EFFECTS Atypical antipsychotics frequently cause major weight gain \
and changes in metabolism. This increases the risk and prevalence of diabetes and high \
cholesterol. Weight, glucose levels, and lipid levels should all be regularly monitored in \
patients taking atypical antipsychotics. \
\
>NEUROLEPTIC MALIGNANT SYNDROME (NMS) NMS is rare. It affects less \
than 1% of patients treated with antipsychotics and is potentially lethal. It involves severe \
muscle rigidity, altered consciousness, autonomic instability (e.g., heart rate and blood \
pressure changes), and high fever, and requires emergency medical attention. \
\
>AGRANULOCYTOSIS Agranulocytosis is a potentially lethal side effect associated \
with Clozaril (clozapine). For this reason Clozaril is usually only administered to patients \
who have "failed" on trials of other antipsychotics. Agranulocytosis is a sudden drop in the \
white blood cell (granulocyte) count that results in a very high risk of serious infection due \
to immune suppression. \
