I. OVERVIEW \
\
The SSRIs are the newest and most widely prescribed antidepressants. The SSRIs are \
generally well tolerated, with few side effects and minimal lethality. The tricyclics are \
highly effective. However, their potential side effects are more serious and they can be fatal \
when taken in overdose. The MAOIs are the oldest class of antidepressants. MAOIs are \
especially effective in treating atypical depression (increased appetite and need for sleep). \
However, MAOIs interact dangerously with certain foods and medications. \
\
II. PRESUMED MECHANISM OF ACTION \
\
The primary mechanism of action of most antidepressants is to block reuptake of serotonin \
and/or norepinephrine, thus increasing the levels of those neurotransmitters in the brain. \
As their name implies, the SSRIs have a selective impact on serotonin. Wellbutrin \
(bupropion) is an anomaly, as its effect is to increase dopamine. It typically takes a couple \
of weeks for antidepressant medications to take effect. \
\
III. DISORDERS TREATED \
\
>MAJOR DEPRESSIVE DISORDER All of the antidepressants have been found to be \
equally effective in treating typical depressions. Patients taking SSRIs usually experience \
fewer and less distressing side effects than with other classes of antidepressants. SSRIs are \
also safer. For this reason, they are now generally considered the first line of treatment for \
depression. \
\
>BIPOLAR DISORDER, DEPRESSED When antidepressants are used to treat \
symptoms of depression in patients with bipolar disorder, typically a mood stabilizer is \
prescribed concomitantly. This is done to minimize the risk of inducing a manic episode. \
Prozac, Paxil, Zoloft, and Wellbutrin are commonly used to treat bipolar depression. \
\
>ANXIETY DISORDERS, TRAUMA-RELATED DISORDERS, OBSESSIVE- \
COMPULSIVE DISORDERS   Antidepressants are widely used in the treatment of \
anxiety disorders, trauma-related disorders and obsessive-compulsive disorders. They are \
a safe and effective alternative to antianxiety medications (e.g., benzodiazepines), and do \
not lead to abuse or dependence. \
\
     PANIC DISORDER In addition to using antianxiety agents Xanax (alprazolam) \
     and Ativan (lorazepam), panic disorder is frequently treated with antidepressants, \
