IV. SIDE EFFECTS \
\
>SELECTIVE SEROTONIN REUPTAKE INHIBITORS (SSRIs) The SSRIs have the \
advantage of having far fewer side effects than the TCAs and MAOIs. Side effects may \
include headaches, nervousness, restlessness, insomnia, and gastrointestinal distress, \
which tend to fade over time. When sexual dysfunction occurs, it may be helped by \
adjusting the dose or switching to another medication. SSRIs carry a black box warning of \
potential risk of suicidal thinking or attempts for children and adolescents. \
\
>TRICYCLIC ANTIDEPRESSANTS (TCAS)   The TCAs may cause severe \
anticholinergic effects (e.g., dry mouth, blurred vision, constipation, urinary hesitation, \
confusion, memory problems). Other frequent side effects are sedation, orthostatic \
hypotension, weight gain, nausea, and sexual dysfunction. TCAs are also linked to \
increased risk of heart disease and are contraindicated in patients with heart conditions, \
high blood pressure, or seizures. \
\
>MONOAMINE OXIDASE INHIBITORS (MAOIs) The MAOIs frequently cause \
orthostatic hypotension, weight gain, edema, sexual dysfunction, and insomnia. The most \
serious side effect is a tyramine-induced hypertensive crisis. Patients who take MAOIs \
must not eat foods high in tyramine because these foods can trigger a dangerous increase \
in blood pressure requiring immediate medical attention. Symptoms of a tyramine-induced \
hypertensive crisis include severe headache, stiff neck, palpitations, sweating, nausea, and \
vomiting. Tyramine-rich foods that need to be avoided include red wine, fava beans, aged \
cheese, liver, orange pulp, pickled or smoked fish or meats, packaged soups, yeast vitamin \
supplements, meat extracts, and dry sausage. Foods that may be consumed only in \
moderation include soy sauce, sour cream, bananas, avocados, eggplants, plums, raisins, \
spinach, tomatoes, and yogurt. Certain medications should also be avoided while taking an \
MAOI. For example, MAOIs can react with SSRIs and cause serotonin syndrome, with \
is potentially life threatening. This dangerous side effect profile in combination with the \
requirement for strict dietary and medication compliance are key reasons that MAOIs are \
much less commonly prescribed than other antidepressants. \
\
V. DEPENDENCE/WITHDRAWAL/OVERDOSE \
\
Antidepressants do not cause dependence, tolerance, or addiction. Abruptly stopping \
antidepressants can precipitate withdrawal symptoms that are not life-threatening. Both \
TCAs and MAOIs are highly lethal when patients attempt suicide by medication overdose. \
Lethality further increases if combined with alcohol. In contrast, the SSRIs and the other \
antidepressants (e.g., Wellbutrin, Remeron) are not very lethal. \
