V. DEPENDENCE/TOLERANCE/WITHDRAWAL/ \
OVERDOSE \
\
Patients on benzodiazepines can develop both physiological and psychological \
dependence. Benzodiazepines vary greatly in how quickly they take effect and in how long \
they last (half-life). The most addictive BZs are those with rapid onset (providing a buzz) \
and a short half-life (such that the patient may experience a mini-withdrawal), such as \
Xanax. Taking the drug as needed (prn) also encourages dependency. \
\
Patients can definitely develop tolerance for benzodiazepines, requiring larger doses to \
have a similar effect. BZs and alcohol are "cross-tolerant;" meaning that people who \
develop a tolerance for benzodiazepines also experience an increased tolerance for alcohol. \
BZs can be used to reduce the symptoms of alcohol withdrawal. \
\
The withdrawal syndrome from the BZs is very serious and can be fatal. Patients should \
never abruptly stop using the BZs but should only gradually taper their use under a doctor's \
direction. Stage one symptoms include tremors, sweating, agitation, and increased \
autonomic reactions. Stage two includes hallucinations and panic. Stage three includes \
single or multiple grand mal seizures. \
\
BZs are rarely fatal when taken alone. However, when taken with alcohol or other CNS \
depressants they can easily be fatal. \
\
 PRECAUTIONS BZs should generally be avoided or only used with extreme caution \
 with older adults. BZ use in older adults is associated with increased risk of falls and \
 fractures, motor vehicle accidents, and cognitive impairment. BZ use should also be \
 limited in patients with a history of alcohol or drug dependence. \
