               THE ETHICS CODE \
\
The Ethical Principles of Psychologists and Code of Conduct of the American \
Psychological Association was officially adopted on August 21, 2002 and became effective \
June 1, 2003. Amendments to Standards 1.02 and 1.03 became effective on June 1, 2010, \
and the amendment to Standard 3.04 became effective January 1, 2017. \
\
This section summarizes the Ethics Code. Elaborations of the code are in italics. \
\
  3.1 INTRODUCTION AND APPLICABILITY \
\
The Ethics Code consists of an Introduction, Preamble, five General Principles, and ten \
Ethical Standards. The General Principles are aspirational, meaning that they are goals \
intended to "guide psychologists toward the highest ideals of psychology." It is explicitly \
stated that they are not enforceable rules. In contrast, the ten Ethical Standards are \
enforceable: they provide the specific guidelines for the ethical behavior of psychologists. \
\
The Ethics Code applies only to the professional and scientific activities of psychologists, \
and not to their private conduct. The Ethics Code explicitly states that professional \
activities include those delivered in person as well as by mail, telephone, internet, and other \
electronic means. \
\
Members and student affiliates of APA are obligated to comply with the Ethics Code. In \
the event of an ethics complaint, ignorance or misunderstanding of an Ethical Standard is \
not considered to be an adequate defense. Psychologists who violate the Ethics Code may \
be sanctioned by APA, including having their membership terminated. The APA may also \
notify other bodies, such as state licensing boards, of these sanctions. Sanctions against an \
APA member may also occur if the member is convicted of a felony, expelled, or \
suspended from a state association, or has his or her license revoked. Even those \
psychologists who are not members of APA may receive sanctions from other bodies that \
\
\
\
                                          Section 3 - Ethics: Introduction \
\
have adopted the Ethics Code, including licensing boards, state psychological associations, \
other professional groups, government agencies, and insurance companies. \
\
The introduction explicitly states that the Ethics Code is not intended to be a basis for civil \
liability: "Whether a psychologist has violated the Ethics Code standards does not by itself \
determine whether the psychologist is legally liable in a court action, whether a contract is \
enforceable, or whether other legal consequences occur." \
\
Civil liability is the issue in malpractice. A malpractice lawsuit can be thought of as based \
on the four D's: dereliction of duty directly causing damages. All four of these conditions \
must be met to hold a therapist liable. Dereliction means that the therapist failed to provide \
care that is reasonable (i.e., negligence). Duty means that the therapist had a legal \
relationship with the patient that gave rise to a duty (e.g., we have no duty to people we \
meet at a party). Dereliction of duty is also called breach of duty. Directly causing \
damages means, as it sounds, that the negligence of the therapist was the cause of some \
sort of harm to the patient. Thus, to prevail in a malpractice lawsuit, a patient must prove \
that the therapist was negligent (dereliction of duty), and that this negligence caused harm \
to the patient (directly causing damages). \
\
Vicarious liability refers to a situation in which someone is held legally liable for either \
the actions or omissions of another person. Thus, a supervisor may potentially be held \
responsible for a supervisee's unethical conduct (e.g., the supervisee's sexual exploitation \
of a patient, the supervisee's failure to report child abuse). \
\
The introduction defines modifiers that are used throughout the Code (e.g., reasonably, \
appropriate, potentially), with the goal of ensuring flexibility and the use of judgment in \
the application of the standards. The term reasonable is defined as "the prevailing \
professional judgment of psychologists engaged in similar activities in similar \
circumstances, given the knowledge the psychologist had or should have had at the time." \
\
When making decisions regarding ethics, psychologists are supposed to consider the Ethics \
Code, applicable laws, psychology board regulations, the guidelines of other scientific and \
professional organizations, and "the dictates of their own conscience." They are also \
supposed to consult with colleagues. When the Ethics Code sets a higher standard of \
conduct than the law, psychologists are bound to uphold "the higher ethical standard." \
However, when there is a conflict between ethics and law (i.e., meeting the ethical \
commitment would seem to violate the law), psychologists must "make known their \
commitment to the Ethics Code and take steps to resolve the conflict." \
