\
and 3) if an informal resolution is attempted, the colleague's response to the attempted \
resolution. \
\
If you learn of the ethical violation directly from your client: If a client, in the course of \
therapy, tells you about another psychologist's offense, you must protect the client's \
confidentiality above all. You may not make a report to the ethics board or state licensing \
board imless authorized by the client (with a release of information). You should also \
provide the client with the necessary information and let the client decide whether to make \
a report. \
\
For example, your client tells you that her previous psychologist, whom you know, often \
made self-disclosing remarks during their sessions, and on several occasions, asked your \
client for feedback about matters relating to his personal life. Your client also tells you that \
on some occasions this therapist tried to hug her against her will. The client's allegations \
against this psychologist seem quite serious. However, you may not make a report to an \
ethics committee or state licensing board because you may not violate the client's \
confidentiality. You should educate the client about what is considered to be appropriate \
and inappropriate conduct for psychologists, as well as about her right to report this \
psychologist, \
\
If you learn of the ethical violation through other means: If you learn about the offense \
by directly observing it, or by hearing about it from the colleague or from someone who is \
not your client, consider the severity of the act. If it is a minor offense, you should first \
discuss the offense with the colleague and explain why the actions were imethical. If the \
psychologist appropriately responds to your attempts at an informal resolution, there is \
nothing more that you need to do. If the psychologist does not respond, you may then file \
a formal complaint. If it is a severe offense, you should report the colleague to an ethics \
committee or state licensing board. \
\
For example, a psychologist who shares office space with you does not lock her filing \
cabinet that contains confidential information. You should first discuss this matter with \
your colleague and inform her that her actions are unethical and illegal. If your colleague \
does not change her behavior, you should consider discussing the matter with the state \
licensing board or ethics committee to find out if you need to file a formal complaint. \
\
Or, a colleague confides in you that he is stressed, and has not been himself because he is \
going through a divorce. He reveals that he is having sex with one of his current clients \
and feels very guilty about it. Even though your colleague does feel guilty, his behavior is \
unethical and illegal and very serious in nature. It is therefore not a matter that can be \
\
\
\
