\
resolved informally. In this situation, you would make a report to the ethics committee or \
state licensing board. \
\
1.06 COOPERATING WITH ETHICS COMMITTEES Failure to cooperate with an \
ethics investigation, whether by APA or a state psychological association, constitutes an \
ethical violation in and of itself. APA cannot suspend or revoke a psychologist's license. \
However, they can inform the state board of any complaints received, and any action taken \
against a psychologist. \
\
1.07 IMPROPER COMPLAINTS Psychologists should not file or encourage the filing \
of ethics complaints that deliberately disregard the facts of a situation. \
\
1.08 UNFAIR DISCRIMINATION    AGAINST COMPLAINANTS    AND \
RESPONDENTS Psychologists should not discriminate against a person because he or \
she has been the subject of an ethics complaint (e.g., discrimination in hiring or promotion). \
However, psychologists are permitted to take action based on the outcome of such \
proceedings. In other words, an employer cannot refuse to hire someone because of an \
unresolved ethics complaint pending against him or her, but if the complaint was \
adjudicated and the person is found guilty of an ethics violation, the employer may take \
this fact into consideration, \
\
2. COMPETENCE \
\
2.01 BOUNDARIES OF COMPETENCE Psychologists should practice within the \
boundaries of their competence. When an understanding of the effect of certain factors \
(age, gender, gender identity, race, ethnicity, culture, national origin, religion, sexual \
orientation, disability, language, and socioeconomic status) is necessary for appropriate \
services or research, psychologists must make sure that they either have or obtain \
appropriate training, supervision, or consultation; otherwise, psychologists should make an \
appropriate referral, except in an emergency situation (see below). When they desire to \
practice in new areas, psychologists should also seek appropriate consultation, supervision, \
or training. \
\
The decision to seek consultation, supervision, training, or to refer out should always be \
based on the best interests of the client. Consultation is most commonly sought on a one- \
time or occasional basis. Supervision, by contrast, is generally considered to be an on- \
going process with careful scrutiny of a case. \
\
\
 \
\
