\
>CONSULTATION   Consultations are appropriate when psychologists are somewhat \
familiar with treating a particular disorder but are not an expert in that area, or when \
psychologists have concerns about whether they can remain objective in treating a client. \
For example, a client comes 10 see a psychologist and presents with symptoms of \
Agoraphobia. The psychologist has had little experience treating agoraphobia, but she \
regularly treats clients with Panic Disorder and other anxiety disorders. As another \
example of consultation, a man seeks treatment with a female psychologist. The \
psychologist notices that she is attracted to this man and begins to feel rather self- \
conscious during sessions with him. She becomes concerned about her ability to provide \
effective treatment for this man. \
\
>SUPERVISION Supervision might be required when psychologists are applying a \
newly learned technique such as hypnosis or biofeedback, beginning to work with a \
specialized population such as the hearing-impaired, or treating a client with a disorder \
the psychologist has training in, but no clinical experience (e.g., Bulimia Nervosa). \
Typically, supervision is sought when psychologists are not yet ready to practice \
independently in the area or with the new population. \
\
>TRAINING Training is vital when psychologists are unfamiliar with a certain area of \
knowledge. Training is usually followed by supervised experience prior to practicing \
independently. For example, a psychologist specializes in psychological testing with \
adults. She would like to expand her practice by offering psychological testing to \
adolescents. However, she has not tested any adolescents since her predoctoral internship \
10 years ago, and has not used any recent instruments for adolescents. This psychologist \
would first need to imdergo the necessary training, (e.g., seminars, reading relevant \
literature), and would then benefit from supervision by a psychologist who specializes in \
testing adolescents in order to help her develop the necessary level of competence in this \
area. \
\
>REFERRING OUT Referring out clients is appropriate in the following situations: a) \
the therapist's personal beliefs and issues interfere with the therapy; b) the client feels \
uncomfortable with the therapist; or c) the therapist lacks competence in treating the \
presenting problem. For example, a psychologist who considers herself a feminist is \
referred a female client who has very traditional beliefs about marriage and women's role \
in society. The psychologist finds that she experiences anger and frustration during her \
first session with this woman, to the point that she is unable to understand this woman's \
difficulties and worldview. She also finds that at times, she is trying to assert her own ideas \
about the need to consider women's rights. Or, a man seeks treatment with a psychologist \
and wants help to overcome huis fear of driving on the freeway. The psychologist practices \
\
\
\
