psychologist must explain the nature of the evaluation and the limits of confidentiality to \
the defendant prior to beginning the evaluation. Any and all information gathered in a \
court-appointed evaluation may be shared with the court; no signed release of information \
is needed. \
\
>COURT-ORDERED THERAPY By contrast, in court-ordered therapy, the court has \
ordered a defendant to seek therapy as a condition of Iris or her sentence. In this situation, \
the defendant generally seeks out a therapist (or program). At the end of treatment, or \
periodically throughout treatment, the court requests information from the treating \
therapist. The psychologist who agrees to treat this client must make sure to clarify the \
nature of the treatment that has been ordered by the court, as well as the information that \
the court needs. The psychologist must then discuss this information with the client and \
obtain informed consent. In addition, the psychologist must generally obtain a signed \
release of information from the client in order to be able to communicate with the court. \
\
One way to remember the differences between court-appointed evaluation and court- \
ordered therapy is to ask the question, "Who is the client?" In court-appointed evaluations, \
the court hires the psychologist and the client is the court. The court has the right to the \
information and there is no confidentiality or need for a release. In court-ordered therapy, \
the client hires the psychologist. The client is the client, and therefore the client has \
confidentiality rights and there is a need for a release. \
\
Confidentiality is the client's right to have communications kept within the bounds of the \
professional client-therapist relationship. Confidential communications are generally not \
to be revealed to third parties. A third party is anyone outside of the professional \
relationship. Privilege is the client's right to keep confidential from being \
disclosed in a legal proceeding. If a client does not want the psychologist to disclose \
confidential communications in a court of law, deposition, etc., the client may invoke or \
assert privilege (or have the psychologist do so on the client's behalf). A court-appointed \
evaluation is considered an exception to privilege; thus, while typically the client holds \
privilege (the right to keep confidential information out of court), in a court-appointed \
evaluation, privilege does not exist. \
\
5. ADVERTISING AND PUBLIC STATEMENTS \
\
5.01 AVOIDANCE OF FALSE OR DECEPTIVE STATEMENTS Public statements \
basically include any written or oral statement in any form other than an entirely private \
conversation or letter. For example, they include advertising, licensing applications, \
brochures, directory listings, curricula vitae, interviews, lectures, and published material. \
