                3.6 APA GUIDELINES \
\
APA has published numerous guidelines. A partial list includes Guidelines for the Practice \
of Telepsychology (2013), Record Keeping Guidelines (2007), Guidelines for Child \
Custody Evaluations in Family Law Proceedings (2010), General Guidelines for Providers \
of Psychological Services (1987), Specialty Guidelines for Forensic Psychologists (2012), \
Guidelines for the Evaluation of Dementia and Cognitive Change (2012), and Guidelines \
for Psychological Practice with Lesbian, Gay, & Bisexual Clients (2011). \
\
In general, guidelines are suggestions or recommendations for professional behavior by \
psychologists. Guidelines differ from standards, which are mandatory and enforceable. \
Guidelines are aspirational in intent. \
\
Some noteworthy areas discussed in APA's various guidelines include the following: \
\
>GUIDELINES FOR THE PRACTICE OF TELEPSYCHOLOGY (2013) Three key \
issues were focused on in the development of the telepsychology guidelines: 1) \
psychologists competence in the use of technology and awareness of its potential impact; \
2) the need to ensure that patients have a full understanding of the risks related to possible \
loss of security and/or breaches of confidentiality; and 3) interjurisdictional practice. \
\
The telepsychology guidelines emphasize the importance of professional training and \
review of relevant literature, documenting choices regarding the use of telecommunication \
technologies, accessing of emergency resources in the patient's local area, informing \
patients of technology-related risks to confidentiality and obtaining informed consent, \
protecting and maintaining confidentiality, safe and appropriate disposal of data, unique \
issues with assessment when using telepsychology technology, and familiarity and \
compliance with laws and regulations when providing telepsychology across jurisdictions. \
\
>RECORD KEEPING GUIDELINES (2007) With regard to content of records, three \
kinds of information may be included: 1) general information such as identifying data, fees \
and billing information, documentation of consent, waivers of confidentiality, and \
mandated disclosures, presenting complaint, diagnosis, plan for services, history; 2) record \
of each client contact to include date of service, duration, type of service, assessment of \
client status; and 3) other specific information such as client reaction to interventions, risk \
factors, plans for future interventions, prognosis, and relevant cultural factors. \
\
\
