 3.7 THE HEALTH INSURANCE PORTABILITY \
     AND ACCOUNTABILITY ACT (HIPAA) \
\
The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is a federal law that was \
signed into effect in 1996. HIPAA was designed to protect Americans with medical \
conditions from losing health insurance when they changed jobs or moved. \
\
The details of HIPAA compliance and its relationship to state laws is a very complex topic. \
 The following summary should not be used as a guide for a solo practitioner or institution \
to become compliant with HIPAA. \
\
>HIPAA'S THREE RULES HIPAA is comprised of three rules: the privacy rule, the \
transaction rule, and the security rule. \
\
     THE PRIVACY RULE The privacy rule of the Health Insurance Portability and \
     Accountability Act (HIPAA) became effective April 14, 2003. The privacy rule \
     provides regulations and safeguards regarding confidential patient information. \
     With the regard to telepsychology, practitioners are required to use HIPAA \
     complaint video services and secure messaging solutions to protect ePHI. \
     Communicating with patients using Skype, FaceTime, or email (e.g., gmail) is not \
     HIPAA complaint. \
\
     THE TRANSACTION RULE The transaction rule became effective October \
     16, 2003. The rule requires that a nationally standardized format be used for all \
     health-care transactions that are transmitted electronically, most notably all \
     insurance claims. Practitioners who submit claims electronically must therefore \
     either use appropriate software or contract with a health-care clearinghouse. (A \
     clearinghouse accepts written data, transforms it into electronic data, and then \
     transmits it to the insurance company). \
\
     THE SECURITY RULE The security rule became effective April 20, 2005. The \
     security rule addresses issues of physical security, such as locking filing cabinets \
     and encrypting emails. \
\
 >HIPAA COMPLIANCE Technically, compliance with HIPAA's rules is only required \
 when health information is transmitted in some electronic form. However, once any \
