 psychologist or an institution. Thus, except for the rare private practice practitioner who \
does not accept third-party reimbursement or use electronic transmissions, HIPAA applies \
to all psychologists. \
\
>HIPAA AND STATE LAW Issues about confidentiality and patient access to records \
are typically governed by state laws and regulations. However, HIPAA is a federal law that \
can take precedence over state law. Specifically, when HIPAA is stricter, it supersedes \
state law. In contrast, when state law is stricter. it supersedes HIPAA. When state law and \
HIPAA are contradictory, making it impossible to comply with both, the practitioner must \
 follow HIPAA. \
\
>HIPAA AND FERPA HIPAA has no jurisdiction over educational records. Privacy \
rights in educational records are governed by the 1974 Family Educational Rights and \
Privacy Act (FERPA), also known as the Buckley Amendment. The Buckley Amendment \
protects the privacy of student records in higher education institutions (e.g., college). It \
includes provisions granting the right of access to one's own records as well as limiting the \
disclosure of the records, such that parents cannot access these records (including student \
health records) without student consent. \
\
>PENALTIES Penalties for failure to comply with HIPAA include: 1) administrative \
sanction by the Office for Civil Rights of Health and Human Services (the promulgators \
of HIPAA); 2) civil penalties of $100 for each violation up to a total of $25,000 a year; and \
 3) fines of up to $250,000 or ten year imprisonment, or both, for deliberate and knowing \
violations of patients' privacy rights. \
\
>BASIC DEFINITIONS HIPAA distinguishes between protected health information \
(PHI) and psychotherapy notes. Most of HIPAA's general provisions govern protected \
health information (PHI). There are more stringent protections for psychotherapy notes. \
\
     PROTECTED HEALTH INFORMATION (PHI) PHI refers to health \
     information that identifies a patient, and that is transmitted or maintained in any \
     form (e.g., on computer, handwritten notes, etc.). PHI includes information about \
     the mental health condition of a patient (e.g., diagnosis, symptoms, prognosis, \
     progress), the provision of services (e.g., medication, treatment modality, treatment \
     plan, frequency of treatment), and payments. Typically, chart notes kept on a \
     psychotherapy patient are considered to be PHI. \
