     PSYCHOTHERAPY NOTES Psychotherapy notes refer to "process notes." Very \
     few psychologists make process notes. Process notes are notes that document or \
     analyze the content of counseling sessions (e.g., dreams, transference). In order for \
     process notes to be considered "psychotherapy notes" and to be accorded special \
     protection, HIPAA requires that these notes be "separated from the rest of an \
     individual's medical record." This means that psychotherapy notes must be kept \
     physically separate from the general medical record (or patient chart). \
\
>GENERALIZED CONSENT AND AUTHORIZATION HIPAA distinguishes \
between generalized consent and authorization. \
\
     GENERALIZED CONSENT Patients must be informed of a practitioner's \
     privacy policy (e.g., given paperwork describing the privacy policy). However, \
     they do not have to give written consent. HIPAA allows for the disclosures of PHI \
     for the purposes of treatment, payment, or to carry out health care operations. In \
     other words, by law, psychologists, medical doctors, and hospitals may disclose \
     and use PHI without a patient's consent if they are doing so for treatment (e.g., a \
     consultation), payment (e.g., billing an insurance company), or health care \
     operations (e.g., utilization review). Although patient consent is technically not \
     needed in these three disclosure situations, it is still considered the standard of \
     practice for psychologists to obtain written permission from patients for any \
     disclosures of confidential information. \
\
     AUTHORIZATION Authorization refers to obtaining patient permission to \
     disclose information on a release of information form. According to HIPAA, a \
     practitioner does not need to obtain authorization (i.e., written releases) for \
     disclosures, as long as any of the disclosures are for the purposes of treatment. \
     payment, or health care operations (as these are covered under generalized consent). \
     However, an authorization is needed for any other type of disclosure. For example, \
     if a patient's employer, a spouse, a school, or the court requests PHI, an \
     authorization from the patient must be secured. Psychologists do not need a patient \
     authorization for mandated disclosures (e.g., Tarasoff, child abuse). \
\
     Psychotherapy notes are recognized as a special class of information with special \
     protections. According to HIPAA, managed care organizations and other third- \
     party reimbursement entities may not require the release of psychotherapy notes to \
     provide reimbursement. To disclose psychotherapy notes to anyone, the patient \
     must complete a specific and detailed authorization. There are of course a few \
