\
The ADA states that discrimination includes using standards, employment tests or other \
selection criteria that screen out an individual with a disability or class of individuals with \
disabilities, unless the test or criteria is shown to be job-related and consistent with business \
necessity. \
\
With regard to substance abuse, the ADA prohibits discrimination against someone who \
has successfully completed or is currently participating in a drug rehabilitation program \
and is no longer using drugs. The act explicitly takes no stand for or against drug testing. \
stating "nothing in this title shall be construed to encourage, prohibit or authorize the \
conducting of drug testing for the illegal use of drugs by job applicants or employees or \
making employment decisions based on such test results." \
\
>GRIGGS VERSUS DUKE POWER COMPANY (1971)   This landmark I/O case \
affected the issue of testing at the workplace. The court ruled that tests that measured broad \
abilities, in which minority group members passed at much lower rates than Whites, were \
unfair to use to make decisions of hiring and promotion. Thus broad general testing was \
faulted, and a requirement was established that tests measure skills necessary for a \
particular job. \
\
II. DISCRIMINATION \
\
There are three major problems that can result in discrimination. These problems can affect \
hiring, evaluation, and promotion. Any combination of these problems can occur (e.g., all \
three can be present or only one might be present). \
\
>ADVERSE IMPACT   Adverse impact is based on the 80% or 4/5ths rule, which \
basically states that the percentage of minorities selected must be at least 4/5ths of the \
percentage of non-minorities selected. This is not the same as saying that one must select \
4/5ths as many minorities as non-minorities. The easiest way to calculate the minimum \
acceptable requirement for selection is to multiply the selection rate for non-minorities by \
.8. For example, a group of applicants seek admission to medical school. If out of one \
hundred non-minority applicants, twenty are selected, the selection ratio is 20/100 or 20%. \
Multiplying .20 by .80 results in .16. So, the minimum acceptable rate for the selection of \
minority applicants would be 16% (e.g., if there are fifty minority applicants, a minimum \
of eight would need to be admitted). \
\
>UNFAIRNESS Unfairness occurs when minorities and non-minorities score differently \
on the predictor test yet perform similarly on the criterion. Graphically, unfairness is \
\
\
