\
depicted as two parallel lines (each line represents a different regression equation used to \
predict performance on the criterion based on the predictor test score). Some theorists argue \
that unfairness rarely occurs. \
\
The MCAT exam is sometimes offered as an example of unfairness, The MCAT attempts \
to predict success in medical school. Some argue that minorities routinely score lower on \
the MCAT than do non-minorities. However, once in medical school, minorities perform \
just as well as their non-minority counterparts. In other words, minorities score differently \
on the predictor (the MCAT) but perform similarly on the criterion (medical school), a \
situation that exemplifies "unfairness." \
\
>DIFFERENTIAL VALIDITY Differential validity occurs when there are significantly \
different criterion-related validity coefficients for different groups on the same test. Put \
more simply, differential validity means that the test is more valid for predicting the \
performance of one group (e.g., males vs. females, Whites vs. Non-Whites) than it is for \
predicting the performance of another. For example, differential validity would exist if the \
MCAT has a criterion-related validity coefficient of .45 for Whites and .25 for Hispanics. \
In this instance, the MCAT would be a far better predictor of success in medical school for \
Whites than for Hispanics. Research suggests that differential validity actually rarely \
occurs. Previous findings in the literature of problems with differential validity are now \
believed to have resulted from low sample size. \
\
