             4.2 HUMAN RESOURCES \
\
Development of human resources focuses on techniques for employee selection, use of \
psychological tests, performance appraisals, training and development, and career \
development theories. \
\
A critical procedure in I/O that affects hiring or promotion is the job analysis. A job \
analysis describes in specific terms the nature of the component tasks performed by \
workers on a particular job. A job analysis includes information about the tools or \
equipment used, the operations performed, education and training required, wages paid, \
and any unique aspect of the job such as safety hazards. To reiterate, a job analysis is a \
procedure for the collection and analysis of data that provides information about the job \
tasks (known as a job description) and job requirements (known as job specifications). A \
job analysis provides the data necessary for many other essential employment-related tasks. \
such as validating selection procedures, determining wages, ascertaining training needs, \
and so forth. It is also associated with a job evaluation, a formal process that determines \
the financial worth of a specific job to an organization. \
\
Job analysis is particularly crucial in order to comply with EEO guidelines regarding fair \
employment. These guidelines require that all employment procedures (e.g., hiring, \
promotions, and evaluations) be based on criteria that are "job-related." Such criteria can \
best be developed with the detailed information provided by a job analysis. \
\
Data for a job analysis can be obtained through either open-ended or structured interviews. \
Data can also be obtained through the critical incident technique. The critical incident \
technique involves ascertaining the specific actions that lead to desirable (successful) or \
undesirable (unsuccessful) consequences on the job. In the example of a customer service \
representative, actions with desirable consequences would include greeting customers in a \
pleasant and professional manner, while actions with undesirable consequences would \
include neglecting to follow through on customer complaints. \
\
\
