\
I. EMPLOYEE SELECTION \
\
Selection and screening options include biodata, interviews, tests, assessment centers, and \
references and letters of recommendation. \
\
A. BIOGRAPHICAL INFORMATION (BIODATA) \
\
Biographical information includes three major techniques: the standard application blank, \
the weighted application blank and the biographical inventory. \
\
>THE STANDARD APPLICATION   The standard application blank is the most \
common type of application. It asks for personal data, including education, employment \
history, etc. \
\
>THE WEIGHTED APPLICATION BLANK    The weighted application blank is \
similar to the standard application in form and content. However, it assigns weights to \
certain variables (e.g., college versus non-college graduates) that then affect the hiring \
process. \
\
>THE BIOGRAPHICAL INVENTORY The biographical inventory, sometimes called \
the BIB (biographical information blank), typically covers the applicant's life in greater \
detail. Questions selected for the BIB are correlated with desirable and undesirable work \
behaviors, and are validated against a specific criterion (e.g., successful work \
performance). BIBs are very good predictors of job success (.32 - . 46 criterion related \
validity coefficients) and they are also good predictors of turnover. They are only used by \
about 7% of American companies because their development can be time-consuming and \
potentially costly, given that they need to be tailored to the specific work behaviors of the \
position. \
\
B. INTERVIEWS \
\
Interviews have the worst criterion-related validity (.10 -. 19). They are better if structured, \
if there are multiple interviewers, and if interviewers are trained. When unstructured, there \
is a high degree of disagreement among interviewers. Furthermore, there are significant \
difficulties with predictive accuracy. \
\
Interviewer biases include first impression, negative information, the contrast effect, \
interviewer prejudices, and the halo effect. \
\
\
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
>FIRST IMPRESSION First impression bias refers to the tendency of the interviewer \
to be swayed by an initial impression of the candidate and to overlook the candidate's \
presentation throughout the remainder of the interview. \
\
>NEGATIVE INFORMATION   Negative information bias refers to the tendency for \
one or two negative items to cause the interviewer to overlook strengths or \
accomplishments. \
\
>THE CONTRAST EFFECT The contrast effect occurs when an interviewer's ratings \
of a candidate are affected by the performance of the previous candidate (e.g., a mediocre \
candidate gets rated more highly because the previous candidate was extremely poor). \
\
>INTERVIEWER PREJUDICES Interviewer prejudices include the personal likes, \
dislikes, and beliefs of the interviewer that bias his or her view of the candidate. \
\
>THE HALO EFFECT The halo effect involves generalizing from one characteristic to \
the entire candidate in either a positive or negative direction. A commonly occurring halo \
effect relates to attractiveness, in that attractive individuals are frequently seen as \
competent, effective, and trustworthy, while unattractive individuals are ascribed with \
many negative qualities. \
\
C. TESTS \
\
>COGNITIVE ABILITY TESTS Tests of cognitive ability (e.g., the Wonderlic \
Personnel Test) and aptitude (e.g., typing tests) are very commonly used and tend to be \
quite good predictors of job success. However, one problem with such tests is that they \
may result in discrimination (see section above on Griggs vs. Duke Power Company). \
\
>PERSONALITY TESTS Personality tests are poor predictors of job performance. \
\
>INTEREST TESTS Interest tests (e.g., Holland's Self-Directed Search) are poor \
predictors of job success but they do correlate with job satisfaction. \
\
>WORK SAMPLE TESTS On work sample tests, candidates demonstrate sample work \
behavior. For example, an applicant for a secretarial position is asked to type a memo, or \
someone wanting to work as a chef at McDonald's cooks a burger. Work samples have \
both high content and criterion-related validity, and, in comparison with other types of \
testing, they tend to be more valid for minorities. \
\
\
 \
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
>TEST BATTERIES Test batteries are almost exclusively used in upper management \
and are good predictors of job performance. \
\
D. ASSESSMENT CENTERS \
\
The Assessment Center is a method of selection that places new job applicants and \
candidates for promotion in a simulated job situation so that their behaviors under stress \
can be observed or evaluated. This approach, also called situational testing, was first used \
by the German army in the 1920s. This approach involves work samples. Assessment \
centers have very good criterion-related validity. \
\
Assessment centers usually involve six to twelve candidates at a time, evaluated as they \
work through a series of exercises over several days. Candidates are interviewed \
extensively. They may be given intelligence and personality tests, but most of the time is \
devoted to exercises that simulate the actual problems of high-level work. The major \
techniques include the in-basket technique and leaderless group discussion. \
\
>THE IN-BASKET TECHNIQUE The in-basket technique presents applicants with \
typical problems and questions that managers would expect to find when they return from \
a vacation. Applicants process this information in a fixed period of time, and after the \
exercise they may be required to justify their decisions. \
\
>THE LEADERLESS GROUP DISCUSSION   In the leaderless group discussion, \
applicants meet as a group to discuss an actual business problem. As the candidates interact \
with each other, their leadership qualities and communication styles are observed. \
\
E. REFERENCES AND LETTERS OF RECOMMENDATION \
\
References and letters of recommendation are often misleading because candidates tend to \
seek them from those who will give them favorable reviews. \
\
\
