F. SELECTION PROCEDURES \
\
Often, many sources of information are included in the selection process. For example, \
college admissions offices often consider high school GPA, SAT scores, interviews, and \
letters of reference. There are three different techniques that can be used to make decisions \
based on multiple criteria. \
\
>MULTIPLE REGRESSION APPROACH This approach is a compensatory \
technique, in which low scores on one predictor can be compensated for by high scores on \
another predictor. For example, an applicant with a low GPA (e.g., 2.5) may still be \
considered for admission if the SAT scores are very high (e.g., over 1400) and the interview \
went well. This approach requires computing a multiple regression equation (see Statistics \
section). \
\
>MULTIPLE CUTOFF This approach is noncompensatory. Here, only applicants who \
meet or exceed the cutoff on each of the predictors will be considered. For example, the \
college will only consider applicants with a GPA of at least 3.0, an SAT score of at least \
1400, and a successful interview. If the GPA is 2.9, it doesn't matter how high the SAT \
score is; that applicant will not be considered. \
\
>MULTIPLE HURDLE This approach is also noncompensatory. The predictors are \
applied in a particular order, and an applicant must pass the cutoff score on the first \
predictor in order to continue in the selection process. For example, only applicants with \
GPAs above 3.0 continue on to have their SAT scores analyzed. Then, only applicants with \
SAT scores above 1400 are granted an interview. This technique is efficient because all \
applicants are given the inexpensive selection techniques (i.e., GPA and SAT scores are \
analyzed), while only a few are given the more expensive technique (i.e., the interview). \
\
II. PERFORMANCE \
\
Performance is believed to be a function of ability, motivation, and opportunity. \
\
Ability refers to innate capacities as well as individual attributes (e.g., gender). Researchers \
have found no differences in overall abilities between men and women. However, women \
tend to have lower expectations of success. \
\
Motivation is reflected by the person's willingness to perform and can be measured by \
work effort. \
\
\
 \
\
