\
Opportunity is thought to be related to environmental variables, including organizational \
support. \
\
A. PERFORMANCE APPRAISALS \
\
Performance appraisals are useful for a variety of tasks, including: decisions about salary, \
promotion, and bonus; identification of employees' strengths and weaknesses; provision \
of feedback to employees; validation of selection criteria; and determination of training \
requirements. \
\
Performance appraisals can be objective, subjective, or focused on results rather than merit \
(e.g., MBO). \
\
A1. OBJECTIVE METHODS \
\
Objective methods of performance evaluation include easily observable and quantifiable \
categories, such as quantity of output, quality of output (number of errors), accidents, \
absenteeism, etc. \
\
A2. SUBJECTIVE METHODS \
\
Subjective methods of evaluation include ratings by supervisors, peers, subordinates, or \
even self-ratings. Ratings can be either comparative (one employee's performance is \
compared with other employees'), or individual/absolute. \
\
>COMPARATIVE METHODS \
\
     STRAIGHT RANKINGS Straight rankings involve listing workers from best to \
     worst. \
\
     FORCED DISTRIBUTION In a forced distribution, people are ranked to fit a \
     distribution, e.g., a few at the top and bottom with most in the middle. \
\
     PAIRED COMPARISON In the paired comparison method, each employee is \
     compared to every other employee in pairs. \
\
\
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
>INDIVIDUAL (ABSOLUTE) METHODS \
\
     GRAPHIC RATING SCALES Graphic rating scales involve ratings on several \
    aspects of a job. For example, a variety of job dimensions (such as work quantity, \
     punctuality, etc.) are assessed on a likert scale. \
\
     BARS (BEHAVIORALLY ANCHORED RATING SCALES)    In BARS, \
     behavioral anchors are based on critical incidents. For example, employees are \
     rated on various aspects of the job, aspects that have been linked to successful job \
     performance. Problems associated with BARS include that scale development is \
     expensive and time-consuming, and that these scales do not tend to measure actual \
     day-to-day activities, but rather hypothetical situations. \
\
     BOS (BEHAVIORAL OBSERVATION SCALE) BOS involves rating the \
     extent to which a person engages in every behavior (e.g., how often the employee \
     finishes projects on time). \
\
     FORCED CHOICE In the forced choice method, the rater must choose between \
    two seemingly equally desirable or undesirable choices (e.g., is reliable/is \
     agreeable, or is headstrong/is slow). This method controls for the halo effect, as \
     well as biases due to leniency and strictness. \
\
     BEHAVIORAL CHECKLIST A rater using a behavioral checklist checks off \
     all the adjectives or descriptors that apply to the employee being rated. \
\
A3. MANAGEMENT BY OBJECTIVES (MBO) \
\
MBO involves a mutual agreement between employees and supervisors on goals to be \
achieved in a given time. This process actively involves employees in their own \
evaluations. MBO consists of two phases: goal setting and performance review. MBO has \
been found to be effective in increasing motivation and productivity, with a meta-analysis \
showing an average gain of 44.6% (Rodgers & Hunter, 1991). \
\
\
