B. ERRORS IN EVALUATION \
\
Although errors in evaluation come from both instrument errors and rater errors, rater \
errors account for the more significant problem. \
\
B1. INSTRUMENT ERRORS \
\
Instrument errors include deficiency errors and contamination errors. \
\
     DEFICIENCY ERRORS Deficiency errors involve excluding important aspects \
     of the job from evaluations. \
\
     CONTAMINATION ERRORS     Contamination errors refer to rating an \
     employee on non-important aspects of the job. \
\
B2. RATER ERRORS \
\
Rater errors include task-based rater biases and ratee-based biases. \
\
>TASK-BASED RATER BIASES These types of errors occur when the rater adopts an \
evaluative set based on the task. Examples include strictness set, leniency set, and central \
tendency set. \
\
     STRICTNESS SET With a strictness set, the rater is overly strict and gives \
     everyone low ratings. \
\
     LENIENCY SET With a leniency set, the rater is overly lenient and gives \
     everyone high ratings. \
\
     CENTRAL TENDENCY SET With a central tendency set, the rater tends to rate \
     everyone as about average. \
\
>RATEE-BASED BIASES Ratee-based biases include the halo error and personal \
biases. \
\
     THE HALO ERROR The halo error occurs when the employee's performance \
     rating is based on one positive or negative aspect of the individual, e.g., style of \
     dress. \
\
\
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
     PERSONAL BIASES   Personal biases, such as prejudices against certain \
     ethnicities, can influence the evaluation of employees. These biases are particularly \
     significant since EEOC guidelines apply not only to issues of hiring but also to \
     promotions, layoffs, and many of the decisions that stem from employee \
     evaluations. \
\
     Some research found that supervisors tend to rate persons of their own race more \
     favorably (Schmitt and Lappin, 1980). In contrast, another study found that both \
     Black and White raters gave lower performance appraisals to black workers than to \
     White workers (Sackett and DuBois, 1991). Sex biases in appraisal also occur, with \
     one study finding that women's ratings were lower when they constituted less than \
     20% of a work group, but higher when they constituted more than 50% of the work \
     group. Finally, age biases occur too, with older workers tending to be rated lower \
     on interpersonal skills and overall job performance. \
\
>OTHER SOURCES OF ERROR \
\
     RECENCY BIASES The recency bias refers to the tendency of an evaluator to be \
    most influenced by an employee's recent behaviors (e.g., evaluates the employee \
     only on the behavior of the last month even though it's a yearly evaluation). \
\
     ATTRIBUTION ERRORS Attribution errors refer to the tendency of supervisors \
     to attribute poor performance to internal factors for workers they don't like, and to \
     external factors for workers they do like. \
\
     OTHER Another source of error is that supervisors tend to rate employees higher \
     when the supervisor participated in the hiring decision. \
\
>STRATEGIES TO IMPROVE RATINGS   Strategies to improve ratings include \
training raters with the instruments to be used, using multiple raters, having raters rate on \
an ongoing basis rather than once or twice a year, and basing performance on clear and \
specific performance standards obtained through a job analysis. \
\
Frame of reference (FOR) training is a particularly successful strategy for reducing rater \
error. In FOR training, raters are provided with clear and specific criteria (i.e., references) \
for what constitutes the different levels of performance (e.g., outstanding, good, average, \
etc.). An example may also be provided for each level. In this manner, all the raters acquire \
a common understanding of what constitutes acceptable or unacceptable performance on \
each job dimension. \
\
\
