III. TRAINING AND DEVELOPMENT \
\
This section describes different types of training approaches, as well as the most significant \
factors that affect training. \
\
A. TYPES OF TRAINING \
\
Training can be provided on the job, on-site, or off the job. The most common types of \
instructional methods include non-participative training, individual participative training. \
and group participative training. \
\
>NON-PARTICIPATIVE TRAINING In non-participative training, the trainee is a \
passive recipient. Examples include watching a training video or listening to a lecture. \
\
>INDIVIDUAL PARTICIPATIVE TRAINING \
\
     PROGRAMMED INSTRUCTION     Programmed instruction makes use of \
     booklets, interactive videotapes, and complex computer software. It involves \
     graduated presentation of material with feedback at each step. The training \
     approach commonly involves self-instruction. Examples include programmed \
     instructions for bank tellers, tax analysts, and insurance salespeople. Programmed \
     instruction is usually restricted to programs that attempt to train a large number of \
    trainees in a short period of time. \
\
     COMPUTER   ASSISTED INSTRUCTION (CAI)   Computer assisted \
    instruction, sometimes called computer based training (CBT), is a derivative of \
    programmed instruction. The instruction is computer based. An example is \
    programs available that teach computer literacy on the computer. \
\
     SIMULATION TRAINING Simulation training, also called vestibule training, \
    involves training in an environment that simulates the actual job. For example, \
     pilots are initially trained in simulated cockpits. Simulation training is costly, but \
    used when necessary. \
\
     JOB ROTATION Job rotation involves exposing trainees (usually managers) to \
     different jobs and departments to acquaint them with all facets of the organization. \
    This is typical of Japanese companies. \
\
\
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
>GROUP PARTICIPATIVE TRAINING   Group participative training includes \
discussion, role-playing, business games, sensitivity training, in-basket training, and \
behavioral modeling. \
\
B. PSYCHOLOGICAL FACTORS AFFECTING TRAINING \
\
>INDIVIDUAL DIFFERENCES Individual differences in ability to be trained can be \
predicted through cognitive tests, biographical data, attitude measures, and work samples. \
Overall, training does not always equalize differences in ability; it may actually magnify \
them. \
\
>PRE-TRAINING EXPECTATIONS The expectations of the individuals being trained \
also affect training success. Individuals with a low sense of self-efficacy are less receptive \
than those with a high sense of self-efficacy. \
\
>MOTIVATION   Trainees with higher levels of motivation learn more and are more \
likely to complete programs. Trainees' motivation can be increased by involving them in \
decisions about the training program, allowing them to participate in a needs assessment, \
and giving them a choice of training courses. Motivation is affected by one's sense of job \
involvement and by locus of control. \
\
>ACTIVE VERSUS PASSIVE PRACTICE Trainees learn the most when they are \
actively involved in the process. \
\
>MASSED VERSUS DISTRIBUTED (SPACED) PRACTICE   Massed practice \
involves providing all the training in a short time period (e.g., in one day), while spaced \
practice refers to training conducted over several sessions. In general, spaced practice is \
better for learning. \
\
>WHOLE AND PART LEARNING Whole learning describes presenting the material \
all at once, while part learning involves presenting the material in smaller units. Slower \
learners may be better able to master new material when it is presented in smaller units. \
\
>TRANSFER OF TRAINING Transfer of training refers to the application of the \
training material to the work setting. Two strategies to enhance transfer of training include \
overlearning and identical elements. The goal of overlearning is to develop very thorough \
knowledge of a task. It is particularly useful for tasks that are infrequently performed, as \
well as for those performed under conditions of stress. Identical elements refer to \
