IV. CAREER DEVELOPMENT THEORIES \
\
Career development theories are broadly grouped into two categories: structural and \
developmental. Structural theories focus on individual traits and occupational tasks (e.g., \
Holland's theory), while developmental theories focus on development across the life span \
(e.g., Super's theory). \
\
A. HOLLAND'S PERSONALITY-JOB FIT THEORY \
\
The major assumption of John Holland's theory is that individuals and job traits can be \
matched, and that close matches will correlate with job success and satisfaction. Holland's \
formula for successful career planning involves knowing one's self (abilities, interests and \
occupational choices), and having information about the world of work (occupational \
profiles, job descriptions, and traits that exist within given occupational roles). \
\
A1. HOLLAND'S TYPOLOGY \
\
Holland classified both personality types as well as work environments into six types, \
which he labeled realistic, investigative, artistic, social, enterprising and conventional \
(RIASEC). On Holland's Self-Directed Search, each person receives a code with the letters \
that represent his or her personality (e.g., RI standing for realistic and investigative). A \
person can receive up to three letter codes, with the first letter representing the dominant \
personality type. \
\
>REALISTIC The realistic type prefers physical activities that require skill, strength and \
coordination. Jobs in this domain include mechanic, drill press operator, or farmer. \
\
\
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
>INVESTIGATIVE The investigative type prefers activities that involve thinking. \
organizing, and understanding. Jobs in this category include biologist, economist or news \
reporter. \
\
>ARTISTIC The artistic type prefers ambiguous and unsystematic activities that allow \
creative expression. Jobs in this domain include painter, musician, or writer. \
\
>SOCIAL The social type prefers activities that involve helping and developing others. \
Jobs in this domain include social worker, teacher, and clinical psychologist. \
\
>ENTERPRISING The enterprising type prefers activities with opportunity to influence \
others and obtain power. Jobs in this category include lawyer, real estate agent, or small \
business manager. \
\
>CONVENTIONAL   The conventional type prefers rule-regulated, orderly, and \
unambiguous activities. Jobs in this domain include accountant, bank teller, or file clerk. \
\
These themes can be organized in the shape of a hexagon. Adjacent themes are most \
similar, while those directly across are most dissimilar. \
\
A2. KEY CONCEPTS \
\
Holland developed several other concepts that pertain to the hexagon. \
\
>CONGRUENCE Congruence refers to the degree of match between the personality type \
and the work environment. The closer the work environment and the personality type are \
on the hexagon, the higher the degree of congruence. For example, someone with an artistic \
personality working as an artist would have a high degree of congruence. Someone with \
an artistic personality working as a drill press operator would have low congruence. A high \
level of congruence correlates with longevity at the job. \
\
>CONSISTENCY Consistency refers to how closely related an individual's first two code \
letters are on the hexagon. For example, the code AS (artistic, social) would have a high \
degree of consistency because the code letters are next to each other on the hexagon. In \
contrast, the code IE (investigative, enterprising) would have low consistency because the \
two code letters are opposite each other on the hexagon. The higher the consistency of an \
individual's code, the more likely the person will exhibit stability in work history. \
\
\
 \
\
                              Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Human Resources \
\
>DIFFERENTIATION Differentiation refers to the distinctness of a profile. The more \
an individual is represented by one personality type, the more distinct the profile is. An \
individual who resembles all six types would have an undifferentiated profile. It is easiest \
to predict the behavior of individuals with highly differentiated profiles. \
\
>ENVIRONMENTAL IDENTITY Environmental identity refers to an individual's view \
that the work environment has a clear and stable system of goals and rewards. \
\
>VOCATIONAL IDENTITY Vocational identity refers to the clarity and stability of an \
individual's own goals and interests. Individuals with high vocational identity make \
decisions more easily and with greater confidence. \
\
B. SUPER'S LIFE/CAREER RAINBOW \
\
Donald Super's theory posits that career decision-making involves a range of changes and \
decisions from career entry to retirement. He outlines five major stages of career \
development: growth (to age 13), exploration (14 - 24), establishment (25 - 44), \
maintenance (45 - 64), and decline or disengagement (65+). Incorporated into the idea of \
developmental tasks is the concept of career maturity, the individual's ability to \
effectively master the tasks of a given stage in preparation for moving to the next stage. \
\
Critical to Super's theory is that career patterns are determined by socioeconomic factors, \
individual abilities, personal characteristics, and opportunities to which persons are \
exposed. Career is viewed as a combination of eight life roles: son/daughter, learner, \
worker, spouse/friend, homemaker, parent/grandparent, leisurite, and citizen. Super also \
proposed that individuals express their self-concepts through choice of vocation. \
\
C. KRUMBOLTZ'S SOCIAL LEARNING THEORY \
\
A developmental theory of career decision-making, Krumboltz proposed that career \
development is based on social learning, environmental conditions and events, genetic \
influences and learning experiences. People choose careers based on what they have \
learned through modeling and reinforcement. \
\
\
\
