     4.3 ORGANIZATIONAL PSYCHOLOGY \
\
Areas in organizational psychology include leadership, job motivation and satisfaction, and \
the organization. \
\
I. LEADERSHIP THEORIES AND APPROACHES \
\
The ways in which leaders behave are based on certain assumptions about human nature \
that they consciously or unconsciously hold. \
\
A. SCIENTIFIC MANAGEMENT \
\
In the early 20th century, foremen (first level supervisors over production workers) were \
promoted from the ranks of workers with little training in leadership. They applied a \
combination of autocratic behavior, aggressiveness, and physical intimidation to force \
workers to produce. The predominant philosophy was that of scientific management, \
espoused by Frederick Taylor, an engineer. His concern was with finding ways to increase \
productivity, i.e., getting the workers and the machines they operated to run faster and more \
efficiently. Scientific management views workers as extensions of machines. Little \
consideration is given to employees as human beings with needs, abilities or interests. \
Workers are considered to be lazy and dishonest, with low levels of intelligence. \
\
B. HUMAN RELATIONS APPROACH \
\
Today's predominant viewpoint is called the human relations approach to management. It \
arose in the 1920s and 1930s under the impact of the Hawthorne studies, which focused \
attention on workers rather than production. \
\
The Hawthorne studies initially set out to study the effects of environmental factors (e.g., \
illumination, temperature, and rest periods) on productivity. In the Hawthorne studies, the \
leaders allowed workers to set their own production pace, and to form social groups. They \
were permitted to talk on the job and their views were solicited. \
\
The results were rather surprising and indicated that psychological factors seemed more \
important in terms of increasing productivity than the physical aspects of the work \
environment. In fact, productivity was increased not because of the changes in the work \
\
\
\
