\
environment, but simply because the workers were being observed. This is known as the \
Hawthorne effect. \
\
The Hawthorne studies also revealed the importance of informal work groups. Although \
management had set a standard for production for these workers, the workers developed \
their own standards, and were reluctant to change them for fear of deviating from the group. \
In addition, the workers considered adhering to the group's norms even more important \
than the extra pay they would have earned for exceeding company standards. \
\
C. THEORY X, THEORY Y AND THEORY Z \
\
McGregor (1960) named the scientific management approach and the human relations \
approach Theory X and Theory Y, respectively. \
\
>THEORY X   Theory X assumes workers are lazy and must be coerced and directed \
since they have no ambition and no sense of responsibility. Theory X underlies typical \
bureaucracies. \
\
>THEORY Y Theory Y assumes that people find satisfaction in their work and that \
control and punishment are not necessary to bring about good performance. Rather, Theory \
Y proposes that people are industrious and creative, seeking challenge and responsibility. \
They function best under a leadership style that is participative. \
\
>THEORY Z Theory Z, described in Ouchi's 1981 book, How American Business Can \
Meet the Japanese Challenge, highlights three critical Japanese management strategies: \
lifelong employment with an emphasis on loyalty, slow promotion with an emphasis on \
non-specialized career paths, and high levels of group decision-making. \
\
D. TRAIT THEORIES OF LEADERSHIP \
\
Trait theories were the initial approach used when studying leadership. They are based on \
the assumption that there is a universal set of traits that can always distinguish good leaders \
from poor leaders, regardless of the situation. However, more than 50 years of research has \
produced limited and inconsistent support for this approach. Meta-analyses have found that \
those characteristics that discriminate between effective and ineffective leaders include \
drive, leader motivation (desire to be a leader rather than power for its own sake), honesty \
and integrity, self-confidence and emotional stability, high cognitive ability, and \
knowledge of the company and industry. \
\
\
 \
\
                          Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Organizational Psychology \
\
Trait approaches have also been used to compare authoritarian, democratic, and laissez- \
faire leaders. An authoritarian leader is one who delegates to employees in an autocratic \
fashion, while a democratic leader is one who seeks employee input in various aspects of \
the organization. A laissez-faire leader is generally not very involved in overseeing the \
operations of the organization and often lets the employees make the decisions. \
\
In terms of satisfaction, democratic leaders are consistently associated with the greatest \
levels of employee satisfaction. In terms of productivity, the findings with democratic \
leaders are mixed, but both authoritarian and democratic leaders appear to have better \
productivity than laissez faire leaders. \
\
E. SITUATIONAL OR CONTINGENCY THEORIES OF \
LEADERSHIP \
\
Situational theories are the focus of much recent research on leadership. These approaches \
broadly argue that the effectiveness of leadership is contingent upon the situation. The most \
prominent situational theories are Fiedler's Contingency (LPC) Theory, Cognitive \
Resource Theory, Vroom and Yetton's Normative Model, House's Path-Goal Theory, and \
Hersey and Blanchard's Situational Leadership Theory. \
\
>FIEDLER'S CONTINGENCY (LPC) THEORY LPC Theory (1967) involves three \
steps. First, it looks at whether the leader (supervisor) is a task-oriented or relationship- \
oriented leader. The least preferred colleague (LPC) is the subordinate whom the leader \
likes the least. \
\
     HIGH LPC If the leader rates his or her least preferred coworker with a high \
     rating, the leader is termed a high LPC leader and is considered to be relationship \
     oriented. \
     LOW LPC If the leader rates the least preferred coworker with a poor rating, the \
     leader is considered to be a low LPC leader and is thought to be task oriented. \
\
Second, the situational control, or favorableness, is assessed. Situational control has to do \
with how likely it is that the task will be accomplished. The likelihood is affected by how \
easy or difficult the task is, how powerful the leader is, and the relationship between the \
leader and the subordinates. \
\
Finally, LPC Theory predicts that low LPCs are most effective as leaders in situations that \
are either highly favorable or unfavorable, while high LPCs are most effective as leaders \
in moderately favorable situations. \
\
\
\
                          Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Organizational Psychology \
\
>COGNITIVE RESOURCE THEORY     Cognitive Resource Theory (Fiedler and \
Garcia, 1987) was developed by Fiedler in response to criticism of his original LPC \
Theory. Cognitive Resource Theory looks at whether a directive versus non-directive \
leadership style will be more effective depending on the cognitive resources (ability) of the \
employees as well as stress levels, experience of the leader, and group support for the \
leader. \
\
>VROOM AND YETTON'S NORMATIVE MODEL Vroom and Yetton's Normative \
Model (1973) focuses on a single aspect of leadership decision-making. The theory is \
concerned with the extent to which leaders allow their subordinates to participate in making \
decisions. \
\
It looks at five styles of leadership: autocratic, consultative, group decision-making with \
the leader, group decision-making without the leader, and autocratic with information. \
According to this model, the most effective style depends on the importance of the \
decision, the degree to which subordinates accept it, and the time required to make the \
decision. \
\
>HOUSE'S PATH-GOAL THEORY   Path-Goal Theory (1971) recommends that the \
leader increase personal payoffs for subordinates and make the paths to the payoffs easier \
by clarifying and reducing roadblocks. The focus is on finding out what each employee \
finds rewarding, assessing the employee's strengths and weaknesses, and helping the \
employee to achieve his or her goals. The four types of leadership styles include directive, \
supportive, achievement oriented, and participative. \
\
>HERSEY AND BLANCHARD'S SITUATIONAL LEADERSHIP This theory looks \
at the employees' readiness to perform. If they are not ready, the leader should tell them \
what to do; if they are more ready, they need less task orientation from the leader. The four \
styles, corresponding to degrees of readiness, are telling, selling, participating, and \
delegating. \
\
F. TRANSACTIONAL AND TRANSFORMATIONAL LEADERS \
\
Bernard Bass distinguished between transactional and transformational leaders. \
\
>TRANSACTIONAL LEADERS A transactional leader is the more traditional leader \
who influences subordinates through daily, fairly emotionless exchanges. The transactional \
leader aims to secure the agreed upon level of performance from the subordinates and may \
make use of rewards, management by objectives, and other conventional means. \
\
\
 \
\
                          Section 4 - Industrial/Organizational: Organizational Psychology \
\
>TRANSFORMATIONAL LEADERS In contrast, the transformational leader aims to \
broaden and elevate the goals of the subordinates. Transformational leaders utilize \
charisma, inspiration, intellectual stimulation, and individualized consideration. \
\
G. LEADERSHIP AND POWER \
\
Psychologists have proposed that there are five types of power involved in a worker's \
willingness to comply with the request of a leader. \
\
>REWARD POWER    Reward power is power based on the ability to provide rewards \
(e.g., offering bonuses for excellent performance). \
\
>COERCIVE POWER   Coercive power is related to the ability to punish (e.g., fire an \
employee for poor performance). \
\
>LEGITIMATE POWER     Legitimate power is based on the hierarchy of the \
organization (e.g., the power that comes from being in a supervisory position). \
\
>REFERENT POWER Referent power is based on identifying with, admiring, or liking \
the person in the leadership position. \
\
>EXPERT POWER Expert power comes from having expertise and skills in the relevant \
area. \
\
The first three types of power are based on position power, while the last two are based on \
personal power. Research suggests that the presence of the combination of expert and \
referent power (sometimes called incremental power) is the most important reason for \
complying with a manager's request (Yukl & Falbe, 1991). Coercive power is most \
negatively correlated with satisfaction. \
\
H. DECISION-MAKING \
\
Two approaches to decision-making are frequently cited: the rational-economic model and \
the administrative approach. \
\
>RATIONAL-ECONOMIC MODEL The rational-economic model, also referred to as \
the classical approach, involves basing decisions on a clear definition of the problem, \
\
\
\
