\
knowing all possible alternatives and consequences of choices, and then choosing the \
optimal solution. \
\
>ADMINISTRATIVE APPROACH    By contrast, the behavioral or administrative \
approach, also referred to as a satisficing style, is associated with Herbert Simon. This \
approach is used when problems are ambiguous, only partial knowledge is available, and \
the first satisfactory alternative is chosen. \
\
I. CONFLICT \
\
Conflict can be intrapersonal, interpersonal, intergroup, or interorganization. Conflict \
resolution can utilize a lose-lose approach typical with compromise, a win-lose approach \
common with competition or authority, or a win-win approach typical in collaborative and \
problem-solving situations. \
\
J. NEGOTIATION \
\
Negotiation can be two-party, group, intergroup, or among constituencies (e.g .. \
management versus labor). Distributive negotiation involves parties claiming part of the \
pie, while integrative/principled negotiation involves attempting to enlarge the pie. \
Arbitration involves a third party who acts as "judge" and issues a binding decision after \
listening to both parties. \
\
II. THEORIES OF MOTIVATION \
\
Theories of motivation can be divided into need or content theories, cognitive or process \
theories, and the reinforcement model. \
\
A. NEED THEORIES OF MOTIVATION \
\
>MASLOW'S NEED HIERARCHY In Maslow's theory, human needs are arranged in \
a hierarchy of importance and people always want what they don't yet have. The five levels \
from lowest to highest are: physiological, safety, belonging and love (social), esteem, and \
self-actualization. At work, belonging needs can be satisfied through developing a social \
network, esteem needs can be satisfied by praise, and self-actualization needs can be \
satisfied by giving employees opportunities for growth and responsibility. This theory has \
received little research support and is judged to have low scientific validity and \
applicability in the workplace. \
\
\
