\
>HERZBERG'S TWO-FACTOR THEORY     Herzberg's Two-Factor Theory, also \
known as Motivator-Hygiene Theory (1966) extends the work of Maslow. It originated \
from research in which Herzberg asked employees, "Tell me a time you felt good about \
your job," and "Tell me a time you felt bad about your job." He found that different factors \
accounted for job satisfaction as opposed to job dissatisfaction. This theory divides needs \
into upper-level and lower-level needs. \
\
     LOWER-LEVEL NEEDS   Lower-level needs, also called hygiene factors or \
     dissatisfies, relate to job context, such as pay, working conditions, supervision, etc. \
     Dissatisfaction results when lower level needs are not met, but meeting them does \
     not produce satisfaction. \
\
     UPPER-LEVEL NEEDS   Upper-level needs, called motivators or satisfiers, \
     relate to job content and include needs for achievement, responsibility, and \
     opportunity. Meeting upper level needs can increase satisfaction and motivation. \
     However, when these needs are not met, dissatisfaction does not result. \
\
Out of Herzberg's work came the concepts of job enrichment and job enlargement. \
\
     JOB ENRICHMENT Job enrichment involves expanding jobs to give employees \
     a greater role in planning and performing their work, thus providing an opportunity \
     to build satisfiers into job content. Herzberg suggested increasing employees" \
     autonomy, authority and freedom, and encouraging employees to take on new. \
     challenging tasks. Job enrichment results in increased satisfaction and performance, \
     decreased turnover and decreased absenteeism. It is also known as "vertical \
     loading." \
\
     JOB ENLARGEMENT Job enlargement simply expands the variety of tasks the \
     employee performs without increasing responsibility or autonomy. Job \
     enlargement increases satisfaction, and only slightly affects job performance. It is \
     also known as "horizontal loading." \
\
>ALDERFER'S ERG THEORY   A modification of Maslow's theory, ERG Theory \
(1972) divides needs into those based on existence, relatedness and growth. Rather than \
arranging the needs hierarchically, Alderfer posits that all needs may influence a person at \
the same time. Further, according to the principle of frustration-regression, if a person is \
frustrated, he or she will move towards a previously met need. In contrast to Maslow, \
satisfying a need (e.g., for creativity) may make the need even stronger. This theory has \
greater empirical support than Maslow. Research has found that people with more educated \
