     VALENCE Valence refers to the value the rewards have for the employees. Third, \
     employees determine how much they value the offered rewards. \
\
>ADAMS'S EQUITY THEORY    Equity Theory (1965) looks at the ratio of self- \
inputs/self-outcomes versus others' inputs/others' outcomes. This theory is based on social \
comparison theory. Adams believes that inequity is a motivating state and that we adjust \
our performance based on things appearing fair or unfair. \
\
>LOCKE'S GOAL SETTING APPROACH Locke's Goal Setting Approach (1968) is \
based on five principles: 1) goals should be specific; 2) goals should be of intermediate to \
high level of difficulty; 3) workers must receive feedback; 4) a sense of self-efficacy will \
increase performance (linked with expectancy theory); and most important 5) employees \
must accept the goals. While participation in goal setting may sometimes yield better \
results than if goals are assigned, the determining factor is whether or not employees accept \
the goals. \
\
C. REINFORCEMENT AND MOTIVATION \
\
The reinforcement model is a set of principles, according to which people perform actions \
that have rewarding outcomes, avoid actions that have punishing outcomes, and stop \
performing actions that have neither rewarding nor punishing outcomes. Research in this \
area has found that performance-contingent rewards are strongly correlated with both \
performance and satisfaction. In contrast, non-performance contingent rewards and \
punishment are not strongly linked with performance and satisfaction. \
\
III. JOB SATISFACTION AND OTHER VARIABLES \
\
Job satisfaction refers to the positive and negative feelings and attitudes we hold about our \
jobs. It depends on work-related factors as well as personal factors. Up to 30% - 40% of \
job satisfaction may be linked to genetic factors. \
\
The relationship between pay and satisfaction is among the most complex. For example, \
according to Maslow's theory, pay could be seen as meeting physiological or safety needs. \
but in some instances, it could also be seen as meeting esteem needs. McClelland sees pay \
as fulfilling different functions for individuals with different needs: as an important source \
of feedback for persons with high nAch; as a source of control for those with a high \
nPower; and, if the money comes in the form of group bonuses, as a source of affiliation \
for those with high nAff. Herzberg notes that adequate salary might meet lower level needs \
