IV. ORGANIZATIONAL ISSUES \
\
A. ORGANIZATIONAL STRUCTURES \
\
There are four common organizational structures. \
\
>TRADITIONAL Traditional, also known as hierarchical, is the typical bureaucracy. \
\
>PROJECT Project is centered on specific products or services. For example, a hospital \
may be structured around "product lines" (e.g., emergency medicine, surgery, and \
education), rather than structured by disciplines (e.g., physicians, nurses, support staff). \
\
>TEAM Team is centered on work teams or groups that report to upper level managers. \
\
>MULTIDIMENSIONAL Multidimensional involves more than one type of structure \
(e.g., both traditional and team). \
\
Overall, the trend is movement away from traditional organizational structures and toward \
multidimensional structures. Rather than centralizing power in a small upper echelon of \
executives, the trend is toward broadly sharing authority and decision-making. \
\
B. PARTICIPATIVE ORGANIZATIONAL STYLE \
\
The participative organizational style rests on three assumptions (Lawler, 1986). The first \
assumption is human relations, or the idea that people want to participate. When people are \
allowed to participate in decision-making, they will accept change more easily, and will be \
more satisfied and committed to the organization. The second assumption is human \
resources, or the notion that people are a valuable resource because they have knowledge \
and ideas. When employees participate in decisions, the result is better solutions. The third \
