assumption is high involvement, the idea that people can be trusted to develop knowledge \
and skills in order to make important decisions about management and their work. \
\
>QUALITY-OF-WORK-LIFE PROGRAMS (QWL) QWL programs target changes \
in organizational style in various ways. They are participative programs intended to \
improve the quality of working life. Workers are involved in teams that meet weekly to \
discuss problems in their areas of responsibility, including extrinsic factors (e.g., physical \
working conditions), and intrinsic factors (e.g., employee involvement and satisfaction). \
QWL programs have been found to have a greater effect on satisfaction than performance. \
\
>QUALITY CONTROL CIRCLES (QCC) Based on the work of Maslow, McClelland \
and Herzberg, QCCs are not concerned with the quality of work life but with specific ways \
to improve the finished product and the level of production. While they may enhance \
satisfaction, the goal is improved quantity and quality of production (which fits in with the \
agendas of total quality management and continuous improvement). \
\
The key principles of QCCs are that workers must be given greater responsibility for their \
work and must be allowed to participate in decisions affecting the nature of the work and \
the way it is performed. A quality control circle consists of 7-10 employees from the same \
department. QCCs typically affect only the organizational unit, not the organization as a \
whole. Membership is voluntary and usually only a small percentage of workers agrees to \
join. Companies with quality control circles report increases in production and satisfaction \
and decreases in absenteeism and turnover. \
\
C. ORGANIZATIONAL DEVELOPMENT AND CULTURE \
\
>ORGANIZATIONAL DEVELOPMENT Organizations are faced with the challenge \
of engaging in continuous self-assessment and planned change. Organizational \
development (OD) focuses on total organizational change and on systematic ways to bring \
about planned changes. The goal is to assist the organization to adapt to a changing work \
environment, to improve its ability to respond to future changes, and to help employees \
develop a new sense of purpose for their organization. OD is an application of behavioral \
science knowledge in a long-range effort to increase the organization's ability to cope with \
change in the external environment and to increase internal problem solving. \
\
OD takes a systems approach to organizational problems. Outside consultants evaluate \
strengths and weaknesses and develop strategies for change. Implementation begins with \
top management and needs management's support. Process goals include communication, \
interaction, and decision-making. Outcome goals involve increasing task performance. \
\
