customs, and behaviors of the organization. An analysis of more than 2,000 companies \
found that those with a culture of high involvement and high participation consistently \
outperformed those that didn't favor involvement and participation (Denison, 1990). \
\
D. COMMUNICATION \
\
There are two basic types of communication networks, those that are centralized and those \
that are decentralized. \
\
>CENTRALIZED COMMUNICATION NETWORKS      Centralized communication \
networks are like a wheel or chain, with one person in the middle who gets all the \
information. They are best for simple tasks, and result in fairly rapid communication. \
\
>DECENTRALIZED COMMUNICATION NETWORKS Decentralized networks are \
like a pinwheel, an all-channel, or a star, in which all members can communicate with one \
another. They are best for tasks involving problem-solving and communication. However, \
they result in slower communication. \
\
Overall, satisfaction is greatest in less centralized networks. Individual satisfaction is most \
associated with the centrality of one's position. The current trend is toward greater \
decentralization of communication. \
\
E. GROUPS IN ORGANIZATIONS \
\
E1. INFORMAL GROUPS \
\
Informal groups are distinguished from formal groups that receive "official" designation \
by the organization to serve a specific purpose. Informal work groups are the organization \
within the organization and have the power to shape employee attitudes, behavior, and \
