productivity. Workers come together informally to establish and promote a set of norms \
and values. These groups can work for or against the company by encouraging or thwarting \
productivity and cooperation with company policies. An example of the power of informal \
work groups came from the Hawthorne studies where a team of 14 workers was observed. \
The group had determined its own standard, called a performance norm, which was below \
the company's standard. Even though they were capable of producing more, they stayed \
within the group norm. A related effect of informal work groups is social loafing, or the \
Ringelmann effect, according to which people don't work as hard in a group as they do on \
their own. \
\
In general, informal groups tend to attract and retain people with similar personality \
characteristics, and they take on a consistent affective tone. The degree of closeness is \
called group cohesiveness. The greater the cohesiveness, the greater is the group's power \
over its members and the greater the pressure to conform. Factors that influence \
cohesiveness include: group size (larger are less cohesive), diversity (more diverse are less \
cohesive), team rewards (increase cohesiveness), outside pressures and threats (increase \
cohesiveness), difficulty to join the group (increases cohesiveness), and frequent \
interactions (increase cohesiveness). Being a part of a group can increase satisfaction, and \
decrease turnover, absenteeism, and job strain. \
\
Stages of group development include forming, storming (including conflicts over \
leadership), norming (initial integration), performing (total integration), and adjourning. \
\
E2. TYPES OF GROUP TASKS \
\
Many tasks may be difficult to perform without groups. Three basic types of group tasks \
are classified as additive, disjunctive, and conjunctive. \
\
>ADDITIVE TASKS   An additive task is one in which group members' separate \
performances are added to produce a combined effect. For example, a group of scientists \
and engineers combine their talents to construct a space shuttle. \
\
>DISJUNCTIVE TASKS A disjunctive task is one in which the outcome is affected by \
the performance of the most effective group member. For example, a group meets to decide \
how to improve the company's marketing strategy, and one person comes up with an \
outstanding idea. \
\
>CONJUNCTIVE TASKS     A conjunctive task is one in which the group's \
accomplishment is limited by the performance of the least effective member. For example, \
