E3. GROUP DECISION-MAKING \
\
Several important findings have been noted with regard to group decision-making. \
\
>GROUP EFFECTIVENESS Groups make better decisions than individuals when the \
problem has multiple parts that are susceptible to division of labor. Heterogeneous groups \
make better decisions than homogeneous groups. However, there can be problems with \
cohesion in heterogeneous groups. The ideal group size for decision-making and \
effectiveness is either five or seven members. In situations requiring deliberation (e.g., \
juries), an even number is more effective. Groups work best when common goals are more \
important to members than individual goals. \
\
>BRAINSTORMING   Brainstorming is one technique for improving group decision- \
making. Brainstorming appears superior to an open group discussion when the goals \
involve creative thinking. Overall, research suggests that when people brainstorm alone, \
they come up with better solutions than when they brainstorm in a group. \
\
>RISKY SHIFT Risky shift is the tendency for people in groups to make riskier decisions \
than they would if they were deciding as individuals. For example, people making business \
investments individually are more cautious, while people who pool their monies and make \
business investments as a group are much more likely to make riskier investments. Because \
of the tendency to make riskier decisions, groups can be more creative and innovative than \
individuals working alone. \
\
>RESPONSE POLARIZATION     Response polarization, also known as group \
polarization, is the tendency for people in groups to become more extreme in their views. \
For example, if someone opposed to abortion joins a group of like-minded people, he or \
she will probably become more strongly opposed to abortion. \
\
>GROUPTHINK   Groupthink occurs in highly cohesive groups when group members \
seek concurrence, consensus, and unanimity more than they seek the best possible \
alternative. When groupthink occurs, there is a tendency for group members to think alike \
and lose their critical evaluative capacities due to social pressures to conform. A significant \
historical example comes from the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941. Prior to the \
attack, the commander-in-chief of the U.S. Pacific Fleet met with his high-level staff \
members at headquarters in Hawaii to discuss whether they should prepare for a possible \
