II. WORK SCHEDULES \
\
When nominal working hours (hours at the job) increase, actual working hours (hours spent \
getting the work done) decrease. The longer the workday or workweek, the lower the \
productivity. This finding holds true even for highly motivated workers. \
\
>COMPRESSED WORK WEEKS Compressed work weeks (e.g. four ten-hour days) \
are utilized by about 20% of the workforce. They result in decreased anxiety, decreased \
turnover, and increased satisfaction. Drawbacks include fatigue and possible customer \
complaints due to unavailable personnel. The effect on productivity is mixed, and generally \
there appear to be initial positive effects which wear off over time. \
\
>FLEXTIME Flextime allows employees to choose when they start and end their work \
day, provided they work their required number of hours and are available during specific \
core hours set by the company (e.g., 10:00 am - 2:00 pm). Flextime is utilized by about \
40% of the workforce. The findings are mixed, in that some say flextime increases morale \
and productivity and decreases lateness, absenteeism, and turnover (Petersen, 1980), while \
others say there are no differences in productivity or satisfaction. \
\
>REST BREAKS Breaks increase morale and productivity and they reduce fatigue and \
boredom. They have maximum effect if taken during the fourth and eighth hour of work. \
\
>SHIFT WORK    In terms of shift work, most workers prefer day work. There is a \
tendency for increased error and decreased output on the night shift. Afternoon and night \
shifts are frequently more stressful than day shifts. Night shifts are correlated with more \
health problems. Rotating shifts are the most detrimental to health. \
\
III. SAFETY \
\
OSHA (1970) regulates safety and health. Six million work-related accidents occur per \
year, with 10,000 to 14,000 deaths. Workers who are most likely to have on-the-job \
accidents are those who have experienced the highest levels of stress in their lives. Hazards \
in the workplace can be reduced by designing safer equipment and taking more care with \
inherently dangerous substances (e.g., solvents). \
\
Safety education and training programs are most effective when there is practice, feedback, \
and reinforcement. Of all interventions, safety incentive programs work the best to reduce \
occupational accidents. \
