         5.1 INTERVENTIONS BASED ON \
                    BEHAVIORISM \
\
Behaviorists believe that behavior is generated and maintained by factors external to the \
person, by various environmental and situational stimuli. Behaviorists propose that \
psychopathology results from problematic learned patterns. \
\
Behavioral interventions fall into three categories: those based on principles of classical \
conditioning, those based on principles of operant conditioning, and those based on social \
learning theory. \
\
I. TREATMENT APPROACHES BASED ON CLASSICAL \
CONDITIONING \
\
Clinical interventions based on classical conditioning involve unlearning previous \
problematic connections (e.g., connections that have resulted in phobias, anxiety, or \
addictions). Change is accomplished by techniques that rely either on counterconditioning \
or on classical extinction. \
\
A. COUNTERCONDITIONING \
\
Counterconditioning is based on the principle of reciprocal inhibition. Reciprocal \
inhibition is the notion that two incompatible responses cannot be experienced at the same \
time, but rather that the stronger response will inhibit the weaker (e.g., fear will inhibit \
pleasure). \
\
\
\
                                  Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Behaviorism \
\
The focus of treatment is on weakening the maladaptive conditioned response (e.g., fear of \
rats) by strengthening an incompatible or antagonistic response (e.g., relaxation). \
\
Specific interventions based on counterconditioning include systematic desensitization. \
sensate focus, assertiveness training, and aversive counterconditioning. \
\
>SYSTEMATIC DESENSITIZATION    Systematic desensitization is a counter- \
conditioning technique developed by Joseph Wolpe. It has most commonly been used to \
treat specific phobias. Desensitization first involves training the client to relax deeply. The \
client then constructs an "anxiety hierarchy." or a list of situations ranked by how much \
anxiety they produce. The therapist has the client relax while gradually exposing the client \
to the feared situation lowest on the hierarchy. Exposure can occur either in imagination or \
in vivo. Once the client can be exposed to an item without any increase in anxiety or muscle \
tension, the therapist proceeds to the next item on the list. The process continues until the \
situation that originally provoked anxiety now elicits only relaxation, which is an \
antagonistic or incompatible response to fear. \
\
Previous research suggested that systematic desensitization was the most effective \
procedure for specific phobias. However, more recent research has concluded that \
treatments that emphasize prolonged and intense exposure (e.g., flooding) are most \
efficacious for specific phobias. \
\
>SENSATE FOCUS This technique, developed by Masters and Johnson, uses pleasure \
as the counterconditioning response to inhibit performance anxiety. Pleasure is elicited by \
body massages that are discontinued at the first sign of anxiety. Anxiety is also diminished \
by initially requiring the couple to abstain from intercourse. The goal is to eventually \
experience pleasure from intercourse with no anxiety. \
\
Masters and Johnson divide the sexual response cycle into four stages: excitement, plateau, \
orgasm, and resolution. In the excitement phase, arousal is initiated either through physical \
factors (e.g., touching) or psychological factors (fantasy). It is this stage that sensate focus \
is designed to influence. The plateau phase involves further increases in stimulation and \
physiological functions (e.g., heart rate, respiration). During the orgasm phase the person \
experiences an intense and pleasurable release of tension, and ejaculation occurs in the \
male. The resolution stage involves a gradual return to pre-excitement levels. \
\
>ASSERTIVENESS TRAINING This technique utilizes the assertive response, which \
is antagonistic to social anxiety. Some people feel anxious in social situations because they \
have difficulty speaking up for what they feel is right or saying no when others take \
