\
guess at what the unconditioned stimulus (US) was, perhaps a mother screaming at the \
sight of the spider. To use exposure to eliminate the phobia, the client would be exposed \
to the spider (CS) while being prevented from fleeing. This exposure would continue until \
the person's fear has extinguished. \
\
Research has found that in terms of extinction, prolonged exposure (e.g., 45 minutes) is \
more effective than multiple, briefer periods of exposure, which can actually exacerbate \
the fear. Exposure with response prevention appears to be more effective than systematic \
desensitization for specific phobias. It is the treatment of choice for obsessive-compulsive \
disorder, and widely used in the treatment of PTSD. In vivo exposure is also typically \
included as part of the cognitive behavioral treatment protocol for social anxiety disorder, \
panic disorder, and agoraphobia. \
\
>EXPOSURE IN IMAGINATION Exposure can also take place in imagination (e.g .. \
asking a client to vividly recall a scene in which the client was attacked). Stampfl developed \
a specific treatment based on exposure in imagination, called implosive therapy. After the \
client is exposed to the feared object in imagination, the therapist interprets possible \
psychosexual themes. Research has demonstrated that the treatment gains from implosive \
therapy were due only to the exposure aspect of the treatment. The elaboration of \
psychosexual themes did not add to treatment effectiveness. \
\
II. TREATMENT APPROACHES BASED ON OPERANT \
CONDITIONING \
\
Clinical interventions based on operant conditioning involve either reinforcement or \
punishment. Typically, a functional assessment is conducted prior to the implementation \
of a reinforcement or punishment paradigm. A functional assessment of behavior involves \
defining the target behavior and determining its antecedents and consequences. It also \
includes identifying the contingencies (i.e., reinforcers and punishers) that serve to \
maintain the behavior. These contingencies can then be manipulated as part of a behavior \
modification program. \
\
A. REINFORCEMENT \
\
Reinforcers can be classified into three types: primary, secondary, and generalized. \
\
     Primary reinforcers are those reinforcers that reinforce everyone at all ages and \
     in all cultures (e.g., food). \
\
\
 \
\
                                  Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Behaviorism \
\
     Secondary reinforcers acquire their reinforcing value through training or \
     experience (e.g., praise). \
\
     Generalized conditioned reinforcers are not inherently reinforcing. However. \
     they take on reinforcing value because they give the person access to other \
     reinforcers (e.g., money, tokens). \
\
Intervention strategies that involve reinforcement include shaping, token economies, \
contingency contracting, the Premack principle, differential reinforcement, and self- \
reinforcement. These are described below. \
\
>SHAPING In shaping by successive approximations, a person is reinforced for every \
step taken toward achieving the target behavior. For example, if a child with autism \
spectrum disorder is being taught to say her name "Michelle," she is reinforced initially for \
making any vocalization, then for saying "M," and so forth, until she can say her name. \
\
>TOKEN ECONOMIES Token economies involve using tokens in a systematic and \
consistent manner as reinforcement for appropriate behaviors. This procedure was \
originally implemented on schizophrenic inpatient wards, where patients were given \
tokens for self-help behaviors (e.g., grooming, making their beds), as well as adaptive, \
prosocial behaviors. Patients could spend their tokens on goods or privileges, such as \
cigarettes, watching television, trips off the ward, etc. Patients were also fined tokens for \
undesirable behaviors (e.g., destroying property). Token economies have since been \
applied in other institutional settings, for example, with individuals with intellectual \
disability, with children with autism spectrum disorder, and with juvenile offenders. \
\
>CONTINGENCY CONTRACTING    Contingency contracting is an application of \
operant conditioning techniques to the naturalistic environment. Contingency contracting \
can be utilized when there are problematic interactions between two or more people. The \
therapist helps the people involved to identify the behaviors they most want from one \
another, and then helps them negotiate a contract for their exchange. \
\
>THE PREMACK PRINCIPLE The Premack principle, also known as the principle of \
reinforcer relativity, involves using a high-frequency behavior (i.e., something a person \
does frequently without any outside coercion) to reinforce a low-frequency behavior (i.e., \
something a person does not often due unless forced). A common example of this principle \
is requiring a child to eat her peas (a low-frequency behavior) before going out to play (a \
high-frequency behavior). This principle is also known as "Grandma's Rule." \
\
\
\
                                  Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Behaviorism \
\
>DIFFERENTIAL REINFORCEMENT OF OTHER BEHAVIORS Differential \
reinforcement of other behaviors (DRO), also known as DRI (differential reinforcement of \
incompatible responses) or DRA (differential reinforcement of alternative responses). \
combines extinction and positive reinforcement. For example, a hyperactive child is \
ignored when she speaks out of turn (extinction), but she is reinforced when she waits for \
her turn to speak, is engaged in on-task behavior, raises her hand to ask questions, or \
remains seated. \
\
>SELF-REINFORCEMENT Self-reinforcement involves administering reinforcement \
to oneself. For example, in implementing a weight management program, a person rewards \
him or herself for each pound lost. Self-reinforcement is one element of behavioral self- \
control or self-regulation procedures. \
\
Other self-control procedures include: self-monitoring, in which one keeps a detailed \
record of what one does, such as everything one eats; and stimulus control, which involves \
narrowing the range of stimuli that elicit a particular behavior (e.g., eating only at specific \
times at a specific table) and developing incompatible responses (e.g., going for a walk \
instead of snacking). \
\
B. AVERSIVE CONTROL OF BEHAVIOR \
\
The four paradigms that involve elements of aversive control of behavior are positive \
punishment, escape learning, avoidance learning, and overcorrection. \
\
>POSITIVE PUNISHMENT   Positive punishment involves applying an aversive \
stimulus (e.g., yelling) after an undesirable behavior has been emitted. Positive punishment \
is rarely used in clinical settings. An example of positive punishment is thought stopping. \
in which the client snaps a rubber band on the wrist whenever thinking an undesirable \
thought. \
\
Research has found that punishment merely suppresses behavior but does not eliminate it. \
To optimize the effectiveness of punishment, it should be delivered at maximum intensity \
the first time, it should be certain, and there should be little delay between the occurrence \
of the undesirable behavior and the punishment. When there is a sequence of undesirable \
behaviors, punishment should be delivered early rather than late in the response sequence. \
For example, a child should be punished when starting to whine rather than waiting for the \
behavior to escalate into a temper tantrum. When punishment is used, alternative routes to \
reinforcement should be made clear. \
\
\
 \
\
                                  Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Behaviorism \
\
>ESCAPE LEARNING In the escape learning paradigm, the aversive stimulus cannot \
be avoided altogether. However, once the aversive stimulus has started, it can be stopped \
by emitting the desired behavior. For example, an animal is shocked and can get the shock \
to stop by pressing a lever. Another example would be a woman who is mugged at gun \
point and can only make the assailant go away by giving him her wallet. \
\
>AVOIDANCE LEARNING In the avoidance learning paradigm, one can entirely avoid \
the aversive stimulus by emitting the desired behavior in time. Typically, a discriminative \
stimulus or cue occurs to let the subject know it's time to emit the behavior. For example, \
a red light flashes, cueing the animal to press the lever. If the animal does so in time, the \
shock can be entirely avoided. Or, on many bills there is a "pay before" date. If payment \
is made in a timely fashion, late penalties and fees can be avoided entirely. \
\
>OVERCORRECTION Overcorrection is a type of punishment that involves restitution \
or reparation, as well as physical guidance. For example, if a child makes a mess in the \
living room, he is not only required to clean up the living room, but also to clean up another \
room. Physical guidance may be necessary to help the person complete the different steps \
of the task. \
\
III. TREATMENT APPROACHES BASED ON SOCIAL \
LEARNING THEORY \
\
The clinical applications of social learning theory typically involve modeling of adaptive \
behaviors to replace maladaptive ones. Modeling procedures are applied in the treatment \
of phobias, to improve social skills, and to repair behavioral deficits. The three well-known \
variations of modeling procedures are symbolic modeling, live or in-vivo modeling, and \
participant modeling. \
\
>SYMBOLIC MODELING     Symbolic modeling, or filmed modeling, involves \
observing a film in which a model (frequently one similar to the viewer) enjoys \
progressively more intimate interaction with a feared object or anxiety-producing setting. \
\
>LIVE OR IN-VIVO MODELING Live or in-vivo modeling entails having the person \
observe a live model engage in graduated interactions with a feared object or anxiety- \
producing situation. \
\
>PARTICIPANT MODELING Participant modeling consists of live modeling plus \
contact with the model. The model gradually guides the person in activities either involving \
