         5.2 INTERVENTIONS BASED ON \
           COGNITIVE-BEHAVIORISM \
\
Only relatively recently has cognition been included on a large scale into the domain of \
behavior theory. It has become clear that organisms do not simply learn associations or \
develop responses by trial and error. Rather, learning is characterized by internal processes \
that must be understood. Early critics of the pure behavioral model of learning included \
Wolfgang Kohler, known for his insight studies with chimps (1925), and Edward Tolman, \
known for his studies with rats that demonstrated "latent learning" (1930). \
\
I. ELLIS: RATIONAL EMOTIVE BEHAVIOR THERAPY \
(REBT) \
\
Rational emotive behavior therapy (REBT), formerly known as rational-emotive therapy \
(RET) was the first cognitive-behavioral treatment approach, born out of Ellis's \
dissatisfaction with psychoanalysis. \
\
REBT approaches problems in a direct and straightforward way, by convincing clients of \
their irrationality. Emotional disturbances are thought to result from irrational beliefs. \
\
Ellis proposed an ABC model to help clarify the role of cognition in behavior, where A is \
an activating event, B is the belief, and C is the consequence or emotional/behavioral \
outcome. While pure behaviorists propose a direct connection between A and C, Ellis \
proposed that it is not the activating event, but rather one's beliefs about the event that \
result in the consequence. The DEF component is the result of therapy, where D is the \
disputing intervention, E is the adoption of a more effective philosophy, and F represents \
new feelings. \
\
Direct instruction, persuasion and logical disputation are the major procedural components \
of REBT. The therapist identifies the nature of the client's irrational beliefs early in \
treatment and actively disputes those beliefs. Clients are trained to recognize their own \
irrational beliefs and to dispute them actively. The therapist models more rational beliefs \
and provides explicit feedback to the client. \
\
\
\
                             Section 5 -Treatment/ Intervention: Cognitive-Behaviorism \
\
Overall, REBT techniques are active and confrontative. They also include modeling, \
homework, relaxation, and rehearsal. REBT therapy is multimodal and integrates \
cognitive, affective and behavioral techniques. \
\
REBT has been applied to an array of problems, including anxiety, depression, anger, \
marital difficulties, interpersonal problems, personality disorders, eating disorders, and \
psychotic behavior. In summary, REBT focuses on providing clients with an alternative \
philosophical system, by relying largely on persuasion and reason as the means of \
modifying beliefs. \
\
II. BECK: COGNITIVE THERAPY (CT) \
\
Beck's cognitive therapy overlaps considerably with Ellis's REBT with regard to its \
cognitive focus. However, Beck's approach differs in that it emphasizes empirical \
hypothesis testing as a means of changing existing beliefs. Behavioral assignments and \
homework are presented as experiments to allow clients to test the validity of their beliefs. \
Beck also makes use of Socratic questioning, which involves continually seeking the \
client's views about the presenting problem. Beck advocates a more collaborative style \
than that used in REBT. \
\
Beck posits that psychological symptoms result from automatic thoughts that are \
maladaptive, such as negative thinking in depression. Such automatic thoughts often occur \
outside of conscious awareness. Beck also coined the terms logical errors, as well as faulty \
conceptions and self-signals. \
\
According to Beck, depression results from a maladaptive cognitive triad. \
\
>NEGATIVE VIEW OF THE SELF The self is viewed negatively and is seen as \
defective and inadequate. \
\
>NEGATIVE VIEW OF THE WORLD   The world is experienced negatively, events \
are interpreted negatively, and there is an expectation of failure and punishment. \
\
>NEGATIVE VIEW OF THE FUTURE There is an expectation of continued hardship \
or a negative appraisal of the future. \
\
Cognitive therapy techniques include such tasks as keeping daily logs, activity scheduling, \
attempting gradual tasks to increase mastery, and encouragement of activities to check out \
\
