\
one's cognitions. The goal is to identify and test negative cognitions, to develop alternative \
and more flexible schemas, and to rehearse both new cognitive and new behavioral \
responses. \
\
III. MEICHENBAUM: COGNITIVE BEHAVIOR \
MODIFICATION (CBM) \
\
Two programs associated with Meichenbaum's CBM are self-instructional training and \
stress inoculation training. Meichenbaum's approach tends to focus on "self-statements," \
or the verbalizations that clients make to themselves. Like Beck, his approach emphasizes \
collaboration and a Socratic style of questioning. \
\
A. SELF-INSTRUCTION THERAPY \
\
Self-instruction therapy is a set of procedures that combines modeling and graduated \
practice with elements of rational emotive theory, to help children or adults who have \
problems with task completion. Self-instruction therapy has been empirically supported for \
children with ADHD. \
\
Self-instruction therapy involves a five-step procedure: \
\
>THERAPIST MODELING First, the therapist models the task at hand, verbalizing the \
steps involved. \
\
>THERAPIST VERBALIZATION Next, the client performs the task while the therapist \
verbalizes the steps. \
\
>PATIENT VERBALIZATION Next, the client performs the task while verbalizing the \
steps. \
\
>PATIENT SILENTLY TALKS THROUGH THE TASK Then, the client performs \
the task while inaudibly moving his or her lips. \
\
>INDEPENDENT TASK PERFORMANCE Finally, the client performs the task while \
thinking the task through. \
\
There is a slight parallel here with protocol analysis. Protocol analysis is a procedure that \
is used when a person is learning a task and is asked to describe aloud the steps being taken \
