\
to solve the task. Protocol analysis is used to gain access to people's problem-solving \
strategies. \
\
B. STRESS INOCULATION TRAINING (SIT) \
\
Stress inoculation training (SIT) provides a set of guidelines for treating stressed \
individuals. Developed by Meichenbaum, SIT has been empirically validated for the \
treatment of PTSD. It has also been widely applied with clients experiencing excessive \
anxiety, stress, problems with anger, and medical problems. \
\
The central concept underlying SIT is that of "inoculation," the idea that bolstering a \
client's repertoire of coping responses to milder stressors can decrease susceptibility to \
more severe stress. The SIT approach allows clients to master stress gradually. \
\
Stress inoculation training involves a three-phase intervention approach: \
\
>EDUCATION AND COGNITIVE PREPARATION In the initial phase clients are \
taught that they do not react directly to events, but rather that their reactions depend upon \
their interpretations of events. Clients also learn that coping abilities profoundly affect the \
subjective experience of stress. \
\
>COPING SKILLS ACQUISITION The second phase focuses on developing new \
coping skills or encouraging clients to utilize already available coping skills. Skills \
typically include relaxation, coping self-statements, imagery, and thought stopping. During \
this phase, skills are taught and practiced primarily in the treatment setting. \
\
>APPLICATION OF SKILLS IN IMAGINATION AND IN VIVO During the final \
stage, clients are encouraged to apply their coping skills on a graduated basis, across \
increasing levels of stressors. Behavioral rehearsal, modeling, and in vivo exposure are \
utilized. A central component of the application phase is relapse prevention. Clients are \
encouraged to explore high-risk situations, to look at how coping might be employed, and \
to view lapses, should they occur, as potential learning opportunities. \
\
