       5.3 CLASSICAL PSYCHOANALYSIS \
\
Freud's view of human nature is basically deterministic. Specifically, he posits that \
behavior is determined by irrational forces, unconscious motivations, biological and \
instinctual drives, and psychosexual events of the first six years of life. \
\
A. PERSONALITY STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONING \
\
Freud divided the structure of personality into three parts: the id, ego, and the superego. \
\
>THE ID The id is the most primitive part of the psyche. It is ruled by the instincts, or \
basic biological drives, which include libido (also called eros or the life instincts), and \
aggression (also called thanatos or the death instincts). Believed to be present at birth, the \
id is largely unconscious, lacks organization, and disregards reality. The id operates on the \
pleasure principle, which seeks immediate gratification without concern about long-term \
consequences. Evidence for unconscious id impulses can be found in dreams, slips of the \
tongue, jokes, and free association. \
\
>THE EGO The ego is the part of the psyche that is modified by interaction with the \
external world. The ego operates on the reality principle (awareness of the real world and \
consequences of behavior) and is able to defer immediate gratification in order to obtain \
greater long-term gratification. The ego can be seen as the "executive," controlling \
consciousness and psychic functions. Its main task, according to classical psychoanalysis, \
is to suspend or satisfy the id impulses using means that are rational, socially acceptable, \
and reasonably safe. \
\
>THE SUPEREGO The superego includes the individual's conscience, moral code, and \
internalized parental and societal standards. The superego forces the ego to satisfy the id \
in a manner that is moral and ethical, according to an internalized set of rules about what \
is good and bad. The weapon of the superego is guilt. The superego embodies the ideal. \
the standard of perfection and is believed to evolve as the child successfully passes through \
the Oedipal stage. \
\
\
\
                            Section 5 -Treatment/ Intervention: Classical Psychoanalysis \
\
Freud delineated two kinds of mental functioning. \
\
>PRIMARY PROCESS     Examples of primary process include dreams and \
hallucinations. The chief characteristic of primary process functioning is an urgent attempt \
at tension reduction, even at the expense of reality. \
\
>SECONDARY PROCESS     Secondary process includes thinking and speaking. \
Secondary process is characterized by a focus on meeting the demands of reality and by \
the ability to delay gratification. \
\
B. ANXIETY AND THE DEFENSE MECHANISMS \
\
Freud believed that neurotic anxiety results when the unacceptable urges of the id become \
too strong to be controlled by the ego, and these impulses begin to edge their way into \
consciousness. At this point, the ego is unable to control the anxiety by rational methods \
and therefore resorts to the ego-defense mechanisms. The specific purpose of the defense \
mechanisms is to prevent the id's forbidden impulses from entering consciousness. \
\
Defense mechanisms work through self-deception and distortion of reality so that the id's \
urges will not have to be acknowledged. The predominant defense mechanisms include: \
repression, regression, projection, displacement, reaction formation, and sublimation. \
\
>REPRESSION Repression is the most basic and commonly used defense mechanism, \
and is believed to underlie all the other defenses. Repression involves forcing disturbing \
impulses out of consciousness. Freud also referred to repression as motivated forgetting. \
\
>REGRESSION Regression involves guarding against anxiety by retreating to behaviors \
of an earlier, less demanding and safer stage of development. \
\
>PROJECTION Projection involves seeing one's unconscious urges (e.g., hostility) in \
another person's behavior. A common outcome is suspicion and paranoia. \
\
>DISPLACEMENT Displacement involves the transference of emotions from the \
original object to some substitute or symbolic representation. Displacement can be a factor \
in phobias. For example, the person who is scared of sex displaces the fear onto snakes and \
develops a snake phobia. \
\
\
 \
\
                            Section 5 -Treatment/ Intervention: Classical Psychoanalysis \
\
>REACTION FORMATION Reaction formation involves engaging in behaviors that \
are the exact opposite of the id's real urges. For example, the mother who has aggressive \
feelings toward her child becomes a doting and overprotective mother. \
\
>INTELLECTUALIZATION   Intellectualization involves distancing the self from \
one's feelings. \
\
>RATIONALIZATION Rationalization involves coming up with self-satisfying, yet \
incorrect reasons for one's behavior. \
\
>SUBLIMATION Sublimation involves finding socially acceptable ways of discharging \
energy from unconscious forbidden desires. A classic example is the individual with a \
desire to smear feces becoming a painter. Sublimation is thought to be not only normal, but \
also desirable. \
\
According to Theodore Millon each personality disorder relies on one primary defense as \
follows: \
\
Schizoid: intellectualization \
Narcissistic: rationalization \
Paranoid: projection \
Borderline: regression \
Histrionic: dissociation \
Dependent: introjection \
Antisocial: acting out \
\
Some theorists argue that people with personality disorders use alloplastic defenses \
whereas neurotic people use autoplastic defenses. Alloplastic reactions to stress involve \
trying to change the external environment or blaming the external environment, as is \
typical of people with Borderline Personality Disorder or Narcissistic Personality Disorder. \
Autoplastic reactions to stress involve trying to change oneself or blaming oneself, as is \
typical of people with Major Depression or anxiety. Hint: "alloplastic" means other ("allo") \
and changing ("plastic"), and "autoplastic" means oneself ("auto") and changing \
("plastic"). \
\
\
