\
    5.4 EXTENSIONS OF PSYCHOANALYSIS/ \
      PSYCHODYNAMIC INTERVENTIONS \
\
Those who have expanded on classical psychoanalysis include the ego psychologists, the \
object relations theorists, the self-psychologists, and the psychoanalytic social \
psychologists (the neo-Freudians). Those who have departed from classical analysis \
include Adler (Individual Psychology) and Jung (Analytical Psychology). \
\
I. EGO PSYCHOLOGY \
\
Ego psychologists focus on the ego's capacity for integration and adaptation. Ego \
psychology represents a transition from the theory of the ego as helpless rider of the id \
horse, to the ego as guiding a person's capacity to master life. \
\
The major ego psychologists include Heinz Hartmann, Anna Freud, and Erik Erikson. \
\
A. HEINZ HARTMANN \
\
Hartmann is known as "the father of ego psychology." He believed that the ego did not \
arise out of the id, but in parallel with it, and therefore concluded that people are not only \
driven by their passions, but also by their thinking. Hartmann differentiated between \
defensive ego functions and ego autonomous functions. He coined the term "conflict-free \
sphere" for those ego functions occurring and developing outside of conflict, including the \
functions of perception, learning, memory, and locomotion. \
\
B. ANNA FREUD \
\
Anna Freud described the ego's capacity for mastery by noting the ego's inherent ability \
to reconcile drive conflicts with the demands of reality. Anna Freud saw the ego as a \
medium through which we can get a fuller picture of the id and superego. \
\
Along with Melanie Klein, Anna Freud is known for her pioneering work in applying \
psychoanalysis with children. Unlike Klein, Anna Freud did not interpret the play of her \
child clients, but rather she interpreted their words. Also, unlike Klein, she attempted to \
\
\
\
                           Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Extensions of Psychoanalysts \
\
form a strong positive bond with her child clients at the outset of treatment, rather than \
remaining neutral. \
\
C. ERIK ERIKSON \
\
Erikson combined ego psychology with psychosocial life span theory. His theory is based \
on the premise that development occurs in response to social crises. Erikson believed the \
ego matures in epigenetic sequences, in which development occurs in a series of stages \
built on mastery of prior stages. \
\
Freud had delineated five psychosexual stages: oral, anal, phallic, latency, and genital. In \
contrast, Erik Erikson posited eight stages of ego development. The first five correspond \
in time to Freud's, but Erikson went on to include stages of adult ego development. \
Whereas Freud interpreted human behavior as a clash between the unconscious id and the \
conscious ego and superego, Erikson described human behavior as an interaction between \
the internal world of the psyche (ego, id, and superego) and the external social world. \
Erikson's contributions are further described in the Developmental section. \
\
II. OBJECT RELATIONS THEORY \
\
Object relations theory deals with the capacity to have mutually satisfying interpersonal \
relationships. The term object refers to the relationship of the infant to another person. \
Freud believed that the infant's early interest in the mother was solely due to her ability to \
satisfy the drive of hunger. In contrast, object relations theorists believe that the child is \
"object-related" from birth; in other words, there is an inherent drive for satisfying object \
relationships that is as fundamental to humans as the need for food. Early object \
relationships are thought to have a profound impact on personality development. \
\
The object relations theorists focus on therapy as an opportunity to experience object \
relations that differ from those experienced as a child. The focus is on integrating split-off \
parts of the self and integrating the good and bad into whole object representations, thereby \
attaining object constancy. Therapists help clients differentiate a clear sense of self, and \
form balanced, realistic attitudes towards others. In treatment, the therapist plays an active \
role and avoids the "blank screen" invisibility of classical analysis. Major object relations \
theorists include Klein, Winnicott, and Mahler. \
\
\
 \
\
                           Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Extensions of Psychoanalysts \
\
A. MELANIE KLEIN \
\
Klein described splitting as a major defense mechanism used when the infant has hostile \
feelings toward a loved object. Out of fear that the hostile feelings could destroy the loved \
object, the infant "splits" the loved object into two, for example the "good breast" which \
is available, soothing and nourishing, and the "bad breast" which is unavailable or \
withholding. The infant then invests the "good breast" with all its loving feelings and \
invests the "bad breast" with all its destructive feelings. Splitting prevents object constancy \
(recognizing the breast as one object with both good and bad capacities). \
\
Melanie Klein worked a great deal with children. She saw play as the child's free \
association and conducted child therapy in a manner very similar to adult analysis. \
\
B. WINNICOTT \
\
D. W. Winnicott discussed the importance of being a "good enough mother," rather than a \
perfect one. He described pathology as resulting from abandoning one's true self and \
adopting a "false self," in other words, disavowing one's inner feelings and behaving in \
ways that are acceptable to others. He also highlighted the importance of the transitional \
object, which serves as a link between developing children and their mothers (e.g., a child's \
favorite blanket or doll). \
\
C. MARGARET MAHLER \
\
Mahler developed a theory that describes the processes of separation and individuation. \
Mahler described six stages of development. These include normal infantile autism, \
symbiosis, differentiation, practicing, rapprochement, and object constancy. (These phases \
are described in greater detail in the Developmental section.) \
\
Separation is the process of becoming a discrete physical entity by physically distancing, \
while individuation is the process of becoming a psychologically independent person, \
which involves maturation of independent ego functions. \
\
III. KOHUT: SELF PSYCHOLOGY \
\
Whereas Freud focused on libidinal development (e.g., the psychosexual stages) as the key \
to understanding the infant's development, Kohut suggested that there was another line of \
development, the development of narcissism. He focused on the earliest stages of a child's \
\
\
\
                           Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Extensions of Psychoanalysis \
\
life, the "pre-oedipal stages." Unlike Freud who saw all narcissism as an unhealthy \
secondary reaction, Kohut posited a "primary narcissism," a healthy kind of narcissism that \
occurs when a baby naturally focuses on getting its own needs met. With appropriate \
caretaking that satisfies "selfobject" needs, the baby develops a healthy self with \
appropriate and healthy narcissism. Selfobject needs include mirroring (approval and \
admiration of the baby), idealizing (the presence of adults worthy of idealization), and \
twinship (the ability to join in with and imitate adults, like a toddler pretending to shave \
when his father does). \
\
Clinically, self-psychologists focus on "empathic attunement" with clients and prefer \
interpretations that are "experience near" rather than "experience distant" (such as those in \
classical psychoanalysis). \
\
IV. NEO-FREUDIANS \
\
The neo-Freudians focused on the impact of social and cultural factors in determining \
personality. They believed that psychological disturbance results from faulty learning and \
involves a characterologically maladaptive style of interacting with the environment. \
\
Psychotherapy is seen as an interpersonal experience in which the therapist can help the \
client examine difficulties in relating to people. The treatment relationship is used to \
facilitate the process of identifying and correcting clients' tendencies to misperceive or \
misinterpret the behavior of others. Major neo-Freudians include Sullivan, Horney, and \
Fromm. \
\
A. HARRY STACK SULLIVAN \
\
Sullivan is known for interpersonal theory. He believed that personality exists only in an \
emotional exchange between people. He argued that the person does not possess a \
personality as much as reflect one in responding to the perception of significant others. \
\
Sullivan drew significantly from Piaget's theory of cognitive development, especially with \
regard to the first two years of life, and specifically about the child's development of \
concepts of causality and experiences of reality. He conceived of three modes of existence, \
the prototaxic, the parataxic, and the syntaxic. \
\
>PROTOTAXIC The prototaxic mode (birth to seven months) involves serial sensation \
and a stream of sensory experiences that are isolated and uncoordinated with one another. \
\
\
 \
\
                           Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Extensions of Psychoanalysis \
\
>PARATAXIC The parataxic mode (8 - 11 months) involves sequential sensations, and \
the dominance of temporal sequence serves as the only conception of causality. To \
Sullivan, transference is an example of a parataxic distortion. \
\
>SYNTAXIC The syntaxic mode (12 months - 2 years) involves causal sensation, logical \
and analytical thinking, and ability to predict cause from knowledge of their effects. \
\
Based in large part on Sullivan's work, interpersonal therapy (IPT) has been developed. \
Considered to be an evidence-based treatment for depression, Interpersonal Therapy (IPT) \
is a 16-session, time-limited therapy model that connects the client's presenting problem \
to interpersonal difficulties. Interpersonal therapy is focused on the here-and-now, on \
current interpersonal relationships, rather than on past conflicts or relationships. One of \
four interpersonal problem areas is commonly targeted: grief, role dispute, role transition, \
or interpersonal deficits. Interpersonal therapy attempts to foster a positive therapeutic \
alliance. The transference relationship is not interpreted, nor are other traditional \
psychodynamic techniques utilized. \
\
B. KAREN HORNEY \
\
Horney believed that neurosis is a culturally defined construct, indicating deviation from a \
common pattern of behavior in a given society. Neurosis develops from the feelings of \
alienation, basic anxiety and basic hostility that result from the child's discovery of \
helplessness in the face of all-powerful, indifferent adults. Basic anxiety results in a rigid \
pursuit of safety, familiarity and security. Horney described three neurotic trends: moving \
compliantly towards others, moving aggressively against others, and moving detachedly \
away from others. \
\
C. ERICH FROMM \
\
Incorporating concepts from Marx and the existentialist philosophers, Fromm viewed \
human's behavior as resulting from sociocultural and economic conditions. He believed \
the experience of freedom frightened most people, hence the title of one of his books, \
Escape from Freedom. He distinguished between two modes of existence, the "having" \
mode and the "being" mode, with the idea that healthier people live primarily in the "being" \
mode. \
\
\
\
                           Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Extensions of Psychoanalysis \
\
V. ADLERIAN PSYCHOLOGY (INDIVIDUAL \
PSYCHOLOGY) \
\
Alfred Adler believed that each person strives for superiority or personal competence, and \
that we struggle not just to survive but to master life. Adler differed with Freud over the \
importance of biological and instinctual determination. While Adler agreed with Freud that \
adults are profoundly influenced by the first six years of life, Adler asserted that humans \
are motivated primarily by social (aggressive) rather than sexual urges. Adler believed our \
happiness or success is largely related to social connectedness and our ability to transcend \
the self. Adler proposed that the more one's lifestyle is connected to struggles for power at \
the expense of social interest, the more likely the person is to engage in maladaptive \
behavior. \
\
Adler believed every child experiences basic feelings of inferiority due to real or perceived \
weaknesses. These inferiority feelings can either motivate mastery or contribute to \
neurosis. Adler argued that neurosis results from a maladaptive effort to compensate for \
feelings of inferiority by adopting a lifestyle (attitudes, aspirations and behavior patterns) \
that is unproductive (e.g., delinquents, psychotics). In general, lifestyle is affected by \
experiences within the family and with siblings, with birth order having significant impact. \
\
In Adlerian therapy, interpretation is a significant therapeutic tool, but what is selected for \
interpretation is quite dissimilar from Freud's genetic interpretations and Jung's \
elaboration of symbolic meaning. In therapy, Adlerians looks for mistaken goals and faulty \
assumptions. Adlerian therapists also focus on encouraging the client because they believe \
most clients are suffering from a sense of discouragement and demoralization. Adlerians \
stress analysis of clients' current concerns and future goals rather than past conflicts. Such \
an emphasis indicates a teleological view of behavior, meaning that behavior is seen as \
determined by the future rather than the past. \
\
Adlerian therapy involves a pragmatic, problem-solving approach, and is characterized by \
an educational process in which the therapist tries to influence clients to form more positive \
attitudes toward themselves and others, and to adopt more effective and socially acceptable \
patterns of living. \
\
There have been significant applications of Adler's work to education and parenting. The \
well-known STEP program (Systematic Training in Effective Parenting) advocates a \
democratic approach to parenting that values and respects the child's contribution. It \
recommends using natural and logical consequences of behavior as the basis of discipline. \
\
\
 \
\
                           Section 5 - Treatment Intervention: Extensions of Psychoanalysis \
\
It also encourages parents to understand their child's misbehavior as reflecting one of four \
mistaken goals (attention, power, revenge, giving up). \
\
VI. JUNGIAN PSYCHOLOGY (ANALYTIC PSYCHOLOGY) \
\
According to Jung, the structure of the psyche includes the conscious ego, the personal \
unconscious (similar to Freud's unconscious), and the collective unconscious. He \
described the collective unconscious as transpersonal or impersonal. Within the collective \
unconscious are the archetypes, which are primordial images and ideas that have been \
inherited, and that are common to all members of the race from the beginning of life. Some \
of the archetypes include the persona (social mask), the shadow (one's hidden aspects), the \
anima (female aspect), and the animus (male aspect). The self is the transcendent part of \
the psyche that encompasses all of the archetypes and components. \
\
Jung believed that neurosis represents the struggle of people to free themselves from the \
interference of the archetypes with their progress toward personality integration and \
fulfillment of their potential. Neurosis is seen not so much as illness but as a striving toward \
psychological maturity, which is termed individuation. Jung's analytical therapy is \
teleological, meaning that behavior is seen as determined by the future rather than the past. \
\
The task of the Jungian therapist is to utilize interpretation to help the client gain awareness \
of the unconscious, with a particular focus on the symbolic meaning of dreams, myths and \
folklore. The therapist's role involves an active effort to guide the client into a productive \
relationship with the elements of the unconscious and thereby liberate growth-promoting \
forces within the personality. Treatment methods are characterized by direct focusing of \
the sessions rather than free association, and an exchange of ideas at the level of a real \
relationship rather than utilizing the transference. Jungians see transference as a projection \
of the personal and/or collective unconscious. \
\
In contrast to Freud's emphasis on infantile development, Jung was much more focused on \
the process of adult development. In fact, as initially practiced by Jung, therapy was \
reserved for adults. Today, however, Jungian therapy is widely used with children as well \
(e.g., using sand trays). \
\
\
\
