\
     5.5 THERAPIES AND INTERVENTIONS \
  BASED ON HUMANISM/ EXISTENTIALISM \
\
The humanists and existentialists both emphasize the client's subjective experiences. These \
therapists subscribe to a phenomenological approach, which requires the therapist to enter \
the client's subjective world. Humanism and existentialism both trust in the client's \
capacity to make positive and constructive conscious choices. The emphasis is on freedom, \
choice, autonomy, purpose, and meaning, and the focus is on the present. \
\
Humanist psychologists believe that people move in the direction of actualization if \
nurtured. A key figure in humanist psychology, Maslow believed we all have the potential \
to proceed through a hierarchy of basic needs towards ultimate health and a fully \
spontaneous expression of the self, called self-actualization. \
\
In contrast, existentialist psychologists believe that we have no internal nature, that the \
world lacks intrinsic meaning, and that people are faced with what to make of this \
meaninglessness. The existentialists were influenced by philosophers, including \
Dostoyevsky, Kierkegaard, Nietzsche, Heidegger, Sartre, and Buber. Key existentialist \
psychologists include Binswanger, Boss, Viktor Frankl, R. D. Laing, Rollo May and Irving \
Yalom. \
\
Therapies based on humanism/existentialism include Client-Centered Therapy (Carl \
Rogers), Gestalt Therapy (Fritz Perls), and Reality Therapy (Glasser). \
\
I. ROGERS: CLIENT/PERSON-CENTERED THERAPY \
\
Client-Centered Therapy rests on the premise that all people have inborn capacities for \
purposive, goal-directed behavior, and, if free of adverse conditions, will develop into self- \
accepting, kind, socialized persons. Faulty learning, however, can cause people to become \
hateful, self-centered, ineffective and antagonistic. Pathology or problems are thought to \
be due to incongruence between the self (true feelings) and experience (ability to be aware \
of these feelings and express them to others). The focus of therapy is on correcting faulty \
learning by providing clients with an opportunity to expand their awareness of and liking \
for themselves. \
\
\
 \
\
                            Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Humanism/Existentialism \
\
Central to this approach is the concept of the phenomenal self, the private world of \
experience and meaning. Rogers believed that a person's behavior can be understood only \
from the person's own subjective point of view and can be changed only by the \
determination to change. Client-Centered Therapy therefore does not offer direct \
suggestion or make interpretations. Rather, the therapist creates an accepting, non- \
threatening atmosphere in which clients can examine and reconsider their ways of thinking \
and feeling. \
\
The client-centered therapist listens in a friendly and empathic manner, reflects clients' \
feeling tone, and encourages clients to manage their own affairs. The therapist thus makes \
it possible for clients to grow through the relationship. to form a more positive view of \
themselves, and to direct themselves toward more productive and self-actualizing patterns \
of behavior. The overall focus of treatment is on clarifying feelings, without judging them \
or elaborating upon them. \
\
The three key characteristics of treatment are empathy, warmth, and genuineness. \
\
>EMPATHY Accurate empathic understanding is the means by which a therapist conveys \
to a client that he or she is being listened to and understood. It involves being sensitive to \
the client's subjective experiences and needs and appreciating distress and difficulties. \
\
>WARMTH Warmth, or unconditional positive regard and acceptance, consists of the \
therapist valuing the client as an individual in his or her own right, refraining from passing \
judgment, maintaining a consistently friendly attitude, and conveying a strong sense of \
caring and commitment. \
\
>GENUINENESS Genuineness or congruence of the therapist involves the therapist \
being truthful and authentic, and saying only what he or she believes, and doing only what \
is comfortable. \
\
II. PERLS: GESTALT THERAPY \
\
In developing Gestalt Therapy, Perls drew on the findings of Gestalt Theory, according to \
which people structure experiences as whole, integrated organisms, not in cognitive or \
affective fragments. Perceptions consist of gestalts which are combinations of figure (what \
is attended to) and ground (what is ignored). Healthy functioning results when individuals \
are able to maintain flexible and adaptive contact with their own needs and with their \
environment. Without this, there can result personality fragmentation, limited awareness, \
and deficiencies in responsibility, authenticity, and self-regulation. \
\
\
\
                            Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Humanism/Existentialism \
\
The focus of therapy is on the client becoming aware of the whole personality by \
discovering those aspects of the self that are blocked from awareness. By reowning parts \
that have been disowned, the client is thus able to achieve integration. An overall goal of \
treatment is to enhance the individual's capacity to communicate or make contact with the \
self and others. \
\
Resistances to contact or boundary disturbances, as described by Polster and Polster, \
include introjection, projection, retroflection, deflection and confluence. \
\
>INTROJECTION Introjection is a process whereby people take information in whole, \
which results in problems with being overly compliant and gullible. \
\
>PROJECTION Projection is a process by which people project their feelings onto \
others, which results in paranoia. \
\
>RETROFLECTION Retroflection is a process in which people turn back onto the self \
what they would like to do to others. This can result in self-destructive behavior. \
\
>DEFLECTION Deflection is a process by which people distance themselves from their \
feelings through distraction, humor, generalization, and asking questions rather than \
making statements. \
\
>CONFLUENCE Confluence involves a lack of awareness of a differentiation between \
the self and others, in an attempt to avoid conflicts. \
\
Gestalt Therapy is active and focuses on awareness, experience and affective expression, \
rather than on a cognitive analysis of behavior. More so than in other humanistic \
approaches, Gestalt therapy uses a variety of specific and graded exercises to facilitate \
experiencing and self-expression. \
\
The empty chair technique involves clients playing out their fantasies, by taking on both \
sides of their conflicts. It may also involve pretending to speak to an individual for whom \
clients have unresolved feelings. With dreams, Gestalt therapists have the client become \
the different parts of the dream. Given their here-and-now orientation, Gestalt therapists \
actively challenge the transference (e.g., they bring the focus back to the present), and also \
discourage questions. \
\
\
 \
\
                            Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Humanism/Existentialism \
\
III. GLASSER: REALITY THERAPY \
\
Reality Therapy has been influenced by both existentialism and REBT. The key feature of \
Reality Therapy is responsibility. Treatment focuses on clarifying clients' values and \
helping clients evaluate their current behavior and plans in relation to these values. The \
end goal is to get clients to accept responsibility. \
\
A key element of reality therapy is Choice Theory (previously known as Control Theory), \
which proposes that we create an inner world that satisfies our needs, one that does not \
necessarily reflect the real world. Our behavior is an attempt to control our perceptions of \
the external world to fit our internal "need-satisfying" world. It is argued that all behaviors \
are generated from within and people have choices in what they do. \
\
Therapy consists of helping the person perceive the consequences of possible courses of \
action and decide on realistic solutions or goals. Once a plan of action is chosen, a contract \
may be signed. Other therapy components may include the use of humor, paradox, and \
skillful questioning. \
\
Reality Therapy has been widely implemented with clinical populations, such as juvenile \
delinquents and prison inmates. Schools Without Failures (SWF) is a program based on \
Glasser's work that has been used in high schools to reduce dropout rates. \
\
\
