\
5.6 OTHER MISCELLANEOUS APPROACHES \
\
I. BERNE: TRANSACTIONAL ANALYSIS (TA) \
\
Transactional Analysis (TA) is rooted in an anti-deterministic philosophy. The goal is for \
clients to become aware of the intent behind their communication, and to eliminate deceit \
so that clients can interpret their own behavior accurately. TA looks at early decisions a \
person has made and the capacity to make new decisions. Key concepts include the ego \
states, transactions, games, strokes, and life scripts. \
\
>EGO STATES The three ego states of parent, adult, and child are components of the \
personality. \
\
>TRANSACTIONS Transactions are interactions between the ego states of two persons. \
Transactions occur at two levels, the social (or overt) level, and the psychological (or \
covert) level. Transactions can be complementary (e.g., adult to adult), crossed (e.g., one \
person communicates adult to adult, while the other responds from child to parent), or \
ulterior (e.g., dual levels of transactions occurring simultaneously, one overt and the other \
covert). \
\
>GAMES A game is an orderly series of ulterior transactions, which commonly ends in \
bad feelings for both players. \
\
>STROKES Strokes are the recognition given to a person. Strokes can be either positive \
(caring and approving) or negative (damaging and disapproving). \
\
>LIFE SCRIPTS Life scripts are patterns that have developed that virtually dictate one's \
life. Out of their own pain, parents give the child messages (injunctions) about how he or \
she must behave in order to receive recognition (strokes). These injunctions result in early \
decisions made by the child which then guide adult development and behavior. \
\
TA techniques include structural analysis (becoming aware of the parent, adult, and child). \
transactional analysis (looking at communication patterns between the person and others), \
analysis of games, and script analysis. \
\
\
 \
\
