\
II. HYPNOTHERAPY \
\
Hypnosis is defined as a state or condition in which the person is able to respond to \
suggestions by experiencing alterations of perceptions, memory, or mood. The essential \
feature is a subjective experiential change. Hypnosis is also called an altered state of \
consciousness, or a dissociated state. \
\
People who have been hypnotized enter a trance state, which can range from light to deep. \
In a light trance changes in motor activity can occur. For example, muscles may relax, \
hands may levitate, and paresthesias (or tingling) can be induced. Characteristic of a \
medium trance include decreased pain sensation and partial or complete amnesia. During \
a deep trance, deep anesthesia as well as visual and auditory experiences can be induced. \
Also associated with a deep trance is the capacity for post-hypnotic suggestion. Regardless \
of the depth of the trance, a hypnotized person will not follow a command if it is something \
she or he does not want to do. \
\
Hypnosis is used for treating chronic pain, asthma, conversion symptoms, and substance \
use. Persons who are not good candidates include individuals with paranoia or obsessive- \
compulsive disorder. \
\
Hypnosis is often used to aid memory. Research has indicated, however, that hypnotized \
individuals report more false memories than true ones. In addition, a person under hypnosis \
is more likely to reconstruct false memories to fill in memory gaps than would a non- \
hypnotized individual being asked similar questions. \
\
Ericksonian hypnotherapy is a specific type of hypnotherapy that involves techniques that \
rely on psycholinguistic nuances as well as relaxation and focus during trance. This \
approach depends more on subtleties of communication than on formal induction of a \
trance. Therapy is manipulative, controlling, and paradoxical at times. \
\
III. BIOFEEDBACK \
\
Biofeedback involves operant conditioning of normally involuntary autonomie nervous \
system (ANS) functions, with the goal of alleviating symptoms. By means of visual and \
auditory displays, the client is given feedback about the status of certain involuntary \
biological functions and is then taught to regulate one or more of these biological states. \
The mechanism of action involves decreased sympathetic arousal. \
\
\
\
                               Section 5- Treatment/Intervention: Other Approaches \
\
Biofeedback is commonly utilized in conjunction with relaxation training. The specific \
type of biofeedback (and relaxation training) selected depends on the client and the nature \
of the problem. Commonly used biofeedback procedures include thermal biofeedback, \
EMG, EEG, and GSR. \
\
>THERMAL BIOFEEDBACK Thermal (temperature) biofeedback measures peripheral \
skin temperature and is commonly used to treat migraine headaches and Reynaud's disease. \
The goal of biofeedback is for the client to be able to increase peripheral temperature. \
Thermal biofeedback is commonly combined with autogenie training (a specific type of \
relaxation training that focuses on warmth and heaviness). \
\
>ELECTROMYOGRAPHY (EMG) EMG measures surface muscle tension (e.g., the \
forehead, jaw, lower back). EMG biofeedback is commonly used to treat clients with \
tension headaches, temporomandibular joint pain (TMJ), and back pain, with the goal of \
either reducing EMG levels, or equalizing the tension in parallel muscle groups (e.g., of \
the lower back). EMG biofeedback is commonly combined with progressive or passive \
muscle relaxation training. EMG is also used for clients requiring neuromuscular \
rehabilitation (e.g., secondary to stroke). \
\
>ELECTROENCEPHALOGRAPHY (EEG) EEG measures brain waves and is used to \
treat people suffering from hyperactivity or seizure disorders. \
\
>GALVANIC SKIN RESPONSE (GSR) GSR, also called electrodermal response \
(EDR), measures skin conductivity or sweat. GSR (in combination with relaxation training) \
can be used in the treatment of generalized anxiety. The goal is to decrease GSR levels. \
\
The research contrasting the effectiveness of biofeedback for different disorders has been \
somewhat inconsistent. EMG biofeedback for tension headaches and thermal biofeedback \
for migraine are both effective treatments. Overall, however, there is some evidence that \
EMG biofeedback is more effective for tension headaches as compared to thermal \
biofeedback for migraines. \
\
IV. FEMINIST THERAPY \
\
Feminist therapists promote independence and autonomy. They do not attempt to bond \
with their clients to avoid fostering dependence. They view sexism as an underlying cause \
of problems and don't focus on "pathology" as such. For example, a feminist therapist \
would probably not diagnose a client with a major depressive disorder, but rather would \
