VI. MOTIVATIONAL INTERVIEWING \
\
Developed by Miller and Rollnick, Motivational Interviewing (MI) is a counseling \
approach that helps clients resolve ambivalence about change. With its emphasis on \
enhancing internal motivational processes, it differs sharply from older approaches that \
relied on direct confrontation and the breaking down of defenses. Applications of \
Motivational Interviewing, including Motivational Enhancement Therapy (MET), have \
been empirically validated for use with substance abuse, health-promotion behaviors, \
medical adherence, and mental health issues. \
\
VII. FIVE-FACTOR THEORY OF PERSONALITY \
(THE "BIG 5" MODEL) \
\
Costa and McCrae (1985) reanalyzed all previous research on personality. Utilizing factor \
analysis on a long list of personality traits, they arrived at five basic personality traits: \
openness to experience (O), conscientiousness (C), extroversion (E), agreeableness (A), \
and neuroticism (N), forming the acronym OCEAN. On each of these factors, individuals \
are scored from low to high. \
\
>OPENNESS TO EXPERIENCE High scorers on this factor are open to new ideas, \
curious, and imaginative. Low scorers are conventional, have narrow interests, and tend to \
be inartistic. \
\
>CONSCIENTIOUSNESS    At the high end, conscientiousness involves being \
responsible, self-disciplined, organized, and achievement-oriented. At the low end. \
individuals are irresponsible, careless, impulsive, lazy, and undependable. A high degree \
of conscientiousness is the trait that has been most consistently associated with job success. \
\
>EXTROVERSION   High scorers are sociable, outgoing, talkative, fun-loving, and \
affectionate, while low scorers are withdrawn, passive, and reserved. \
\
>AGREEABLENESS   At the high end, individuals are good-natured, gentle, warm. \
trusting, and cooperative. At the opposite end. individuals are irritable, argumentative, \
vindictive, and untrusting. \
\
>NEUROTICISM Individuals who score high are emotionally unstable, insecure, \
anxious, and moody. People who score low are emotionally stable, even-tempered, calm, \
easy-going, and relaxed. \
\
