              5.7 FAMILY THERAPIES \
\
Overall two theoretical models have influenced family therapists: general systems theory \
and cybernetics. \
\
General systems theory posits that the system is an interaction of component parts, which \
seeks to attain homeostasis. \
\
Cybernetics focuses on the circular nature of feedback loops. Feedback loops can be either \
negative or positive. A negative feedback loop tends to decrease deviation in a system, \
with the end result of maintaining the status quo. The classic example of a negative \
feedback loop is a thermostat, whose function is to minimize changes in temperature. When \
the temperature begins to rise, cooling systems are engaged to bring it back down, and \
when the temperature begins to fall, heating is engaged to bring it back up, thus maintaining \
homeostasis. A positive feedback loop increases deviation or change. A clinical example \
of a positive feedback loop is a marital argument in which the actions of each spouse \
escalate the argument, leading to increasing levels of distress. An example of a negative \
feedback loop is a family returning to its normal healthy functioning after a disruptive life \
event, such as the death of a family member. \
\
Theories of family therapy include psychodynamic, structural, communications, strategic, \
family systems, and behavioral/social learning. \
\
I. PSYCHODYNAMIC FAMILY THERAPY \
\
Psychodynamic family therapy focuses on facilitating individual maturation in the context \
of the family system and on freeing family members from unconscious patterns of anxiety \
and projection rooted in the past. This approach emphasizes helping family members \
clarify communication and honestly admit feelings. \
\
Lidz described two deviant types of marital relationships, marital schism and marital skew, \
which can each lead to impaired parenting and disrupted sex-role learning for the child. \
\
>MARITAL SCHISM   Marital schism involves severe, chronic discord and \
disequilibrium, where threats of separation are common and recurrent. Communication \
centers on power struggles and efforts to avoid facing the schism between the spouses. \
\
\
\
                                Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Family Therapies \
\
Parents tend to seek support from their children and attempt to diminish the worth of the \
other parent in the children's eyes. \
\
>MARITAL SKEW In marital skew, the relationship is not threatened by separation but \
skewed toward meeting the needs of one member at the expense of the needs of others. For \
example, a mother forms an overly close relationship with one child at the expense of the \
other children and her husband. \
\
In both problematic patterns of relationship, there is a failure to develop a reciprocally \
rewarding parental coalition. In both patterns, the parents lack role reciprocity, defined as \
a common understanding and acceptance of each other's roles, goals, and values. Family \
sculpting is a technique that can be used, with the therapist both interpreting the sculpture \
and modifying it in ways to suggest new relationships. \
\
II. OBJECT RELATIONS FAMILY THERAPY \
\
Object relations family therapy is a specific branch of psychodynamic family therapy that \
focuses on the transferences and projections between couples or family members. \
According to this theory, problems are caused when members unconsciously project \
unwanted elements of themselves onto others in the family. As a result of these projections. \
the members experience dissatisfaction and try to change one another. Therapy focuses on \
helping each family member to become aware of what is being projected, and then to \
address these unwanted elements within each person. Framo is well known for conducting \
family-of-origin sessions in which a troubled couple first meets with one spouse's entire \
family-of-origin and then, in a later session, meets with the other spouse's family-of-origin. \
\
III. MINUCHIN: STRUCTURAL FAMILY THERAPY \
\
According to Minuchin's structural model, the family is viewed as a single, interrelated \
system, which is assessed along a variety of dimensions: the hierarchy of power, the clarity \
and firmness of boundaries, and the significant alliances and splits (subsystems). \
\
In a healthy family, there is a hierarchy with a strong parental coalition on the topmost \
level. Boundaries are clear and firm, yet there is flexibility in the system that allows for \
autonomy and interdependence, individual growth, as well as adaptive restructuring in \
response to changing developmental and environmental demands. By contrast, pathology \
results from structural imbalances such as a malfunctioning hierarchical arrangement, or \
poor boundaries that may be too rigid or too diffuse. Rigid boundaries result in disengaged \
\
\
 \
\
                                Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Family Therapies \
\
or emotionally distant relationships, while diffuse boundaries result in enmeshed \
relationships. \
\
Minuchin described three chronic boundary problems: triangulation, detouring, and stable \
coalitions. \
\
>TRIANGULATION In triangulation, a child is caught in the middle of the parents" \
conflict, with each parent demanding that the child side with him or her. Whenever the \
child sides with one parent, he or she is viewed as attacking the other. The child ultimately \
becomes paralyzed. \
\
>DETOURING In detouring, the parents express their distress through one child, who \
becomes the identified client. This serves to create a false sense of harmony between the \
parents, with the parents either blaming the child as the source of the family's problems, \
or uniting to protect the sick, weak child. \
\
>STABLE COALITION In a stable coalition, one parent unites with the child against \
the other parent, in a rigid cross-generational coalition. \
\
The goal of structural family therapy is to unbalance or reorganize the family's structure \
in such a way that dysfunctional elements are removed. The therapist assumes the role of \
an expert, as he or she diagnoses dysfunctional elements and develops interventions to \
correct them. At the outset of therapy with the family, the structural therapist "joins" the \
family, and attempts to understand the family's dynamics by adopting its style of \
interaction. Therapy then focuses on shifting members' positions in order to disrupt \
malfunctioning patterns and to strengthen the parental hierarchy, with the goal of creating \
clear and flexible boundaries. Specific strategies for unbalancing the family's homeostasis \
include the therapist taking sides, blaming, and forming coalitions. \
\
Structural Family Therapy has been demonstrated to be highly effective in the treatment of \
childhood and adolescent problems, such as asthma, diabetes, and anorexia, as well as in \
the treatment of adults with drug addictions. \
\
IV. COMMUNICATIONS FAMILY THERAPY \
\
The communications family therapists include Virginia Satir, Paul Watzlawick, Gregory \
Bateson, Don Jackson, and Jay Haley. Also referred to as the MRI group because of their \
\
\
\
                                Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Family Therapies \
\
work done at the Mental Research Institute in Palo Alto in the 1960s, these family therapists \
have focused on communication and its impact on family functioning. \
\
The MRI group coined the term "double bind." A double bind is a maladaptive \
communication that typically involves at least three elements: an injunction telling the \
person that if they do or don't do something they will be punished; a secondary injunction \
which is generally nonverbal, conflicting with the first at a more abstract level, and also \
enforced by punishment; and a tertiary injunction prohibiting the victim from escaping the \
field (e.g., by not allowing the victim to point out the inconsistency). \
\
An example of a double bind is a hospitalized psychiatric patient who, when visited by his \
mother, puts his arm around her shoulders only to feel her stiffen. When he quickly \
withdraws his arm, the mother comments, "Don't you love me anymore?" When he then \
blushes, she scolds "Dear, you must not be so easily embarrassed and afraid of your \
feelings." The impossible dilemma is that if he shows his love he is wrong, if he withholds \
his love he is wrong, and if he comments on the situation (by blushing) he is wrong. \
\
The MRI group formulated the double bind theory of schizophrenia, which saw double \
binds as contributing to the etiology of the schizophrenia. This theory has not been \
empirically supported. \
\
Communications family therapy addresses communication problems by implementing \
both direct and indirect techniques. Direct techniques include teaching and pointing out \
problematic communication patterns. Indirect techniques include paradoxical interventions \
such as prescribing the symptom. An example of a paradoxical intervention would be \
telling a couple with marital problems to fight at least three hours a day. \
\
V. HALEY: STRATEGIC FAMILY THERAPY \
\
Haley's strategic approach is a combination of Minuchin's structural approach, with a \
focus on hierarchies, and the communications approach, with a focus on family \
communication and interactions. According to Haley, normal family functioning involves \
flexibility, a large behavioral repertoire for problem-solving and life-cycle passage, and \
clear rules governing the family's hierarchy. Pathology results from a malfunctioning \
hierarchy, or triangles and coalitions across the hierarchy. \
\
Haley views the family's presenting problem and symptoms as a communicative act within \
an interactional pattern. Treatment focuses on resolving the presenting problem only. \
\
\
 \
\
                               Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Family Therapies \
\
which is defined by behavioral objectives and criteria. Underlying conflicts or pathology \
are not addressed. The focus is on interrupting the rigid feedback cycle and defining a \
clearer hierarchy, utilizing such techniques as paradoxical interventions. Haley was \
influenced by Milton Erickson. \
\
VI. MILAN GROUP: SYSTEMIC FAMILY THERAPY \
\
Systemic Family Therapy is associated with the Milan group (Palazzoli, Boscolo, Cecchin, \
and Prata), which subsequently split up. It involves elements of general systems theory and \
cybernetics (feedback loops), as well as components of strategic theory, such as \
communication, reframing, and paradox. Key aspects of treatment include circular \
questioning and prescription of rituals. \
\
>CIRCULAR QUESTIONING The Milan group noted that families presenting to \
treatment frequently did not function reciprocally, but rather that one subsystem, coalition, \
or individual was trying to establish control over the family. Circular questioning is a \
technique that aims at gathering information (hypothesis formation) and at the same time \
introducing information into the family system. For example, while the therapist maintains \
an attitude of neutrality, each family member is asked in turn to express his or her views \
on the relationships and differences between other family members. Circular questioning \
thus transforms families' ways of thinking from linear and causal to reciprocal and \
interdependent. \
\
>PRESCRIPTION OF RITUALS The purpose of prescribing rituals is to alter the \
family's direction from its current course. Some therapists using this approach tailor rituals \
to the specific needs of each family. Others always prescribe the same ritual which may \
involve parental secrecy and parental outings framed as disappearances. \
\
VII. BOWEN: FAMILY SYSTEMS THERAPY \
\
According to Bowen, healthy families have clearly differentiated family members and \
there is an overall balance of intellectual and emotional forces. By contrast, families with \
pathology function as a single organism and the identified patient is that part of the \
organism through which overt symptoms are expressed. \
\
One central concept in Bowen's theory is the family emotional system (undifferentiated \
family ego mass), which refers to the emotional oneness that exists and shifts about within \
the family in definite patterns of emotional reactivity. According to Bowen's concept of the \
\
\
\
                                Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: Family Therapies \
\
multigenerational transmission process, the emotional dysfunction of an individual \
results from emotional processes that have lasted in the family over several generations. \
\
The essential goal of treatment is personal differentiation from the family-of-origin: the \
ability to be one's true self in the face of familial or other pressures that threaten loss of \
love or social position. The family presenting for treatment is assessed on two levels: a) \
the degree of fusion or emotional cutoff, versus the ability to differentiate, and b) the \
analysis of emotional triangles in presenting problems. An emotional triangle is defined \
as a three-party system arranged so that the closeness of two members tends to exclude a \
third. \
\
The role of the therapist is twofold, first to shift the hot triangle, the one that relates to the \
presenting problem, and second, to work with the most psychologically available family \
members, individually if necessary, on achieving enough personal differentiation so that \
the hot triangle doesn't recur. Modification of relationships in the family system occurs \
through de-triangling and repairing of emotional cutoffs. Bowen also originated the \
genogram, a historical survey of the family going back several generations. \
\
VIII. SOLUTION-FOCUSED THERAPY \
\
Solution-focused therapy (also called solution-focused brief therapy or SFBT) has its roots \
in the MRI group and was initially developed by Steve de Shazer. As the name suggests, \
this model encourages clients to focus on their strengths and to identify solutions, either \
ones that have already worked in the past or ones that might work in the future. The model \
is built on the assumption that expectations are very powerful. Therefore, it attempts to set \
up positive expectations in both therapist and client, for example, the expectation that \
problems can be solved quickly and easily. Similar to the MRI approach, this model also \
assumes that a therapist only has to cause a relatively small change in the client because a \
small change usually starts a process that leads to bigger changes. Solution-focused therapy \
is typically very brief-as short as three to four sessions. \
\
Solution-focused therapy is known for its use of several types of questions. First, the \
miracle question asks, "Suppose one night, while you were asleep, there was a miracle \
and this problem was solved. How would you know? What would be different?" Not only \
can this question foster a problem-solving approach, it can also help clients look beyond \
the problem to what they are really wanting. For example, a client who wants help with \
panic attacks realizes that what he really wants is to engage in more fun activities, which \
is something he can start doing even while he still has panic disorder. As a result, the panic \
\
