\
attacks become less of an obstacle in his life and may even lessen in severity. Second, the \
exception question asks clients to think about times when they didn't have the problem. \
so that they can discover what they were doing that was effective at that time. This question \
also helps foster a more positive outlook in which the problem is controllable. Finally, the \
scaling question simply asks clients to rate their problem on a scale of 0 to 10 (ten being \
how they will feel the day after the miracle). This question can help highlight small \
improvements and reduce all-or-nothing thinking. \
\
IX. NARRATIVE THERAPY \
\
Originated by Michael White, narrative therapy moves away from a systems view of \
problems. White argues that symptoms do not serve functions, but rather that they oppress \
people. Symptoms are thought to result from clients developing stories that are "problem- \
saturated descriptions," filled with a sense of powerlessness. \
\
White takes a directive role in helping clients to "re-story," by casting their difficulties as \
a "struggle for control" with a symptom. First, the symptom is externalized, as though it \
were an entity separate from the client. For example, a boy who is encopretic comes to call \
his problem "Sneaky Poo." Second, White asks questions to demonstrate "unique \
outcomes"-those successes that have been hidden by the focus on problems. For example, \
the encopretic boy is asked, "Can you recall an occasion when you could have given in to \
Sneaky Poo, but you didn't?" (This question and approach is very similar to the exception \
question in solution-focused therapy.) Finally, as change occurs, new questions are asked \
to strengthen and solidify the success and the new identity that emerges. For example, when \
the boy shares a success, White might ask, "What does this tell you about yourself that is \
important for you to know?" \
\
X. BEHAVIORAL AND COGNITIVE-BEHAVIORAL \
FAMILY THERAPY \
\
According to proponents of the behavioral family therapy model (e.g., Liberman, \
Patterson, and Alexander), normal family functioning results when adaptive behavior is \
rewarded, maladaptive behavior is not reinforced, and the benefits of being a member of \
the family outweigh costs. In troubled families, maladaptive behavior is reinforced by \
family attention, and there are insufficient rewards as well as communication deficits. \
Treatment focuses on concrete, observable behavioral goals. Key interventions include \
changing contingencies of social reinforcement and improving communication. \
\
\
\
