\
In cognitive-behavioral family therapy, relationship-related cognitions are seen as the \
underlying cause of the feelings and behavior of family members. Therapists assess the \
cognitive appraisals that family members make of each other, and then intervene to \
promote positive relationship-related cognitions that cause growth and adaptive \
functioning. \
\
XI. MARITAL BEHAVIORAL THERAPY \
\
Most marital behavior therapies share the following goals and techniques. First, a thorough \
behavioral analysis of the couple is completed. Second, positive reciprocity is established, \
which increases the couple's positive and loving behaviors toward each other. Third, \
communication skills are taught, including "I" statements, staying in the present, and \
positive feedback. Fourth, problem-solving skills are improved, including negotiation and \
contingency contracting. \
\
Richard Stuart, one of the pioneers of marital behavior therapy, developed an approach that \
combines operant learning principles with social exchange theory. According to the social \
exchange model, behavior in relationships is maintained by its ratio of costs and benefits. \
The daily and weekly behavioral exchanges that occur between spouses ultimately lead to \
satisfaction or dissatisfaction. This dynamic is addressed directly in therapy through \
contingency contracting, in which each spouse agrees to perform certain behaviors in \
exchange for the other spouse performing certain behaviors, a kind of quid pro quo. \
\
The overall aim of Stuart's therapy is to enhance positive behavioral change. He is \
particularly well known for his technique of caring days: one day of the week, a spouse \
deliberately performs behaviors that have been requested by the other spouse. The requests \
must be positive, specific, "small" (i.e., easily done in one day), and not a focus of current \
marital conflict. This technique is intended to increase positive reciprocity and \
commitment. \
\
