               5.8 GROUP THERAPY \
\
It is generally believed that a freely interacting process group, with few restrictions, will \
eventually develop into a social microcosm of the participant members. Group provides an \
excellent opportunity for clients to experience multiple simultaneous transferences. Within \
the context of a process group, clients thus have the opportunity to quickly demonstrate \
their interpersonal difficulties and pathology, \
\
According to Yalom, there are twelve distinct factors that contribute to the therapeutic \
benefits of being a part of a group: insight, the instillation of hope, universality, imparting \
information, altruism, corrective recapitulation of the primary family group, development \
of socializing techniques, imitative behavior, interpersonal learning, group cohesiveness, \
catharsis, and existential factors. Yalom contends that catharsis is a necessary but not \
sufficient condition for therapeutic change. There are several factors that Yalom believes \
do not contribute to group therapy's effectiveness, including leadership style, ideological \
school, and confrontation. \
\
Cohesiveness is considered to be the most critical component of successful group therapy. \
Cohesiveness is analogous to the relationship or rapport in individual therapy, and it is \
defined as the attractiveness of the group to its members. Cohesive groups show greater \
acceptance, intimacy and understanding, and also permit greater expression of hostility and \
conflict among members and towards leaders. \
\
The therapists' tasks include shaping the group into a therapeutic social system. Group \
norms are created as a result of explicit and implicit direction from the leaders as well as \
more influential group members. \
\
Yalom has proposed that process groups evolve through three stages. \
\
The initial stage is characterized by attempts of group members to get oriented. \
Participation is hesitant, with the content and communication style of group members being \
stereotyped and restricted. The group discusses topics of little personal significance and \
searches for commonalities. Members give and seek advice. In this stage, group members \
typically talk to the therapists, rather than with one another. \
\
\
\
                                 Section 5-Treatment/Intervention: Group Therapy \
\
The second stage is characterized by conflict among group members, rebellion toward \
group leaders, and attempts at dominance. \
\
If the second stage is successfully negotiated, the group enters the third stage. \
characterized by the development of closeness, intimacy and cohesion. During the third \
stage group members talk freely with one another. \
\
Yalom has proposed that in group therapy, appropriate open conflict or disagreement \
between the leaders is healthy and can be a positive model for group members. \
Additionally, self-disclosure by group leaders is frequently beneficial to group participants. \
\
Selection of members for process-oriented outpatient groups should typically exclude \
individuals who have suffered brain damage, have hypochondriasis, are sociopaths, are \
acutely psychotic, or are actively using drugs and alcohol. Research has demonstrated that \
participants most likely to drop out early include persons who have significant denial, a \
high degree of somatization, lower motivation, severe pathology, lower SES, lower IQ, and \
are generally less likable. Overall, clients with the fewest skills are the most likely to fail \
in groups. \
\
Group composition should ideally consist of members who are heterogeneous in terms of \
conflict, and homogeneous in terms of ego strength. Ideal group size is about seven or \
eight, with an acceptable range of five to ten members. \
\
Conducting group therapy raises ethical issues with regard to confidentiality. While it is \
impossible to mandate and enforce confidentiality, the importance of confidentiality should \
be brought up early on, and members should periodically be reminded of it. Confidentiality \
is enforced on an "honor system." \
\
