            5.9 CRISIS INTERVENTION \
\
A crisis is an internally experienced, acute disturbance resulting from a person's inability \
to cope with events experienced. Crisis theory centers on the concept of homeostatic \
equilibrium. At equilibrium, the individual is in a relative state of psychosocial balance, \
where the person's usual coping techniques are operating sufficiently to handle daily \
problems. During a crisis, the person is faced with an obstacle that is, for a time, \
insurmountable by the person's customary methods of problem solving. \
\
Caplan has delineated four phases of a typical crisis situation: 1) when the crisis begins, \
the person feels emotional tension and disorganization, and tries to manage the situation \
by previously learned coping mechanisms; 2) these coping efforts fail to resolve the \
problem and further disorganization occurs; 3) there is a greatly increased tension level \
with further mobilization of internal and outside resources, perhaps help-seeking and/or a \
change of direction and goals; and 4) if these intensified efforts fail to resolve the crisis, \
extensive personality disorganization and emotional breakdown may occur. \
\
The most crucial aspect of crisis intervention is rapid treatment, with the goal of resolving \
the crisis and avoiding the development of chronic symptoms. Specific elements of \
treatment include: rapidly establishing rapport with the client, reviewing the steps that have \
led to the crisis, helping the client to gain an understanding of his or her maladaptive \
reactions, and helping the client to develop more adaptive ways of dealing with the crisis. \
The client is also taught strategies to avoid hazardous situations that are likely to produce \
future crises. Crisis intervention is terminated as soon as it appears that the crisis has been \
resolved and that the client understands the steps that led to its development and resolution. \
\
Crisis intervention must be distinguished from short-term therapy. The focus in crisis \
intervention is on the crisis itself, and on restoring the client to the pre-crisis level of \
functioning. By contrast, short-term therapy focuses on helping the client to attain a higher \
level of functioning by addressing conflicts, interpersonal problems, and other long- \
standing issues. \
\
\
