      5.10 COMMUNITY INTERVENTIONS \
\
Community psychology focuses on the prevention, treatment and rehabilitation of mental \
disorders through the use of organized community programs. The community psychology \
movement has it roots in the 1963 Community Mental Health Centers Act, in which \
community mental health centers (CMHCs) were created to provide five services: \
inpatient, emergency, consultation, day care (including halfway houses and outpatient \
treatment), and research and education. \
\
In an effort to reach more people and intervene earlier, community psychology extends \
mental health's sphere of operations beyond hospitals and clinics to more natural settings, \
such as churches, schools, and inner-city storefronts. Community psychology also \
emphasizes mental health consultation and training of nonprofessionals, which can expand \
services exponentially. \
\
I. CONSULTATION \
\
Consultation is considered an indirect service in which a consultant shares knowledge and \
skills with providers, programs, agencies or organizations, rather than providing direct \
clinical care to individuals or groups. Caplan delineated four categories of consultation: \
client-centered case consultation, consultee-centered case consultation, consultee-centered \
administrative consultation, and program-centered administrative consultation. \
\
>CLIENT-CENTERED CASE CONSULTATION   In this type of consultation, the \
consultant helps the consultee with an individual client. The consultant may make an expert \
assessment of the client's problems and then suggest specific ways to handle the case. For \
example, a consultant helps a therapist develop a treatment plan for a child who is \
diagnosed with conduct disorder. \
\
>CONSULTEE-CENTERED CASE CONSULTATION    In consultee-centered case \
consultation, the consultant helps the consultee with difficulties he or she is having in \
working with clients, whether the problems stem from inexperience, lack of skill, or \
difficulties with objectivity. For example, a therapist who commonly experiences \
countertransference toward clients diagnosed with borderline personality disorder meets \
with a consultant to work on ways to address her reactions. \
