education and competence training. Examples of primary prevention include alcohol and \
drug education, Head Start, and vaccinations. \
\
>SECONDARY PREVENTION Secondary prevention focuses on early identification \
and prompt treatment of an illness or disorder that already exists. The goal of secondary \
prevention is to stop relatively mild disorders from becoming more serious and prolonged. \
Thus, secondary prevention reduces the prevalence of a disorder (the number of cases of \
the disorder present at any given time) by shortening a disorder's duration. Examples \
include mammograms, hotlines, aggressively treating children with conduct disorder to \
prevent the development of antisocial personality disorder, screening children for learning \
disabilities and providing special programs early on. prompt treatment of earthquake \
victims evidencing trauma, etc. \
\
>TERTIARY PREVENTION   Tertiary prevention focuses on reducing the residual \
effects of a chronic disability or minimizing further negative consequences of an \
established, serious disorder. Examples of tertiary prevention include vocational \
rehabilitation and day treatment centers for clients with schizophrenia, and 12-step \
programs for alcoholics or addicts. \
\
                   WHAT'S THE DIFFERENCE \
     PRIMARY VERSUS SECONDARY VERSUS TERTIARY PREVENTION \
\
Primary prevention prevents the problem or disorder from occurring altogether. In contrast, \
secondary prevention involves early identification of and aggressive treatment for a \
disorder or problem that already exists. Tertiary prevention is targeted at minimizing the \
long-term consequences of a chronic condition. \
