         5.11 GENERAL THERAPY ISSUES \
\
I. CHILD ABUSE \
\
The National Center on Child Abuse and Neglect estimates that one million children are \
maltreated each year, and that there are between 2,000 and 4,000 deaths each year caused \
by abuse and neglect. \
\
>PHYSICAL ABUSE Of children who are physically abused, roughly 32% are under age \
five, 27% are between five and nine, 27% are between 10 and 14, and 14% are between 15 \
and 18. More than half of all abused or neglected children are children who were born \
prematurely or had low birth weight. \
\
Abused children are typically perceived by their parents as developmentally slow, \
different, and hard to discipline. Hyperactive children are especially vulnerable to physical \
abuse. Most abused children come from poor, socially isolated homes, where the \
perpetrators have inappropriate expectations of their children. \
\
Most commonly, the perpetrator of physical abuse is female. About 80% of all perpetrators \
live in the homes of the abused child. Of children who are physically abused, about 80% \
live in homes with two parents, and 20% in single parent households. Ninety percent of \
perpetrators of physical abuse were severely abused as kids. Most abusers do not have a \
history of major psychiatric problems, although substance abuse is quite common. \
\
>SEXUAL ABUSE There are 150,000 - 200,000 new cases of child sexual abuse reported \
each year, which is probably a significant underestimate. A family member perpetrates \
approximately 50% of all cases of sexual abuse. The most common abusers are fathers, step- \
fathers, uncles, and older siblings. Father-daughter incest often involves a passive, weak or \
otherwise incapacitated mother, a daughter who takes on the maternal role, a father who \
abuses alcohol, and overcrowding. About 25% of the cases of sexual abuse involve children \
under the age of eight. Sexual abuse peaks between the ages of nine and twelve. \
\
\
\
                              Section 5 - Treatment/Intervention: General Therapy Issues \
\
II. DOMESTIC VIOLENCE \
\
>THE NATIONAL VIOLENCE AGAINST WOMEN SURVEY According to the \
National Violence Against Women Survey, published in July 2000 by the National Institute \
of Justice and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 25% of women surveyed and \
7.5% of men surveyed reported being raped or physically assaulted by an intimate partner at \
some point in their life. Based on these findings, it is estimated that every year some 1.5 \
million women and over 800,000 men are victims of domestic violence (also termed intimate \
partner violence). Violence against women is not only more common, it also tends to be more \
chronic and result in more serious injuries. The survey found higher rates of stalking than \
previously reported: 8% of women and 2% of men reported being stalked, leading to estimates \
of over 1 million stalkings a year. All forms of intimate partner violence appear underreported, \
however, especially by men. \
\
Although race and ethnicity have some bearing on the incidence of violence, their impact \
is lessened when other variables are controlled for. Reports of intimate partner violence do \
differ among types of relationships: 22% of women in heterosexual relationships, 11% of \
women in lesbian relationships, 23% of men in gay relationships, and 7% of men in \
heterosexual relationships reported being raped, physically assaulted or stalked. \
\
Violence often occurs along with emotionally abusive and controlling behaviors. In fact, \
the variable that best predicted the likelihood of violence was the presence of a verbally \
abusive partner. \
\
>OTHER FINDINGS ON DOMESTIC VIOLENCE Many reports indicate that spousal \
abuse occurs most frequently in concert with alcohol or crack abuse. Other reports suggest \
that occurrence of spousal abuse is not correlated with substance use per se, but that the \
severity of the abuse is. \
\
Abusive men are likely to have come from violent homes and have witnessed spousal \
abuse. Some reports suggest that they may have a higher rate of having been abused \
themselves. Abusers tend to be immature, dependent, nonassertive, and to generally feel \
inferior. The abusive act becomes self-reinforcing, with cycles of abuse continuing and \
escalating over time. \
\
The research suggests that change in the perpetrator of the abuse takes place only when the \
victim refuses to tolerate the situation any further. The best long-term results seem to \
follow arrest of the perpetrator. \
\
\
 \
\
                             Section 5-Treatment/Intervention: General Therapy Issues \
\
Some theorists differentiate between expressive and instrumental spousal abuse. \
Expressive abuse is less deliberate and results from difficulty managing emotions. \
Instrumental abuse is a more deliberate attempt to use violence as a means of control. \
Expressive abuse is more amenable to psychological treatment than instrumental abuse, \
but left untreated, expressive abuse typically becomes instrumental over time. \
\
III. RAPE \
\
Rape is an act of violence and humiliation. It is a way used by some to express power or \
anger. Sexual feelings are not typically central to the act. In fact, many men who rape \
experience sexual dysfunction during the act of rape itself. \
\
Rape often occurs in concert with another crime. Additionally, alcohol is involved at least \
50% of the time. Rape most commonly occurs within race. \
\
Rape is highly underreported, with possibly only one in ten cases reported. Most rapes are \
premeditated, with about one-third by strangers and two-thirds by perpetrators known to \
the victim. The victim being raped is frequently in a life-threatening situation and sequelae \
include shame, humiliation, confusion, fear, and rage, feelings which typically last a year \
or longer. \
\
IV. DIVORCE \
\
It is estimated that 40-50% of all marriages in the United States end in divorce. At the time \
of divorce, children of divorce tend to have more social, academic, and behavioral \
problems than children from intact homes. Some children of divorce become aggressive, \
withdrawn, or lose interest in schoolwork and socializing. \
\
The age of the child at the time of divorce can affect his or her reactions. Younger children \
are more anxious at the time of the divorce and have less realistic expectations of what \
caused it, but they adapt more quickly and have fewer bad memories than children who are \
older at the time of divorce. Typically, three to six-year-olds feel responsible and seven to \
twelve-year-olds show decreases in school performance. Adolescents feel they could have \
prevented the divorce but, at the same time, they also feel hurt by and are critical of their \
parents. In general, recovery from divorce takes children from three to five years. While \
most children of divorce adjust reasonably well, up to one-third experience lasting trauma. \
\
\
\
