       5.12 PSYCHOTHERAPY OUTCOME \
                      RESEARCH \
\
The most extensive and comprehensive research that looks at psychotherapy outcome are \
meta-analytic studies. A meta-analysis applies the methods and principles of empirical \
research to the process of reviewing the literature. The findings of individual studies are \
quantified in a common way, by using an effect size. An effect size is a measure of standard \
deviation units of difference between treated and untreated subjects. \
\
The earliest comprehensive research of therapy outcome was that of Eysenck (1952), in \
which he reported that two thirds of all neurotics improved over a two-year period whether \
or not they received treatment. He also noted that treated people actually seemed to do \
worse than non-treated people. Eysenck's study has been widely criticized for non-random \
assignment to the treatment versus no treatment condition, providing attention to the so- \
called non-treated people (which could account for their improvement), and the lack of \
distinction between therapists administering treatment. \
\
Since Eysenck's time it has been suggested that the spontaneous improvement rate is closer \
to 40% (Bergin & Lambert, 1978). Furthermore, subsequent meta-analytic studies (e.g., \
Smith, Glass, and Miller, 1980), have found an average effect size of .85 in comparing \
treated and untreated individuals. This indicates that at the end of treatment, the average \
treated person is better off than 80% of the untreated sample. \
\
In a meta-analytic study (Howard, et. al., 1986), 50% of clients were measurably improved \
by the eighth session, and 75% of clients were measurably improved by the end of six \
months. Another finding of meta-analysis is that treatment gains are generally maintained, \
and they are maintained regardless of the length of follow-up. In comparing different types \
of treatment, Luborsky et. al. (1975) suggested that treatment outcomes are essentially \
similar for all types of treatment. \
\
>TREATMENT MANUALS AND EVIDENCE-BASED TREATMENT (EBT) Due to \
both scientific and economic considerations, research into evidence-based treatments has \
become increasingly popular. Division 12 of the American Psychological Association has \
published a list of treatments that have been empirically validated for specific disorders. These \
treatments are further ranked by how strong the research support is, e.g., "well-established," \
"probably efficacious." \
\
\
\
                         Section 3 - Treatment/Intervention: Psychotherapy Outcome Research \
\
The majority of well-established treatments are of short-term duration, use a behavioral or \
cognitive-behavioral approach and make use of treatment manuals. Treatment manuals \
provide standardized protocols to treat specific disorders. They facilitate research because \
they minimize differences in treatment that might occur when different therapists provide \
treatment or when therapists tailor treatment to the needs of a specific client. By decreasing \
the threat of variability in procedures, adherence to a treatment protocol increases the \
likelihood that statistical significance will be found. Treatment manuals also facilitate the \
dissemination of proven treatments to the general community of mental health \
practitioners. They simplify training requirements and even make it possible for less highly \
trained practitioners to provide appropriate treatment. \
\
Despite its advantages, the treatment manual approach also receives much criticism. First, \
many treatments approaches do not lend themselves to short-term standardized formats. \
Treatments that are probably efficacious are therefore not studied and validated. Second, \
treatment manuals prevent practitioners from tailoring treatment to the specific needs and \
 strengths of individual clients. \
\
The evidence-based (empirically validated) treatment approach comes under broader \
criticisms as well. EBT depends on efficacy research, in which tight experimental control \
maximizes internal validity. In addition to relying on short-term manualized treatment, \
efficacy studies typically recruit volunteers with easily diagnosed and uncomplicated \
disorders. Volunteers with co-morbid disorders or ambiguous diagnoses are not accepted. \
Finally, a treatment may be considered effective even when it fails to help over 30% of \
those who complete treatment. Efficacy studies are therefore criticized for not reflecting \
the real world of psychotherapy and psychotherapy clients. In other words, they are \
comparatively low in external validity or generalizability. In contrast, effectiveness \
research studies psychotherapy as it is actually practiced by practitioners in the real world. \
Compared to the numerous well-done efficacy studies, there are only a few effectiveness \
studies, which take longer and are more cumbersome. \
\
One of the best effectiveness studies was the 1995 Consumer Reports study, which \
analyzed the responses of 7,000 people to questionnaires about mental health treatment. \
This report concluded that clients benefited very substantially from psychotherapy, with \
90% of treated clients doing well. Long-term treatments yielded better outcomes than \
short-term treatments. Clients receiving medication as well as therapy did not benefit more \
than clients receiving therapy alone. Furthermore, no specific modality led to better \
outcomes for any disorder. Psychiatrists, psychologists, and social workers did not differ \
in effectiveness. However, they all did better than marriage counselors and long-term \
