family doctoring. Clients whose length of therapy or choice of therapist was limited by \
insurance or managed care did worse. \
\
There were many limitations to the Consumer Reports study, including the absence of a \
control group, non-random assignment, possible biased sampling, and reliance on \
retrospective self-report. Interestingly, many of the study's findings contradict those of \
efficacy studies. For example, in most efficacy studies, approximately 65% of clients \
improve, and short-term treatment appears to be highly effective. Some conclude that this \
discrepancy means that therapy outcomes may differ in the laboratory versus "in the field." \
Others attribute it to differences in research methodology. \
\
>CLIENT VARIABLES Client variables make up the largest contribution to therapeutic \
outcome, much larger than specific treatment methods or the therapy relationship. Key \
variables include the client's ability to relate and the client's amenability to new learning. Sue \
et al. (1976) examined issues of client variables in terms of dropout and outcome. They found \
that 23% of clients starting therapy dropped out after the first session and 70% dropped out \
before the tenth session. Overall, individuals of lower social classes and with less education \
drop out earlier and more frequently than those of higher SES and with more education. \
Persons of lower SES and education also tend to be assigned to less experienced therapists. \
African Americans tend to terminate earlier than Whites, but these findings are inconclusive \
and may relate to social class variables. Overall, social class affects duration of treatment but \
it appears to have no effect on outcome. \
\
Sex and age have been found to be unrelated to length of treatment or outcome. Overall, \
clients with symptoms of anxiety and depression improve the most, and those with somatic \
complaints improve the least. Likeability and attractiveness of clients is correlated with a \
positive outcome. \
\
>THERAPIST VARIABLES Non-technical aspects of therapists appear to be the most \
influential in affecting outcome. In terms of gender, it appears that treatment is facilitated with \
a female therapist or when client and therapist are of the same gender. Overall, there is \
relatively little difference in outcome whether client and therapist are matched for ethnicity. \
Nevertheless, clients seem to prefer therapists of their own ethnicity and may participate more \
in the early stages of treatment; thus there may be fewer premature terminations. Therapist \
attractiveness, trustworthiness, and expertness account for 35% of the outcome variance. \
Therapist competence does seem to have some impact on outcome, with more experienced \
therapists having a lower treatment dropout rate. \
\
\
