>THE THERAPY RELATIONSHIP   Substantial research has demonstrated that the \
quality of the therapy relationship is as important, and sometimes more important to \
psychotherapy outcome than the method of treatment used. The Psychotherapy Division of \
APA (Division 29) has issued an updated report (2011) which concludes that several aspects \
of the therapy relationship can now be considered as "demonstrably effective." These include \
the therapeutic alliance in individual, youth, and family psychotherapy; cohesion in group \
therapy; empathy; and collecting client feedback. Aspects deemed to be "probably effective" \
included goal consensus, collaboration, and positive regard. Aspects deemed "promising but \
insufficient research to judge" included congruence/genuineness, repairing alliance ruptures, \
and managing countertransference. \
\
>SOME GENERAL RESEARCH FINDINGS   People seem to do as well in therapy \
whether they are seen for individual therapy or in group therapy. People over the age of 65 \
have the lowest rates of psychiatric disorders, with the most common disorder being dementia. \
People between the ages of 45 and 64 have the next lowest rate of psychiatric problems. \
Individuals between the ages of 25 and 44 have the highest rates of psychiatric disturbance. \
\
Women are more likely than men are to seek treatment for psychiatric problems. Married \
men and women present less frequently for treatment and seem to have less \
psychopathology as compared with divorced or single individuals. Rates of psychiatric \
disorders are lower for college than non-college graduates, and for suburban and rural \
rather than inner-city inhabitants. \
