                     6.1 OVERVIEW \
\
  Research design refers to the specific setup of a research study. Key issues include the \
  selection of variables (independent and dependent), the types of research (experimental, \
  quasi-experimental, and non-experimental), design strategies (group and single subject), \
  time frames, and sampling procedures. \
\
  I. INDEPENDENT VARIABLES (IVS) AND DEPENDENT \
  VARIABLES (DVS) \
\
  >INDEPENDENT VARIABLES (IVS) Independent variables form the basis of the \
  groups that are being compared. For example, when three treatments for depression are \
  being contrasted, type of treatment is one iv. If males and females are being compared, \
  gender is one iv. \
\
  There are two main types of IVs-IVs that are directly manipulated by the researcher, and \
  IVs that are pre-existing and therefore cannot be manipulated by the researcher. \
\
       MANIPULATED IVs Independent variables that are manipulated are commonly \
       termed environmental or situational variables. For example, in contrasting three \
       treatments for depression (cognitive-behavioral, psychodynamic, and medications), \
       the IV is type of treatment and it is a manipulated IV. \
\
       NON-MANIPULATED IVs Subject or individual difference variables refer to \
       independent variables that cannot be manipulated by the researcher because they \
       are pre-existing. For example, in contrasting men and women, the IV of gender \
       cannot be manipulated. \
\
  \
 \
\
                                      Section 6 - Research Design: Overview \
\
>DEPENDENT VARIABLES Dependent variables are the outcome measures selected. \
For example, level of depression can be measured with scores on the beck depression \
inventory. Dependent variables can be nominal, ordinal, interval, or ratio. \
\
II. TYPES OF RESEARCH \
\
>TRUE EXPERIMENTAL The hallmark of true experimental research is that at least \
one iv is manipulated and subjects are randomly assigned. For example, a study is \
conducted to compare the effects of two types of treatment for anxiety. In this situation, \
the iv of treatment is manipulated, and the subjects are randomly assigned to one of the \
two treatment groups. \
\
>QUASI-EXPERIMENTAL In quasi-experimental research, at least one iv is \
manipulated, but there is non-random assignment of subjects, typically because subjects \
are already in pre-existing groups. For example, an experiment investigating the effects of \
two different treatments might administer one treatment to the patients of a hospital ward \
(ward a) and a second treatment to the patients of a different hospital ward (ward b). \
Because the wards were pre-existing and the patients weren't randomly assigned to the \
treatment groups, this design would be considered quasi-experimental. \
\
>OBSERVATIONAL, PASSIVE OR NON-EXPERIMENTAL In observational. \
passive, or non-experimental research, there is no intervention or manipulation. These \
studies are sometimes called correlational, but this is a misnomer because they do not use \
statistics of correlation (e.g., pearson r) but rather statistics that detect group differences \
(e.g., anova). An example of such a design would be a study comparing the extent of \
cigarette smoking in adolescent males and females. In this study the iv is gender, which \
cannot be manipulated. The dv is extent of cigarette smoking. \
\
III. DESIGN STRATEGIES AND MEASUREMENT \
\
A. GROUP DESIGNS \
\
When conducting research with groups of subjects, the design can be either a between \
groups design, a within subjects design, or a mixed design. \
\
>BETWEEN GROUPS DESIGN   The between groups design only compares groups \
that are independent. An example would be a study looking at the differences in reading \
levels of two different classes of second grade students. \
\
\
\
                                      Section 6 - Research Design: Overview \
\
>WITHIN SUBJECTS DESIGN In a within subjects design, the groups contrasted are \
correlated or related. There are three conditions that lead to correlated data: 1) subjects are \
repeatedly measured ("repeated measures"); 2) subjects have been matched prior to their \
assignment to the groups; or 3) subjects have an inherent relationship (e.g .. pairs of \
identical twins). \
\
A specific subtype of the repeated measures design involves subjects that are exposed to \
several different interventions or conditions, in sequence. For example, a researcher is \
looking at differences in ability to remember nouns, verbs, and nonsense syllables. All \
subjects are given all three types of word lists to remember. Because of possible carryover \
effects, this research requires counterbalancing, whereby subjects are divided into thirds. \
One group receives nonsense syllables first, the second receives nouns first, and the third \
receives verbs first. The Latin Square is the most sophisticated form of counterbalancing. \
\
>MIXED DESIGN A mixed design involves groups that are both independent and \
correlated. For example, patients are assigned to two different treatment groups for \
depression which are later compared (independent groups). Each group is also measured \
before and after treatment (correlated groups or repeated measures). \
\
B. SINGLE SUBJECT DESIGNS \
\
The hallmark of the single subject design is that one or very few subjects are studied \
intensively, and each subject is measured many times, typically during baseline as well as \
during treatment. Single subject approaches are referred to as idiographie; in contrast, \
group approaches are termed nomothetic. Single subject designs include the AB, ABAB, \
multiple baseline, simultaneous treatment, and the changing criterion. \
\
A significant problem associated with any single subject design is autocorrelation, or the \
effect of measuring the same person repeatedly, which results in highly correlated data. \
\
>AB DESIGN In an AB design, a baseline condition (A) is followed by a treatment \
condition (B). For example, a subject is trying to lose weight. Her weight is recorded \
repeatedly during the baseline phase, and then her weight continues to be recorded during \
the prescribed dietary intervention phase (i.e., treatment condition). The most significant \
problem associated with the AB design is the threat of history. Specifically, when \
improvement is noted, it is hard to determine whether it was the intervention that caused \
the change or some other event (e.g., treatment began during the summer and the subject \
always eats less when the weather is hot). \
\
\
 \
\
                                      Section 6 - Research Design: Overview \
\
>ABAB DESIGN In the ABAB design, baseline and treatment conditions are alternated \
in the following sequence: baseline (A), treatment (B), baseline (A), treatment (B). For \
example, an autistic child engages in head banging. The number of episodes of head \
banging is recorded daily, for at least one week, during the baseline phase. While treatment \
is implemented over the course of several weeks, the number of episodes of head banging \
continues to be recorded daily. Then, treatment is temporarily discontinued (return to \
baseline) and the incidence of head banging continues to be monitored daily. Finally, \
treatment is resumed and head-banging episodes are still recorded daily. \
\
The ABAB design protects against the threat of history. If the expected pattern of change \
is found (e.g., less head banging during treatment, more head banging during baseline), it \
is highly unlikely to be caused by a factor external to treatment. The two problems \
associated with the ABAB design are failure of the dependent variable (which is being \
measured daily) to return to baseline, and issues of ethics with regard to removing treatment \
that is effective. \
\
>MULTIPLE BASELINE DESIGN The multiple baseline design involves research in \
which treatment is applied sequentially or consecutively across subjects, situations, or \
behaviors. The multiple baseline design resolves the problems associated with AB and \
ABAB designs, but it tends to be more time consuming and expensive. \
\
     MULTIPLE BASELINE ACROSS SUBJECTS An example of a multiple \
     baseline across subjects design would involve research looking at the effect of \
     medication on hyperactivity for three different children with ADHD. All three \
     children are measured repeatedly during the initial baseline phase (e.g., daily for \
     one week). The first child is then given medication and monitored daily, while the \
     second and third children continue to be measured daily without any treatment \
     (baseline continues). The second child is then given medication and monitored \
     daily, while the third child continues to be monitored without any treatment \
     (baseline continues). After the second child's treatment is well under way, the third \
     child is put on medication. \
\
     MULTIPLE BASELINE ACROSS SITUATIONS An example of multiple \
     baseline across situations would involve applying an intervention to one problem \
     behavior of one subject in three different settings or situations (e.g., a behavioral \
     intervention for tantrums at home, at school, and in the park). Treatment would \
     again be applied consecutively. \
\
\
\
                                      Section 6 - Research Design: Overview \
\
     MULTIPLE BASELINE ACROSS BEHAVIORS An example of multiple \
     baseline across behaviors would involve an intervention for three problem \
     behaviors of one subject. The intervention would be applied first to one problem \
     behavior (e.g., head banging), next to the second behavior (e.g., rocking), and \
     finally to the third behavior (self-biting). \
\
>SIMULTANEOUS (ALTERNATING) TREATMENT DESIGN The simultaneous \
or alternating treatment design involves two or more interventions implemented \
concurrently during the treatment phase. Treatments are balanced and varied across time \
of day. This allows for comparison of the relative effectiveness of two or more \
interventions for an individual. For example, the effectiveness of two behavioral \
interventions to decrease head banging (e.g., M & M's versus praise) could be contrasted \
by alternating them during the day and balancing them across different days. \
\
>CHANGING CRITERION DESIGN In the changing criterion design, an attempt is \
made to change behavior in increments to match a changing criterion. For example, a \
person who drinks ten cups of coffee per day would like to dramatically cut back. To help \
this person reduce or eliminate coffee consumption, the researcher would first set the \
criterion at eight cups of coffee per day. Once the person is only drinking eight cups per \
day, the criterion would be changed to six cups per day, and so forth, until the person no \
longer drinks coffee. \
\
C. BEHAVIORAL MEASUREMENT \
\
>TIME SAMPLING Time sampling is a type of behavioral measurement that is useful \
when a behavior is not discrete, and thus has no distinct beginning and end. The two types of \
time sampling are momentary time sampling and whole-interval sampling. Time sampling \
would be appropriate, for example, when measuring to what extent a person attended to a \
speaker during a lecture. Time sampling involves breaking the period of interest into smaller \
periods of time (e.g., the two-hour lecture is broken into one-minute intervals). \
\
     MOMENTARY TIME SAMPLING Momentary time sampling involves the \
     observer simply recording whether the target behavior is present or absent at the \
     moment that the time interval ends. \
\
     WHOLE-INTERVAL SAMPLING Whole-interval sampling (also called interval \
     sampling or interval recording) involves scoring target behavior positively only if it \
     is exhibited for the full duration of the time interval. \
\
\
 \
\
