\
>EVENT RECORDING Event recording or sampling involves tallying the number of \
times the target behavior occurred. It is useful when the target behavior is discrete and occurs \
relatively infrequently (e.g., counting the number of times that a student arrived to school \
late). \
\
IV. CONDITIONS OF EXPERIMENTATION \
\
>ANALOGUE RESEARCH Analogue research evaluates treatment under conditions \
that only resemble or approximate clinical situations. Typically, the problems studied are \
less severe. For example, the participants are college students and volunteers, the therapists \
are graduate students, and treatments tend to be highly standardized. Analogue research \
allows for tight experimental control but limited generalizability. \
\
>CLINICAL TRIALS Clinical trials refer to outcome investigations conducted in clinical \
settings. Due to being conducted in clinical settings, some methodological compromises \
and sacrifices often have to be made. \
\
V. TIME FRAME \
\
>CROSS-SECTIONAL RESEARCH Cross-sectional research looks at differences \
across sections (e.g., different ages) by sampling subjects from the age categories of \
interest, at one point in time. For example, a study looks at how much time persons spend \
on the internet in groups of persons of different ages (e.g., 20-year-olds, 40-year-olds, and \
60-year-olds). Cross-sectional research is subject to problems with cohort effects. In the \
example given, it may be the case that persons who are younger use the internet more than \
those who are older, simply because they have grown up with computers. This would be \
an example of a cohort effect. \
\
>LONGITUDINAL RESEARCH Longitudinal research involves following a group of \
subjects over many years in order to understand the changes that take place as people age. \
An example would be tracking a group of people from infancy through old age and looking \
at changes in savings habits. Problems with longitudinal research include significant \
expense and high dropout rates. \
\
>CROSS-SEQUENTIAL RESEARCH Cross-sequential or cohort-sequential research \
attempts to correct for problems associated with both cross-sectional and longitudinal \
research. Cross-sequential research takes several cross sections (e.g. Of age groups) and \
follows them over much briefer periods of time. An example would be a study looking at \
health habits across the life span. Rather than studying several groups of persons of \
