individuals over their entire lifespan (longitudinal research), groups of persons at different \
ages would be tracked for a period of five to ten years. \
\
VI. SAMPLING PROCEDURES \
\
One of the most important issues in subject selection is that subjects be a representative \
sample of the population. The major selection strategies include simple random sampling. \
stratified random sampling, proportional sampling, systematic sampling, and cluster \
sampling. \
\
>SIMPLE RANDOM SAMPLING In simple random sampling, every member of the \
population has an equal chance of being randomly selected. For example, in a study of \
registered voters in California, voters would be randomly selected from the roster of all \
registered voters, thereby ensuring that every registered voter in California had an equal \
chance of being selected. \
\
>STRATIFIED RANDOM SAMPLING In stratified random sampling, the population \
is first divided into strata (e.g., age levels, income levels, ethnic groups), and then a random \
sample of equal size from each stratum is selected. An example would be first dividing the \
population into various different SES levels, and then selecting equal numbers of subjects \
from each SES level. \
\
>PROPORTIONAL SAMPLING In proportional sampling, individuals are randomly \
selected in proportion to their representation in the general population. For example, a \
given population is 85% White, 10% Hispanic, and 5% African American. The subject \
pool selected from this population would then be 85% White, 10% Hispanic, and 5% \
African American. \
\
>SYSTEMATIC SAMPLING Systematic sampling involves selecting every kth element \
after a random start, e.g., if 100 out of 1000 persons are needed, every tenth person is \
selected. Such sampling needs to be arranged in such a way that it is not biased. \
\
>CLUSTER SAMPLING Cluster sampling involves identifying naturally occurring \
groups of subjects (clusters) and randomly selecting certain clusters (e.g., classes at a \
university or schools within a particular school district). Once the clusters have been \
selected, all subjects within each cluster are surveyed. For example, a psychologist wants \
to study achievement in 8th graders in the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD). \
\
