      6.2 THREATS IN RESEARCH DESIGN \
\
 The goal of research is to draw inferences about the relationships among variables. \
 Experimentation attempts to minimize ambiguity in reaching these inferences. Factors that \
 can interfere with drawing clear conclusions are considered to be threats. They include \
 threats to internal validity, threats to construct validity, threats to external validity, and \
 threats to statistical conclusion validity. \
\
 I. THREATS TO INTERNAL VALIDITY \
\
 Ideally, when differences between groups are found, researchers can conclude that the \
 intervention (IV) caused the change in outcome (DV). Threats to internal validity refer to \
 factors other than the IV that may have caused the change in the DV. \
\
 >HISTORY History refers to specific incidents that intervene between measuring points, \
 either in or outside of the experimental situation. For example, an intervention targeted at \
 increasing earthquake preparedness is implemented with a group of subjects (e.g., they \
 view a movie). The subjects' level of preparedness is measured and compared before and \
 after the intervention. If a sizable earthquake were to occur between measurement periods, \
 it would not be clear if an increase in preparedness were due to the intervention or to history \
 (i.e., the earthquake that occurred outside of the experimental situation). The best control \
 for history is a control group. \
\
 >MATURATION Maturation refers to factors that affect the subjects' performance \
 because of the passing of time (fatigue, maturing). For example, a group of young children \
 is put in a two-year program to help them develop greater coordination for sports. It would \
 be difficult to determine whether the program actually helped improve coordination or \
 whether the children's coordination improved simply because of biological maturation. \
 The best control for maturation is also a control group. \
\
>TESTING OR TEST PRACTICE Testing or test practice occurs when familiarity with \
 testing affects scores on repeated testing. For example, a group of children is measured on \
 a novel task. They are then given the intervention and retested. They show significant \
 improvement on the task upon retesting. It is not clear if the improvement is due to the \
 intervention or to the effects of test practice. The best control for testing is the Solomon \
 Four-Group design. \
