 The Solomon Four-Group design involves dividing subjects into four groups. One group \
 is measured pre and post and gets the intervention in between. The second group is \
 measured pre and post, but does not get the intervention. The third group is measured post \
 only and gets the intervention. The fourth group is measured post only and does not get the \
 intervention. \
\
>INSTRUMENTATION Instrumentation refers to changes in observers or the calibration \
 of equipment. An example of a problem with instrumentation is that biofeedback electrodes \
(especially GSR) tend to show reductions in scores as the equipment wears out. In research \
 designed to look at the effects of a relaxation intervention, it would be difficult to ascertain \
 whether observed reductions in GSR might be due to the effects of treatment or to problems \
 with instrumentation. A control group would correct for this problem. \
\
>STATISTICAL REGRESSION Statistical regression, or regression to the mean, is the \
tendency for extreme scores (scores very much above or below the mean) to become less \
 extreme (closer to the mean) on retesting, even without any type of intervention. For \
example, subjects who scored extremely high on the Beck Depression Inventory (BDI) \
 would most likely score a bit lower upon a second administration of the BDI. So, if a \
 depression treatment were targeted at persons who scored extremely high on the BDI, it \
 would be difficult to determine if any reductions in score were actually due to treatment or \
simply to the effects of regression to the mean. A control group is the best way to manage \
 possible problems related to statistical regression. \
\
>SELECTION BIAS Selection bias is caused by non-random assignment. For example, \
 if the first twenty subjects who volunteer for a research study are assigned to one treatment, \
 and the second twenty subjects who volunteer are assigned to a different treatment, any \
 differences found between the groups may not only be due to the effects of treatment but \
 may also be due to differences in the type of subjects who volunteer early versus late. \
 Problems due to selection are best avoided by using random assignment. \
\
 >ATTRITION OR EXPERIMENTAL MORTALITY    Attrition or experimental \
 mortality is a concern when there is a differential loss of subjects from the groups. For \
 example, less depressed subjects may drop out of the control group while more depressed \
 subjects may drop out of the treatment group. As a consequence, the treatment group \
 appears less depressed at the end of treatment. However, the apparent lower level of \
 depression may not be due to the effects of treatment but rather to the pattern of attrition. \
 To assess for problems of attrition, subjects who drop out should be compared on relevant \
 variables by running t-tests. \
\
 \
\
                                        Section 6 - Research Design : Threats \
\
>DIFFUSION Diffusion occurs when the no-treatment group actually gets some of the \
 treatment, thus clouding treatment effects. For example, anxious subjects are assigned to \
 two groups. One group receives specific cognitive-behavioral interventions for anxiety \
 reduction, while the other group merely receives non-specific elements of therapy, such as \
 reflective statements. However, during the research, some cognitive strategies are \
 inadvertently discussed in the control group. At the end of the study, anxiety seems to be \
 lessened in both groups of subjects. While it is hard to completely eliminate the problem \
 of diffusion, tighter control over the experimental situation can help. \
\
 II. THREATS TO CONSTRUCT VALIDITY \
\
 If an experiment has good internal validity and it can be concluded that the intervention \
 (e.g., cognitive-behavioral therapy) did cause a change in the DV (e.g., level of depression), \
 it is still important to ascertain whether it was the intended factor (e.g., eliciting automatic \
 thoughts) that caused the effect, or whether it was something else (e.g., attention). \
 Construct validity (as described by Kazdin) refers to factors other than the desired specifics \
 of our intervention that result in differences. These factors are often lumped under threats \
 to external validity. \
\
>ATTENTION AND CONTACT WITH CLIENTS Attention and contact with clients \
 can be a threat, for example, in an experiment intended to assess the effectiveness of a \
 particular therapy technique. In this situation, it is hard to tell whether the change in the \
 patients is due to the actual technique used, or is merely due to contact with the therapist. \
\
 >EXPERIMENTER EXPECTANCIES Experimenter expectancies, also known as the \
 Rosenthal effect, refer to the cues or clues transmitted to the subjects by the experimenter. \
 For example, when interviewing subjects about their symptoms of depression, the \
 experimenter inadvertently smiles and nods encouragingly only at those subjects who \
 received the actual medication, which then results in these subjects reporting more \
 improvement. Having the experimenter blind to the subjects' treatment condition can \
 control for this threat. \
\
>DEMAND CHARACTERISTICS Demand characteristics are factors in the procedures \
 that suggest how the subject should behave. For example, subjects given medication are \
 told that the medication might cause certain side effects, and in fact subjects then report \
 more side effects. By contrast, subjects given the placebo are told there won't be any side \
 effects, and they then report no side effects. To reduce demand characteristics, subjects \
 should be blind to their treatment condition. \
\
 \
 \
\
                                        Section 6 - Research Design: Threats \
\
>JOHN HENRY EFFECT The John Henry effect, also called compensatory rivalry, \
occurs when persons in a control group try harder than usual in the spirit of competition \
with the experimental group. In this situation, members of the control group may actually \
outperform persons in the experimental or treatment group. John Henry was a legendary \
railroad steel driver, who swung his hammer in competition with a steam drill. He \
outperformed the steam drill, although he later died from overexertion. To control or \
eliminate the John Henry effect, the experimental and control groups should not know \
about each other. If this is not possible, the groups should not be given any sense of \
competition. \
\
III. THREATS TO EXTERNAL VALIDITY \
\
When significant findings are obtained, it is important to ascertain whether the results can \
be generalized from the sample studied to the population. Factors that interfere with \
generalizability are called threats to external validity. \
\
>SAMPLE CHARACTERISTICS Sample characteristics refer to differences between \
the sample and the population. For examples, volunteers used to study the effect of a \
particular intervention for sleep problems may somehow differ from the population of \
persons with sleep problems who do not volunteer for research. Volunteers may be more \
enthusiastic, more compliant, more willing to engage in treatment, etc. It would therefore \
be difficult to generalize from the sample of volunteers to the population of interest. \
\
>STIMULUS CHARACTERISTICS Stimulus characteristics, such as artificial research \
arrangements, are features of the study with which the intervention is associated. For \
example, research assessing memory functioning in the laboratory may not be \
generalizable to memory functioning in naturalistic settings. In fact, the elderly generally \
demonstrate much better memory ability on real-world tasks than laboratory tasks. \
\
>CONTEXTUAL CHARACTERISTICS    Contextual characteristics refer to the \
conditions in which the intervention is imbedded. Reactivity is a significant threat to \
external validity. Reactivity occurs when subjects behave in a certain way just because \
they are participating in research and being observed. The Hawthorne effect is a \
frequently described example of reactivity. \
\
\
\
                                       Section 6 - Research Design: Threats \
\
IV. THREATS TO STATISTICAL CONCLUSION \
VALIDITY \
\
If statistically significant results are not obtained, it is important to look at whether the \
treatment was ineffective, or whether the lack of significant findings was due to statistical \
problems. \
\
Threats to statistical validity include low power, unreliability of measures, variability in \
procedures, and subject heterogeneity. \
\
>LOW POWER Low power is defined as a diminished ability to find significant results. \
Factors that can contribute to low power include small sample size and inadequate \
interventions (e.g., treatment for depression lasting only two sessions). \
\
>UNRELIABILITY OF MEASURES Even if the intervention is effective, significant \
differences may not be found if the outcome measure used is unreliable. \
\
>VARIABILITY IN PROCEDURES Variability in procedures refers to inconsistency \
in treatment procedures, which can obscure significant treatment findings. This threat is \
especially of concern in psychotherapy outcome research. \
\
>SUBJECT HETEROGENEITY Subject heterogeneity makes it more difficult to find \
significance differences between groups. In research looking for differences, the greater \
the subject heterogeneity (e.g., subjects vary in age from 15 to 60, or varying significantly \
in terms of diagnosis), the less the likelihood is of finding significance. \
\
V. INTERRELATIONS OF THREATS \
\
Using a control group and random assignment can minimize most threats to internal \
validity. The dilemma is that the more controlled or precise the experiment is, the less \
generalizable it is likely to be, or put differently, the greater the internal validity, the lower \
the external validity. \
\
