 C. STANDARD SCORES \
\
Standard scores are based on the standard deviation of the sample. Examples include z- \
scores, t-scores, IQ scores, SAT scores, and EPPP scores. Z-scores are the most basic \
standard scores in that they correspond directly to standard deviation (SD) units. Z-scores \
 have a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one. For example, a z-score of +2 \
represents a score that is 2 SDs above the mean. The shape of the z-score distribution is \
 always identical to the shape of the raw score distribution. Transforming raw scores into z- \
scores does not normalize a distribution. \
\
 In any distribution, the area under the curve represents 100% of people. In most \
 distributions, the area under the curve consists of values that are +/- 3 SDs, which is to say \
 that almost 100% of the people will have scores between +/- 3SDs from the mean. In any \
 normal distribution, z-scores (or standard deviations) always correspond to the same \
