      6.7 SELECTING STATISTICAL TESTS \
\
In deciding what statistical test is appropriate to analyze a given set of data, a researcher \
(or EPPP candidate) must first tease out what type of question is being addressed in the \
research. Three questions are commonly asked in research: questions of difference \
(analyzed with Chi-square, Mann-Whitney, t-test, ANOVA, etc.); questions of relationship \
and prediction (analyzed with Pearson r, Biserial, multiple regression, etc.); and questions \
of structure or fit (analyzed with principal components or factor analysis, cluster analysis). \
\
I. TESTS OF DIFFERENCE \
\
A. SELECTING THE APPROPRIATE TEST OF DIFFERENCE \
\
There are many statistical tests that are used to analyze questions of difference. Once it has \
been ascertained that the research involves looking at differences between groups, the \
following three steps can be taken to determine the specific statistical test needed. \
\
>TYPE OF DATA OF THE DV Assuming only one DV, it is important to know what \
type of data the DV or outcome measure is (NOIR). If the DV is nominal or ordinal, a non- \
parametric test will be used (e.g., Chi-Square, Mann-Whitney, Wilcoxon). If the DV is \
interval or ratio, a parametric test will usually be used (e.g., a t-test or ANOVA). If there \
is more than one DV (interval or ratio data), the statistic of choice will be MANOVA. \
\
>NUMBER OF INDEPENDENT VARIABLES, & LEVELS OF INDEPENDENT \
VARIABLES It is easiest to assess the levels of the independent variable(s) by looking at \
what groups are being compared. If males and females are being compared, this represents \
two levels (groups being compared) of one IV (gender). If cognitive-behavioral treatment \
is being compared with psychodynamic treatment versus no treatment, this represents three \
levels (groups being compared) of one IV (type of treatment). \
\
>SAMPLE (GROUP) INDEPENDENCE VERSUS CORRELATION It is crucial to \
sort out whether the groups (samples) being compared for each IV are independent or \
correlated. If people are randomly assigned to groups, or are grouped based on a pre- \
existing characteristic (e.g., gender or ethnicity), the groups or data are considered \
independent. \
\
\
