Three factors can result in the groups or data being correlated: 1) subjects that are measured \
at more than one point in time (e.g., a group of subjects measured on the Beck Depression \
Inventory prior to treatment, during treatment, and after treatment); 2) subjects that are \
matched prior to their assignment to groups (e.g., subjects matched on income, IQ, or some \
other relevant characteristic); and 3) an inherent relationship between pairs of subjects \
(e.g., twins, siblings, and spouses all have an inherent relationship). \
\
>ASSUMPTIONS FOR PARAMETRIC TESTS There are three assumptions that must \
be met in order to use a parametric test (e.g. t-test, ANOVA, MANOVA): 1) the data must \
be interval or ratio; 2) there must be homoscedasticity, which means that there should be \
similar variability or standard deviations in the different groups; and 3) the data must be \
normally distributed. If one of these assumptions is not met, the statistic of choice will \
typically be one that is used with ordinal data (e.g., Mann-Whitney). \
\
>ASSUMPTION FOR THE CHI-SQUARE TEST   The main assumption of the Chi- \
Square test (a non-parametric test) is that there is independence of observations. In other \
words, the Chi-Square cannot be used when subjects are measured more than once (i.e., \
repeated measures). \
