Degrees of freedom refers to the number of possible variations in outcome that can be \
obtained. What follows are some of the basic formulas for calculating degrees of freedom \
for chi-square, t-tests, and one-way ANOVAs. \
\
C1. CHI-SQUARE \
\
>SINGLE SAMPLE CHI-SQUARE In the single sample chi-square, nominal data are \
collected for one independent variable. For example, 100 psychologists are sampled as to \
their voting preference (Democrat, Republican, or Libertarian). In this case, there are three \
groups (or columns). The formula for degrees of freedom in the single sample chi-square \
is: df =# columns - 1. In this case, 3 - 1 = 2 degrees of freedom. \
\
>MULTIPLE SAMPLE CHI-SQUARE In the multiple sample chi-square, nominal data \
are collected for two independent variables. For example, 100 psychologists are sampled \
as to their voting preference (Democrat, Republican, or Libertarian) as well as their \
ethnicity (White, Asian, African American, Hispanic, and Native American). In this case, \
there are three groups for voting preference (columns) and five groups for ethnicity (rows). \
The formula for degrees of freedom for the multiple sample chi-square is: df = (# rows - \
1) x (# columns - 1). In this case, (3 - 1) x (5 - 1) or 2 x 4 = 8 degrees of freedom. \
\
C2. T-TESTS \
\
>T-TEST FOR SINGLE SAMPLE In the t-test for single sample, interval or ratio data \
are collected for one group of subjects. For example, scores on the Beck Depression \
inventory are obtained for 30 subjects. The formula for degrees of freedom for the t-test \
for single sample is: df = N - 1. In this case, 30 - 1 - 29 degrees of freedom. \
\
>T-TEST FOR MATCHED OR CORRELATED SAMPLES In the t-test for matched \
or correlated samples, interval or ratio data are collected for two correlated groups of \
subjects. For example, scores on the Beck Depression inventory are obtained for a total of \
30 subjects, 15 in each group. The formula for degrees of freedom for the t-test for matched \
or correlated samples is: df = # pairs - 1. In this case, 15 - 1 = 14 degrees of freedom. \
\
>T-TEST FOR INDEPENDENT SAMPLES   In the t-test for independent samples, \
interval or ratio data are collected for two independent groups of subjects. For example, \
scores on the Beck Depression inventory are obtained for a total of 30 subjects, 15 \
