G. TREND ANALYSIS \
\
When the independent variable is quantitative (e.g., dosage of drug, hours of food \
deprivation, intensity of the unconditioned stimulus), the outcome will frequently be non- \
linear. In this case, researchers are less interested in the differences between the groups, \
and more interested in the trend of the data, or the ups and downs. Trend analysis, an \
extension of the ANOVA, is used to analyze such non-linear data. \
\
II. TESTS OF RELATIONSHIP AND PREDICTION \
\
The two broad categories of tests of relationship and prediction are bivariate and \
multivariate tests. As a rule, statistics that depict relationships between variables are termed \
correlations, while statistics that predict are termed regressions or analyses. \
\
A. BIVARIATE TESTS \
\
>THE CORRELATION COEFFICIENT Bivariate correlations look at the relationship \
between two variables, X and Y, where neither is an IV in the truest sense. X is typically \
viewed as the predictor, while Y is considered to be the criterion. Bivariate relationships \
are mathematically depicted with a correlation coefficient, which ranges in value from -1.0 \
to +1.0. Correlation coefficients describe the relationship between X and Y in terms of both \
strength (the absolute value) and direction (- vs. +). \
\
Correlations are graphically depicted with a set of data points. Each data point represents \
one person's score on both X and Y. The closer the data points cluster around a line, the \
stronger the correlation. The more spread out the data points are, the weaker the correlation. \
