\
>THE COEFFICIENT OF DETERMINATION The coefficient of determination is \
calculated by squaring the correlation coefficient. For example, if the correlation between \
education and income is .50, the coefficient of determination is .52, or .25. The coefficient \
of determination represents the amount of variability in Y that is shared with, explained \
by, or accounted for by X. In other words, it can be concluded that 25% of the variability \
in income is explained by education, which leaves 75% of the variability in income to be \
accounted for by other factors (e.g., motivation, connections, luck, etc.). \
\
>THE SIMPLE LINEAR REGRESSION EQUATION   When two variables have no \
correlation (the correlation = 0.0), knowing the value of X provides no information about \
the value of Y. For example, if there were no relationship between education and income. \
knowing a person's education level would not make it possible to predict income level. \
\
When a correlation other than 0.0 is obtained, there is an implication of prediction. A \
simple linear regression (prediction) equation is derived, based on the line of best fit \
through the scatter plot. It is calculated by computer using the least squares criterion. The \
regression equation is expressed in the formula: Y = a + bX. In this case, one variable (X) \
is defined as the predictor while the second (Y) is defined as the criterion. The coefficient \
'a' is a constant, and is the intercept, which determines the height of the line. The \
coefficient 'b' is referred to as the slope, which determines the steepness of the line. \
\
>ASSUMPTIONS OF BIVARIATE CORRELATIONS      There are three basic \
assumptions of bivariate correlations: a linear relationship between X and Y. \
homoscedasticity, and an unrestricted range of scores on both X and Y. \
