     thought to be influencing or confounding both the predictor and the criterion. For \
     example, if it is believed that a third variable such as parental education affects both \
     SAT and GPA, this variable could be measured and its effect removed from the \
     correlation of SAT and GPA. \
\
     PART (SEMIPARTIAL) CORRELATION A part or semipartial correlation \
     examines the relationship between the predictor and the criterion with the influence \
     of a third variable removed from only one of the original variables. For example, \
     when SAT and GPA are correlated, the effect of SES might be removed only from \
     SAT scores. \
\
     MODERATOR VARIABLE A moderator variable is defined as a variable that \
     influences the strength of the relationship between the predictor and criterion. \
     Sometimes a correlation is stronger at certain points in the scatter plot and weaker \
     at others. For example, assume there is a strong correlation between income and \
     smoking, such that lower income people tend to smoke more. Now, assume that \
     this relationship differs depending on a person's age. In other words, when people \
     are older, there is a stronger correlation between income and smoking, and when \
     people are younger, there is a weaker correlation between income and smoking. \
     "Age" would then operate as a moderator variable that affects the strength of the \
     correlation. \
\
     MEDIATOR VARIABLE A mediator variable explains why there is a \
     relationship between the predictor and the criterion. For example, education might \
     explain the link between SES and smoking. When you control for the effect of the \
     mediator (e.g., education), the relationship between the predictor and the criterion \
     then goes down to almost 0. \
\
B. MULTIVARIATE TESTS \
\
Multivariate tests of correlation and prediction involve several Xs (predictors or IVs) and \
one or more Ys (criterions or DVs). \
\
>MULTIPLE R Multiple R (or multiple correlation) is a correlation between two or more \
IVs (X) and one DV (Y), where Y is always interval or ratio data, and at least one X is \
interval or ratio data. For example, a multiple R of .70 might be calculated for the \
relationship between time studied for the EPPP (X1) and number of practice tests completed \
(X2), and score on the EPPP (Y). \
\
\
