\
Squaring multiple R (R2), generates the coefficient of multiple determination, an index \
of the amount of variability in the criterion (Y) that is accounted for by the combination of \
all the predictors (Xs). When multiple R of .70 is squared, the result is .49. This suggests \
that 49% of the variability in scores on the EPPP can be accounted for by a combination of \
number of hours studied and number of practice tests completed prior to the exam. \
\
>MULTIPLE REGRESSION Using the multiple R, a multiple regression equation can \
be derived, which then allows the prediction of the criterion (Y) based on the values of the \
predictors (Xs). The multiple regression equation is expressed in the formula: Y = a + b1X1 \
+ b2X2 + b;X3, etc, where 'a' is a constant and the intercept, and each 'b' is a non- \
standardized partial slope. 'b' values can be converted to beta values, which are \
standardized partial slopes. \
\
The key distinction to keep in mind is that 'b' values should be used when comparing \
variables between studies or samples (i.e., across two regression equations), while beta \
values should be used when comparing variables within a study or sample (i.e., within one \
equation). \
\
To optimize the ability to predict, it is desirable to have a low correlation between \
predictors (Xs) and a moderate to high correlation between each predictor and the criterion \
(Y). Multicollinearity is a problem that occurs in a multiple regression equation when the \
predictors are highly correlated with one another, and therefore essentially redundant. \
\
Multiple regression is a compensatory technique because low scores on one predictor can \
be compensated for by high scores on another predictor. (See the Industrial/ Organizational \
section for more details on how multiple regression differs from the noncompensatory \
techniques of multiple cutoff and multiple hurdle.) \
\
The two most common subtypes of multiple regression are stepwise regression and \
hierarchical regression. \
\
     STEPWISE REGRESSION Stepwise regression is computer-generated, and can \
     be implemented either forward or backward. In a forward regression, the computer \
     adds predictor variables one at a time, starting with the predictor that has the highest \
     correlation with criterion outcome. Predictors continue to be added until there is no \
     significant change in R2. In backward regression, predictor variables are removed \
     one at a time, starting with the variable that contributes the least to criterion \
     outcome, until there is a significant change in R2. Stepwise regression allows the \
     researcher to come up with the fewest possible predictors. \
\
\
