\
     HIERARCHICAL REGRESSION   In a hierarchical regression, the researcher \
     controls the analysis, adding variables to the regression analysis in the order that is \
     most consistent with the theory being proposed. \
\
>CANONICAL R AND CANONICAL ANALYSIS     An extension of multiple R. \
canonical R is a correlation between two or more IVs and two or more DVs. Canonical R \
allows you to evaluate the relationship between two sets of variables, one identified as a \
predictor set, and the other as the criterion set. For example, the relationship between time \
spent studying for the EPPP (X1) and number of practice tests completed (X2), with score \
obtained on the exam (Y1) and amount of subjective distress experienced while taking the \
exam (Y2). A canonical analysis is an extension of canonical R, enabling us to predict two \
criterion scores based on two predictor scores. \
\
>DISCRIMINANT FUNCTION ANALYSIS The discriminant function analysis is a \
special case of the multiple regression. As with the multiple regression, the discriminant \
analysis is used when there are two or more predictors (Xs) and one criterion (Y). However, \
the distinction is that the discriminant analysis is used when the criterion variable (Y) is \
nominal (categorical) rather than interval or ratio. Discriminant analysis allows a \
researcher to predict membership in a group based on knowledge of a set of predictor \
variables. For example, a discriminant function analysis would be used to predict the \
likelihood of passing or failing the EPPP (categorical Y) based on time spent studying for \
the EPPP (X1) and the number of practice tests completed (X2). \
\
>LOGLINEAR ANALYSIS Loglinear analysis, sometimes referred to as logit analysis, \
is used to predict a categorical criterion (Y) based on categorical predictors (Xs). For \
example, a loglinear analysis would be used if type of graduate school (categorical X1.) \
and sex (categorical X2) were used to predict likelihood of passing or failing the EPPP \
(categorical Y). \
\
Multiple regression, canonical correlation, discriminant analysis, and loglinear analysis are \
all considered to be compensatory when applied to decision making. \
\
The correlational and predictive tests described above can never be used to infer causal \
relationships. By contrast, two approaches, path analysis and structural equation modeling. \
apply correlational techniques to causal modeling. \
\
>PATH ANALYSIS Path analysis applies multiple regression techniques to testing a \
model that specifies causal links among variables. Path analysis is not designed to sift \
through data for interesting relationships. Rather, it depends upon a researcher having \
