III. TESTS OF STRUCTURE \
\
Tests of structure or fit are applied to a set of variables (e.g., items or subtests) when the \
researcher is interested in discovering which variables in the set fit best together or form \
coherent subsets that are relatively independent of one another. For example, a factor \
analysis was used to see which subtests of the WAIS best fit together and how many \
underlying factors account for the subtests. Tests of structure include the factor analysis \
and the cluster analysis. \
\
A. FACTOR ANALYSIS \
\
Factor analysis is a statistical technique used to reduce a large number of variables into a \
smaller number of factors. \
\
>FACTORS Factor analysis operates by extracting as many significant factors from the \
data as is possible. A factor is a dimension that consists of any number of variables (e.g., \
items or subtests). For example, an attractiveness scale that measures 17 different elements \
of attractiveness (e.g., kind, exciting) can be factor analyzed to see whether the scale is \
measuring one or several dimensions (factors) underlying attractiveness. The successive \
factors extracted in factor analysis are not of equal strength. The first is always the \
