strongest, the second, next strongest, and so forth. The stronger the factor, the more it will \
account for or explain the variability in scores. \
\
>EIGENVALUES The strength of a factor is indicated by its eigenvalue. Factors with \
eigenvalues less than 1.0 usually are not interpreted or considered significant. Eigenvalue \
is also sometimes described as characteristic root. \
\
>CORRELATION MATRIX    Factor analytic techniques begin with the correlation \
matrix, a table of intercorrelations among tests or items. The results of a factor analysis are \
ultimately expressed in a factor matrix, which is a table that shows the loading of every \
item on every factor, as well as each factor's eigenvalue. \
\
>FACTOR LOADINGS To determine which variables constitute a common factor, \
factor loadings are computed. Each factor loading is a correlation between a variable (e.g., \
item or subtest) and the underlying factor. By convention, loadings are interpreted if they \
are equal to or exceed plus or minus .30. \
\
After factor loadings are obtained, they must be interpreted. To make the factors distinct \
and more interpretable, factor rotation is used. The two types of rotation are orthogonal \
and oblique. \
\
>ORTHOGONAL ROTATIONS AND COMMUNALITY In an orthogonal rotation, \
the axes remain perpendicular (90 degrees). An orthogonal rotation always results in \
factors that have no correlation with one another. Orthogonal rotations are generally \
preferred because they are easier to interpret. \
\
In an orthogonal rotation, communalities can be calculated. Communality refers to how \
much of a test's variability is explained by the combination of all the factors. To compute \
communality for a given test, the factor loadings are squared and then added together. \
