             TEST CONSTRUCTION \
\
The domain of test construction focuses on the adequacy of the tests used for psychological \
measurement. Tests must have adequate levels of reliability and validity. \
\
                     6.8 RELIABILITY \
\
I. OVERVIEW \
\
Reliability is defined as the amount of consistency, repeatability, and dependability in \
scores obtained on a given test. Consider the fact that if a candidate were to take two \
alternate forms of the EPPP a week apart, the candidate might score 550 on one form and \
570 on the other. What accounts for both the difference and yet the closeness in scores? A \
large part of each score is due to knowledge and ability (which is consistent from test to \
test), while another part of each score is due to error or random factors (which fluctuate \
from test to test), According to Classical Test Theory, any obtained score is a combination \
of truth and error, or X T + E. \
\
When a group of people takes a test, there will be a certain amount of variability among. \
or differences between, all the scores obtained. Some of the difference in scores is due to \
true score variability (variability due to real differences in ability or knowledge in the \
test-takers), while the remainder is error variability (variability caused by chance or \
random factors). \
\
      THE TRUE SCORE MODEL OR CLASSICAL TEST THEORY \
\
          Total variability = True score variability + Error variability. \
\
            Reliability is the proportion of true score variability. \
\
\
