EXAMPLE: The total variability in scores for any test is always 100%. If the true score \
variance is equal to 80% and error variance is equal to 20%, reliability would be .80. Thus, \
reliability equals the proportion of true score variability. \
\
The reliability coefficient is symbolized as either or I'et. This should be easy to \
remember, because reliability is commonly derived by correlating scores obtained on the \
test given at one point in time (x Of t) with scores obtained on the test given at a second \
point in time (x or :). The range of the reliability coefficient is from 0.00 to 1.00, and a \
minimum acceptable reliability is .80. There is no such thing as negative reliability. The \
reliability coefficient is interpreted directly as the percentage of true score variability. This \
differs from both the Pearson r and the validity coefficient, both of which are squared to \
determine the amount of shared or explained variability. \
\
Common sources of error in tests include content (or item) sampling, time sampling, and \
test heterogeneity. \
\
>CONTENT SAMPLING Error due to content sampling occurs when a test, by chance, \
has items that tap into a test-taker's knowledge base, or items that don't tap into a test- \
taker's knowledge. \
\
>TIME SAMPLING Time sampling error occurs when a test is given at two different \
points in time, and the scores on each administration are different because of factors related \
to the passage of time (e.g., forgetting over time). \
\
>TEST HETEROGENEITY Error due to test heterogeneity occurs when a test has \
heterogeneous items tapping more than one domain. \
\
II. FACTORS AFFECTING RELIABILITY \
\
The factors that affect the reliability of a test include the number of items, homogeneity of \
items, range of scores, and ability to guess. \
\
>NUMBER OF ITEMS Reliability is increased when the number of items is increased, \
and is decreased when the number of items is reduced. \
\
>HOMOGENEITY OF ITEMS Homogeneity of items refers to items tapping similar \
content areas. All things being equal, the more homogeneous the items are, the greater the \
reliability. \
\
\
\
