\
>RANGE OF SCORES An unrestricted range, or a full spread of scores, maximizes \
reliability. A restricted range has the reverse effect and reduces the reliability coefficient. \
The range of scores obtained is related to the heterogeneity of the subjects: the more \
heterogeneous the subjects are on the dimension being measured, the greater the range of \
scores. (This is just an application of the general principle covered in the statistics section \
that correlation coefficients are always diminished when the range of scores is restricted.) \
\
>ABILITY TO GUESS The easier it is to guess (e.g., true-false tests), the lower reliability \
is. This is because reliability indicates true score variability or how much of a score is based \
on what the test taker really knows. If it's easy to guess, one's score will be less dependent \
on what one knows, and more due to chance factors. \
\
III. FOUR ESTIMATES OF RELIABILITY \
\
Although the exact value of the reliability coefficient can never be known, it can be \
estimated in one of four ways. \
\
A. TEST-RETEST RELIABILITY \
\
Test-retest reliability (expressed as the coefficient of stability) involves correlating pairs \
of scores from the same sample of people who are administered the identical test at two \
points in time. For example, the EPPP is administered to a group of candidates, and the \
same test is given to the same group of candidates several months later. Generally, as the \
time interval between the administrations of the test increases, the correlation decreases. \
Therefore, the major source of error for test-retest reliability is time sampling. \
\
B. PARALLEL FORMS RELIABILITY \
\
Parallel, alternate, or equivalent forms reliability (expressed as the coefficient of \
equivalence) is calculated by correlating the scores obtained by the same group of people \
on two roughly equivalent but not identical forms of the same test administered at two \
different points in time. Because it requires two forms of the same test to be developed, \
establishing parallel forms reliability can be costly and time-consuming. An advantage of \
this type of reliability is that practice effects are minimized, since subjects are not exposed \
to the same items. The EPPP is an example of a test that has parallel forms. The two major \
sources of error are time and content sampling. Error due to time sampling occurs because \
of the span of time between the first and second administrations of the tests. Error due to \
