C. INTERNAL CONSISTENCY RELIABILITY \
\
Internal consistency reliability looks at the consistency of the scores within the test; \
therefore, the test is administered only once to one group of people. There are two typical \
ways to assess internal consistency: the first is split-half reliability, and the second is either \
Kuder-Richardson (KR-20 & KR-21) or Cronbach's coefficient alpha. \
\
>SPLIT-HALF RELIABILITY Split-half reliability is calculated by splitting the test in \
half (e.g., odd versus even items), and then correlating the scores obtained on each half by \
each person. When the test is split in half, the correlation is based on half the number of \
items. For example, a 200-item test is split into two sets of 100 items. Because reducing \
the number of items has the effect of lowering reliability, split-half reliability \
underestimates the true reliability of a test. Therefore, when calculating split-half \
reliability, the Spearman-Brown formula is typically used. The Spearman-Brown \
prophecy formula tells us how much more reliable the test would be if it were longer. The \
source of error for split-half reliability is item or content sampling. For example, someone \
might, by chance, know more of the odd items than the even items. \
\
     SPEEDED TESTS Split-half reliability is inappropriate for speeded tests. On a \
     speeded test, only very easy items are included; typically, subjects get all items \
     correct. However, subjects are allotted a limited amount of time in which to \
     complete the test. Scores are expressed in terms of the number of items that were \
     completed within the allotted time frame (e.g., digit symbol-coding on the WAIS- \
     III). Because subjects typically get all completed items correct, there should be a \
     nearly perfect correlation between halves of the test. Thus, the use of split-half \
     reliability will result in an estimate of reliability that is artificially inflated or \
     spuriously high. The preferred reliability coefficient to use for speeded tests is \
     alternate forms. Next best is test-retest reliability despite possible problems due to \
     practice effects. \
\
     POWER TESTS Power tests have items that are of varying difficulty level, and \
     subjects are provided sufficient time to complete them all. Scores are generally \
     expressed in terms of percentage correct. The EPPP is an example of a power test. \
\
