>KUDER-RICHARDSON (KR-20 & KR-21) & CRONBACH'S COEFFICIENT \
ALPHA Kuder-Richardson (KR-20 and KR-21) and Cronbach's coefficient alpha are very \
sophisticated forms of internal consistency reliability. Essentially, they involve analysis of \
the correlation of each item with every other item in the test. This form of reliability is \
calculated by taking the mean of the correlation coefficients for every possible split-half. \
KR-20 and KR-21 are used when the items are scored dichotomously, as either correct or \
incorrect (e.g., the EPPP). Coefficient alpha is used when items are scored non- \
dichotomously, and there is a range of possible scores for each item or category (e.g., a \
likert scale). KR-20 is used when items vary in difficulty level, while KR-21 is used when \
all items are essentially of equal difficulty. \
\
Error in KR-20, KR-21, and coefficient alpha is due to content sampling and test \
heterogeneity. \
\
D. INTERRATER RELIABILITY \
\
Interscorer or interrater reliability looks at the degree of agreement between two or more \
scorers when a test is subjectively scored. The best way to improve this reliability is to \
provide opportunity for group discussion, practice exercises, and feedback. These methods \
are even superior to training the raters. Interscorer reliability can be expressed as percent \
agreement (the percentage of time that the raters agree on their overall ratings), Pearson r \
(correlating the scores given by the raters to each examinee), Kappa statistic, or Yule's Y. \
\
IV. STANDARD ERROR OF MEASUREMENT \
\
If a test were perfectly reliable, the test would perfectly and consistently assess a person's \
knowledge or abilities, but since no test is perfectly reliable, there is always going to be \
error in measurement. For example, the person who obtains a score of 120 on an IQ test \
might not have an exact IQ of 120. \
\
To get some idea of the average amount of measurement error in each person's score on \
any given test, a theoretical distribution can be constructed. This distribution would consist \
of one person's scores if he or she were tested hundreds of times with alternate or equivalent \
forms of the test. (This process parallels what is done with the standard error of the mean.) \
For example, hundreds of alternate forms of the EPPP could be administered to one person \
(some people's version of hell). On each administration, the person would obtain a slightly \
different score. If the scores were plotted, they would fall into a bell-shaped distribution. \
The standard deviation of this distribution would indicate the average amount of \
measurement error, or the standard error of the measurement. \
\
