                    6.9 VALIDITY \
\
Validity is defined as the meaningfulness, usefulness, or accuracy of a measure. The three \
basic types of validity are content, criterion-related, and construct validity. Validity either \
tells how well a test is measuring what it is supposed to be measuring (typically content or \
construct validity), or it can tell us how well a test can be used to infer criterion performance \
(criterion-related validity). \
\
In contrast with content, criterion-related, and construct validity, which are objectively \
determined, face validity refers to the degree to which a test subjectively (at face value) \
appears to measure that which it purports to measure. \
\
I. CONTENT VALIDITY \
\
Content validity addresses how adequately a test samples a particular content area, such as \
statistics, spelling, or secretarial skills. Content validity is quantified by asking a panel of \
experts if each item is essential, useful/not essential, or not necessary, yet no numerical \
validity coefficient is derived. Content validity applies to tests that require knowledge of a \
particular content domain, and generally involves looking at data like course objectives \
and job criteria. For employment tests to be content valid, they must include a \
representative sample of job-related skills. \
\
II. CRITERION-RELATED VALIDITY \
\
Criterion-related validity addresses how adequately a test score can be used to infer, \
predict, or estimate criterion outcome (e.g .. how well do SAT scores predict college GPA). \
Criterion-related validity is calculated by using a Pearson r to correlate the test scores (also \
known as predictor scores) with criterion scores (also known as outcome scores). The test \
scores are symbolized as 'x', and the outcome scores are symbolized as 'y.' The criterion- \
related validity coefficient (Ixy) ranges from -1.0 to +1.0, with validities as low as .20 \
frequently considered acceptable. The higher the coefficient (either positive or negative), \
the more valid the predictor. A negative validity coefficient indicates an inverse \
relationship between the predictor and the criterion. For example, if a test of rudeness is \
used as a predictor, and monthly sales is the criterion, these two variables would likely \
have an inverse relationship (e.g., the ruder someone is, the lower monthly sales would be). \
\
\
