When there is a reasonable correlation between the predictor and the criterion (Tsy), a \
regression equation can be constructed by computer. With such an equation, a given test \
score can be used to predict the person's criterion score. To determine how much of the \
outcome (criterion variability) can be accounted for or explained by the predictor, the \
criterion-related validity coefficient must be squared. \
\
EXAMPLE: It is found that scores on a practice test have a .50 correlation with scores on \
the EPPP. If this correlation is squared, the result is .25, which means that 25% of the \
variability in the actual exam score (criterion) is accounted for by performance on the \
practice test (predictor). This also means that 75% of the variability of the actual exam \
score is accounted for by other factors. \
\
Two subtypes of criterion-related validity exist: concurrent and predictive validity. \
\
>CONCURRENT VALIDITY In concurrent validity, the predictor and criterion are \
measured and correlated at about the same time. For example, a practice test and the EPPP \
are administered to a group of examinees within a few days or weeks, and the scores are \
correlated. \
\
>PREDICTIVE VALIDITY In predictive validity, there is a delay between the \
measurement of the predictor and the criterion. For example, SAT scores are used to predict \
college GPA, but the SATs are administered four or more years before college GPA can \
be calculated. \
\
A. STANDARD ERROR OF ESTIMATE \
\
If a predictor test has perfect criterion-related validity, the test would accurately and \
precisely predict criterion performance. However, since no test is perfectly valid, there is \
always some error in estimating a person's criterion score based on a test score. \
\
To get some idea of the average amount of error in estimating each person's criterion score, \
a theoretical distribution can be constructed. This distribution would consist of one \
person's criterion scores if he or she were measured hundreds of times on the criterion. \
(This process parallels what is done with the standard error of the mean and the standard \
error of measurement.) The spread, or variability, in this distribution is the average amount \
of error in estimating. It is known as the standard error of estimate. \
\
