     Item response theory is used to calculate to what extent a specific item on a test \
     correlates with an underlying construct. Put differently, item response theory looks \
     at a subject's performance on a test item as representing the degree to which the \
     subject has a latent trait. For example, correctly answering a difficult statistics \
     question would indicate a subject is high in the latent trait of "statistics ability." \
\
     One of the key advantages of IRT is that it can be used to compare a subject's \
     performance on two measures that have different types or number of items, or are \
     scored differently. IRT is also used to develop individually tailored "adaptive" tests, \
     in which an answer to one question in a domain area determines whether another \
     question in that area will be asked. Such tests end up having the fewest number of \
     items necessary to assess a subject's performance. \
\
>TEST REVISION Test revision is the final step. After item analysis, a subset of test \
items is kept, and the rest of the items are thrown out. The criterion-related validity \
coefficient for this subset is then calculated. Afterwards, the test is cross-validated: it is \
administered to a new sample in order to test out its validity on another group of people. \
Cross-validation always results in shrinkage of the criterion-related validity coefficient. \
Shrinkage occurs because of sample differences. Since the items were selected because \
they were the best for that specific original sample, they cannot possibly be as good for a \
different sample of people. \
\
D. FACTORS AFFECTING CRITERION-RELATED VALIDITY \
\
The factors that affect the criterion-related validity coefficient include the range of scores, \
the reliability of the predictor, the reliability of the predictor and the criterion, as well as \
criterion contamination. \
\
>RANGE OF SCORES The range of scores affects criterion-related validity. Validity is \
maximized by an unrestricted range of scores on both the predictor (x) and the criterion \
(y). Any restriction in range will reduce criterion-related validity. The range of scores \
obtained is related to the heterogeneity of the subjects. The more heterogeneous the \
subjects are in terms of the factor being assessed, the greater the range of scores will be. \
\
\
