\
When assessing a test's validity, construct and content validity are mutually exclusive. For \
example, a test of statistics measures how well subjects have mastered the content domain \
of statistics (content validity). By contrast, a questionnaire designed to measure aggression \
does not assess how much knowledge the subjects have of the domain of aggression; rather, \
it is intended to measure the hypothetical construct of aggression (construct validity). \
\
Criterion-related validity focuses on how well the test predicts a criterion outcome, and it \
can be of interest in conjunction with either a test of content or a test of a construct. For \
example, a test of statistics (content) can be used to predict scores on the EPPP. Or. a \
questionnaire about aggression (construct) could be used to predict future encounters with \
the legal system. \
