     7.1 ATTRIBUTIONS AND HEURISTICS \
\
I. ATTRIBUTION THEORIES \
\
Attribution theories focus on the causal explanations that people generate to explain why a \
particular event or outcome has occurred. \
\
>HEIDER Heider (1958), the originator of attribution theory, proposed that people make \
either dispositional or situational attributions. \
\
     DISPOSITIONAL ATTRIBUTIONS A dispositional or internal attribution \
     locates the cause of a behavior within the person. For example, a person's poor \
     performance on an exam is attributed to lack of effort in preparation. \
\
     SITUATIONAL ATTRIBUTIONS A situational or external attribution locates \
     the cause of the behavior outside the person. For example, a person's poor \
     performance on an exam is attributed to the test's unfairness. \
\
>KELLEY Harold Kelley (1967, 1973) proposed that when people make attributions, \
they consider three types of information: consistency, distinctiveness, and consensus. For \
example, a person is rude and obnoxious at work one day. In order to decide whether the \
