\
      CONSISTENCY Consistency refers to whether the person behaves the same way \
     over time. In this scenario, one would consider whether the person is consistently \
     rude and obnoxious at work, in which case the behavior would be seen as high in \
     consistency. By contrast, if this were a one-time or infrequent occurrence, the \
      behavior would be considered low in consistency. \
\
      DISTINCTIVENESS Distinctiveness refers to whether a person's behavior is \
     unique to the specific situation or stimulus. For example, if the person is rude and \
      obnoxious only at work, the behavior is high in distinctiveness. If she or he is rude \
     and obnoxious at parties too, the behavior is low in distinctiveness. \
\
      CONSENSUS Consensus refers to whether other people in the same situation tend \
     to respond similarly. For example, if most people at work are rude and obnoxious, \
      the behavior is high in consensus. By contrast, if the person who is rude and \
      obnoxious at work is the only one behaving this way, the behavior is low in \
     consensus. \
\
 According to Kelley, people tend to make internal attributions for behaviors that are high \
 in consistency and low in distinctiveness and consensus (i.e., the person engages in the \
 behavior consistently over time in many different situations, and other people do not \
 engage in that behavior in the same situation). People tend to make external attributions \
 when the behavior is high is all three areas of consistency, distinctiveness, and consensus \
(i.e., the person engages in the behavior consistently over time but only in this specific \
situation, and other people engage in that behavior in the same situation). \
\
 >WEINER Weiner (1974) added a second dimension to the study of attributions, \
 stability. In addition to examining the internal versus external dimension on attributions, \
 he looked at whether attributions are made to stable versus unstable factors. For example, \
 an unemployed person has been unable to find work for six months. A stable internal factor \
 might be lack of ability, in that the person does not have the necessary skills for seeking \
 employment. An unstable internal factor might be lack of effort in searching for work. A \
 stable external factor might be a poor economy, in which few jobs are available. An \
 unstable external factor could be bad luck. \
\
 Attribution theory has contributed to our understanding of depression and learned \
 helplessness. Research has demonstrated that when a person attributes negative events to \
