 II. ATTRIBUTIONAL BIASES \
\
 When they make attributions, people frequently do not have access to all the relevant \
 information. People therefore rely on causal schemas or general beliefs regarding the \
 causes of behavior, and these schemas are often erroneous. \
\
 >THE FUNDAMENTAL ATTRIBUTION BIAS The fundamental attribution bias or \
 error (Jones & Nisbett. 1971) refers to a bias toward attributing the behavior of others (the \
actor) to internal or dispositional causes, while underestimating the influence of situational \
 variables. One explanation for this bias relates to saliency, or what is more noticeable. \
 Dispositional factors (e.g., the welfare-cheaters depicted in the media) are frequently more \
 salient than situational factors (e.g., those factors that lead to poverty and joblessness). One \
 of the most significant problems resulting from the fundamental attribution bias is \
 "blaming the victim." \
\
>THE ACTOR-OBSERVER BIAS The actor-observer bias describes a situation in \
 which persons attribute their own actions to situational factors while minimizing the role \
 of dispositional elements, and attribute others' behavior to dispositional factors. One \
 explanation may be that we have greater self-knowledge as compared to knowledge about \
 others. Research on this bias has met with inconsistent results. \
\
