III. HEURISTICS \
\
Heuristics are shortcuts or guidelines that people use to categorize other people, situations, \
or events. Even though heuristics serve to simplify thinking, they can often result in \
incorrect judgments. Three common heuristics include the availability heuristic, the \
representative heuristic, and the simulation heuristic. \
\
>AVAILABILITY HEURISTIC The availability heuristic proposes that people estimate \
the likelihood of a situation by how easily they can recall it. Based on the availability \
heuristic, it is easier to remember events that are witnessed frequently than those that are \
not witnessed frequently. For example, in one study, people were asked to rate common \
causes of death. The subjects incorrectly rated death by firearms as a more common cause \
of death than death from asthma, since firearm deaths receive so much more publicity. \
\
>REPRESENTATIVE HEURISTIC According to the representative heuristic, people \
make judgments about other people or events based on what they believe is a typical \
example of a particular category. For example, when people hear about rape or spousal \
abuse, they will most commonly assume that the victim is female and the perpetrator is \
male. \
\
>SIMULATION HEURISTIC The simulation heuristic suggests that people develop \
mental images of situations, and then use these mental images to make judgments about \
facts in their lives. For example, in a study, physicians were asked whether they had ever \
