                   7.2 ATTITUDES \
\
An attitude is a learned predisposition to respond to a particular stimulus or situation. \
Attitudes can be formed from direct experience, for example, by eating ice cream. Attitudes \
can also be formed through indirect observation, for example, by listening to your parents \
discuss a social issue. An attitude has three components: cognitive, affective, and \
behavioral. \
\
The cognitive component consists of the thoughts and beliefs. For example, a person might \
believe that abortion is not acceptable. \
\
The affective component involves feelings. For example, the person who opposes abortion \
may feel angry or frustrated that abortion is legal. \
\
The behavioral component consists of predispositions to act in certain ways. The person \
who has negative thoughts and feelings about abortion might protest outside an abortion \
clinic. \
\
The three components of an attitude do not always correspond. In fact, the research \
suggests that there is only a weak positive relationship between thoughts and feelings, and \
subsequent behaviors (about a .15 correlation). In a classic study in the mid-1930s, LaPiere \
traveled across the U.S. with a Chinese couple, eating in restaurants and staying in hotels. \
Prejudice was fairly common at that time against Asians. However, only one restaurant \
refused to serve them. Six months after the trip, when LaPiere wrote to these same \
restaurants and asked whether the owners would serve Asians, 90% said they would not! \
One idea that has been proposed to explain the discrepancy between thoughts or feelings \
and behavior is the concept of situational constraint. For instance, perhaps the people \
who served LaPiere and the Chinese couple feared making a scene in front of other \
customers. \
\
