I. CONSISTENCY THEORIES \
\
Consistency theories propose that attitude formation and change are organized by a need \
to impose structure and order on one's understanding of the environment. Four consistency \
models are described below, including balance theory, symmetry theory, congruity theory, \
and cognitive dissonance theory. \
\
>BALANCE THEORY Balance theory explains attitude change when two people have \
attitudes toward the same object or activity. Heider (1946) proposed that a balanced state \
exists when all the elements are positively related, or when one is positive and two are \
negative. By contrast, an unbalanced state exists when all the elements are negative, or \
when one element is negative and two are positive. When there is imbalance, the people \
involved will move toward changing their feelings. \
\
This theory becomes much easier to understand with examples. A balanced state would \
exist if two friends, Joe and Beth, both really liked a political candidate (i.e., all the \
elements were positively related), or both had very negative feelings about the candidate \
(i.e., one positive element and two negative elements). An imbalanced state would exist if \
Joe really liked the candidate and Beth strongly disliked the candidate (two positive \
elements and one negative element). An imbalanced state would also exist if Joe and Beth \
disliked each other and both disliked the candidate (three negative elements). In order to \
create more balance, Joe and Beth would either have to change their feelings toward each \
other or toward the candidate. \
\
>SYMMETRY THEORY Symmetry theory (Newcomb, 1961) extends balance theory \
by considering the intensity of the relationship. He posited that the stronger the bond \
between the two people, the more intense any imbalance (lack of symmetry) will be felt \
and the stronger the motivation will be to change attitudes. Thus, a strong friendship \
between Joe and Beth will lead to greater attitude change than a weak friendship. \
\
>CONGRUITY THEORY   Congruity theory (Osgood, 1955) further extends balance \
theory by making predictions about which attitudes will change. It posits that a person will \
favor the object toward which he or she already feels the most affinity. For example, if \
Joe's affinity for Beth is stronger than his affinity for the candidate, Joe is likely to decrease \
his support for the candidate, and thus bring the relationship into more balance. \
Alternatively, if Joe likes the candidate more than he likes Beth, he is likely to decrease his \
affinity for Beth. \
\
\
 \
\
