\
>COGNITIVE DISSONANCE   Cognitive dissonance (Festinger, 1957), the most \
popular of the consistency theories, proposes that people change their attitudes to reduce \
the aversive arousal they experience when they become aware of inconsistency in their \
cognitions. This inconsistency, or dissonance, frequently becomes most apparent when the \
person holds a particular attitude and has behaved as if he or she had the exact opposite \
attitude. Essentially, cognitive dissonance results in people changing their attitudes to \
match their actions. \
\
In their classic experiment, Festinger & Carlsmith (1959) recruited subjects to perform a \
dull task. After doing this for one hour, as the subject was leaving, he or she was asked to \
do the experimenter a favor and tell the incoming participant that the task was interesting. \
Subjects were paid either $1 or $20 to do so. Each subject was then asked to complete a \
questionnaire describing his or her true feelings about the task. Subjects paid $1 reported \
greater liking for the task than the subjects paid $20. While all subjects experienced \
dissonance between attitude (a boring task) and behavior (lying by saying the task was \
interesting), those paid $1 for the lie felt more discomfort and therefore changed their \
attitudes more. \
\
The research suggests four circumstances in which attitude change results from cognitive \
dissonance: postdecisional dissonance, effort justification, insufficient justification, and \
insufficient deterrence. \
\
     POSTDECISIONAL DISSONANCE Postdecisional dissonance occurs when a \
     person is faced with two good choices, and he or she becomes upset at not choosing \
     one of the alternatives. The person then emphasizes the positive features of the \
     alternative he or she did choose. \
\
     EFFORT JUSTIFICATION Effort justification occurs when a person is upset at \
    having spent significant effort on a goal that turns out not to be very worthwhile. \
     The person then emphasizes the positive qualities of the goal. \
\
     INSUFFICIENT JUSTIFICATION Insufficient justification occurs when a \
     person performs an undesirable behavior for a small inducement. The person then \
     emphasizes the positive qualities of the behavior. \
\
     INSUFFICIENT DETERRENCE Insufficient deterrence occurs when a person \
     does not perform a desirable action because of a small deterrent. He or she then \
     emphasizes the negative aspects of the action. \
\
\
