II. SELF-PERCEPTION THEORY \
\
Self-perception theory (Daryl Bem) is a competing theory to the consistency theories. \
According to this theory, people infer their attitudes as well as their emotions by observing \
their own behavior. This theory has been described by the phrase, "I did it, so I believe it!" \
Self-perception theory does not require "dissonance." or some kind of aversive arousal to \
motivate attitude change. For example, if someone who favors a ballot measure gives a \
speech supporting it, that person will usually feel even more positive about the measure \
afterwards, reasoning, "If I gave a speech for it, then I really must favor it!" Cognitive \
dissonance theory would be unable to explain this attitude change. \
\
Advocates of self-perception theory reinterpret the classic Festinger & Carlsmith study. \
They argue that subjects simply observed their own behavior: those paid $20 assumed that \
they were lying for profit and those paid $1 assumed that they wouldn't be lying for such \
low payment and must have enjoyed the task. There are research studies that support both \
theories. Overall, it appears that self-perception theory is most applicable when current \
behavior is in the same direction as past behavior and cognitive dissonance theory is most \
applicable when there is a discrepancy between current and past behavior. \
\
According to self-perception theory, the person who engages in an activity for a large \
reward might conclude that he or she enjoys the activity less than the person who engages \
in the same activity for little or no external reward. The overjustification hypothesis \
extends this idea and posits that people lose interest in previously desirable activities after \
performing them for too much justification. Research has found that if an individual who \
engages in an activity out of intrinsic motivation is given external incentives, the original \
intrinsic motivation will decrease. For example, if a child who enjoys reading is given a \
reward for reading books, she will come to believe that her motivation for reading is to \
earn the reward (extrinsic factor), and not simply to engage in an activity that she finds \
pleasurable (intrinsic factor). Therefore, when she is no longer rewarded for reading, she \
is likely to read on a less frequent basis or even stop reading. \
\
III. SELF-CONCEPT \
\
A number of theories describe how people maintain or adjust their self-concepts. \
\
>SELF-VERIFICATION THEORY Developed by Swann, self-verification theory \
posits that people are motivated to confirm their self-concept, even if it is negative. For \
