feedback that confirms a negative view of themselves. \
\
>BEHAVIORAL CONFIRMATION   A competing theory, behavioral confirmation, \
posits that people are motivated to confirm the expectations that others have of them. For \
example, students with varying levels of ability perform better when their teachers have \
been led to believe that these students are gifted. In this case, students seek to fulfill the \
teacher's view of them. However, there is much research that fails to support this theory \
and shows that people actively resist when others have negative expectations of them. \
\
>SELF-ENHANCEMENT THEORY According to self-enhancement theory, people are \
motivated to think favorably of themselves and behave in ways that cause others to see \
them favorably as well. \
\
Obviously, these three theories are contradictory. There is some research support for each \
of these theories in certain situations. Overall, self-verification theory seems the most \
robust, particularly when the self-concept is well established. \
