IV. ATTITUDE CHANGE \
\
Persuasion involves efforts to alter attitudes and beliefs. The effectiveness of persuasion is \
influenced by three factors: the source of the communication, the message itself, and the \
audience. \
\
A. PERSUASION \
\
>CHARACTERISTICS OF   THE SOURCE   The relative weight of various \
characteristics of the source depends on whether the communicator is attempting to change \
attitudes on important or unimportant matters. On relatively unimportant matters (e.g., \
breakfast cereal), the source is most influential when he or she is likable, similar to the \
recipient of the communication, and physically attractive (e.g., models on TV \
commercials). On important, deeply held convictions, the most important factor is the \
credibility of the source. Credibility consists of both trustworthiness (the communicator is \
perceived as having little to gain) and expertise. While positions advocated by highly \
credible and prestigious persons are more readily adopted than those expressed by less \
reputable sources, there is a sleeper effect, which involves people forgetting the source of \
the communication over time, but remembering the message. \
\
\
\
