\
Research has demonstrated a double standard for persuasion styles for men and women. \
Women who use a more tentative speech style (e.g., "I'm not an expert.") were more \
effective in persuading men. However, with a female audience, a more powerful speaking \
style was more effective. Recent research on women as persuasive communicators supports \
the idea that the most effective approach involves women combining assertive language \
with non-verbal cues that communicate friendliness and cooperation. \
\
>CHARACTERISTICS OF THE MESSAGE When it comes to characteristics of the \
message, some researchers have found that appeals to logic and reason are most persuasive, \
whereas others have found that appeals to emotions are more powerful. One common \
emotional appeal is to fear. Recent research supports the idea that for fear tactics to work, \
they must engender a lot of fear, the message must be believable, and specific instructions \
for avoiding the danger must be offered. \
\
Another factor that may affect persuasion is the order in which the message is presented. \
When there is a long gap between a speech and the desired action (e.g., voting in an \
election), the speaker who speaks first will be remembered best. This phenomenon is \
known as the primacy effect. When the gap is smaller, such as a few days, the speaker \
who speaks last is best remembered by the audience. This phenomenon is known as the \
recency effect. \
\
