\
>AFFECTIVE The affective component consists of feelings and emotions towards the \
objects of prejudice. \
\
>BEHAVIORAL The behavioral component consists of predispositions to act in certain \
ways (e.g., discrimination). \
\
A. SOURCES OF PREJUDICE \
\
A variety of sources of prejudice and discrimination are thought to exist. These include \
learning, cognitive processes, personality traits, economic and political competition, and \
displaced aggression. \
\
>LEARNED PREJUDICE People can learn prejudices in the same way they learn other \
attitudes, through classical and operant conditioning, and social learning. \
\
Research on sex stereotypes has found that males are seen as more competent than females \
by both males and females. When asked to rate a prose passage purportedly written by a \
male versus a female, both males and females consistently rated the male's passage as better \
written. Another study looked at attributions given to men and women for success on \
traditionally masculine versus traditionally feminine tasks. The success of males was \
universally attributed to ability regardless of type of task, while the success of females was \
attributed to ability only on the traditionally female task, and to luck on the traditionally \
male task. \
\
>COGNITIVE PROCESSES People frequently attempt to make sense of the complex \
social world by creating ingroups and outgroups. Ingroups are categories in which people \
see themselves as members, while outgroups consist of all others. People tend to see \
ingroup members as more attractive, possessing more desirable personality attributes, and \
as behaving in more socially acceptable ways. This is referred to as ingroup favoritism and \
outgroup negativity. Another cognitive bias, the outgroup homogeneity effect, is the \
tendency to see more diversity among members of one's ingroup and less among the \
outgroup. This tendency is reflected in statements such as, "They all look alike to me." \
\
>PERSONALITY TRAITS The most salient personality trait associated with prejudice \
is authoritarianism. According to Adorno, people who score high on his F scale are highly \
authoritarian, and are likely to have been raised by domineering fathers and punitive \
mothers. As they grow up, they displace their anger and hatred toward their parents onto \
anyone deviant, disobedient, or who is a member of a minority ethnic group. \
\
\
\
                                    Section 7 - Social Multicultural: \
\
>COMPETITION FOR LIMITED RESOURCES Some research has supported the \
idea that prejudice develops out of competition for limited resources, and is then \
maintained because it results in economic and political advantages to the dominant group. \
In the U.S., lower-class Whites hold more racist attitudes than higher-class Whites. perhaps \
because the upper class is not threatened by minority competition, while lower-class \
Whites might be. \
\
>DISPLACED AGGRESSION A final idea is that prejudice comes out of displaced \
aggression. When the source of frustration is either bigger or capable of retaliating, or when \
the cause of frustration is ambiguous, people displace aggression, or scapegoat, innocent \
victims. \
\
B. REDUCING PREJUDICE AND DISCRIMINATION \
\
Research shows that the best ways to combat prejudice is to encourage cooperation rather \
than competition. In Sherif's (1966) Robber's Cave study, researchers created strong \
feelings of ingroup and outgroup identification in a group of 11 and 12 year old boys at a \
summer camp. After using competition to create prejudice and hatred between two rival \
groups, the researchers demonstrated how cooperation could successfully eliminate it. The \
experimenters created tasks that required expertise, labor, and cooperation from both \
groups, where prizes were given to all for successful completion. \
\
Sherif's study showed the importance of cooperation rather than competition, and \
especially the importance of superordinate goals in reducing prejudice. Superordinate \
goals are higher than individual goals, and are goals that can only be achieved with both \
groups working together, and are of benefit to both parties. \
\
Other researchers have found that sometimes increasing contact between two groups can \
reduce hostility. This is most likely to happen when, in the process, negative stereotypes \
can be disconfirmed. \
\
The best outcome measure of successful intergroup relations, in programs such as school \
integration, is actual measures of behavioral interaction (e.g., kids playing together on the \
playground). \
\
