           7.3 THEORIES OF EMOTION \
\
Three well-known theories of emotion are the James-Lange theory, the Cannon-Bard \
 theory, and Schacter's two-factor theory. \
\
>JAMES-LANGE THEORY According to the James-Lange theory, emotions result \
 from perceiving bodily reactions or responses. For example, an individual is presented with \
a stimulus (e.g., sees a mugger) and the body automatically reacts (e.g., heart rate increases, \
the person begins to run). The individual perceives the bodily reactions and interprets these \
as the emotion of fear. In other words, this theory proposes "I'm running and my heart is \
pounding, so I must be afraid." Overall, research has not supported this theory. \
Physiological arousal commonly occurs in the absence of emotion (e.g., during physical \
exercise). In addition, individuals are not able to perceive the subtle differences in \
physiological arousal that occurs during various emotional states (e.g., fear versus \
excitement). \
\
>CANNON-BARD THEORY The Cannon-Bard theory proposes that emotions and \
bodily reactions occur at the same time. When an individual perceives an event (e.g., sees \
a mugger), messages are sent simultaneously to the hypothalamus (responsible for \
physiologically arousing the body) and to the amygdala (causing the subjective experience \
of fear). Accordingly, bodily reactions are not necessary in order to experience feelings. \
Some support for this theory comes from research that has demonstrated that animals that \
have been surgically prevented from experiencing physiological arousal nevertheless \
display emotional behavior (e.g., growling). \
\
>SCHACTER'S TWO-FACTOR THEORY Schacter's two-factor theory posits that \
 emotion results from information from two systems: internal (e.g., hypothalamus and \
amygdala) and external (e.g., context). Specifically, this theory contends that the \
 experience of emotion is a function of both physiological arousal and cognitive labeling. \
In essence, an individual experiences physical arousal and then looks to the environment \
(external cues) for help labeling the emotion. For example a racing heart (arousal) at the \
 opening of the Olympics (external cues) may be labeled "excitement" whereas the same \
heart racing at the start of the licensing exam may be labeled "anxiety." \
\
This theory received support from Schacter and Singer's (1962) epinephrine studies. \
Subjects were injected with epinephrine and as a result, experienced physical arousal. \
\
