I. PERSON PERCEPTION AND IMPRESSION \
 FORMATION \
\
Person perception, or social perception, refers to the process of forming impressions of \
others. Person perception is thought to be influenced by both affective and cognitive \
 elements. \
\
In forming initial impressions of social and intellectual qualities of others, people typically \
make evaluative assessments based on either positive or negative affective reactions. These \
judgments may be distorted by perceptual biases (e.g., halo effect, primacy effect). For \
example, research has indicated that when forming impressions of others, one tends to view \
another person more favorably if the person first appears competent, and then fails or \
makes mistakes, as compared with a person who fails at a task first and then succeeds. This \
 is presumably because people tend to hold on to information that is presented first. \
\
Person perception is also influenced by cognitive components, because individuals actively \
attempt to develop coherent and meaningful impressions of others. Typically, people create \
social schemas or organized ideas about people, which influence person perception. Social \
schemas are heavily influenced by social context. The impact of social context on person \
 perception was demonstrated in Rosenhan's (1973) study, where seven "normal" people \
 called for appointments at various hospitals, and on arrival complained of hearing voices \
that said "empty," "hollow," and "thud." Other than this single complaint and giving false \
names and occupations, each gave truthful information to the interviewer and acted \
normally. All were admitted to the various hospitals, and all but one were diagnosed with \
schizophrenia. Once inside the hospital, the "pseudopatients" acted normally and never \
mentioned hearing voices. Nevertheless, the hospital staff continued to think of them as \
patients and treated them as such. The average length of stay was 19 days! \
\
