II. SOCIAL COMPARISON \
\
Social comparison theory states that especially when no objective standards exist, people \
tend to compare themselves to others in order to evaluate their own behavior, attributes, \
and abilities. Depending on the circumstance, people compare themselves to others who \
they perceive as quite similar, a little better, or a little worse (e.g., in attributes such as \
attractiveness, wealth, intelligence, success). \
\
Upward comparisons, in which a person compares him or herself to persons who are \
slightly superior, can raise self-esteem by suggesting that improvement is possible. Yet \
upward comparisons can also lower self-esteem by suggesting that the person is not \
performing adequately. \
\
Downward comparisons, in which a person compares him or herself to people who are \
slightly worse, can raise self-esteem by suggesting the person is doing well, or can lower \
self-esteem by reminding the person that his or her own performance could easily \
deteriorate. \
\
III. ATTRACTION \
\
Social psychologists have found several significant factors in interpersonal attraction. \
These include physical attractiveness, proximity, similarity, and reciprocity. \
\
>PHYSICAL ATTRACTIVENESS   Research has consistently shown that physical \
attractiveness is one of the most important factors in our initial liking or loving of others. \
As early as six months of age, infants will spend more time looking at photographs of \
attractive rather than unattractive people. In preschool, beautiful children are more popular \
and rated as more intelligent and well-adjusted by their teachers. As adults, attractive \
individuals are seen by both sexes as more interesting, intelligent, independent, and \
sexually warm. People prefer physically attractive partners, but the matching hypothesis \
posits that people of approximately equal physical attractiveness are likely to select each \
 other. \
\
>PROXIMITY Proximity, physical nearness, or propinquity is another major factor in \
attraction. Proximity appears to promote attraction largely because of mere exposure. \
Familiarity appears to strongly enhance attractiveness and overall liking. \
\
>SIMILARITY The major cementing factor for a long-term relationship is similarity. \
The similarity hypothesis proposes that people similar in social background and values \
