V. AGGRESSION \
\
Aggression is any form of behavior directed toward harming or injuring another living \
being. Theories that attempt to explain aggression have focused on internal as well as \
external explanations for aggression. Internal factors include instinct and biology. External \
factors include frustration, social learning, group influence, and crowding. \
\
>INSTINCTS In terms of the contribution of instinct, Freud proposed that aggressive \
impulses are inborn and instinctive. Ethologists also believe that aggression is instinctual \
and that it evolved because it contributes to survival of the fittest. Ethologists believe \
aggression prevents overcrowding and allows the strongest animals to win mates and \
reproduce the species. Most social psychologists reject both of these instinctual theories. \
\
>BIOLOGICAL THEORIES One focus on the biological theories of aggression has \
been on the study of the brain and nervous system. This research has supported the \
existence of "aggression centers" in the brain (especially the hypothalamus, amygdala, and \
other parts of the limbic system). A second line of biological research has focused on the \
role of hormones, especially testosterone, in aggressive behavior. \
\
>FRUSTRATION-AGGRESSION HYPOTHESIS    One of the most well-known \
theories of aggression is the frustration-aggression hypothesis proposed by Dollard (1939), \
according to which aggression is always due to frustration, and frustration always leads to \
some form of aggression. Experimental tests of this hypothesis have produced conflicting \
results. \
\
>SOCIAL LEARNING THEORY    Social learning theorists believe we learn to be \
aggressive by observing models behaving aggressively and by seeing others rewarded for \
aggressive behavior. Considerable evidence does exist that the media can contribute to \
aggression. Cross-cultural research among children in five countries found that TV \
violence did increase aggressiveness, and that aggressive children do tend to seek out \
violent programs. Several studies found that when TV is introduced to new areas of the \
world, there is an abrupt and dramatic increase in homicide rates. \
\
>GROUP MEMBERSHIP Group membership strongly influences all our behaviors, \
including aggression. Deindividuation is one form of group influence on aggression. Group \
roles (e.g., prison guard) can also influence aggression. \
\
\
