>CROWDING Another factor that may affect aggression is crowding. Crowding tends \
to affect men more than women and leads to a heightened sense of arousal for both positive \
and negative emotions. \
\
VI. SOCIAL INFLUENCE \
\
Social influence refers to the influence that people have upon the beliefs or behaviors of \
others. Two widely researched areas of social influence are conformity and obedience. \
\
A. CONFORMITY \
\
Conformity involves changing one's behavior as a result of real or imagined social or group \
pressure. Two well-known studies on conformity are those of Sherif (1935) and Asch \
(1951). \
\
Sherif (1935) studied the autokinetic effect, which is the tendency for people to perceive \
a stationary point of light to be moving in a darkened room. Sherif found that the \
individual's judgment depended on the group's judgment. Subjects initially tested alone \
changed their judgments the second time around to conform to the group norm. \
\
Asch (1951) studied subjects' responses to a simple task in which subjects were shown a \
card containing three lines (A, B, and C), and were asked to select the line closest in length \
to a fourth line (X). When subjects were placed in a group with six experimental \
confederates who responded incorrectly before the subject, one-third of subjects conformed \
and agreed with the group's obviously incorrect choice. In further studies, Asch found that \
group size and unanimity were major influencing factors. Conformity peaked when groups \
included 7 people that were unanimous. \
\
It appears that in general three factors affect conformity. These include normative social \
influence, informational social influence, and reference groups. \
\
>NORMATIVE SOCIAL INFLUENCE Normative social influence refers to pressure \
to conform based on a need for approval and acceptance by the group. For example, a \
person's choice of clothing is influenced by the type of clothes his friends wear. \
\
Associated with normative social influence are the informal norms of a particular group. \
People's behaviors are highly influenced by the informal norms of the small groups of which \
