they are members. For example, research has shown that teenagers are more affected by \
their peers' sexual behavior than by information on HIV prevention. \
\
>INFORMATIONAL SOCIAL INFLUENCE Informational social influence refers to \
pressure to conform based on the assumption that the other person has more information \
than you. For example, a person buys a certain brand of ski equipment because a friend, \
who is an avid skier, recommended it. \
\
>REFERENCE GROUPS Reference groups refer to people we admire, like, and want \
to resemble, which can include athletes, movie stars, parents, teachers, supervisors, friends, \
etc. For example, a person is influenced to buy Wheaties because of the endorsement of a \
famous athlete. \
\
While much of the research on conformity has focused on majority group influence, there \
has also been research looking at the impact of a person holding a minority opinion within \
the group. (Note that this research concerns someone with a minority opinion, not an ethnic \
minority individual in a group of individuals from the majority culture.) The likelihood of \
this person influencing the group is enhanced when the person with the minority viewpoint \
persists in expressing his or her position, is firm yet flexible, and is logically consistent and \
coherent. Additional factors influencing persuasiveness include the degree to which the \
position is consistent with the predominant social culture of the group, and the extent to \
which the individual agrees with the majority view regarding most other group issues. \
\
Another concept associated with conformity is idiosyncrasy credits. Idiosyncrasy credits \
can be earned by initially conforming to the group's norms. If a person has earned \
idiosyncrasy credits, the group is more tolerant when she or he later deviates from certain \
group norms. In other words, a group will allow a member to deviate from the established \
norms if she or he has previously complied with group norms. \
\
B. OBEDIENCE \
\
A second form of social influence, obedience, involves following a direct command. \
usually from someone in authority. The classic studies on obedience were those of Milgram \
(1963, 1974). In Milgram's studies, subjects were brought into a laboratory, ostensibly to \
study the effects of punishment on learning. Subjects were instructed to provide shocks to \
another subject (actually a confederate) when the latter gave a wrong response or no \
response. The shock meter was labeled from "slight shock" to "DANGER: Severe Shock," \
and up to XXX (450 volts). Although no shock was actually administered, confederates" \
responses ranged from uttering sounds of pain, pounding on the walls, pleas to stop, and \
