deathly silence. A total of 65% of the subjects obeyed the commands of the experimenter \
and administered the most severe levels of shock. \
\
The key factors that appear to play a role in obedience include the power of persons in \
positions of authority, placement of responsibility (in Milgram's experiment subjects were \
assured early on that the experimenter was responsible for the well-being of the learner), \
and gradualism. In Milgram's experiment, the levels of shock were gradually increased. It \
has been proposed that the initial mild levels of shocks may have worked as a foot-in-the \
door technique, whereby once a participant complied with the initial request, he or she \
may have felt trapped by his or her behavior and the nature of the situation. A key factor \
that has been shown to reduce obedience is witnessing a disobedient model. \
\
VII. GROUPS \
\
A group consists of two or more people who have some mutually recognized relationship \
with one another. Being a part of a group can significantly influence behavior, decision- \
making, and task performance. The three basic types of group tasks are classified as \
additive, disjunctive, and conjunctive. \
\
>ADDITIVE TASKS An additive task is one in which group members' separate \
performances are added to produce a combined effect. For example, a group of scientists \
and engineers combine their talents to construct a space shuttle. \
\
>DISJUNCTIVE TASKS A disjunctive task is one in which the outcome is affected by \
the performance of the most effective group member. For example, a group meets to decide \
how to improve the company's marketing strategy, and one person comes up with an \
outstanding idea. \
\
>CONJUNCTIVE TASKS    A conjunctive task is one in which the group's \
accomplishment is limited by the performance of the least effective member. For example, \
one member of a team that oversees quality control sleeps during his shift, resulting in \
significant product errors. \
\
A. GROUP INFLUENCE ON BEHAVIOR \
\
Behavior can be significantly affected by the roles played in a group. In the now classic \
Stanford University prison study by Zimbardo (1978), 20 well-adjusted young college men \
were paid $15 a day to participate in a simulation of prison life and were randomly assigned \
