to be either prisoner or guard. While planned to last two weeks, the study was stopped after \
six days because of alarming psychological changes in the participants. The guards were \
 seriously abusing their power and the traumatized prisoners were becoming more and more \
depressed. According to interviews conducted after the study, the students became so \
absorbed in their roles that they forgot they were volunteers in a university experiment. \
\
Groups can also exert a powerful influence by inducing feelings of anonymity. \
 Deindividuation refers to the process of suspending one's private self-identity and \
adopting instead the identity of the group. It involves both decreased self-awareness and \
 decreased self-regulation. Zimbardo (1970) created conditions of anonymity by having \
 NYU female students wear identical white coats and hoods resembling members of the Ku \
 Klux Klan. When given the opportunity to administer shocks to other female volunteers \
 (actually confederates), the women in costume gave twice the amount of shock as the \
 women who were not in costume and wore large name tags. Zimbardo's experiment \
demonstrated that the critical factor in deindividuation is anonymity, not just group \
membership. \
\
 B. DECISION-MAKING IN GROUPS \
\
Group decision-making has been described as being influenced by three phenomena: risky \
shift, group polarization, and groupthink. \
\
 >RISKY SHIFT Risky shift describes the tendency for people in groups to make riskier \
decisions than they would if they were deciding as individuals. For example, people \
making business investments individually are more cautious than people who pool their \
monies and make business investments as a group. Because of tendencies to make riskier \
decisions, groups can be more creative and innovative than individuals working alone. \
\
>RESPONSE POLARIZATION     Response polarization, also known as group \
polarization, describes the tendency for people in groups to become more extreme in their \
 views. For example, someone opposed to abortion who joins a group of like-minded \
individuals will be likely to end up more strongly opposed to abortion. \
\
>GROUPTHINK Groupthink occurs in highly cohesive groups when group members \
seek concurrence, consensus, and unanimity more than they seek the best possible \
alternative. When groupthink occurs, there is a tendency for group members to think alike \
and lose their critical evaluative capacities due to social pressures to conform. A significant \
historical example comes from the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941. Prior to the \
attack, the commander-in-chief of the U.S. Pacific Fleet met with his high-level staff \
