                     DIVERSITY \
\
The APA Ethics Code mandates awareness and respect for human differences in terms of \
age, gender, gender identity, race, ethnicity, culture, national origin, religion, sexual \
orientation, disability, language, and socioeconomic status (SES). This section focuses \
primarily on the area of ethnicity and culture, and also includes small sections on \
socioeconomic status and on issues affecting LGBTQ people. \
\
>EMIC VS. ETIC Traditionally, psychology has taken an etic or universal view of people: \
it has assumed that there are universal principles underlying personality, psychopathology, \
and psychotherapy. For example, theories like those of Maslow and Rogers assume that \
optimal human development is the same for all individuals regardless of culture. \
Historically, psychology has taken an individualistic perspective, highly valuing traits such \
as autonomy and self-actualization. \
\
Increasingly, however, an emic or culture-specific view is being encouraged. From an emic \
perspective, every culture has its own norms and values. No one model of mental health \
can be applied to all. For example, what may be considered unhealthy neediness in one \
culture may be adaptive functioning in another. In general, interdependence and social \
relatedness are more highly valued in nonwestern cultures. \
