  7.5 IMMIGRATION AND ACCULTURATION \
\
>IMMIGRATION    Immigration is in itself a significant stressor. Studies have \
demonstrated higher rates of psychiatric hospitalization in the U.S. for immigrant groups. \
especially young men. Many immigrant families experience conflict and stress because the \
family members acculturate at different rates and to different degrees. Most often, children \
and teenagers acculturate more quickly than parents, and there ensues a clash of cultural \
values between the generations. Psychiatric problems tend to peak between one year and \
three years after immigration. \
\
>ACCULTURATION Acculturation is the process by which members of one cultural \
group learn about and adopt the beliefs and behaviors of another group. Although \
acculturation is usually in the direction of a minority group adopting habits and language \
patterns of the dominant group, acculturation can be reciprocal-that is, members of the \
dominant group can adopt patterns typical of the minority group. For example, some White \
teenagers adopt the clothing and speech of hip-hop culture. \
\
>ENCULTURATION Enculturation is defined as the process of learning one's own \
culture, influenced primarily by home and family. \
\
>BICULTURAL   Although different writers use the term bicultural differently, it \
generally refers to people who have successfully integrated two or more separate aspects \
of their cultural identity. Such values, beliefs, and behaviors can come both from the \
person's original cultural identity (e.g., minority) as well as from another culture (e.g., \
majority). Biculturalism is the final stage of most models of racial/cultural identity \
development (see below). \
\
I. BERRY'S THEORY OF ACCULTURATION \
\
J. W. Berry has proposed that the two key factors in the acculturation process are cultural \
maintenance, and contact and participation. Cultural maintenance refers to valuing and \
preserving cultural identity. Contact and participation refers to involvement with the \
dominant culture and other cultural groups. \
\
\
\
                          Section 7 - Social & Multicultural: Immigration \
\
According to Berry's theory, there are four acculturation strategies based on the interaction \
of the two factors. \
\
>ASSIMILATION When individuals assimilate, they do not maintain their cultural \
identity, but they do seek regular interaction with other cultures. Assimilation may be \
evidenced by changes in language preference, adoption of dominant attitudes and values, \
membership in social groups and institutions, and loss of separate political or ethnic \
identification. \
\
>SEPARATION Separation occurs when individuals place value on their original culture \
and wish to avoid interaction with people from other cultures. \
\
>INTEGRATION    Integration occurs when people maintain their original cultural \
identity while also interacting with people from other cultures. \
\
>MARGINALIZATION   Marginalization occurs when people do not maintain their \
cultural identity and do not seek interaction with people from other cultures. \
\
