     7.6 PHYSICAL AND MENTAL HEALTH \
\
I. HEALTH CARE UTILIZATION \
\
Overall, racial and cultural minorities are underrepresented in the mental health system. \
People from minority groups may not seek mental health services because they distrust the \
providers and agencies or view therapy as a potential instrument of oppression. \
\
In terms of general medical care, people of color do not receive the same quality of care \
that Whites do, resulting in a higher mortality rate among people of color. There is also a \
much higher rate of being uninsured among minorities, for example about 16% of \
Hispanics are uninsured compared to approximately 6% of Whites. Even when minorities \
are insured, they are more likely to rely on visits to the emergency room for their primary \
care, suggesting that they have less access to private physicians. \
\
II. CULTURAL ISSUES IN MENTAL DISORDERS \
\
>CROSS-CULTURAL VALIDITY OF MENTAL DISORDERS      Many mental \
disorders categorized in DSM-5 are found throughout the world with similar and \
recognizable symptoms. These disorders include schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, panic \
disorder, and obsessive-compulsive disorder. Prevalence rates for these disorders, \
including schizophrenia, are also relatively equivalent. \
\
>CROSS-CULTURAL VARIATION IN MENTAL DISORDERS    The prevalence \
rates of some disorders vary greatly across countries, presumably indicating that social and \
cultural factors play a causal role. For example, the prevalence rate of major depression \
ranges from 2 to 19 percent across countries. \
\
>CULTURAL CONCEPTS OF DISTRESS The DSM-5 describes cultural concepts of \
distress as the ways that cultural groups experience, understand, and communicate \
emotional pain, behavioral problems, or difficult thoughts. Cultural concepts of distress \
include cultural syndromes, cultural idioms of distress, and cultural explanations or \
perceived causes. \
\
\
\
                           Section 7 - Social & Multicultural: Physical and Mental Health \
\
     CULTURAL SYNDROMES Cultural syndromes are clusters of attributions and \
     symptoms that tend to occur among persons in specific groups or communities, and \
     which are recognized as a pattern of experience (e.g., ataque de nervios). \
\
     CULTURAL IDIOMS OF DISTRESS Cultural idioms of distress are shared or \
     collective ways of expressing distress that may not involve specific syndromes or \
     symptoms (e.g .. "nerves"). Somatization, or the expression of distress through \
     somatic complaints, is a common idiom of distress. Certain physical symptoms are \
     more common among certain cultural groups than others (e.g., stomach symptoms \
     among Whites and Hispanics, cardiopulmonary symptoms among Asians). \
     Members of some cultural groups more easily admit to somatic complaints than \
     emotional distress. This preference to present with somatic complaints is viewed \
     by contemporary theorists as a sociocultural phenomenon and not as a reflection of \
     the patient's defensiveness or lack of psychological sophistication. \
\
     CULTURAL EXPLANATIONS OR PERCEIVED CAUSES       Cultural \
     explanations or perceived causes are the attributions, labels, or ways of explaining \
     the causes of illness, symptoms, or distress. \
\
III. CULTURAL ISSUES IN PSYCHOTHERAPY \
\
>CULTURAL ENCAPSULATION   Cultural encapsulation can significantly impede \
effective psychotherapy when clients are of a different cultures background than the \
therapist. Cultural encapsulation occurs when the therapist makes narrow assumptions \
about reality, minimizes cultural variation among individuals, disregards evidence \
disconfirming the superiority of the dominant culture, resorts to technique-oriented \
strategies and short-term solutions, and judges others according to the encapsulated \
therapist's self-reference criteria. \
\
>CULTURAL COMPETENCE Cultural competence refers to the ability to provide \
appropriate and effective services to minority group members, taking into consideration \
their languages, histories, traditions, and values. To be culturally competent, therapists \
must be aware of their own cultural values as well as the culture of their patients, and work \
to acquire the skills and knowledge to provide appropriate and effective treatment. \
\
\
 \
\
