      7.7 SOCIOECONOMIC STATUS (SES) \
\
The socioeconomic status of most racial minority groups is disproportionately lower than \
that of Whites. Lower SES has repeatedly been correlated with higher levels of mental \
illness and psychological distress. For example, people with the lowest level of SES are \
two to three times more likely to have a mental disorder than those with the highest level \
of SES. It is still controversial whether lower socioeconomic status causes mental illness \
(i.e., it is stressful to be poor), mental illness causes socioeconomic status (i.e., \
psychological problems impair effective behavior, causing "downward drift"), or \
diagnostic procedures are inherently biased. For example, in one study, individuals with \
identical symptoms were diagnosed as having schizophrenia when they were of low SES \
whereas they were diagnosed as having bipolar disorder when they were of higher SES. \
\
In psychotherapy, individuals of lower SES and education drop out at a higher rate than \
those of higher SES and education. They also tend to be assigned the least experienced \
counselors and psychotherapists. When individuals of lower SES remain in therapy. \
however, they derive as much benefit as those of higher SES. Some believe that SES may \
actually account for differences in treatment outcome that are typically attributed to race. \
\
\
\
                                Section 7 - Social & Multicultural: Sexual Orientation \
\
            7.8 SEXUAL ORIENTATION \
\
LGBTQ people commonly face social stigmatization, discrimination, and even violence \
because of their sexual orientation. These experiences put gay men at greater risk for \
mental health problems and emotional distress. (Research is still sparse on the effect of \
these factors on lesbians.) Overall, however, extensive research shows that there are few \
significant differences in psychological functioning between heterosexual people and \
people who are LGBTQ. \
\
Adolescence poses unique challenges to LGBTQ youth. They are more likely than their \
heterosexual peers to abuse substances, attempt suicide, and become victims of violence, \
including within the family. Those who are rejected by their parents are more likely to \
become homeless, contract HIV, or become prostitutes. In middle and late adulthood, \
people in same-sex relationships tend to receive less support from their families of origin \
as compared to heterosexual people. \
\
The term heterosexism refers to ideas and actions that denigrate non-heterosexual \
behavior. Like racism and sexism, heterosexism can occur both on cultural and \
psychological levels. Although the terms homophobia and heterosexism are often used \
interchangeably, heterosexism is currently the favored term. The term homophobia \
implies fear and hatred of gays and lesbians. It refers to a specific mental state and is not \
as encompassing as heterosexism. \
\
I. GAY AND LESBIAN IDENTITY DEVELOPMENT \
\
R. R. Troiden has developed a model of gay and lesbian identity development that has four \
stages. \
\
>STAGE ONE: SENSITIZATION This stage occurs before puberty. The child feels \
different from peers, may be marginalized, and ultimately internalizes a negative self- \
concept. The child's sense of differentness is related more to gender (i.e., feeling different \
from other boys or girls) rather than to sexuality. \
\
>STAGE TWO: IDENTITY CONFUSION In this stage, which occurs around the age \
of 17 or 18. there is a growing recognition of homosexual feelings and impulses, and, at \
