          7.9 CULTURE AND ETHNICITY \
\
I. COMMUNICATION STYLES \
\
Communication styles differ significantly between cultures. Some of the differences \
include proxemics (use of personal space), kinesics (body movements, including facial \
expressions and eye contact), and paralanguage (vocal cues, including loudness, pauses, \
 and rate of speech). \
\
Cultures also differ in the importance placed on the context of the communication. \
\
>LOW-CONTEXT COMMUNICATION      In a low-context communication, the \
meaning of the communication is based on what is explicitly verbalized. What matters are \
the words that are actually said. Middle-class White American culture not only tends to use \
a low-context communication style, it actually tends to value this style highly (e.g., "say \
what you mean," "be direct"). \
\
>HIGH-CONTEXT COMMUNICATION      In a high-context communication, the \
situation and non-verbal cues significantly affect the meaning of what is verbalized. The \
same words can have an entirely different meaning depending on how and when they are \
said. For example, a hesitant "yes" in Filipino culture actually means a polite refusal. \
African Americans, Asian Americans, Hispanics, and Native Americans generally use a \
high-context communication style. \
\
II. MINORITY IDENTITY DEVELOPMENT MODEL \
\
The Minority Identity Development Model is the most comprehensive and accepted of \
contemporary models of racial and cultural identity (Atkinson, Morton & Sue, 1993). Each \
of the five stages is defined in terms of attitudes toward the self, one's own minority group, \
different minority groups, and the dominant culture. \
\
>STAGE ONE: CONFORMITY In this first stage, the minority person unequivocally \
prefers the dominant culture. The person therefore has negative attitudes about oneself, \
one's own minority group, as well as other minority groups. \
\
\
 \
\
