\
>STAGE TWO: DISSONANCE In the dissonance stage, the person begins to appreciate \
aspects of the minority culture and to question the values and customs of the dominant \
culture. This stage is marked by conflict between the old deprecating attitudes toward \
oneself, one's minority group, and other minority groups, and the newer positive attitudes \
that are developing. \
\
>STAGE THREE: RESISTANCE (also called Immersion) In the resistance stage, the \
person tends to completely endorse minority-held views, experience a strong sense of \
identification with the minority group, and reject the dominant values of society and \
culture. The person experiences conflict between ethnocentrism and empathy for other \
minority groups. Racial pride is substituted for previous self-hatred. \
\
>STAGE FOUR: INTROSPECTION   Introspection involves a deeper analysis of \
attitudes and feelings. The person begins to discover that the level of intensity of negative \
feelings directed toward White society is draining. Furthermore, the person recognizes that \
many elements of White U.S. culture are highly functional and desirable. The person may \
feel that rigidly held onto minority-group views have weakened personal autonomy, and \
thus concerns are raised about uncritically appreciating one's group. Ethnocentrism also \
diminishes, and is replaced by an interest in the oppression experienced by other groups. \
\
>STAGE FIVE: SYNERGETIC ARTICULATION AND AWARENESS (also called \
Integrative Awareness) This final stage involves the ability to be both appreciative and \
appropriately critical of aspects of one's own culture, the dominant culture, and other \
minority cultures. \
\
III. BLACK IDENTITY DEVELOPMENT \
\
Some earlier, though similar, models of identity formation have focused solely on Black \
identity development. According to Jackson's model, a Black person's identity is strongly \
influenced by experiences of racism and oppression. The person moves through four \
stages: passive-acceptance, active-resistance, redirection, and internalization. \
\
>CROSS'S MODEL According to this model, an African American person moves \
through five stages, from a White frame of reference to a positive Black frame of reference: \
preencounter (similar to conformity), encounter (similar to dissonance), immersion- \
emersion (similar to resistance), internalization (similar to introspection and the \
beginning of synergetic articulation and awareness), and internalization-commitment \
(similar to synergetic articulation and awareness). \
\
\
\
                              Section 7 - Social Multicultural: Culture and Ethnicity \
\
IV. HELMS'S WHITE RACIAL IDENTITY \
DEVELOPMENT MODEL \
\
Helms developed a model of White racial identity development that includes six stages. \
\
>STAGE ONE: CONTACT In this stage, White individuals are fairly ignorant, and don't \
recognize racism and their own White privilege. There may be a curiosity, timidity or \
trepidation about people of color, and a superficial and inconsistent awareness of being \
White. Some White people remain in this stage indefinitely. \
\
>STAGE TWO: DISINTEGRATION    In this stage, individuals begin to feel \
uncomfortable with the advantages of being White, and with the role of Whites in \
maintaining racism. To cope with this dissonance, many individuals deny the existence of \
racism or avoid people of color. \
\
>STAGE THREE: REINTEGRATION    In the reintegration stage, the person \
consciously acknowledges a White identity, including the belief that Whites are superior \
to people of color. Thus, the person in the reintegration stage accepts the belief in White \
racial superiority and the inferiority of other racial groups. \
\
>STAGE FOUR: PSEUDO-INDEPENDENCE In the fourth stage, the person begins to \
actively question the proposition that Blacks are innately inferior to Whites, Some Whites \
in this stage try to disavow their own Whiteness and associate with people of color. This \
attempt usually results in a sense of alienation from Whites, as well as from many people \
of color who are suspicious of their friendliness. \
\
>STAGE FIVE: IMMERSION/EMERSION    Self-examination and information- \
seeking characterize this stage. The person examines his or her own racial identity, striving \
to replace myths about race with accurate information. One outcome may be trying to \
change White people and their attitudes towards people of color. \
\
>STAGE SIX: AUTONOMY In this stage, the person achieves a positive redefinition of \
being White that includes an ongoing openness to new information and new ways of \
thinking about racial and cultural variables. \
\
 HINT: Although "integration" is usually seen as a positive, such as "integrative \
 awareness" in the minority identity model, the reintegration stage of Helms's model is \
 not positive, as it involves endorsing White racial superiority. \
\
\
 \
\
