\
V. CULTURAL GROUPS \
\
Although the U.S. includes many diverse ethnic and cultural groups, there are four \
recognized minority groups: Hispanic Americans, African Americans, Asian \
Americans/Pacific Islanders, and Native Americans/Alaska Natives. According to the 2010 \
census, the ethnic breakdown of the U.S. population is: 17% Hispanic American, 13% \
African American, 5% Asian American, 1% Native American, and 63% White (non- \
Hispanic). About one third of all new entrants into the workforce are minorities. \
\
Current multicultural guidelines encourage psychologists to learn about the cultures of the \
people with whom they work. At the same time, psychologists are cautioned against \
oversimplification and stereotyping. In fact, there is tremendous heterogeneity within each \
of the recognized minority groups. For example, there are 43 different ethnic subgroups \
among Asian Americans/Pacific Islanders, with over 100 different languages and dialects \
spoken. Very often, within-group differences are greater than between-group differences. \
For example, a recent immigrant from Honduras may differ more from a third-generation \
Mexican American who speaks only English than either do from a middle-class White \
American. \
\
A. HISPANIC AMERICANS \
\
By the year 2050, over one-fourth of the U.S. population will identify as Hispanic. Hispanic \
culture is generally considered collateral as opposed to individualistic, because it highly \
values family and social connectedness. \
\
>MENTAL HEALTH ISSUES Central American immigrants often have a history of \
significant war-related trauma and high rates of PTSD. Cultural concepts of distress among \
Hispanics include susto (fright), nervios (nerves), mal de ojo (evil eye), and attaque de \
nervios (screaming, crying, aggression, dissociation, fainting). \
\
Emotional symptoms are often expressed in terms of physical complaints. In other words, \
the Hispanic idioms of distress are often somatic in nature. It is therefore very important \
that this illness language is not mistaken for somatie symptom disorders. Somatie symptom \
disorders should be diagnosed with care among Hispanics. \
\
As with other minorities, Hispanics tend to be underserved by the mental health system. \
There are proportionately very few Hispanic mental health professionals. Because an \
estimated 32% of the Hispanic population does not speak English fluently, language often \
