is able to convey respect. Overall, the therapy relationship should be egalitarian. \
\
There is some research to suggest that a Black person's stage of racial identity may affect \
attitudes toward counseling, with those in any stage other than the first preferring to see a \
Black counselor. Other research suggests that the key variable is whether the therapist is \
culturally sensitive. \
\
Nancy Boyd-Franklin advocates a multisystems approach to working with African \
American and other minority families. From this perspective, a family's struggle must be \
understood not only in terms of family dynamics and family systems, but in its larger \
environmental and cultural context. She encourages meetings outside of the consultation \
room and active involvement with the different systems that influence clients, such as the \
school, the church, social services, and the extended family. \
\
In the area of assessment of intelligence, some research does indicate that African \
American children perform better when assessed by same-race examiners. However, the \
more powerful variable appears to be the examiner's competence, expertise, and ability to \
establish rapport with the child. \
\
C. ASIAN AMERICANS/PACIFIC ISLANDERS \
\
Some theorists characterize Asian American culture as collateral, because interdependence \
is favored over autonomy. Other theorists consider it lineal, because there are clear lines of \
authority. The family structure tends to be hierarchical and patriarchal. \
\
>MENTAL HEALTH ISSUES Cultural concepts of distress among Asian Americans \
include neurasthenia and hwa-byung ("suppressed anger syndrome," involving \
palpitations, headache, dysphoria, and anxiety). Among Southeast Asian refugees, PTSD \
occurs at a high rate because of traumas experienced before or during immigration. \
\
Asian Americans utilize mental health treatment at a very low rate, most likely because \
shame and stigma are associated with having mental health problems. These problems may \
be expressed in an indirect manner, through physical complaints and academic or \
vocational problems. Language also poses a significant barrier to treatment for about a \
third of all Asian Americans. \
\
>IMPLICATIONS FOR TREATMENT Research has shown that Asian Americans \
generally prefer a structured therapeutic approach in which the therapist is active and \
