\
Developmental psychology focuses on age-related changes in behavior and abilities \
 throughout the lifespan, from conception to death. This section first describes some of the \
 basic concepts relevant to human development, and then focuses on physical development, \
 cognitive development, and psychosocial development. This section concludes with a \
 discussion of risk and protective factors in development. \
\
                8.1 BASIC CONCEPTS \
\
 I. TYPES OF DEVELOPMENTAL CHANGE \
\
 It has been proposed that there are two kinds of developmental change: qualitative and \
 quantitative. \
\
 >QUALITATIVE CHANGE Stage theorists, including Piaget, Kohlberg, and Erikson, \
 propose that development is discontinuous, and that periods of little change alternate with \
 periods of abrupt and rapid change. According to stage theorists, children who do not \
 master stage-specific issues are at increased risk for subsequent developmental failures. \
 Stage theorists assert that differences between adults and children are qualitative rather \
 than quantitative. For example, differences in thinking between the concrete operational \
 child and formal operational adolescent represent a qualitative shift in thinking, rather than \
 simply knowing more. \
\
 >QUANTITATIVE CHANGE    Continuity proponents, including Robbie Case, a \
 proponent of the information processing approach, argue that development is continuous, \
 with new abilities, skills, and knowledge developing gradually and relatively uniformly \
 over time. This model suggests that differences between adults and children in terms of \
 thinking and behavior are more quantitative, rather than qualitative. For example, an adult \
 can remember more than a child because of maturation of neurological processes, a \
developmental process that proceeds steadily and gradually over time. \
\
 \
\
                                     Section 8 - Developmental: Basic Concepts \
\
 II. INFLUENCES ON DEVELOPMENT \
\
 Development is influenced by many factors. Broadly these can be classified as genetic and \
 environmental influences, and normative and non-normative influences. \
\
 A. GENETIC AND ENVIRONMENTAL INFLUENCES \
\
 Heredity refers to the inborn genetic endowment that a person receives from his or her \
 biological parents. Environmental influences refer to influences outside the person, \
 beginning in the womb. Teasing out the specific impact of either heredity or environment \
 on development is difficult, as the distinction between the two quickly blurs. \
\
 Current models of development propose that genetic and environmental variables transact \
 continually over time. Some research suggests that with regard to certain aspects of \
 development (e.g., personality, IQ), the relative weight of genetic and environmental \
 influences changes over time. It has been suggested that environment affects outcome more \
 significantly in the early years than in later adulthood. For example, environmental \
 influences explain significant variability in IQ in childhood, but not in adolescence. There \
appears to be a gradual penetrance throughout life of genetic predispositions. \
\
 When it comes to environmental influences, Urie Bronfenbrenner has proposed an \
 ecological approach to development that delineates five levels of environmental influence. \
 He suggests that to understand a person's development, we must study the person in the \
 context of multiple environments: the microsystem, the mesosystem, the exosystem, the \
 macrosystem, and the chronosystem. \
\
 >THE MICROSYSTEM   The microsystem is the everyday environment the person \
 encounters, and includes the home, school, work, or neighborhood. The microsystem \
 consists of bi-directional relationships with parents, siblings, teachers, friends, etc. \
\
 >THE MESOSYSTEM   The mesosystem consists of the interaction or links between \
 various microsystems, such as the home and school, work and friends, etc. For example, a \
 child's parents meet with his teacher to strategize how to facilitate learning for him. \
\
 >THE EXOSYSTEM The exosystem describes the relationship between two or more \
 settings, at least one of which does not contain the person, but indirectly affects him or her. \
 For example, a child is not directly involved in the parents' workplace but may nevertheless \
 be very influenced by how the workplace affects the parents. \
\
 \
 \
\
                                     Section 8 - Developmental: Basic Concepts \
\
>THE MACROSYSTEM The macrosystem includes the influences of culture, religion, \
 the economy and political systems. \
\
 >THE CHRONOSYSTEM The chronosystem addresses the role of the passage of time \
 in the person's life. It encompasses changes that take place in the family, such as birth of \
 siblings or moving to a new neighborhood, as well as changes in the larger environment, \
 such as economic growth or war. \
\
 B. NORMATIVE AND NON-NORMATIVE INFLUENCES \
\
 Psychologists and researchers make the distinction between normative and non-normative \
 events that influence development. \
\
>NORMATIVE INFLUENCES ON DEVELOPMENT    Normative events are those \
 that occur in a similar way for most people. Normative events are further classified as either \
 age-graded or history-graded. \
\
      AGE-GRADED NORMATIVE EVENTS An age-graded normative event is an \
     event that is commonly experienced by people of a particular age group. Examples \
     include puberty and menopause, entering kindergarten, or retirement. \
\
     HISTORY-GRADED NORMATIVE EVENTS    A history-graded normative \
     event is an event that is common to a particular cohort, for example, the great \
     depression, the Vietnam war, women's liberation, or the impact of television and \
     computers. \
\
>NON-NORMATIVE INFLUENCES ON DEVELOPMENT     Non-normative life \
 events are unusual events that have a major impact on an individual's life. Non-normative \
 events can include typical events that occur at an atypical time of life, such as death of a \
 parent when the child is young, or atypical events such as a birth defect, or a fire consuming \
 one's home. \
\
 C. CRITICAL AND SENSITIVE PERIODS \
\
>CRITICAL PERIODS A critical period is defined as a specific time during an \
 organism's life span when it is most sensitive to environmental influences or stimulation. \
 A specific structure or phenomenon must occur during the critical period, or it will not \
 occur at all. For example, during the embryonic stage of development (the first eight weeks \
\
