\
 after conception), certain organs form. If they do not form properly at this stage, they will \
 never be able to develop properly. The embryo is thus most vulnerable to (i.e., \
 agents that cause birth defects) during this critical period. Another famous example of \
 critical periods was Konrad Lorenz's finding that goslings that had imprinted on him \
 between 12 and 17 hours after birth continued to follow him even when other geese later \
 became available as models. \
\
 >SENSITIVE PERIODS In the study of human development, particularly cognitive and \
 emotional development, the term sensitive period is preferred over critical period. During \
 a sensitive period, stimulation and learning has more of an impact than it will at any other \
 time. For example, children learn language best and most easily from the ages of one to \
 three. However, children who are deprived of language during these years can still develop \
 language later. \
\
 Unlike animals who have critical periods in attachment behavior, human children are able \
 to make attachments after the first year of life. In fact, these attachments can be of equal \
 intensity and quality as those from the first year of life. One of the most encouraging \
 consequences of this finding is that many adopted children are still able to make healthy \
 attachments to caregivers even in late childhood. \
