         8.2 PHYSICAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
This section focuses on physical development throughout the lifespan, beginning with \
heredity. This is followed by a description of the physical aspects of prenatal development, \
development in infancy and childhood, adolescent and adult development, and physical \
development in late adulthood. \
\
I. HEREDITY \
\
A. BASIC CONCEPTS \
\
Genes and chromosomes transmit hereditary characteristics. From conception, each human \
cell contains 23 pairs of chromosomes, on which there are thousands of genes, the carriers \
of hereditary traits. The gene is composed of DNA and RNA, which contain the genetic \
code. In addition to its genetic importance, RNA has been noted to have a significant role \
in memory functioning. \
\
Of the 23 pairs of chromosomes, 22 pairs are autosomes chromosomes unrelated to \
sexual expression. The twenty-third pair consists of the two sex chromosomes, one coming \
from the father, the other from the mother. The sex chromosome of every ovum is an X, \
but the sperm may contain either an X or a Y. When an X-carrying sperm fertilizes the \
ovum, the zygote formed is XX, a female. In contrast, when a Y-carrying sperm fertilizes \
the ovum, the zygote formed is XY, a male. \
\
>GENOTYPE   The genotype is the genetic makeup of the person, containing both \
expressed and unexpressed characteristics. \
\
>PHENOTYPE The phenotype is the observable characteristics of the person. \
\
Some genes have strong penetrance, and they express themselves in virtually all \
environments (e.g., genes for height). By contrast, many genes (e.g., genes for weight) have \
only partial penetrance, and environmental factors are strongly associated with their \
expression. Twin studies are most commonly used to assess the relative genetic, \
biological, or dispositional contribution to a variable or variables under study. \
\
\
\
                                 Section 8 - Developmental: Physical Development \
\
B. GENETIC & CHROMOSOMAL ABNORMALITIES \
\
Every year, about 6% of babies born in the United States are born with physical or mental \
disabilities. Many of these disabilities are due to genetic and chromosomal abnormalities. \
Some abnormalities are due to sex chromosome abnormalities, such as Klinefelter's and \
Turner's. The majority, however, are due to autosomal abnormalities. These include Down \
syndrome, PKU, and sickle cell anemia. \
\
>KLINEFELTER'S SYNDROME   Klinefelter's syndrome occurs only in men and \
results from an extra X chromosome (XXY). Men with Klinefelter's tend to be taller, less \
intelligent (IQ around 90), and have abnormal development of secondary sex \
characteristics (e.g., partial breast development, small testicles, high pitched voice). They \
are unable to have children. \
\
>TURNER'S SYNDROME Turner's syndrome occurs only in women and results from \
a missing X chromosome (X0). These women generally have normal intelligence but have \
abnormal development of secondary sexual characteristics (e.g., no menstruation, no \
ovulation). \
\
>DOWN SYNDROME Down syndrome, or trisomy 21, involves three chromosomes on \
chromosome 21. Down syndrome is characterized by intellectual disability, a broad skull, \
slanted eyes, physical deformities, and reduced activity. \
\
>PKU (PHENYLKETONURIA) PKU is an inherited autosomal recessive disorder \
caused by a defective gene that affects metabolism, such that phenylalanine cannot be \
metabolized. PKU can result in severe mental deficiency. If detected early, babies can be \
put on a special phenylalanine-free diet, which will ward off these serious problems. \
\
>HEMOPHILIA   Hemophilia is a sex-linked recessive disorder that causes excessive \
bleeding. Found predominantly in males, it requires frequent transfusion of blood with \
clotting factors. \
\
>SICKLE-CELL ANEMIA Sickle-cell anemia is an autosomal recessive disorder that \
occurs primarily in African Americans, with one in 500 African Americans having the \
disease, and one in 12 being carriers. Sickle-cell anemia results in deformed, fragile red \
blood cells that can clog the blood vessels, causing anemia, severe pain, stunted growth \
and frequent infections. Treatment includes transfusions and painkillers. \
\
\
 \
\
                                 Section 8 - Developmental: Physical Development \
\
II. PRENATAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
Conception or fertilization occurs when the female's ovum combines with the male's \
sperm, forming a new cell, the zygote. The period between conception and birth is called \
gestation and lasts nine months for humans. During gestation, the zygote multiplies itself \
through the process of cell division and develops into an embryo, and then a fetus. \
\
The prenatal period is divided into three stages, including the germinal, embryonic, and \
fetal stages. \
\
>THE GERMINAL PERIOD During the germinal period, which lasts from conception \
to two weeks, the zygote rapidly divides and ultimately implants itself onto the uterus wall. \
\
>THE EMBRYONIC PERIOD The embryonic period lasts from two weeks (the time \
of implantation on the uterus wall) to eight to twelve weeks. The embryonic stage involves \
the start and rapid development of the major organ systems and structures, including the \
nervous, respiratory, circulatory and digestive systems, as well as the eyes, ears, and limbs. \
Almost all birth defects occur during the first trimester. \
\
The embryo is most vulnerable to the effects of teratogenic agents (agents that cause birth \
defects) such as medications, virus, or radiation in the first eight to twelve weeks, when \
basic structures are being formed. \
\
>THE FETAL PERIOD The fetal period lasts from eight to twelve weeks until birth. \
This stage involves rapid growth, with the organs and other systems developing more \
complexity. In addition, less crucial body parts, such as nails and lashes, begin to form. \
\
During the fetal period and for the first few years of life, growth and development proceed \
in a cephalocaudal fashion (from the top of the body down), which means that the head \
and upper body develop before the lower body. \
\
A. MATERNAL FACTORS IN PRENATAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
Several maternal factors affect the development of the embryo or fetus, including nutrition \
and substance use. \
\
>NUTRITION The mother's diet during pregnancy bears significant impact on the health \
of the fetus. Malnutrition is most detrimental while the fetus is still in utero, at a time when \
significant physical growth and brain development is taking place. \
\
\
\
