\
>ALCOHOL    Excessive alcohol use during pregnancy can result in fetal alcohol \
syndrome (FAS), characterized by delayed growth, physical deformities, delayed motor \
development, decreased intelligence and learning disabilities, short attention span, \
restlessness, irritability, and hyperactivity. \
\
>COCAINE Cocaine use during pregnancy has been associated with an increased risk \
of spontaneous abortion, prematurity, low birth weight, neurological problems, and a \
smaller head circumference. Babies exposed to cocaine in utero are not as alert or \
responsive emotionally or cognitively as babies who have not been exposed to cocaine. In \
later years, problems with organization, language skills, and emotional attachment are \
commonly evidenced. \
\
>NICOTINE Nicotine use during pregnancy can result in infant death and low birth \
weight. In addition, in school aged children, long-term complications are similar to those \
found in children whose mothers abuse alcohol during pregnancy, and include poor \
attention span, hyperactivity, lower IQ, and perceptual-motor problems. \
\
B. SEXUAL DIMORPHISM \
\
Sexual dimorphism refers to the systematic differences between individuals of different \
sex in the same species. Sex differences in humans are thought to result from an interaction \
between environmental and biological factors; the details of this process are still being \
worked out. One theory, the organizational/activational hypothesis, proposes that \
hormones influence sex differences in two phases. First, in early life, males and females \
are exposed to different levels of the hormones that organize the nervous system. Second, \
at puberty, males and females are exposed to different levels of the sex steroids that activate \
the previously organized nervous system. Overall, humans exhibit less sexual dimorphism \
than many other species. A hot area of research and controversy, sexual dimorphism is \
clearly evident in the human brain. For example, women tend to have a denser corpus \
callosum. \
\
