III. PHYSICAL DEVELOPMENT DURING INFANCY AND \
CHILDHOOD \
\
This section describes significant aspects of physical development during infancy and \
childhood, including reflexes, perceptual development, motor development and brain \
development. \
\
A. REFLEXES \
\
Infants are born with a number of reflexes, many of which are present in utero. These \
reflexes include the Moro reflex, the rooting reflex, the Babinski or plantar reflex, the grasp \
reflex, and the sucking reflex. Most of these reflexes disappear during the first year. \
\
>MORO REFLEX   The Moro reflex involves the baby extending the legs, arms, and \
fingers, and arching the back in response to being startled (e.g., by a loud noise or by being \
dropped). \
\
>ROOTING REFLEX The rooting reflex is characterized by the baby turning the head, \
opening the mouth and beginning sucking movements in response to the baby's cheek \
being stroked with a finger or nipple. \
\
>BABINSKI REFLEX The Babinski reflex is characterized by the baby spreading out \
the toes and twisting the foot when the sole of the baby's foot is stroked. \
\
>GRASP REFLEX In the grasp reflex, the baby makes a firm fist around an object that \
is placed in the hand. \
\
B. PERCEPTUAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
Perceptual development includes the senses of touch and pain, taste, hearing, smell, and \
vision. With the exception of vision, most of the infant's senses are well developed at birth. \
\
>TOUCH AND PAIN The sense of touch is the first sense to develop, and it is believed \
to be the most mature of the senses during the first few months of life. There is indication \
that infants feel pain from birth and become more sensitive to pain in the days after \
delivery. \
\
\
\
                                 Section 8 - Developmental: Physical Development \
\
>TASTE Newborns seem to prefer tastes that are sweet over those which are sour or \
bitter. The preference for sweet tastes has adaptive functions, since the mother's milk is \
rather sweet. Infants tend to reject foods that do not taste good. \
\
>HEARING The sense of hearing is well developed at birth and is actually believed to \
be acute before birth. Newborn infants have the ability to distinguish sounds, for example, \
between new speech sounds and more familiar ones. Research suggests that infants prefer \
female voices, and that newborns are able to recognize speech as a special class of sound. \
\
>SMELL The sense of smell is well developed at birth. There is evidence that infants can \
differentiate the smell of their mother's milk from that of a stranger. \
\
>VISION Vision is not well developed at birth. The newborn's peripheral vision is very \
narrow, although it develops rapidly between two and ten weeks. Color perception is poor \
until about four months. Acuity at birth is poor (somewhere between 20/200 and 20/600). \
and the infant achieves 20/20 acuity between six months and two years. At birth, the infant \
is incapable of binocular vision, and thus lacks the capacity for depth perception. Binocular \
vision typically develops at about four or five months of age. \
\
Gaze fixation and visual following of faces provides evidence that infants generally prefer \
visual stimuli that resemble faces. By one month, infants can distinguish their mother's \
face from that of others. \
\
Cross-modal fluency refers to the ability to imitate facial expressions. This ability, which \
is first exhibited at two to three weeks of age, involves matching a visual schema of a facial \
expression with a proprioceptive-tactile schema of the act that produces the facial \
expression. \
\
At two months, the social smile emerges and the infant smiles when a face (or even a face- \
like mask) is presented. \
\
C. MOTOR DEVELOPMENT \
\
Milestones in motor development during infancy and the corresponding average ages are \
as follows: ability to lift head (6 weeks), rolling over (4 months), sitting alone (7 months). \
crawling (9 months), standing with support (9 months), standing alone (12 months), first \
steps and walking alone (12 - 15 months), and walking up steps (16 months). Rates of \
