D. BRAIN DEVELOPMENT \
\
The brain develops faster than any other part of the body during the prenatal period and the \
first two years of life. At birth, the brain is 25% to 33% of its adult size, by age two about \
75%, and by age 5 about 90%. There are five stages in brain development. In the \
proliferation stage, new cells are created within the neural tube. This occurs when the \
embryo is about 2 - 3 weeks old. During the second stage of migration, immature neurons \
migrate to specific brain locations and start to join other neurons to form brain structures. \
This occurs when the embryo is about 8 weeks. The third stage is differentiation, in which \
neurons begin to take on a more differentiated or distinct look, developing axons and \
dendrites. Following differentiation is myelination in which a myelin sheath is developed \
around the axons of some neurons. Most myelination takes place after birth. The final stage \
is synaptogenesis, in which the synapses are formed. Synaptogenesis also predominantly \
takes place postnatally. \
\
The infant's brain at birth contains the majority of neurons it will ever have. After birth, \
brain development occurs as the neurons grow in size, become myelinated, develop more \
axons and dendrites, and increase their connections. It is thought that synaptic connections \
strengthen in response to experience. \
\
The brain of a young child has significant capacity for plasticity, or flexibility in \
functioning. For example, up until the age of about seven or eight, children can recover \
language function if the dominant hemisphere has been damaged. After seven or eight \
years, however, progress is limited. It is believed that by age seven or eight, considerable \
sensory integration occurs, and the brain has lateralized functioning (different hemispheres \
control different functions). As a result, there is a firmly established pattern of handedness \
and footedness. By age seven or eight there is also increasingly mature performance on \
tests of visual-motor and neuroperceptual skills. \
\
\
