By middle childhood, hippocampal development appears complete, with capacities for \
declarative memory emerging in addition to procedural memory. By the age of ten, children \
brought up unilingually have difficulty learning to speak an unaccented second language. \
\
Some brain development does continue beyond adolescence. Myelination, for example, \
continues into a person's twenties, enhancing processing speed, attention span and frontal \
lobe functioning. \
\
IV. PHYSICAL DEVELOPMENT DURING ADOLESCENCE \
AND ADULTHOOD \
\
Puberty is a biological event. It involves the maturation of the sexual system and marks the \
possibility for successful reproduction. During puberty, growth hormones and gonadal \
hormones initiate and sustain a growth spurt that causes dramatic increases in height, \
weight, and the skeletal system. Puberty typically occurs between 10 and 12 years of age \
for girls and includes menarche, the first menstrual period. For boys, it typically occurs \
between 12 and 14 years of age and includes the spermarche, the first ejaculation. As a \
result of hormonal secretions, secondary sexual characteristics develop such as facial hair, \
breasts, deepening of the voice, etc. \
\
Early physical maturation has different effects for boys and girls in the United States. Boys \
who physically mature early tend to enjoy a more positive psychological adjustment \
overall, with better scholastic performance, better self-image, and greater popularity. One \
study suggests, however, that early maturing boys may exhibit greater behavior problems. \
For girls, early physical maturation has mixed effects, including higher academic \
achievement and independence, but lower self-esteem, poorer body image, and more \
conflicts with parents. In fact, when these early maturing girls lower their academic \
achievement, they actually become more popular and have a more positive self-image. \
Some researchers have found that by twelfth grade, differences between early and late \
maturers have disappeared for both boys and girls. \
\
In middle age, typically between 45 and 55, women experience menopause, the end of the \
menstrual cycle. Decreases in estrogen production result in physical changes but current \
research does not support the myth of menopause as a time of psychological instability, \
loss of sexual interest, mood swings, and depression. The term male climacteric describes \
the more gradual changes that occur in men due to decreased testosterone, such as weight \
gain, loss of muscle strength, graying of hair, and diminished sexual responsiveness. \
\
