V. PHYSICAL DEVELOPMENT DURING LATE \
ADULTHOOD \
\
>AGING A variety of physical abilities gradually decline after middle age and into late \
adulthood. Cardiac output decreases, blood pressure increases, and visual and hearing \
acuity decline. The central nervous system begins to degenerate with loss of neurons and \
changes in tissues and supporting neurons. Many of these decreases, however, are \
dramatically affected by the environment and lifestyle choices. \
\
The maximum human life span appears to be between 110 and 120 years. Two explanations \
for aging include primary aging and secondary aging. \
\
     PRIMARY AGING The upper limit on the human life span is thought to be due \
     to primary aging, the inevitable changes in physical and mental processes. \
     Explanations for primary aging include programmed theories, which hold that \
     aging is genetically controlled, and the wear-and-tear theory which holds that daily \
     stressors wear out the body's cells. \
\
     SECONDARY AGING    Secondary aging results from disease, disuse, and \
     neglect of the body. Secondary aging may account for much of the deterioration \
     typically associated with growing old in our society. \
\
>SEXUAL ACTIVITY Sex drive does not tend to diminish with age, and the likelihood \
of sexual activity in the later years is closely related to the frequency of sexual activity \
during younger years. Research has indicated that people who were sexually active are \
likely to remain sexually active during old age. Men who have been sexually active can \
generally engage in some sort of sexual activity well into their seventies or even eighties. \
while women are physiologically able to be sexually active as long as they live. For women, \
the lack of an available partner is typically the main barrier to sexual activity. \
