VI. HEALTH \
\
A variety of factors are thought to affect health outcomes. \
\
>THE HEALTH BELIEF MODEL The health belief model focuses on how perceptions \
of vulnerability and beliefs about illness influence health behavior (e.g., to what extent the \
person modifies diet, exercises, or receives inoculations). The health belief model is \
multicausal and proposes that health behavior results from the joint influence of \
psychosocial factors (e.g., demographic variables, peer pressure), perceived susceptibility \
to disease and perceived seriousness of the disease, as well as the perceived benefits of \
preventative action versus perceived barriers to preventative action. \
\
>HEALTH RISK FACTORS AND LIFE EXPECTANCY Research has identified \
smoking as the single most significant source of preventable health risks and premature \
deaths. Obesity is thought to be the most common nutritional problem among older adults \
in the United States. Overeating, lack of exercise, and lack of a balanced diet are the major \
contributing factors. It is therefore important to assess nutrition in older adults as it is a \
highly significant factor contributing to overall well-being. \
\
Gender and race affect life expectancy. In terms of gender, women tend to outlive men. In \
terms of race, White Americans typically outlive non-White Americans. \
\
>STRESS AND HEALTH Research on the impact of stress on well-being has suggested \
that a good support network can reduce the risk of emotional distress. However, it is not so \
much the size of the social network that is important, but the person's perception of having \
an adequate social network. This is known as the social buffer hypothesis. \
\
The Holmes and Rahe Social Readjustment Rating Scale (1967) was developed to measure \
life stress and to be used as a tool for examining the stress-illness relationship. The scale \
consists of 43 items ranging in point value from most stressful at 100 (death of a spouse). \
followed by divorce at 73 points, on down. Other items included are marriage (50 points). \
retirement (45), death of a close friend (37), and foreclosure on a home (30). \
