         8.3 COGNITIVE DEVELOPMENT \
\
This section focuses on cognitive development throughout the lifespan. This section \
includes a description of language development/reading, cognitive development, and moral \
development. \
\
I. LANGUAGE DEVELOPMENT/READING \
\
A. STAGES OF LANGUAGE DEVELOPMENT \
\
It is believed that language development proceeds through the same stages regardless of \
which language a child is learning. These stages include crying, cooing, babbling, word \
comprehension, echolalia, holophrasic speech, and telegraphic speech. \
\
>CRYING Crying is the newborn's only means of communication. Different patterns, \
pitches and intensities can signal hunger, sleepiness, or anger. \
\
>COOING Between six weeks and three months babies begin to coo and laugh. Cooing \
includes squeals, gurgles, and sounds like "ahhh." \
\
>BABBLING Babbling involves repeating consonant-vowel strings, such as ma-ma-ma. \
Babbling typically begins between four and six months. While infants initially babble in \
the sounds of all languages, they begin to restrict babbling sounds to those of their own \
language by about six months of age. \
\
>WORD COMPREHENSION By about nine to ten months, babies begin to understand \
words such as "no" or the baby's name. \
\
>ECHOLALIA    Echolalia involves deliberate imitation of sounds without \
comprehension. At about nine to ten months babies are able to string together sounds in a \
pattern that sounds like language, but has no meaning. Additionally, at around this time, \
children lose the ability to differentiate sounds that are not part of the language they hear \
spoken. \
\
\
\
                                Section 8 - Developmental: Psychosocial Development \
\
>HOLOPHRASIC SPEECH The average baby says a first word sometime between 10 \
and 14 months. During the stage of holophrasic speech (typically 12 - 18 months), babies \
use a single word or even a syllable to express a complete thought. The smallest unit of \
speech is the phoneme (e.g., da), and the smallest meaningful unit is termed a morpheme \
(e.g., daddy). By 15 months, the typical toddler uses 10 different words, while language \
comprehension is much greater. By 18 months, the median expressive vocabulary is 50 \
words. \
\
>TELEGRAPHIC SPEECH   The next important linguistic breakthrough comes when \
the toddler puts two words together to express one idea. Generally children do this between \
18 and 24 months. By 24 months, the median vocabulary is 200 words. Typically. \
vocabulary grows most rapidly between two-and-a-half and three years. \
\
B. THEORIES OF LANGUAGE DEVELOPMENT \
\
Theories about language development have been split along nature versus nurture lines. \
Proponents of the nativist position argue that an inborn mechanism is responsible for \
acquiring language, while proponents of the nurture position argue that language is \
acquired through experience. \
\
>THE NATIVIST VIEW    Noam Chomsky exemplifies the nativist view. He \
hypothesized that children are born with an innate language acquisition device (LAD), a \
pre-wiring for language, so they require only minimal exposure to adult language in order \
to develop speech. Chomsky argues that the LAD enables children's brains to analyze the \
language that they hear around them and to make sense of its rules of grammar and syntax. \
\
Support for the nativist position includes the fact that children generally learn their native \
language in the same sequence, without receiving any formal instruction. Furthermore, \
newborns seem to have the capacity to differentiate between similar sounds. \
\
>THE NURTURIST VIEW Those who favor a nurturist position contend that language \
is acquired by means of interaction with the environment, through a process of imitation \
and reinforcement. Nurturists contend that children initially make random sounds, and only \
those that are reinforced by adults are eventually repeated. Children are also reinforced for \
imitating the sounds that they hear. Nurturists further argue that children learn grammar \
through exposure to examples of correct syntax. \
\
\
 \
\
                                Section 8 - Developmental: Psychosocial Development \
\
>THE INTERACTIONIST VIEW Currently most favored is the interactionist position, \
which holds that language development results from the combination of both nature and \
nurture. According to this view, children have an inborn mechanism for acquiring \
language, which is influenced by biological and cognitive maturation, as well as \
interactions with the environment. \
\
One of the most significant sources of environmental influence is a baby's parent. Parents \
repeat the sounds that the baby makes, and when the child is starting to talk, parents repeat \
the child's words and pronounce them correctly. Further, parents expand the child's speech \
by adding to it, for example, when the child says "me go," the parent says, "yes, you want \
to go." \
\
Most parents speak slowly to their infants, in simple statements, using small words, and a \
high-pitched voice. This is known as "Motherese" or child-directed speech, and occurs \
across all languages and social classes. \
\
Some research has found that mothers talk to their daughters more, and that girls are \
generally more advanced than boys in language development. \
\
In terms of the environmental influence of a bilingual home, at one point it was thought \
that children exposed to two languages showed early deficiencies in both languages. \
Current research suggests that these deficiencies don't occur and that, in fact, knowledge \
of two languages may increase cognitive flexibility. \
\
According to the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis, speakers of different languages actually think \
differently because of the structure of their languages; in other words, language influences \
how we think. Support for this hypothesis is mixed. \
\
C. DYSLEXIA \
\
Dyslexia refers to difficulties in reading, or a reading disorder. People with dyslexia have \
difficulty matching speech sounds with written words. The prevalence rates for dyslexia \
range from three to 20% of the school population. Dyslexia seems to be equally common \
among boys and girls. Dyslexia may have a genetic component, and tends to be more \
common in children from lower SES, and from larger families. \
\
There are different types of dyslexia, some of which include deep dyslexia, surface \
dyslexia, phonological dyslexia, and neglect. \
\
\
\
