\
>DEEP DYSLEXIA A person with deep dyslexia mistakenly reads a given word as one \
with a similar meaning. For example, a person reads coat instead of jacket. \
\
>SURFACE DYSLEXIA In surface dyslexia, the person cannot recognize words, and \
instead, sounds them out. Therefore, irregular words, such as "come," are mispronounced. \
(Come is an irregular word because it is pronounced differently than other words that are \
spelled in a similar fashion, such as dome or home.) \
\
>PHONOLOGICAL DYSLEXIA    In phonological dyslexia, the person cannot read \
non-words aloud; otherwise, reading might be near perfect. For example, the person cannot \
read "squiflish." \
\
>NEGLECT Neglect involves misreading of the first or last half of a word. For example \
a person reads "slap" as "slit." \
\
II. DEVELOPMENT OF COGNITION \
\
Cognitive psychologists view people as active, growing beings, and as doers who actively \
construct their world. The two predominant theories of cognitive development are Piaget's \
stage theory and the information processing approach, described below. This section \
concludes with a brief focus on adolescent thinking. \
\
A. PIAGET'S STAGE THEORY \
\
Jean Piaget concentrated on the intensive study of relatively few children, sometimes called \
an idiographic approach. Piaget proposed that children have an innate capacity for \
adapting to the environment. He demonstrated that the child's intellect is fundamentally \
different from the adult's, and that people progress through distinct specific stages in \
cognitive and intellectual development. \
\
His theory of genetic epistemology proposes that we possess innate, genetic intellectual \
capabilities that make growth of abstract thought possible. Central to his theory is \
epigenesis, which holds that growth and development occur in a series of stages, each of \
which is built on the successful mastery of the previous stage. \
\
\
 \
\
