\
 A1. BASIC PRINCIPLES \
\
Piaget stated that cognitive development takes place as a result of three interconnected \
principles: organization, adaptation, and equilibration. \
\
>ORGANIZATION   Organization refers to the development of increasingly complex \
systems of knowledge. Piaget proposed that children and adults organize their knowledge \
as mental representations of reality, in order to help make sense of their experiences. \
Within these mental representations are cognitive structures called schemata, which are \
organized patterns of behavior that people use as a guide for thinking about or acting in a \
particular situation. For example, babies initially have independent schemas for looking \
and grasping. As babies mature they integrate the separate schemas into a single schema \
that allows for looking at an object while holding it. \
\
>ADAPTATION    Piaget defined adaptation as the way a person deals with new \
information. Adaptation involves changes to the individual's schemata to enhance the \
ability to survive, and it occurs through two complementary processes: assimilation and \
accommodation. Assimilation and accommodation work together to produce cognitive \
growth. \
\
     ASSIMILATION Assimilation is the process of taking in a new experience and \
     incorporating it into existing cognitive structures. For example, when a child sees \
     an eagle for the first time and calls it a "bird," the child is assimilating a new \
     experience (eagle) into an existing schema (birds). When the child sees an airplane \
     and also calls it a "bird," the child is once again assimilating but this time, the child \
     is making a mistake by doing so. \
\
     ACCOMMODATION Accommodation involves adjusting to reality demands by \
     reorganizing or modifying the existing cognitive structure or schema. When the \
     child creates a new schema for eagles or planes, accommodation is occurring. \
\
>EQUILIBRATION Equilibration describes the need for and striving toward \
equilibrium, or balance between the person and the outside environment, as well as among \
the person's schemata. This need for equilibrium helps determine the extent to which the \
child uses assimilation or accommodation to organize experiences. For example, if a child \
cannot understand a new situation using current schemata, the child will move toward \
accommodation, develop new patterns, and thereby restore equilibrium. \
\
\
\
                                Section 8 - Developmental: Psychosocial Development \
\
A2. PIAGET'S FOUR STAGES \
\
Piaget's four stages leading up to the capacity for adult thought are sensorimotor, \
preoperational, concrete operational and formal operational. The rate at which different \
children move through the stages varies, and decalage, or unevenness within a given \
child's cognitive development, is a common occurrence. \
\
>THE SENSORIMOTOR STAGE   The sensorimotor stage corresponds to birth until \
the time of significant language acquisition-typically age two. In this stage, infants learn \
through sensory observation and gain control of their motor functions through activity. \
exploration, and manipulation of the environment. The spatial, visual, and tactile world of \
the infant expands during this period, and the child actively interacts with the environment \
using previously learned behavior patterns. \
\
     OBJECT PERMANENCE The critical accomplishment during the sensorimotor \
     stage, which occurs sometime after three to four months (some say as late as eight \
     months), is the development of object permanence-the ability to understand that \
     objects continue to exist independent of the child's involvement with them. Infants \
     become able to maintain a mental image (representation) even when the object is \
     not present. This enhanced capacity has been used to explain the development of \
     separation protest and stranger anxiety. \
\
     SYMBOLIC REPRESENTATION With the emergence of language near the end \
     of the sensorimotor stage, the child becomes more capable of symbolic \
     representation. \
\
>THE PREOPERATIONAL STAGE   The stage of preoperational thought, from age \
two to seven, is characterized by increased use of symbols and language far beyond the \
sensorimotor period. \
\
     INTUITIVE THINKING   During the preoperational stage, thinking and \
     reasoning are intuitive, that is, children are unable to think logically and \
     deductively. \
\
     EGOCENTRISM During this phase children are egocentric, and unable to take \
     the perspective of another person. \
\
\
 \
\
                                Section 8 - Developmental: Psychosocial Development \
\
     PHENOMENALISTIC CAUSALITY Preoperational children employ a type of \
     magical thinking called phenomenalistic causality in which events that occur \
     together are thought to cause one another. \
\
     ANIMISM Preoperational children demonstrate animistic thinking, by which they \
     endow inanimate objects with psychological attributes such as feelings or \
     intentions. \
\
     IRREVERSIBILITY Irreversibility refers to the inability to mentally undo \
     something. For example, if a ball of clay is rolled into the shape of a log, the \
     preoperational child cannot imagine returning it to its original ball shape. \
\
     CENTRATION Centration is the tendency to focus on one aspect of a problem at \
     a time. For example, the preoperational child will identify two rows of identical \
     objects as the same, but if the objects in one of the rows are more spread out, the \
     child will say the longer row has more objects. In another example, a young child \
     may have trouble understanding that his mother is both a mother to him and a sister \
     to his aunt. From the child's point of view, the woman must either be a mother or \
     a sister but can't be both. \
\
>THE CONCRETE OPERATIONAL STAGE     The stage of concrete operations, \
spanning seven to eleven years, is so named because the child can operate and act on real \
or imagined concrete objects. \
\
     OPERATIONAL THOUGHT During this stage, egocentric thought is replaced \
     with operational thought, which permits attending to a wide array of information. \
     Children can now use logical thought processes, and can serialize, or place objects \
     in order according to one or more dimensions (e.g., weight, color, etc.). Children \
     are able to reason and follow rules and regulations. \
\
     CONSERVATION   During the concrete operational stage, children develop \
     conservation, the ability to recognize that even though shape and form might \
     change, the objects still conserve other characteristics. \
\
>THE FORMAL OPERATIONAL STAGE The stage of formal operations, from age \
eleven through the end of adolescence, is characterized by the ability to apply operations \
to abstract concepts in addition to concrete objects. Adolescents become capable of \
hypothetical thinking ("What if?") and deductive reasoning ("If . .. then"). (Deductive \
