Inductive reasoning is something uniquely human and involves the ability to generalize.) \
During the formal operational stage, individuals acquire the abstract reasoning skills to \
comprehend algebra, which involves manipulating symbols. \
\
     METACOGNITION During the formal operational stage, adolescents develop \
     metacognitive capacities, the ability to think about their thinking, and to explore \
     personal values and compare them with others. Not all adolescents enter this stage \
     at the same time. In fact, some people never enter this stage, but remain in the \
     concrete operational stage throughout their lives. \
\
Although Piaget has been subjected to many criticisms, his descriptions and observations \
of cognitive development have generally been confirmed. A key criticism is based on the \
finding that performance is sensitive to contextual influences. When tasks are simplified. \
or more familiar material is used, children perform better. Thus, some argue that Piaget has \
underestimated children's abilities at certain ages. Piaget also did not sufficiently address \
cultural and educational influences on cognitive development. \
\
An important concept associated with Piaget is constructivism. According to \
constructivism, a person develops new knowledge based on the foundation of previous \
learning, and by interacting with objects and events in the environment. When applied to \
schooling, constructivists place emphasis on the student, rather than the teacher. The \
teacher is a facilitator who assists students to construct their own conceptualizations and \
solutions to problems. \
\
In terms of cognitive development, Piaget believed that peers are highly influential in the \
child's cognitive development. Through interaction with peers, the child is confronted with \
different worldviews and comes to recognize that his or her view of the world may not be \
viable (e.g., may be egocentric, illogical). Parents, on the other hand, may be too \
cognitively advanced and therefore too intellectually removed from the child to play as \
significant of a role. \
