B. VYGOTSKY'S SOCIAL DEVELOPMENT THEORY OF \
COGNITION \
\
According to Vygotsky, cognitive development results from social interaction. All higher \
cognitive functions, such as language, thinking, and memory, begin within the relationships \
the child has with others, and are later internalized. For example, a young child tends to \
narrate what he or she is doing (e.g., "I'm putting the books on the shelf and then I'm going \
to eat ice cream.") While Piaget would view this as egocentric speech, Vygotsky would \
consider this a necessary step in the child's development of the capacity to internalize \
thoughts. Unlike Piaget, Vygotsky believed that development was too complex to be \
divided into stages. Although both theorists recognized the role of peers in a child's \
learning, Vygotsky emphasized the influence of adults more than Piaget did. \
\
Vygotsky defined the zone of proximal development as the distance between what the \
child can do independently and what the child can do with adult guidance or peer \
collaboration. For example, a three-year-old girl can dress herself if she does it along with \
her older sister, but she cannot do it all by herself. According to Vygotsky, instruction \
should be targeted toward this zone, i.e., toward a developmental level just above the \
child's current developmental level. \
\
Social development theory has led to the instructional strategies of scaffolding and \
reciprocal teaching. In scaffolding, teachers adjust their level of help based on the child's \
performance. For example, the teacher may talk the child through a task (e.g., carrying \
numbers in math addition problems), until the child is able to complete the task \
independently. Then the teacher withdraws the assistance. Reciprocal teaching involves \
a dialogue between the teacher and students. For example, they may discuss various \
problem-solving strategies for math problems rather than the teacher presenting the \
"correct" strategy. \
\
C. INFORMATION PROCESSING \
\
The information processing approach is a newer model that views cognitive development \
as distinctly different from Piaget's views. Piaget's theory is a stage theory that focuses on \
qualitative differences that occur at different stages. By contrast, information processing \
focuses on quantitative changes that occur more smoothly, continuously and gradually over \
the life span. \
\
\
\
                               Section 8 - Developmental: Psychosocial Development \
\
Differences in cognitive abilities across different age groups are explained on the basis of \
differences in experience and knowledge. For example, it has been found that two-year- \
olds can typically repeat only two digits, four-year olds can repeat three or four digits, and \
ten-year-olds can repeat about six digits. Information processing theory proposes that this \
improvement in memory results from a gradual, more effective use of memory strategies, \
such as rehearsal (repeating information over and over) and mnemonics (rules such as 'i' \
before 'e' except after 'c'), as the child ages. \
\
Preschoolers have a limited attention span, limited short-term memory capacity, use \
unsystematic approaches to solve problems, and frequently don't focus on the most \
relevant aspects of a problem. By contrast, adolescents have more knowledge gained \
through experience, and this knowledge influences learning strategies and efficiency. \
Adolescents are better able to distill the critical features of a new problem and recognize \
how a new problem resembles older, familiar problems (an isomorph). More experienced \
problem solvers may be better able to withstand the confusion of new vocabulary, \
unfamiliar subjects or new ideas, and to place the problem in the context of what they \
know, called "transfer processing." \
\
Information processing theory sees enhanced cognitive capacities of adolescents as \
resulting from a larger foundation of information, better skills in discerning isomorphs, \
more thorough scanning, flexible use of learning strategies, and enhanced abilities to self- \
monitor. \
\
D. ADOLESCENT THINKING \
\
Adolescent thinking presents contradictions and complexities. According to Elkind, \
although adolescents are capable of sophisticated problem solving, their thinking can also \
be rather immature, as a result of inexperience with abstract thought. Elkind has delineated \
several attitudes and behaviors typical of adolescents. These include finding fault with \
persons in authority, argumentativeness, indecisiveness, hypocrisy (not living up to values \
espoused by the adolescent), self-consciousness, and a sense of invulnerability. \
\
>PERSONAL FABLE   The term personal fable refers to adolescents' beliefs that they \
are somehow special, and that rules of conduct do not apply to them. Based on this belief, \
many adolescents think that they are invulnerable. It is not uncommon for adolescents to \
believe that they can use drugs without any negative consequences or engage in \
unprotected sex without becoming pregnant or contracting diseases. \
\
\
