\
>IMAGINARY AUDIENCE    Adolescents often operate under the assumption that \
everyone is thinking about the same thing that they are thinking about, specifically, \
themselves. Early adolescent thinking is commonly characterized by extreme self- \
consciousness. This self-consciousness frequently involves an imaginary audience. An \
imaginary audience is a person or group of people perceived as closely observing the \
adolescent, when in fact they are not. The adolescent believes that these people are as \
concerned with the adolescent's appearance or behavior as she or he is. \
\
E. COGNITIVE CHANGES ASSOCIATED WITH AGING \
\
Cognitive abilities do not globally decrease as people age; some abilities remain intact, or \
even improve, while others slowly worsen. Intellectual capacities are broadly divided into \
two categories, crystallized intelligence and fluid intelligence. \
\
>CRYSTALLIZED INTELLIGENCE Crystallized intelligence refers to practiced and \
overlearned skills that are predominantly verbal. Crystallized intelligence appears to \
remain intact with aging and may even improve overall. On the WAIS-IV, older adults find \
Vocabulary, Information, and Comprehension the easiest of the subtests, and scores on \
these subtests may only begin to show a decline in the 70s. Some verbal abilities, such as \
word knowledge and naming skills, show minimal declines. In contrast, speech \
comprehension and fluency generally decrease. \
\
>FLUID INTELLIGENCE Fluid intelligence refers to capacities for problem solving \
in novel situations. Fluid intelligence is believed to peak in adolescence and thereafter \
gradually decline. On the WAIS-IV, the performance subtests are therefore experienced as \
the most difficult, with subtest scores beginning to decline in the 30s or 40s. \
\
The classic aging pattern therefore involves a decline in performance skills with verbal \
skills remaining intact. Previously, this pattern was thought to reflect differences in \
crystallized versus fluid abilities. However, since cognitive speed clearly declines with age, \
this slowing may better explain the discrepancy between verbal and performance subtest \
scores. Some hypothesize that an overall slowing in the central nervous system causes the \
decrease in processing speed. Decreases in visual acuity and auditory sensitivity may \
further account for diminished cognitive performance. \
\
Among older adults, there is a general trend in the direction of better performance when \
the person is dealing with familiar and/or simple stimuli, and by contrast, impairment when \
dealing with unfamiliar, novel, and/or complex stimuli. Overall, older adults tend to show \
