decreased abilities in complex attentional tasks, certain higher-order cognitive processes, \
and some aspects of memory. \
\
>ATTENTION   In the area of attention, older adults tend to do well on simple tasks but \
show problems with more complex tasks, such as ones that require attention to more than \
one source of information. \
\
>HIGHER-ORDER COGNITIVE PROCESSES   In terms of higher-order cognitive \
processes such as problem-solving, reasoning, conceptualization, and planning, older \
adults don't do as well as younger adults when tested in laboratory-like situations. \
Interestingly, older adults do as well as, or even outperform, younger adults when these \
same processes are assessed in terms of everyday, real-world functioning (ecologically- \
based evaluation). \
\
>MEMORY    While some aspects of memory functioning appear to remain intact, others \
seem to decline with age. Short-term memory is thought to consist of two components: \
primary memory and working memory. \
\
     PRIMARY MEMORY Primary memory is a passive "holding tank" for small \
     amounts of information requiring no manipulation (e.g., remember five digits in \
     sequence). Primary memory is thought to remain intact in older adults. \
\
     WORKING MEMORY By contrast, working memory briefly holds and \
     manipulates information (e.g., repeating the five digits in reverse order). Working \
     memory is thought to decline with age. \
\
In terms of long-term memory, episodic memory (e.g., what you had for breakfast or did \
you remember to lock your car) shows the most decline with age. In contrast, both semantic \
memory (knowledge or facts and meanings) and procedural memory (memory for motor \
skills) remain intact with age. \
\
It is hypothesized that memory problems associated with older adulthood are due to \
problems with both encoding and retrieval, with retrieval problems being more significant. \
In general, older adults seem less efficient and less precise in encoding new information. \
Older adults also have significantly more trouble with recall as compared with recognition \
(recall puts more demands on the retrieval system than recognition does). Tasks requiring \
recall of word lists, prose passages, and word pairs, all tend to be difficult for older adults. \
\
\
