III. MORAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
Three important contributors to theories on moral development are Piaget, Kohlberg, and \
Gilligan. \
\
A. PIAGET'S THEORY OF MORAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
According to Piaget, moral development is linked to cognitive development. Piaget \
asserted that children make sounder moral judgments when they possess the cognitive \
ability of being able to see things from more than one perspective. \
\
Piaget asserted that moral reasoning develops in two stages: the morality of constraint \
stage, and the morality of cooperation stage. \
\
>HETERONOMOUS MORALITY    In this first stage (ages five to ten), the morality of \
constraint dominates. Young, egocentric children think rigidly about morality; children \
cannot imagine more than one way of looking at a moral issue. In this stage, children \
believe that rules are decided upon by authority figures, cannot be changed, must be \
followed without question, and that any offense deserves punishment (unless they are the \
offenders). \
\
>AUTONOMOUS MORALITY     In the second stage, which occurs at about age ten, \
the morality of cooperation is evident. This stage is characterized by flexibility. By this \
point in time, children have had the opportunity to interact with many people and have \
experienced a wide range of viewpoints. They realize that there is not one unchangeable \
standard of right and wrong. In this stage children can consider more than one aspect of \
the situation and can consider the intent behind behavior. Children come to realize that \
rules are flexible, are agreed upon by others, and can be changed if necessary. \
\
\
\
                                Section 8 - Developmental: Psychosocial Development \
\
B. KOHLBERG'S THEORY OF MORAL REASONING \
\
Like Piaget, Kohlberg asserted that how people think about moral issues reflects cognitive \
development. Kohlberg further proposed that people arrive at moral judgments on their \
own, rather than by internalizing parental or societal standards. \
\
Kohlberg's theory of moral development involves three general stages, each of which is \
subdivided into two substages, for a total of six substages of moral development. \
\
>PRECONVENTIONAL MORALITY    Preconventional morality (from ages four to \
ten) emphasizes compliance with rules to avoid punishment and get rewards. At this stage, \
moral judgment is self-centered, and people act out of self-interest. The two substages are \
the Punishment-Obedience Orientation (Stage 1), with a focus on avoiding punishment, \
and Instrumental Hedonism (Stage 2), involving obedience to rules with the hope that good \
deeds will be rewarded. \
\
>CONVENTIONAL MORALITY Conventional morality (typically reached after age \
ten) emphasizes conforming to rules to get approval from others. At this stage, standards \
of those in authority have been internalized, and people want to be considered "good." \
Moral reasoning advances from being self-centered to other-centered. The two substages \
are the Good Boy/Good Girl orientation (Stage 3), with a concern for gaining approval \
through obedience, and the Law and Order orientation (Stage 4), with a focus on doing \
one's duty, and maintaining social order. \
\
>POSTCONVENTIONAL    MORALITY (MORALITY    OF AUTONOMOUS \
MORAL PRINCIPLES) Postconventional morality (which can begin by age 13, in \
young adulthood, or never) involves recognition that there are sometimes conflicts between \
moral or socially accepted standards. In this stage, the person makes moral decisions based \
on what is right, fair, or just. Morality of Contract, Individual Rights, and Democratically \
Accepted Laws (Stage 5) emphasizes valuing the will of the majority, and the welfare of \
society. Morality of Individual Principles of Conscience (Stage 6) is a morality based on \
what the individual believes is right, regardless of legal restrictions or opinions of others. \
People in this stage act in accordance with internalized standards. \
\
Kohlberg's work has been criticized as lacking cultural sensitivity and being biased toward \
a Western individualistic view, in that the highest stage of morality places individual \
conscience over societal demands and norms. \
\
