A. FREUD AND ERIKSON \
\
Freud's theory of development, which focused on childhood, was organized around his \
libido theory. According to Freud, childhood phases of development correspond to \
successive shifts in the investment of sexual energy to areas of the body associated with \
eroticism. He distinguished between the oral phase (birth to one year), the anal phase (one \
to three) the phallic phase (three to five), latency (five or six to adolescence) and genital \
phase (adolescence through adulthood). \
\
Erik Erikson accepted Freud's theory of infantile sexuality but also saw developmental \
potentials at all stages of life. He constructed a model of the life cycle consisting of eight \
stages, extending into old age. Erikson proposed that successful negotiation of each \
development task results in specific strengths. \
