B. MARGARET MAHLER \
\
Mahler developed a theory that describes the processes of separation and individuation. \
Mahler described six stages of development. These include normal infantile autism, \
symbiosis, differentiation, practicing, rapprochement, and object constancy. \
\
Separation is the process of becoming a discrete physical entity by physically distancing, \
while individuation is the process of becoming a psychologically independent person, \
which involves maturation of independent ego functions. \
\
>NORMAL INFANTILE AUTISM In normal infantile autism (1st month), the baby is \
unaware of the external world. Research has not supported Mahler's conception and has \
rather demonstrated that the newborn is much more aware of the environment than had \
previously been believed. \
\
>SYMBIOSIS In symbiosis (2 - 4 months), the baby feels that she and the mother are \
one, rather than separate entities. \
\
>DIFFERENTIATION During the differentiation stage (5 -10 months), the child is able \
to distinguish between self and other objects, which ushers in stranger anxiety, as the \
child is increasingly aware of the unfamiliar. \
\
>PRACTICING During the practicing period (10 - 16 months), the child discovers the \
ability to physically separate the self from the mother. During this period the child initially \
crawls, and then moves on to free, upright locomotion, which paradoxically creates \
separation anxiety. \
\
>RAPPROCHEMENT During rapprochement (16 - 24 months), there is increased need \
for the mother to share the child's new skills and experiences, and a great need for love. \
\
>OBJECT CONSTANCY Object constancy (2 - 3 years), which begins at the age of two \
or three, is the ability to maintain the image of the mother when she is not present, as well \
as to unify the good and bad into a whole representation. \
