II. SOCIAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
This section highlights significant areas in social development, including attachment, \
parenting, gender role development, social interaction, issues in education, adolescent \
development, and social issues in late adulthood. \
\
A. ATTACHMENT \
\
Researchers have studied attachment behaviors in nonhuman primates (e.g., Lorenz and \
Harlow), as well as in human infants (e.g., Bowlby and Ainsworth). In humans, attachment \
appears to be an active, reciprocal, enduring relationship. \
\
>KONRAD LORENZ   Ethological studies show that nonhuman primates demonstrate \
attachment behavior patterns that are presumed to be instinctual. An example of this is \
imprinting, in which certain stimuli are capable of eliciting innate behavior patterns during \
a critical period of the animal's development. For example, Lorenz found that goslings that \
had imprinted on him between 12 and 17 hours after birth continued to follow him even \
when other geese later became available as models. \
\
>HARRY HARLOW Experiments by Harlow in the 1950s studied monkeys reared with \
wire surrogate mothers and terry cloth surrogate mothers. The monkeys preferred and spent \
more time clinging to the terry cloth surrogates, even if the feeding was done by the wire \
mothers. When frightened, the monkeys ran to the terry cloth mothers for security. Harlow \
described this as contact comfort, and highlighted the importance of pleasurable tactile \
sensations as a contributor to attachment behavior. Contact comfort appears to be equally \
if not more important between human mothers and infants. \
\
Harlow also found that monkeys placed in isolation during the first few months of life \
showed abnormal and autistic-like social and sexual behaviors. When placed with normally \
reared younger monkeys, there was a significant but not complete remission of pathology. \
\
>JOHN BOWLBY   John Bowlby formulated attachment theory, and proposed that \
attachment is crucial to healthy development. Bowlby suggested a Darwinian evolutionary \
basis for attachment behavior, in that it ensures that adults protect their helpless young. He \
