proposed that newborns are biologically equipped with both verbal and nonverbal \
behaviors (e.g., crying, clinging, smiling) that function to elicit instinctive nurturing \
responses from the caretaker. \
\
Bowlby described a syndrome of maternal deprivation that occurs in some children under \
two years old who are placed in institutions and separated from their mothers for extended \
periods of time (e.g., over three months). Bowlby described a predictable sequence of \
behavior that includes protest, despair, and detachment. \
\
     PROTEST When separated initially, the child protests by crying, calling out, and \
     searching for the lost person. \
\
     DESPAIR As the period of separation continues, the child shows signs of feeling \
     hopeless that the mother will ever return. \
\
     DETACHMENT During this final step, the child emotionally separates the self \
     from the mother. In the detachment phase the child responds in an indifferent \
     manner when the mother returns. \
\
The effect of deprivation of maternal attention is also described by Ren\'e9 Spitz, who coined \
the term anaclytic depression to describe the syndrome of weepiness, withdrawal, \
insomnia, decline of health and affect found in babies deprived of maternal attention \
somewhere between six and eight months of age. \
\
>MARY AINSWORTH     The attachment relationship between infant and caregiver \
begins at birth and becomes increasingly important in the second half of the first year, \
corresponding to the time of development of stranger and separation anxiety. By the time \
the infant is one year old, the quality of the attachment relationship can be measured using \
the Strange Situation Procedure in the laboratory. This procedure looks at how infants \
organize their behavior around the attachment figure when they are mildly stressed in a \
strange room by encountering an unfamiliar adult and then being left briefly by the \
attachment figure. \
\
Ainsworth (1978) has delineated three different levels of attachment: secure attachment, \
avoidant attachment, and ambivalent or resistant attachment. Future research (e.g., Main \
and Solomon) identified a fourth pattern- disorganized-disoriented attachment. \
\
\
