     SECURE ATTACHMENT Securely attached babies (about 65% of all babies) \
     are warm and responsive. When exposed to the stranger, these infants seek \
     closeness and contact with the mother, may show moderate distress upon \
     separation, and greet the mother with enthusiasm when she returns. It is \
     hypothesized that a parenting style of sensitive and responsive caregiving is \
     associated with secure attachment. \
\
     AVOIDANT ATTACHMENT Avoidant babies (approximately 20% of babies) \
     do not seek closeness and contact with the mother, treat the mother like a stranger. \
     rarely cry when she leaves the room, and ignore her on her return. They may even \
     prefer the stranger over the mother. It is believed that a caregiving style of aloofness \
     and distance, or intrusiveness and overstimulation is associated with avoidant \
     attachment. \
\
     AMBIVALENT (RESISTANT) ATTACHMENT   Ambivalent babies (about \
     10% of babies) are clingy and become upset when the mother leaves the room. \
     When the mother returns, the babies are happy and reestablish contact, but they \
     show their ambivalence by then resisting the mother's comforting behaviors. They \
     may cry, kick, or squirm to get away. Ambivalent babies do little exploring and \
     appear angry toward both the mother and the stranger. Caregivers of ambivalent \
     babies have been characterized as inconsistent and insensitive. \
\
     DISORGANIZED-DISORIENTED ATTACHMENT    Infants who have a \
     disorganized-disoriented attachment exhibit no clear strategy in dealing with the \
     mother. They may be unresponsive when the mother returns. At times, they may \
     avoid and resist the mother. At other times, they may freeze and stop moving when \
     the mother comes near. The most striking characteristic of these infants is that they \
     exhibit fear and confusion toward their mothers. The disorganized-disoriented \
     attachment is believed to be the least secure pattern of attachment, and is commonly \
     associated with abuse of the infant, or unresolved abuse issues of the caretaker. \
\
Research has demonstrated that infants classified as securely versus insecurely attached at \
12 and 18 months differ emotionally and behaviorally in preschool and during the school- \
