Cross-cultural research has indicated that children's culturally influenced expectations of \
how a parent should behave affects the results of parenting styles (e.g., a Korean child will \
likely view an authoritarian parent as loving and concerned). Indeed, cross-cultural \
research has strongly suggested that the key variable that affects outcome is warmth versus \
rejection. Parental rejection and hostility, across cultures, are associated with more \
behavior problems, difficulty in interpersonal relationships, and psychological problems. \
\
>WORKING MOTHERS    There have been significant inconsistencies in the research \
on the effects of working mothers and the impact of day care on childhood development. \
Few clear-cut conclusions have emerged. This seems to be largely due to the fact that there \
are wide differences in quality across day care settings, as well significant variations in the \
quality of caregiving at home. \
\
One general finding is that children of working mothers tend to have more egalitarian views \
of sex roles than children of stay-at-home mothers. In terms of cognitive development, \
there is some evidence that middle class boys in daycare have slightly lower academic \
performance than middle class boys whose mothers do not work. However, lower class boys \
placed in daycare seem to do better academically than lower class boys who are raised at \
home. In terms of emotional development, a large study found no dangers to healthy \
attachment even in infants entering day care before three months. In terms of social \
development, the findings appear mixed, in that children who experienced day care tend to be \
more sociable, self-confident and persistent, yet they have also been found to be more \
disobedient, less polite, bossier and more aggressive with other children. \
\
In the U.S., while fathers are more involved in carrying out childcare responsibilities, \
mothers perform the majority of childcare. \
\
>GAY AND LESBIAN PARENTS The research on gay and lesbian parents has shown \
that children of these parents are as well adjusted as children of heterosexual parents. \
Furthermore, these children show equivalent rates of homosexuality as in the general \
population (some say 5% - 10%). \
\
>SINGLE PARENTS With regard to effects on children of single parent homes, the \
most consistent finding is lower levels of achievement. This is largely thought to be due to \
the effects of low family income, or poverty. \
