C. GENDER ROLE DEVELOPMENT \
\
While sex refers to the biological status of being either male or female, which is determined \
at conception, gender refers to the cultural and individual meanings that are attached to the \
status of being male or female. \
\
>STAGES OF GENDER ROLE DEVELOPMENT \
\
     GENDER ROLES Gender roles refer to the societal expectations for appropriate \
     male or female behavior. Gender roles begin to develop virtually from birth and \
     develop throughout life. \
\
     GENDER IDENTITY   Gender identity refers to the individual's perception of \
     him or herself as a male or a female. At 18 months there is an emergence of the \
     objective self (facial recognition of the self in mirrors, photos, etc.), which paves \
     the way for the beginning of gender identity consolidation. Gender identity is \
     usually achieved by the age of three years at the latest (e.g., a three-year-old boy \
     knows he is a boy). \
\
     GENDER CONSTANCY    Gender constancy describes the attainment of the \
     recognition that gender does not change with dress or behavior (e.g., once a male, \
     always a male, even if wearing a dress). Gender constancy is attained by age five \
     or six. \
\
>THEORIES OF GENDER ROLE DEVELOPMENT \
\
Four major theories of gender role development have been proposed. These include social \
learning theory, cognitive-developmental theory, gender schema theory, and \
psychoanalytic theory. \
\
     SOCIAL-LEARNING THEORY   This theory contends that children acquire \
     their gender roles through the process of imitation and reinforcement. \
\
     COGNITIVE-DEVELOPMENTAL THEORY       Cognitive-developmental \
     theory considers the child's thinking process as the key force behind gender role \
     development. According to Kohlberg, children first develop a concept of gender \
     identity and then develop gender constancy. The cognitive attainment of gender \
     constancy motivates them to want to be "proper" girls and boys. Critics of this \
\
\
\
