\
     theory note that gender roles develop much before the age or five or six. For \
     example, children frequently show preferences for sex-appropriate toys within the \
     first two years of life. \
\
     GENDER-SCHEMA THEORY    Gender-schema theory is currently the most \
     accepted theory of gender role development. It suggests that children use gender as \
     a schema to organize their world. Gender-schema theory considers both social \
     learning and the child's cognitive processes as involved in gender role acquisition. \
     For example, a girl plays with dolls because she has observed other girls doing so, \
     and because her mother has rewarded her with praise. In addition, she has a \
     category for "girl," recognizes that she belongs to this category, and defines this \
     category, in part, by enjoyment of dolls. \
\
     PSYCHOANALYTIC THEORIES Psychoanalytic theories emphasize the role \
     of the Oedipus complex, in which the guilt and anxiety about sexual attraction to \
     the other-sex parent is resolved by identifying with the same-sex parent. The theory \
     argues that "biology is destiny." Differences in male-female genital structures \
     account for differences in behavior and personality. Most current gender role \
     theorists do not draw on psychoanalytic theories. \
\
D. DEVELOPMENT OF RACIAL AWARENESS \
\
The bulk of the research suggests that between the ages of three and four, children become \
aware of differences based on racial or ethnic background. By age four, children still do \
not fully understand racial differences, but they have begun to realize that color differences \
have social meaning. At this age, children also begin to exhibit a preference for same-race \
playmates. \
\
E. SOCIAL INTERACTION \
\
>PLAY Children's play has been categorized both in terms of the levels of social play \
(e.g., by looking at the nature of the interactions) and in terms of cognitive play (reflecting \
the level of cognitive development). \
\
Social play typically proceeds through four stages: solitary play, parallel play, associative \
play and cooperative play. Solitary and parallel play dominates through age two. Between \
ages two and three, children begin to engage in associative and cooperative play. \
\
\
