\
     SOLITARY PLAY In this stage the child plays alone with toys that are different \
     from those of other children around him or her, and makes no effort to engage other \
     children in play. \
\
     PARALLEL PLAY In this type of play, the child plays independently but next \
     to other children, using toys similar to those being used by the other children. \
     However, the child plays beside, but not with, other children. \
\
     ASSOCIATIVE PLAY The child engaged in associative play interacts with other \
     children and shares toys. However, the child acts as he or she wishes, and does not \
     adopt any roles. \
\
     COOPERATIVE PLAY In this type of play, the child is part of a group that has \
     some common goal (e.g., to make something, to play a formal game, etc.). The \
     child takes on a role and supplements the effort of others in the group. \
\
Piaget has suggested that children progress through four levels of cognitive play: repetitive \
play, constructive play, imaginative play and formal games with rules. \
\
     REPETITIVE PLAY   Repetitive play involves simple, repetitive muscular \
     movements, such as rolling a ball. \
\
     CONSTRUCTIVE PLAY    Constructive play involves using materials to \
     construct or create something, such as building a tower with blocks. \
\
     IMAGINATIVE PLAY     Imaginative play involves fantasy and drama. \
     Imaginative play involves taking on pretend roles such as Batman, or playing \
     doctor. It is believed that imaginative play serves a crucial role in the early years of \
     allowing children to try out new roles and master difficult feelings. \
\
     FORMAL GAMES WITH RULES    The development and adherence to rules \
     while playing games varies with children's ages. Between the ages of four to seven. \
     rules fluctuate and are egocentrically motivated. From ages seven through eleven \
     rules are followed more carefully. By adolescence, rules of any game are seen as \
     absolute, and adolescents require that they be followed. \
\
>FRIENDSHIP During the preschool years, children play with same sex, as well as \
opposite sex peers. In latency, children tend to engage more in activities with same sex peers. \
\
\
\
