\
During childhood, girls tend to be more concerned with the quality of their friendships, while \
boys place more emphasis on the number of friends that they have. Factors that may account \
for a child's lack of popularity include an unattractive appearance, poor academic \
performance, and shyness. \
\
>DELINQUENCY AND AGGRESSION    Research has suggested that the nature of \
children's interaction with their parents tends to influence their social adjustment. One \
extensive study revealed that the nature of adolescents' relationships with parents was the \
single factor that best accounted for delinquency. This study further revealed that the \
incidence of delinquency among boys from unhappy, though intact homes is greater than \
among boys from "broken homes." It is possible that this may be related to the style of \
interaction with the father that may involve aggression, or the father may model aggressive \
behavior. \
\
According to Patterson's coercion model of aggression, three steps lead to delinquency. \
First, children learn to be aggressive by observing coercive and antisocial behavior in the \
parents. Such parents respond to a child's noncompliance with increasingly coercive and \
aggressive behaviors. Poor parenting practices then unwittingly reinforce coercive \
behavior on the part of the child. A cycle of escalating coerciveness ensues. The child's \
coercive behavior leads to conduct problems. Second, the child with conduct problems \
experiences academic failure and peer rejection. Third, the child then experiences a \
depressed mood and is more likely to join a deviant peer group. \
\
>BULLYING Experts do not view bullying as a normal part of childhood, but as a \
behavior that indicates serious potential problems both for the bully and the victim. \
According to research from the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development \
(NICHD), 16% of students in the U.S. report being bullied during the current term. Girls \
tend to use and receive verbal or psychological bullying more than physical bullying. \
Although school is the site for the majority of bullying incidents, the most severe forms of \
bullying happen outside school where there is less adult protection. Intervention programs \
in the school have been shown to be effective in reducing bullying, sometimes by more \
than 50%. \
\
Overall, current research does not support the theory that bullies suffer from insecurity and \
low self-esteem. The NICHD found that those who bully are more likely to be involved in \
other violent behavior or may be involved in violent behavior in the future (e.g., carrying \
a weapon, fighting). Perry, a noted researcher in bullying, has similarly found that children \
who demonstrate chronic aggressive behavior before the age of eight are more likely to \
