F. ISSUES IN EDUCATION \
\
>TEACHER EXPECTATIONS AND INTERACTIONS   Research by Rosenthal and \
colleagues has suggested that teachers' expectations have an impact on students' academic \
performance (Rosenthal effect). When teachers have high expectations of their students, \
students tend to perform better than when teachers expect little from them. \
\
Studies have also been conducted on the impact of students' gender on interactions with \
teachers. These studies have indicated that female and male teachers tend to have a greater \
degree of interaction with male students, though these interactions tend to be more critical \
or negative. This pattern holds true in preschool through college. Further, teachers of both \
sexes seem to more frequently praise females for effort and cooperation, while they praise \
males more often for ability and achievement. \
\
>COOPERATIVE LEARNING CLASSES In cooperative learning classes, students of \
different ability levels and cultural backgrounds work together, or cooperate, on \
completing assignments and projects. Research has demonstrated that these classes are \
beneficial for low-ability students in terms of improving their academic functioning. These \
classes may or may not help to improve the academic performance of high-ability students. \
Cooperative learning programs have also been found to effectively reduce cultural biases \
and stereotypes. \
\
>MONTESSORI SCHOOLS   The key principle underlying Montessori schools is that \
maximum learning comes from manipulation of materials (sensory-motor stimuli), rather than \
through traditional classroom instruction and rote learning. Children in Montessori schools \
are grouped with peers of different ages and abilities (e.g., 3- to 5-year-olds, 6- to 9-year-olds. \
and 10-year-olds and up), because it is believed that the older children can facilitate learning \
in the younger ones. Thus, children have different experiences over time of first being the \
