G. ADOLESCENT ISSUES IN SOCIAL DEVELOPMENT \
\
>IDENTITY FORMATION    Adolescence is a significant time of life for identity \
formation. One researcher, James Marcia, has described four possible identity states or \
statuses for adolescents: identity achievement, foreclosure, moratorium, and diffusion. \
These categories differ in terms of two factors, crisis and commitment. \
\
     IDENTITY ACHIEVEMENT    The person who is in the state of identity \
     achievement has actively struggled and explored several options and then \
     developed her or his own set of goals and values. Thus, the adolescent has resolved \
     the crisis and made a commitment. \
\
     FORECLOSURE An adolescent who is in the state of identity foreclosure has \
     committed to a goal without exploring other alternatives. This adolescent tends to \
     accept a ready-made identity chosen by an authority figure. For example, a person \
     becomes a physician because both parents are physicians and believe that their child \
     should also be a physician. Thus, there has been an absence of crisis for the \
     adolescent, yet a commitment has been made. \
\
     MORATORIUM The person in the moratorium status has not yet made a definite \
     commitment and is in the active process of struggling with decisions, and exploring \
     interests and needs. The adolescent in moratorium is in crisis, with an absence of \
     commitment. The most typical outcome will be some resolution of the crisis with \
     the ability to commit. \
\
     IDENTITY DIFFUSION Identity diffusion describes the adolescent who lacks \
     direction, is not committed to goals and values, and is not seriously considering \
     options or trying to develop goals. In the state of identity diffusion, both crisis and \
     commitment are absent. Some people in this category become aimless drifters. \
\
>ADOLESCENCE AND CULTURE Perceptions of adolescents, in terms of maturity, \
are heavily influenced by social events. For example, during times of war, older \
adolescents are generally seen as mature and able to fight. By contrast, during periods of \
economic depression when there is significant competition for limited work, adolescents \
are seen as immature and not yet prepared to enter the work force. \
\
