Researchers have studied differences between minority and non-minority adolescents in \
terms of important social issues. It has been found that minority adolescents are much more \
likely to be raised by a single parent, with higher likelihood of poverty, less education, \
increased drug use, and if female, raising a child as a single parent. The greatest social risk \
for African American adolescents is murder, with homicide rates being six times that of \
Whites. \
\
Sexual experiences, in terms of age of onset, are also associated with social and ethnic \
background. African American adolescents of both sexes are more likely than Hispanic or \
White peers to have had sex at each age throughout their teens. Much of this is influenced \
by what is considered culturally normative. Overall, earlier sexual activity is linked to early \
pregnancy and greater likelihood of contracting STDs, with contraceptive use becoming \
more common only as adolescents become older. Only 60% of teens report use of a condom \
during the last intercourse. Pregnant adolescents are more likely than other mothers to \
deliver low-birth weight infants, who in turn are more likely to have developmental delays. \
\
All sexually transmitted diseases are more common among poor and minority children as \
compared with other groups. A 1993 study found that in teenagers, 51% of AIDS cases in \
boys, and 75% in girls were racial or ethnic minorities, with the bulk being African \
American. \
\
Conflicts between parents and teens typically intensify around puberty and then begin to \
subside. Adolescents are more susceptible to peer pressure in early adolescence, and this \
begins to lessen after the age of 13 or 14. \
\
One in eight adolescents drops out of school. Four out of five prison inmates are high- \
school dropouts. Dropouts are twice as likely to be unemployed as compared with high \
school graduates. \
