A. TEMPERAMENT \
\
Most theories of temperament suggest temperament is rooted in biological differences. \
While many believe temperament exists from birth, few reliable differences in \
temperament have been identified in the first six months of life. \
\
Thomas & Chess (1977) have described three major categories of temperament into which \
65% of babies can be reliably separated. \
\
>EASY TEMPERAMENT    Easy temperament (40% of all babies) is defined by a \
regular, adaptable, mildly intense style that is positive and responsive. \
\
>DIFFICULT TEMPERAMENT Difficult temperament (10% of all babies) describes \
children who are moody, easily frustrated, tense, and overreact to most situations. \
\
>SLOW-TO-WARM-UP INFANTS   Slow-to-warm-up infants (15% of all babies) are \
mild in responding, are somewhat shy and withdrawn and need time to adjust to new \
experiences or people. \
\
One of the greatest influences on the child's development is thought to be the goodness- \
of-fit between the child's temperament and the environment. For example, a slow-to- \
