B. DEVELOPMENT OF EMOTIONAL EXPRESSION \
\
At birth, emotional expression is rather limited. The infant appears to display one of three \
emotional states: distress, contentment, or interest. By six months of age, a fuller display \
of emotion is evident, including contentment, joy, surprise, interest, sadness, disgust, and \
anger. It is believed that by seven to nine months, emotions, as displayed by a smile or \
pout, are used instrumentally by the infant in an attempt to get his or her way. \
\
As they get older, infants detect and share affective states with their parents. Social \
referencing. for example, becomes common at about one year of age. At this time, the \
child will use cues from another person, such as the mother, to deal with affective \
uncertainty (e.g., whether a situation is dangerous or exciting). \
\
By age two, self-conscious emotions of embarrassment, empathy and envy are clearly \
evident. For preschoolers, a significant developmental task involves learning to better \
regulate emotions. At this age, the attainment of object constancy, described by Mahler, is \
important for facilitating emotional regulation. The preschooler needs to develop the ability \
to self-soothe, and to reduce and tolerate the anxiety that emerges in response to separation \
from the primary caretaker. Object constancy depends on the child's capacity to recall an \
image of the caretaker as soothing even when the caretaker is absent. \
\
There is strong support that certain basic emotions may be innate. For example, infants in \
their first day of life manifest facial expressions that mimic adult expressions of emotion. \
At a young age, infants are able to recognize facial expressions in others. In addition, the \
expression of certain emotions is extremely similar across cultures. Modern evolution \
theory holds that basic emotions originate in the subcortical limbic system and therefore \
evolved prior to thought (which occurs in the more evolved cortical system). Along these \
lines, several theorists propose that there are seven to ten primary emotions that are \
culturally universal (typically including some versions of fear, anger, disgust, surprise, joy, \
shame, contempt, sadness, and interest). However, more complex emotions such as love \
and remorse require higher cortical processes. \
\
Adolescence is a period that has traditionally been associated with difficulties managing \
emotions. Empirical investigation, however, offers little support for the idea that \
adolescence is a period of emotional turmoil and intense conflict between parents and their \
