   8.5 RISK AND PROTECTIVE FACTORS IN \
                   DEVELOPMENT \
\
While the predominant focus in the area of developmental psychology is on normal \
development, an equally important area that merits attention and understanding is \
developmental deviation or psychopathology. Developmental psychopathology is broadly \
thought to be a function of risk and protective factors. \
\
>RISK FACTORS In terms of risk factors, three categories are generally delineated: risk \
factors at the level of the individual (e.g., defective genes, difficult temperament), risk \
factors at the level of the family (e.g., mentally ill parent, child abuse), and those at the \
level of the community (e.g., discrimination, poverty). \
\
One strategy to determine the overall risk for developmental psychopathology is to add up \
the specific risk factors faced, thereby creating an adversity index. Most people can cope \
with a small number of risk factors, especially if protective factors are also present. \
However, when many risk factors are present, individuals frequently begin to show signs \
of disturbance. \
\
It turns out that risk factors rarely occur in isolation, and that a given risk factor can \
sometimes more accurately be described as an accumulation of many separate risk factors. \
The risk factors of poverty and maternal substance abuse are used as examples. \
\
     POVERTY Poverty brings biological risks, including lack of prenatal care, higher \
     rates of prenatal drug and alcohol exposure, and poorer nutrition. Poverty is \
     associated with a nearly 50% greater risk of prenatal and postnatal infant deaths. \
     Poverty can also have significant effects on parenting style, and responsiveness to \
     the infant or child's needs, which can lead to problems with attachment. Attachment \
     problems can result in subsequent behavioral problems, impulse control problems, \
     low self-esteem, poor peer relations, and diminished cognitive performance. \
     Lower-income neighborhoods also tend to have higher rates of delinquency and \
     crime, with children experiencing increased exposure to adult criminal behavior. \
     substance abuse, and child abuse. \
\
\
