\
     MATERNAL SUBSTANCE ABUSE Maternal substance abuse brings with it a \
     myriad of risks. Most significantly, substances (e.g., alcohol, cocaine) ingested \
     during pregnancy, called teratogens, can have direct toxic effects on the fetus and \
     cause long-term developmental problems. In large quantities, for example, alcohol \
    has been linked to fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS); even small amounts of alcohol \
     (less than one drink per day) may lead to effects that are similar to FAS but are less \
     severe. Furthermore, the drug abusing lifestyle is frequently associated with \
     inadequate nutrition and poor prenatal care. Drug abuse is more common among \
     women living in poverty, and substance use during pregnancy is highly correlated \
     with parental psychopathology. Additionally, chaos, disorganization, and multiple \
     caregivers commonly mark the caregiving environment of infants born to substance \
     abusing mothers. \
\
The potency of any particular risk factor appears to vary with age and sex. Overall, boys \
appear more vulnerable to risk factors from the prenatal period to about age ten, while girls \
grow more vulnerable to risk factors during their teens. In general girls appear to possess \
a wider range of coping skills than boys, especially in their ability to form relationships. \
\
>PROTECTIVE FACTORS/RESILIENCE Protective factors are generally less well \
understood. Physical health, normal or high IQ, and economic advantage are examples of \
protective factors. In particular, research has consistently highlighted the importance of \
two factors in accounting for resilience: good cognitive functioning and positive \
relationships (e.g., the ability to obtain help and to find and use an external support system). \
Garmezy proposed an interpersonal view of protective factors, stressing three categories: \
personality disposition of the child, supportive family environment, and an external support \
system that reinforces a child's coping efforts. \
