I. OVERVIEW \
\
The DSM-5 is organized based on developmental and lifespan considerations, as well as a \
clustering of disorders based on internalizing and externalizing factors. The DSM-5 begins \
with disorders thought to reflect developmental processes that manifest early in life (e.g., \
the neurodevelopmental and schizophrenia spectrum disorders), followed by diagnoses that \
more commonly manifest in adolescence and young adulthood that are internalizing (e.g., \
depressive, anxiety, somatic), disorders that are externalizing (e.g., impulsive, disruptive \
conduct and substance use), and ending with diagnoses related to later life (e.g., \
neurocognitive). \
\
The DSM-5 moved to a nonaxial documentation of diagnosis with separate notation for \
important social and contextual factors and disability. The WHODAS (WHO Disability \
Assessment Schedule) is included in the DSM-5 section called emerging measures and \
models. Also included in that section are clinician-rated dimensions of psychosis symptom \
severity, cultural formulation, an alternative DSM-5 model for personality disorders, and \
conditions for further study (e.g., attenuated psychosis syndrome, persistent complex \
bereavement disorder, internet gaming disorder, suicidal behavior disorder). \
\
According to the DSM-5, "A mental disorder is a syndrome characterized by clinically \
significant disturbance in an individual's cognition, emotion regulation, or behavior that \
reflects a dysfunction in the psychological, biological, or developmental processes \
underlying mental functioning. Mental disorders are usually associated with significant \
distress or disability in social, occupational, or other important activities." (DSM-5, p. 20). \
An expectable or culturally approved response to a stressor or loss is not a mental disorder. \
Additionally, socially deviant behavior per se is not a mental disorder, unless the deviance \
results from a dysfunction in the person. The medication-induced movement disorders and \
other conditions that may be a focus of clinical attention, are also not considered mental \
disorders. \
