  9.2 NEURODEVELOPMENTAL DISORDERS \
\
 The neurodevelopmental disorders typically manifest early in development, commonly \
 before the child enters grade school. The developmental deficits result in impairment in \
 personal, social, academic, or occupational functioning. The range of deficits is variable. \
 from very specific (e.g., specific learning disorder) to global (e.g., autism spectrum \
 disorder). Neurodevelopmental disorders frequently co-occur. \
\
 I. INTELLECTUAL DISABILITY \
\
 Intellectual disability (intellectual developmental disorder) involves deficits in general \
 mental abilities (e.g., reasoning, problem solving, abstract thinking, academic learning), as \
 well as deficits in adaptive functioning in one or more areas (e.g., communication, social \
 participation, independent living) across multiple environments (e.g., school, home, work). \
 Onset is during the development period. \
\
 Persons with intellectual disability typically have IQ scores that are two or more standard \
 deviations below the mean. The level of severity is based on adaptive functioning, not IQ \
 score, as adaptive functioning determines how much support a person will require. \
\
 Adaptive functioning is assessed in three areas: the conceptual/academic domain, which \
 involves memory, language, reading, writing, math reasoning, problem solving, etc .; the \
 social domain, which involves empathy, interpersonal communication, friendship abilities, \
 social judgment, etc .; and the practical domain, which involves personal care, money \
 management, recreation, school and work task organization, etc. Specifiers for severity \
 include: mild, moderate, severe, and profound. \
\
 Intellectual disability, mild is characterized by some difficulties in learning academic skills \
 (in children), and impairments in abstract thinking, executive functioning, and short-term \
 memory (in adults); immaturity in social interactions (including risk of gullibility) with \
 possible difficulty regulating emotions and behavior; a need for some support with \
 complex daily living tasks (e.g., money management, home and child-care organization, \
 transportation), health care and legal decisions, and learning of a skilled vocation. \
\
 Intellectual disability, moderate is characterized by significant lags in academic skill \
 development (for adults, academic skills are typically at an elementary level); capacity for \
 relationships in spite of marked deficits in social and communicative behavior, and \
\
