limitations in social judgment and decision-making; the capacity for self-care (with \
extensive training), employment in jobs that require limited conceptual and communication \
skills, and need of considerable support to manage social expectations, transportation, \
health, money management, etc. \
\
Intellectual disability, severe is characterized by limited attainment of conceptual skills, \
with little understanding of written language, number concepts, time, etc .; spoken language \
is very limited in terms of vocabulary and grammar, comprehension is limited to simple \
speech and gestures, yet relationships are a source of pleasure; support and supervision is \
needed for all activities of daily living and decisions that must be made. \
\
Intellectual disability, profound is characterized by motor and sensory impairments; very \
limited understanding of communication in speech and gestures, and use of nonverbal \
communication; dependency on others for all aspects of care, with some ability to \
participate (e.g., in recreation, carrying dishes to the table). \
\
Deficits in both intellectual functioning and adaptive functioning are typically determined \
by clinical assessment as well as standardized testing. Deficits in adaptive functioning may \
be assessed with the Vineland Adaptive Behaviors Scale. \
\
Intellectual disability may involve prenatal, perinatal, or postnatal etiologies. About 75% \
of all cases of intellectual disability are prenatal in origin, about 10 -15% perinatal (from 1 \
pound in utero to 1 month after birth), and 10 - 15% postnatal. \
\
Genetic factors have a small influence on intellectual disability, accounting for only about \
5% of the cases (e.g., chromosomal abnormalities, such as Down's syndrome). \
\
Environmental factors play a much larger role. During the prenatal period, the most \
common cause of intellectual disability is alterations during the embryonic stage of \
development (from conception to 8 weeks). Factors that may lead to intellectual disability \
include poor maternal nutritional state, poor maternal personal health habits, limited access \
to health care, and exposure in utero to pollutants, chemicals, and toxins (e.g., maternal \
alcohol consumption). \
\
During the perinatal period, intellectual disability may be caused by fetal malnutrition, \
hypoxia, prematurity, trauma, or viral infections. Intellectual disability occurring \
postnatally is usually brought about by hypoxic ischemic injury, traumatic brain injury. \
seizure disorders, severe and chronic social deprivation, toxins, or infection. \
