III. AUTISM SPECTRUM DISORDER \
\
>AUTISM SPECTRUM DISORDER The essential features of autism spectrum disorder \
include: a) persistent deficits in social communication and social interaction across \
multiple contexts (e.g., deficits in social-emotional reciprocity, deficits in nonverbal \
behaviors in social interaction, deficits in developing and understanding relationships); and \
b) restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior, interests, or activities as manifest by at least \
two of the following: stereotyped or repetitive motor movements, use of objects, or speech; \
inflexible adherence to routine; restricted, fixated interests; or hyper- or hyporeactivity to \
sensory input. \
\
Symptoms must be present in the early developmental period, and must cause clinically \
significant impairment in social, occupational, or other important areas of functioning. \
\
Severity level is coded in terms of level of support needed for deficits in both social \
communication as well as restricted, repetitive behavior: Level 1 - requiring support, Level \
2 - requiring substantial support, and Level 3 - requiring very substantial support. \
Specification of with or without accompanying intellectual impairment and with or without \
accompanying language impairment is also recorded. \
\
\
\
                                 Section 9 -DSM-5: Neurodevelopmental Disorders \
\
The frequency of autism spectrum disorder in the population is 1%. Many persons with \
autism spectrum disorder also have intellectual impairment and/or language impairment. \
The prognosis is best with an absence of intellectual impairment and functional language \
by age 5. Male to female ratio is 4:1. Heritability estimates for autism spectrum disorder \
are quite high (ranging from about 35% to 90% in twin studies), with as many as 15% of \
all cases associated with a known genetic mutation. \
\
Symptoms of autism spectrum disorder are typically evident in the second year of life \
(between 12- 24 months) but may be seen earlier if the delays are more severe or later if \
the symptoms are more subtle. \
\
A savant is an individual with striking abilities (e.g., able to play music perfectly after \
hearing it just once, or able to do complex mathematical calculations in his or her head) \
who is otherwise disabled in everyday cognitive functions and/or social interactions. \
Savant abilities are sometimes found in individuals with autism spectrum disorder (i.e., \
"autistic savant"). \
\
Autism spectrum disorder shares some features with Rett syndrome. This syndrome, found \
almost exclusively in females, is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by normal \
prenatal and perinatal development, normal psychomotor development through 5 months, \
and normal head circumference at birth. Between 5 months and 48 months, there is a \
sudden deceleration of head growth, acquisition of stereotyped hand movements, loss of \
social engagement, and the appearance of poorly coordinated movements. However, after \
this period, there is typically an improvement in social communication skills and autistic \
features are no longer a major concern. \
\
IV. ATTENTION-DEFICIT/HYPERACTIVITY DISORDER \
\
>ATTENTION-DEFICIT/HYPERACTIVITY DISORDER (ADHD)   Attention- \
deficit/hyperactivity disorder is characterized by a persistent pattern (at least 6 months) of \
inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity. Some of the symptoms must have been \
present before 12 years of age, and impairment from the disorder must occur in at least two \
settings and be severe enough to interfere with functioning. \
\
Criteria for inattention are met when the person has six or more of the following symptoms \
(for adolescents and adults at least five symptoms are required): failure to pay attention to \
details resulting in careless errors, difficulty sustaining attention to tasks, does not seem to \
listen when spoken to directly, does not follow through or fails to finish assignments, has \
