difficulty organizing tasks, avoids tasks requiring sustained attention, frequently loses \
things (e.g., homework assignments), is easily distracted, and is forgetful in daily activities. \
\
The criteria for hyperactivity-impulsivity are met when the person has six or more of the \
following symptoms (for adolescents and adults at least five symptoms are required): \
frequently fidgets or squirms, stands up when remaining seated is expected, runs or climbs \
excessively in inappropriate situations, has difficulty playing quietly, is constantly "on the \
go," talks excessively, blurts out answers before questions are completed, has difficulty \
waiting for his/her turn, and interrupts or intrudes on others. \
\
This disorder is coded either as: combined presentation, predominantly inattentive \
presentation, or predominantly hyperactive/impulsive presentation. Severity is coded as \
mild, moderate, or severe. The clinician must also specify if in partial remission in \
situations in which the full criteria were previously met, but fewer than full criteria have \
been met for the past 6 months, with symptoms still resulting in impairment. \
\
ADHD occurs in about 5% of children and 2.5% of adults. According to the DSM-5, \
ADHD is more common in males than females with a ratio of about 2:1. Medications used \
in the treatment of ADHD include the stimulants Ritalin (methylphenidate), Concerta \
(methylphenidate), Adderall (amphetamine), and Dexedrine (dextroamphetamine), and the \
non-stimulant Strattera (atomoxetine). Non-pharmacological interventions for children \
with ADHD include behavior therapy, social skills training, parenting education, and \
neurofeedback (formerly called EEG biofeedback). For adults with ADHD, cognitive \
behavioral therapy (CBT) is an evidence-based treatment. \
\
The diagnosis of ADHD can be particularly difficult to establish prior to age 4, mainly \
because it is hard to distinguish normal variations in behavior from the hyperactivity \
associated with ADHD. The disorder tends to be relatively stable through early \
adolescence; in adolescence and adulthood, symptoms of motoric hyperactivity decrease, \
while difficulties with restlessness, inattention, poor planning, and impulsivity continue. A \
significant proportion of children with ADHD remain impaired into adulthood. \
\
Associated features of ADHD may include low frustration tolerance, irritability, or mood \
lability, as well as social rejection and interpersonal conflict. Academic achievement and/or \
work performance is often impaired. When the diagnosis is ADHD combined presentation, \
there is frequently a comorbid oppositional defiant disorder (about 50% of the time) or \
conduct disorder (about 25% of the time). Most children with disruptive mood \
dysregulation disorder have ADHD, although most children with ADHD do not have \
disruptive mood dysregulation disorder. Specific learning disorder also commonly co- \
