V. SPECIFIC LEARNING DISORDER \
\
Specific learning disorder is diagnosed when there are difficulties learning and using \
academic skills, with the presence of at least one symptom for at least 6 months despite \
interventions targeting the difficulties: inaccurate or slow and effortful reading, difficulty \
understanding the meaning of what is read, difficulties with spelling, difficulties with \
written expression (e.g., multiple grammatical or punctuation errors), difficulties mastering \
number facts or calculation, or difficulty with mathematical reasoning. The affected \
academic skills are substantially below those expected for the person's age, and the \
learning problem interferes with academic/occupational performance or activities of daily \
living. The criteria for substantially below are achievement test scores that are at least 1.5 \
standard deviations (SD) below the population mean for age (below the 7th percentile), not \
better accounted for by intellectual disabilities. \
\
All academic domains and subskills that are impaired should be coded. Specifiers include: \
with impairment in reading (word reading accuracy, reading rate or fluency, reading \
comprehension); with impairment in written expression (spelling accuracy, grammar and \
punctuation accuracy, clarity and organization of written expression); and with impairment \
in mathematics (number sense, memorization of arithmetic facts, accurate or fluent \
calculation, accurate math reasoning). Severity is specified as mild, moderate, or severe. \
\
The term dyslexia refers to problems with accurate or fluent word recognition, poor \
decoding, and poor spelling abilities. When the term dyslexia is used, any additional \
difficulties should also be noted (e.g., problems with reading comprehension). \
\
Dyscalculia refers to problems with numerical processing, problems learning arithmetic \
facts, and difficulty performing accurate calculations. When the term dyscalculia is used, \
any additional difficulties should also be noted (e.g., difficulties with math reasoning). \
\
\
 \
\
                                 Section 9-DSM-5: Neurodevelopmental Disorders \
\
The prevalence rate for specific learning disorder is 5% - 15%. Specific learning disorder \
is more common in males than females (ratios range from 2:1 to 3:1). Comorbid disorders \
may include neurodevelopmental disorders (e.g., ADHD, autism spectrum disorder) and \
other mental disorders (e.g., anxiety disorders, depressive and bipolar disorders, \
oppositional defiant disorder, conduct disorder). \
\
VI. MOTOR DISORDERS \
\
>DEVELOPMENTAL COORDINATION DISORDER This disorder is characterized \
by deficits in daily activities that require motor coordination, which may be manifested by \
marked delays in achieving motor milestones, or by clumsiness, poor performance in \
sports, or poor handwriting. \
\
>STEREOTYPIC MOVEMENT DISORDER    The essential feature of stereotypic \
movement disorder is motor behavior that is repetitive and nonfunctional (e.g., body \
rocking, head banging, self-biting, etc.) that interferes with normal activities or results in \
self-inflicted bodily injury. Stereotypic movement disorder cannot be diagnosed if the \
stereotyped behaviors are attributable to the effects of a substance or neurological \
condition, or is better explained by another disorder (e.g., obsessive-compulsive disorder, \
trichotillomania). The clinician must specify if with or without self-injurious behavior as \
well as the severity: mild, moderate, or severe. \
\
>TIC DISORDERS Tics are sudden, rapid, recurrent, non-rhythmic, stereotyped motor \
movements or vocalizations. Tic disorders include: Tourette's disorder, persistent \
(chronic) motor or vocal tic disorder, and provisional tic disorder. Tourette's disorder \
involves multiple motor and one or more vocal tics. The tics may wax and wane in \
frequency, but have been present for more than 1 year since first tic onset. Persistent \
(chronic) motor or vocal tic disorder involves single or multiple motor or vocal tics, but \
not both, present for more than 1 year since first tic onset. Provisional tic disorder involves \
single or multiple motor and/or vocal tics present for less than 1 year since first tic onset. \
Onset of all tic disorders is before age 18. \
\
While tics are generally experienced as involuntary, they can be voluntarily suppressed for \
a limited time. Tics may increase under stress and may decrease during absorbing activities. \
Motor tics include eye blinking, neck jerking, shoulder shrugging, facial grimacing. \
grooming behaviors, jumping, or touching. Vocal ties include throat clearing, grunting, \
sniffing, barking, copralalia (swearing) and echolalia. Common treatment medications \
include Catapres (clonidine), an anti-hypertensive agent, and Haldol (haloperidol), an \
antipsychotic. The SSRI's, such as Prozac (fluoxetine), are also used. \
\
\
\
                                 Section 9 -DSM-5: Neurodevelopmental Disorders \
\
Tourette's disorder occurs in about 5 out of every 1,000 children, with males more \
commonly affected than females (ratio varying from 2:1 to 4:1). Children with Tourette's \
disorder are more likely to experience ADHD, obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD), or \
separation anxiety disorder, while adolescents and adults are more likely to experience \
major depressive disorder, substance use disorder, or bipolar disorder. \
\
