    9.3 SCHIZOPHRENIA SPECTRUM                   AND \
        OTHER PSYCHOTIC DISORDERS \
\
The disorders in this section are all characterized by abnormalities of one or more of the \
following: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized thinking (speech), disorganized or \
abnormal motor behavior (including catatonia), and negative symptoms. \
\
Delusions are fixed, false beliefs that are unchangeable. The content varies (e.g., \
persecutory, grandiose, somatic) and may be non-bizarre or bizarre. Non-bizarre delusions \
involve situations that are possible (e.g., a person believes he or she has exceptional \
abilities or that his or her spouse is unfaithful), while bizarre delusions are clearly \
implausible (e.g., the person believes that aliens have removed his or her internal organs). \
\
Hallucinations are vivid and clear perceptions that occur without external stimulus. While \
they may occur in any sensory modality, auditory hallucinations are most common in \
schizophrenia and related disorders. Auditory hallucinations tend to be experienced as \
voices that are distinct from one's own thoughts. \
\
Disorganized thinking is usually inferred from speech, in which the person switches from \
one topic to another (derailment or loose associations) or provides answers that diverge \
from questions asked (tangentiality). \
\
Grossly disorganized or abnormal motor behavior (including catatonia) may range from \
childlike "silliness" to unexpected agitation, typically interfering with goal-directed \
behaviors and activities of daily living. Catatonia involves a marked decrease in reactivity \
that ranges from resistance to instructions (negativism), to maintaining odd posture, to lack \
of verbal or motor response (mutism and stupor). Additionally, catatonia can involve \
excessive motor activity (catatonic excitement) or repeated stereotyped movements, \
grimacing, and echoing of speech. Although historically associated with schizophrenia, \
catatonic symptoms may occur in other mental disorders (e.g., bipolar or depressive \
disorders) and in medical conditions. \
\
Negative symptoms that are common in schizophrenia include diminished emotional \
expression (e.g., facial expression, eye contact, intonations of speech, etc., that give \
emotional emphasis to speech) and avolition (decrease in self-initiated purposeful \
activities). Other negative symptoms include alogia (reduced speech output), anhedonia \
(diminished pleasure) and asociality (lack of interest in social interactions). \
\
\
\
                     Section 9 - DSM-5: Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders \
\
Severity is rated by assessing the primary symptoms of psychosis (delusions, hallucination, \
disorganized speech, abnormal psychomotor behavior, and negative symptoms). Severity \
is specified on a 5-point scale for each symptom, based on presence and strength of the \
symptom from 0 (not present) to 4 (present and severe). \
\
The specifier with catatomia may be coded for any of the psychotic disorders when \
indicated by the presentation. Criteria for catatonia involve a clinical picture that is \
dominated by three or more of the following symptoms: stupor (no psychomotor activity). \
catalepsy (posture is held passively, against gravity), waxy flexibility (resistance to \
positioning by another), mutism (no verbal response), negativism (no response to \
instructions or external stimuli), posturing (actively maintaining a posture against gravity). \
mannerism (caricature of normal actions), stereotypy (repetitive non-goal-directed \
movements), agitation, grimacing, echolalia (mimicking another's speech), or echopraxia \
(imitating another's movement). \
\
>SCHIZOTYPAL PERSONALITY DISORDER This disorder is considered part of the \
schizophrenia spectrum and is also included in the personality disorders section (where \
diagnostic criteria are described). \
\
>DELUSIONAL DISORDER This disorder involves one or more delusions of at least 1 \
month's duration and an absence of additional symptoms found in schizophrenia (e.g., \
hallucinations, disorganized speech, disorganized or catatonic behavior, or negative \
symptoms). In delusional disorder, apart from the direct impact of the delusions, the \
person's behavior is relatively unimpaired and is not obviously odd. If manic or major \
depressive episodes occur concurrent with the delusion, the duration of the mood episode \
is brief relative to the duration of the delusion. \
\
Specifiers for delusional disorder include: erotomanic type, grandiose type, jealous type, \
persecutory type, somatic type, mixed type, and unspecified type. Erotomanic type involves \
delusions in which another person, usually of higher status, is in love with the individual. \
Grandiose type is characterized by delusions of inflated self-worth, power, knowledge, or \
a special relationship to a deity or famous person. Jealous type involves delusions in which \
the person believes that a sexual partner is being unfaithful. Persecutory type is \
characterized by delusions in which the person is being persecuted or ill treated, which may \
trigger violent behavior. Somatic type involves delusions relating to body functions and \
sensations (e.g., the belief that one emits a foul odor). Mixed type involves characteristics \
of more than one of the above types, without any single theme predominating. Unspecified \
type involves delusions whose themes are not characteristic of any of the above types. \
\
\
 \
\
                     Section 9 - DSM-5: Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders \
\
Additionally, the specifier with bizarre content is used when the delusion is bizarre (not \
plausible). \
\
The age of onset for delusional disorder is typically in middle to late adulthood, although \
it can occur at a younger age. The most common subtype is persecutory. The functional \
impairment is usually more circumscribed in comparison with other psychotic disorders; \
nevertheless, the impairment may be substantial. \
\
>BRIEF PSYCHOTIC DISORDER Brief psychotic disorder is characterized by one or \
more of the following: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech, or grossly \
disorganized or catatonic behavior. The episode lasts anywhere from 1 day to 1 month, \
with eventual return to premorbid levels of functioning. It should be specified as with \
marked stressor, without marked stressor, or with postpartum onset. The specifier with \
catatonia is also used when catatonia is part of the symptom presentation. \
\
>SCHIZOPHRENIFORM DISORDER   The symptoms of schizophreniform disorder \
are identical to schizophrenia, distinguished only by duration. The diagnosis of \
schizophreniform disorder is made when the duration of the illness is at least 1 month but \
less than 6 months. When the person has symptoms for less than 6 months and has not yet \
recovered, the diagnosis is typically schizophreniform disorder (provisional) because if the \
disturbance persists beyond 6 months, the diagnosis is changed to schizophrenia. Specifiers \
include: with good prognostic features and without good prognostic features. Good \
prognostic features include two or more of the following: onset of prominent psychotic \
symptoms within 4 weeks of the first noticeable change in behavior (acute onset), \
confusion or perplexity, good premorbid social and occupational functioning, and absence \
of flat or blunted affect. The specifier with catatonia is also used when catatonia is part of \
the symptom presentation. \
\
>SCHIZOPHRENIA Diagnostic criteria for schizophrenia require the presence of two \
or more of the following characteristic symptoms, each present for a significant portion of \
time during a 1-month period: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech, grossly \
disorganized or catatonic behavior, and negative symptoms (e.g., diminished emotional \
expression, avolition). At least one of the symptoms must be delusions, hallucinations, or \
disorganized speech. In addition, for a significant portion of time since onset, the person \
must be functioning at a level markedly below previous functioning in such areas as work, \
interpersonal relations, or self-care. Continuous signs of the disturbance must persist for at \
least 6 months, with active symptoms present for at least 1 month. During prodromal or \
residual periods, the signs of disturbance may include only negative symptoms or two or \
more symptoms in attenuated forms (e.g., odd beliefs, unusual perceptual experiences). \
\
\
\
                     Section 9 - DSM-5: Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders \
\
The specifier with catatonia is also used when catatonia is part of the symptom \
presentation. \
\
The age of onset for schizophrenia is typically between the late teens and early 30s, with \
onset prior to adolescence rarely occurring. According to the DSM-5, the median age of \
onset is in the early to mid-20s for men and in the late 20s for women. The onset may be \
abrupt or gradual, and most cases involve a prodromal phase, which is characterized by \
deterioration in overall functioning. The course of schizophrenia is quite variable but full \
remission is rather uncommon. Some individuals with the illness have a course \
characterized by exacerbations and remissions, while others show progressive \
deterioration. \
\
According to the DSM-5, the lifetime prevalence rate of schizophrenia is .3% - . 7%. The \
male to female ratio is about equal. Prognosis is best with good prior functioning, abrupt \
onset, fewer negative symptoms, minimal cognitive impairment, and female gender \
(women tend to have fewer negative symptoms). Later onset has been associated with \
better prognosis. However, the effect of age of onset on prognosis is likely related to gender \
(as females have a later age of onset). Suicide risk is high in individuals with schizophrenia, \
with approximately 5% - 6% committing suicide and about 20% attempting suicide on one \
or more occasions. \
\
First-degree relatives (e.g., siblings) have a concordance rate of 10% and thus have an \
approximately twelve-fold greater risk of developing schizophrenia than does the general \
population. Identical twins have a 50% concordance rate. The risk of developing \
schizophrenia when both parents have the disorder is about 45%. Relatives of individuals \
with schizophrenia also have an increased risk of developing other schizophrenia spectrum \
disorders, including schizotypal and paranoid personality disorder, and delusional disorder. \
\
As measured by magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), brains of persons with schizophrenia \
show enlargement of the lateral and third ventricles, a smaller cerebral cortex, and a smaller \
thalamus (the filter for sensory input). Positron emission tomography (PET) scans indicate \
that individuals with schizophrenia have decreased frontal lobe activity. Frontal lobe \
abnormalities have been associated predominantly with the negative symptoms of \
schizophrenia (e.g., flat affect, avolition). \
\
Medication management is a key component to the effective treatment of schizophrenia \
and is usually life-long. The most commonly used medications are the novel \
antipsychotics, although traditional antipsychotics are still widely used as well. (Please see \
the section of Psychopharmacology for more details.) \
\
\
 \
\
                     Section 9 - DSM-5: Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders \
\
 A variety of psychosocial interventions have demonstrated effectiveness in treating \
schizophrenia, including cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) and family psychoeducation \
(FP). Because expressed emotion (EE) by family members (i.e., criticism, hostility, and \
emotional over-involvement) has been repeatedly shown to predict relapse, many family \
approaches work to decrease EE and focus on the family and patient's strengths and \
resiliency. Social skills training (SST), another well-established evidence-based treatment, \
teaches skills related to communication, assertiveness, disease management and \
independent living. Supported employment, cognitive remediation, and social \
learning/token economy programs have also been found to be highly effective in the \
treatment of individuals with schizophrenia. \
\
>SCHIZOAFFECTIVE DISORDER   Criteria for schizoaffective disorder include an \
uninterrupted period of illness during which there has been a major mood episode (e.g., \
major depressive or manic) concurrent with the symptoms of schizophrenia. In addition, \
during that period of illness, there have been delusions or hallucinations for at least 2 weeks \
without prominent mood symptoms. Furthermore, mood symptoms are present for a \
substantial portion of the total duration of both the active and residual periods. Specifiers \
include: bipolar type or depressive type. Bipolar type applies if a manic episode is part of \
the presentation, whether or not a major depressive occurs. Depressive type applies only if \
major depressive episodes are part of the presentation. The specifier with catatonia is also \
used when symptoms of catatonia are evident. \
\
>SUBSTANCE/MEDICATION-INDUCED PSYCHOTIC DISORDER Substances \
that can induce a psychotic disorder include alcohol, cannabis, hallucinogens (including \
PCP), inhalants, sedatives, hypnotics and anxiolytics, and stimulants (including cocaine). \
\
>PSYCHOTIC DISORDER DUE TO ANOTHER MEDICAL CONDITION Medical \
conditions that are known to manifest with delusions or hallucinations include neurological \
conditions (e.g., neoplasms, migraines, Huntington's disease, epilepsy), endocrine \
 disorders (e.g., hyper- and hypothyroidism), and metabolic conditions (e.g .. \
hypoglycemia). Specifiers include: with delusions or with hallucinations. \
\
>CATATONIC DISORDER DUE TO ANOTHER MEDICAL CONDITION Medical \
conditions that are known to manifest with catatonia include neurological conditions (e.g., \
neoplasms, head trauma, encephalitis) and metabolic conditions (e.g., hypercalcemia. \
diabetic ketoacidosis). \
\
