\
>BIPOLAR I DISORDER The essential feature of bipolar I disorder is the occurrence \
 of at least one manic episode. The manic episode may be preceded or followed by \
 hypomanic or major depressive episodes, but other mood episodes are not necessary for \
 the diagnosis. \
\
 The mood episode should be specified as mild, moderate, or severe; when full criteria for \
 a mood episode are not met, it should be specified as in partial remission or in full \
 remission. The current or most recent episode is also specified as manie, hypomanic, \
 depressed, or unspecified. \
\
 Additional specifiers include: with anxious distress, with mixed features, with rapid \
 cycling, with mood-congruent or mood-incongruent psychotic features, with catatonia, \
 with peripartum onset, and with seasonal pattern. \
\
 The lifetime prevalence rate of bipolar disorder is about 1%. Bipolar disorder is equally \
 common in males and females, and more common in high-income than low-income \
 countries. Bipolar disorder has the highest concordance rates of all the major mental \
 disorders; the concordance rates are 80% for identical twins and 20 - 25% for fraternal \
 twins and siblings. The risk of suicide in individuals with bipolar disorder is at least 15 \
 times that of the general population. Bipolar disorder may account for 25% of all completed \
 suicides. \
\
 \
\
