\
 Mean age of onset for the first manie, hypomanic, or depressive episode is 18 years. Bipolar \
 disorder is typically recurrent; more than 90% of people who have had a single manic \
 episode go on to have future mood episodes. Research has indicated that stressors play \
 more of a role in precipitating the first and/or second episodes of the disorder than \
 subsequent episodes. Medication management for bipolar disorder is typically lifelong and \
 commonly prescribed medications include Lithium, Tegretol, or Depakene (valproic acid). \
 Psychoeducation (providing information about bipolar disorder with the goal of improving \
 adherence to medications) has strong research support. \
\
 >BIPOLAR II DISORDER Bipolar II disorder is diagnosed when there has been at least \
 one major depressive episode and at least one hypomanic episode. Additionally, there has \
 never been a manic episode. \
\
 The mood episode should be specified as mild, moderate, or severe; when full criteria for \
 a mood episode are not met, it should be specified as in partial remission or in full \
 remission. The current or most recent episode is also specified as hypomanic or depressed. \
\
 Additional specifiers include: with anxious distress, with mixed features, with rapid \
 cycling, with mood-congruent or mood-incongruent psychotic features, with catatonia, \
 with peripartum onset, and with seasonal pattern. \
\
 The average age of onset for bipolar II disorder is mid-20s (later age than bipolar I \
 disorder). Bipolar II disorder appears to be more common in women than men. The risk of \
 bipolar II disorder is highest among relatives of people with bipolar II disorder. \
\
 >CYCLOTHYMIC DISORDER    Cyclothymic disorder includes the presence of \
 numerous periods of hypomanic symptoms and numerous periods of depressive symptoms, \
 over the course of at least 2 years (1 year in children and adolescents). During the 2-year \
 period, the hypomanic and depressive periods have been present at least half the time, and \
 the person has not been without symptoms for more than 2 months at a time. Criteria for a \
 major depressive, manic, or hypomanic episode have never been met. Additionally. \
 symptoms must cause significant distress or impairment in functioning. The specifier with \
 anxious distress is coded when indicated. \
