\
          9.5 DEPRESSIVE DISORDERS \
\
The depressive disorders all involve sad, empty, or irritable mood, along with somatic and \
cognitive changes that significantly affect functioning. \
\
>DISRUPTIVE MOOD    DYSREGULATION DISORDER    Disruptive mood \
dysregulation disorder involves recurrent temper outbursts (verbal or physical), occurring \
on average three or more times a week for over 1 year, in at least two settings. Additionally. \
between temper outbursts, the mood is persistently irritable or angry most of the day, nearly \
every day. The diagnosis must not be made before age 6 or after age 18 and the symptoms \
must have been present before age 10. The diagnosis requires that there has never been a \
period of more than 1 day in which the symptoms of a manic or hypomanic episode have \
been present. \
\
>MAJOR DEPRESSIVE DISORDER Major depressive disorder requires the presence \
of a major depressive episode, characterized by five or more symptoms during a 2-week \
period that represent a change from previous functioning. At least one of the symptoms \
must be either (a) depressed mood or (b) loss of interest or pleasure. Other symptoms \
include: weight loss or gain, or change in appetite; insomnia or hypersomnia; psychomotor \
agitation or retardation; fatigue or loss of energy; feelings of worthlessness or guilt; poor \
concentration or indecisiveness; and recurrent thoughts of death or suicidal ideation, intent, \
or plan. Additionally, the diagnosis requires that the person has never experienced a manic \
or hypomanic episode. \
\
The DSM-5 notes that normal response to significant loss (e.g., bereavement, serious \
medical illness, natural disaster) may include intense sadness, insomnia, loss of appetite, \
and rumination. A key distinction between grief and a major depressive episode (MDE) is \
that in grief, feelings of emptiness and loss predominate, while in MDE there is a persistent \
depressed mood and inability to experience pleasure. Additionally, the dysphoria in grief \
tends to occur in waves, associated with thoughts of the loss, rather than being persistent. \
Themes in MDE include feelings of self-loathing, worthlessness, and wanting to end one's \
life due to inadequacy (e.g., feeling undeserving, unable to cope); these themes are not \
typically seen with grief and loss. The presence of a major depressive episode in addition \
to the normal response to loss should be considered and diagnosed when appropriate. \
\
When full criteria for a major depressive episode are currently met, major depressive \
disorder is coded with the specifiers of mild, moderate, or severe. When full criteria for a \
