major depressive episode are not met, course is specified as either in partial remission or \
in full remission. \
\
Additional specifiers include: with anxious distress, with mixed features, with melancholic \
features, with atypical features, with mood-congruent or mood-incongruent psychotic \
features, with catatonia, with peripartum onset, and with seasonal pattern. \
\
Major depressive disorder, with peripartum onset is thought to occur in about 10% to 15% \
of new mothers. Symptoms include severe anxiety, irritability, insomnia, lack of interest \
in the infant, guilt, suicidal ideation, and poor concentration, as well as weepiness and \
sadness. These symptoms can continue for months if untreated. In contrast, postpartum \
blues (or baby blues) are much more widespread, occurring in 50% - 80% of mothers just \
after delivery. The symptoms are less severe and relatively short-lived. Postpartum blues \
involve crying, irritability, poor sleep, weeping, and a sense of emotional vulnerability. \
Typically, postpartum blues begin in the first week after birth, and last no longer than a \
few weeks. There is no DSM-5 diagnosis for postpartum blues. Postpartum psychosis is \
relatively rare, occurring in .2% of the population. It is characterized by hallucinations \
(e.g., command hallucinations to kill the infant) or delusions (e.g., beliefs that the baby is \
possessed or has special powers). It is typically coded as brief psychotic disorder, with \
postpartum onset. \
\
Major depressive disorder can begin at any age, although incidence peaks in the 20s. The \
course of major depressive disorder is variable, with some individuals rarely experiencing \
remission, and others experiencing isolated episodes with full return to premorbid \
functioning between episodes. Recovery commonly begins within 3 months of onset for 2 \
out of 5 individuals and within 1 year for 4 out of 5 individuals. Factors associated with \
lower recovery rates include current episode duration, psychotic features, prominent \
anxiety, personality disorders, and symptom severity. Risk of recurrence is higher when \
the preceding episode was severe, in younger individuals, or in persons who have had \
multiple episodes. \
\
The rate of major depressive disorder is equal in prepubertal girls and boys; it is 1.5 to 3 \
times higher in females than in males beginning in early adolescence. Concordance rates \
are 55 - 60% for identical twins and 20% for fraternal twins and siblings. Risk factors for \
major depressive disorder include neuroticism (negative affectivity), adverse childhood \
experiences, and stressful life events (which may precipitate a major depressive episode). \
The possibility of suicide exists at all times during major depressive episode. \
\
\
\
