\
Other disorders that are commonly comorbid with major depressive disorder include \
substance-related disorders, panic disorder, obsessive-compulsive disorder, anorexia \
nervosa, bulimia nervosa, and borderline personality disorder. \
\
Treatment for Major Depressive Disorder \
\
There are many evidence-based treatments for depression; among the most prominent are \
cognitive therapy, interpersonal therapy, behavior therapy/behavioral activation, and self- \
management/self-control therapy. Behavioral activation has been shown to be just as \
effective as medication in treating depression and more effective than cognitive therapy in \
treating severe depression. \
\
Medications are also frequently used in the treatment of depression. (For a detailed \
discussion of these medications, refer to the Psychopharmacology section.) \
\
Suicide \
\
According to the most recent data from the Centers for Disease Control (2010), suicide is \
the 10th leading cause of death for all people in the U.S. The suicide rate for men is four \
times higher than that of women, although a higher percentage of women report suicidal \
thoughts and women attempt suicide three times as often. \
\
Suicide rates differ among age ranges and ethnic groups. Rates are reported per 100,000. \
A significant shift has recently taken place in that the highest rates of suicide are now found \
among those 45 to 64 years of age (18.63), the next highest rates are found among those \
who are 85 years or older (17.62), with all other age ranges significantly lower (< 15.00). \
The suicide rate is lowest among those 15 - 24 years of age (10.54). \
\
In terms of ethnic groups in the U.S., the suicide rate is highest among Whites (14.13) \
followed by Native Americans (11.00). A much lower and fairly equivalent rate (<6.5) \
occurs among Asians, African Americans, and Hispanics. Overall, suicide rates are highest \
in the western states. \
\
Ninety percent of people who commit suicide have a mental disorder, most often a mood \
disorder, schizophrenia, a personality disorder, or substance use disorder. Expressions of \
hopelessness are a stronger predictor of suicide than the presence and severity of \
depression. \
\
\
 \
\
