\
The single best predictor of completed suicide is a history of serious suicide attempts, with \
the greatest risk occurring within the days and weeks immediately following a \
hospitalization. In addition to a mental disorder and a past suicide attempt, the most \
frequently cited risk factors include being male, being single or living alone, a family \
history of suicide, and chronic pain or chronic illness. \
\
>PERSISTENT DEPRESSIVE DISORDER (DYSTHYMIA) This disorder is \
diagnosed when there is a depressed mood for most of the day, for more days than not, for \
at least 2 years (1 year in children and adolescents). While depressed, the person \
experiences two or more of the following symptoms: change in appetite, insomnia or \
hypersomnia, low energy or fatigue, low self-esteem, poor concentration or difficulty \
making decisions, and feelings of hopelessness. These symptoms cause significant distress \
or impairment in functioning. During the 2-year period the person has not been without \
symptoms for more than 2 months at a time. Criteria for a major depressive episode may \
be continuously present for 2 years. Additionally, there has never been a manic or \
hypomanic episode, and criteria for cyclothymia have not been met. \
\
Specifiers for persistent depressive disorder include: early onset (onset before age 21) or \
late onset (at age 21 or older); severity level of mild, moderate, or severe; and in partial \
remission or in full remission. \
\
For the most recent 2 years of the disorder, the clinician must specify: with pure dysthymic \
syndrome (no MDE), with persistent major depressive episode (full criteria for MDE met \
during preceding 2 years); with intermittent major depressive episode, with current episode \
(current MDE with periods of 8 weeks or more with symptoms below threshold for MDE); \
and with intermittent major depressive episodes, without current episode (no current MDE. \
but one or more MDE in the preceding 2 years). \
\
Additional specifiers include: with anxious distress, with mixed features, with melancholic \
features, with atypical features, with mood-congruent or mood-incongruent psychotic \
features, and with peripartum onset. \
\
Persistent depressive disorder often has an early and insidious onset and, by definition, a \
chronic course. Early onset (e.g., before age 21) is associated with higher likelihood of \
comorbid personality disorders and substance use disorders. \
\
>PREMENSTRUAL DYSPHORIC DISORDER This disorder is diagnosed when in \
the majority of menstrual cycles there are at least five symptoms present in the week before \
the onset of menses, symptoms start to improve within a few days after the onset of menses, \
