                                       Section 9 - DSM-5: Anxiety Disorders \
\
             9.6 ANXIETY DISORDERS \
\
Anxiety disorders typically include both fear and anxiety. Fear is an emotional response to \
a real or perceived emotional threat, and is often associated with increased autonomic \
arousal, escape behaviors (e.g., fight or flight), and even panic attacks. Anxiety is the \
anticipation of a future threat, and is often associated with muscle tension, vigilance in \
anticipation of future danger, and avoidant behaviors. \
\
Many anxiety disorders develop in childhood and tend to persist if untreated. Most occur \
more frequently in females (about 2:1 ratio). The anxiety disorders section is arranged \
developmentally, with disorders sequenced based on typical age of onset. \
\
Panic attacks are discrete period of intense fear or discomfort that develop abruptly and \
reach a peak within ten minutes accompanied by four or more physical and/or cognitive \
symptoms: palpitations or pounding heart, sweating, trembling, sensations of shortness of \
breath, feeling of choking, chest pain, nausea or abdominal distress, feeling dizzy or \
lightheaded, chills or heat sensations, numbing or tingling (paresthesias), derealization or \
depersonalization, fear of losing control or going crazy, and fear of dying. Panic attacks \
may be expected (e.g., a response to a typically feared situation) or unexpected (e.g., \
occurring for no apparent reason). Limited-symptom panic attacks are panic attacks with \
fewer than four symptoms. \
\
In the DSM-5, panic attacks may be used as a specifier for any anxiety disorder as well as \
other mental disorders (e.g., depressive and psychotic disorders). Panic attacks that co- \
occur with another mental disorder are associated with increased symptom severity, higher \
rates of suicidality, and poorer treatment response. \
\
>SEPARATION ANXIETY DISORDER    This disorder is characterized by a \
developmentally inappropriate and excessive anxiety concerning being away from home \
or away from the person(s) to whom the individual is attached. Criteria include three or \
more of the following: distress when separation occurs or is anticipated, worry about harm \
befalling one's major attachment figure(s), worry about getting lost or kidnapped, \
reluctance to go out (e.g., school or work refusal) because of fear of separation, \
reluctance/fear of being alone without the major attachment figure, reluctance/refusal to go \
to sleep without being near one's major attachment figure(s), repeated nightmares about \
separation, and repeated physical complaints when separation occurs or is anticipated. The \
\
\
\
