\
duration of the disturbance must be at least 4 weeks in children and adolescents, and \
typically 6 months or more in adults. Separation anxiety disorder is the most prevalent \
anxiety disorder in children younger than 12 years. \
\
Separation anxiety disorder frequently develops after life stress, especially after a \
significant loss. The most common evidence-based treatment for separation anxiety \
disorder is cognitive-behavioral therapy, often including the parents. Family therapy is \
sometimes used as well. When school refusal is present, this diagnosis should only be \
considered if the school refusal is due to a fear of separation from attachment figures; the \
goal is then to return the child to school as soon as possible. \
\
>SELECTIVE MUTISM Selective mutism involves a consistent failure to speak in \
specific social situations when speaking is expected, in spite of speaking in other situations. \
As a result, this disturbance interferes with educational or occupational achievement, or \
with social communication. A minimum of 1 month's duration is required for the diagnosis. \
Onset is usually before age 5. \
\
The failure to speak in children with selective mutism (SM) is related to fear and anxiety, \
not willfulness or disobedience. Typical psychosocial treatments include some \
combination of behavioral therapy and cognitive therapy. Behavioral therapy usually \
includes desensitization and relaxation protocols, of which guided imagery is sometimes a \
part. \
\
>SPECIFIC PHOBIA A specific phobia involves a marked fear or anxiety caused by \
the presence or anticipation of a specific object or situation. Exposure to the stimulus \
provokes an immediate anxiety response (which may include a panic attack) and the phobic \
situation is either avoided or endured with intense distress. The fear or anxiety is out of \
proportion to the actual danger, and typically lasts for 6 months or more. \
\
Specifiers are based on the phobic stimulus and include: animal, natural environment (e.g., \
heights, storms), blood-injection-injury, situational (e.g., airplanes, elevators), or other \
(e.g., loud sounds, costined characters). It is common for individuals to have multiple \
specific phobias (e.g., 75% of individuals with specific phobias fear more than one \
situation or object), in which case multiple diagnoses are given. \
\
A blood-injection-injury phobia differs from other phobias in that with a blood-injection- \
injury phobia the initial physiological response to the phobic stimulus is an increase in \
heart rate followed by a decrease in heart rate. With other phobias the physiological \
response to the phobic stimulus is a sustained elevated heart rate. \
\
\
 \
\
                                       Section 9-DSM-5: Anxiety Disorders \
\
Individuals with specific phobias are at increased risk for developing other anxiety \
disorders, depressive and bipolar disorders, substance-related disorders, somatic symptom \
and related disorders, or personality disorders (especially dependent personality disorder). \
\
Exposure-based therapies are the treatment of choice for specific phobias. In-vivo exposure \
usually yields the strongest results; massed exposure may result in more robust clinical \
improvements. Therapist-assisted exposure-based procedures (e.g., participant modeling, \
guided mastery) are highly effective. Virtual reality exposure is useful for phobias that may \
be difficult to treat in-vivo (e.g., flying phobia). Systematic desensitization, which involves \
pairing exposure with relaxation, may be preferred by patients who cannot tolerate or who \
are unwilling to try in-vivo exposure. Systematic desensitization is typically an effective \
treatment but requires more time and is less successful at decreasing avoidance. Many \
exposure therapies also include a cognitive component, which can be particularly helpful \
for certain phobias (e.g., claustrophobia, dental phobia). \
\
>SOCIAL ANXIETY DISORDER (SOCIAL PHOBIA) Social anxiety disorder \
involves fear of one or more social situations in which the person is exposed to potential \
scrutiny by others. Examples include social interactions (e.g., conversations), being \
observed (e.g., eating or drinking in front of others), and performing (e.g., giving a speech). \
The person fears his or her behavior will be embarrassing, humiliating, or lead to rejection. \
The fear, anxiety, or avoidance is persistent, typically lasting 6 months or more. If the fear \
is restricted to speaking or performing in public, the specifier performance only should be \
used. \
\
There is strong research support for treating social anxiety disorder with cognitive therapy \
and with behavioral approaches (including exposure and relaxation). Combining cognitive \
and behavior therapies (e.g., CBT) seems to yield the best results. \
\
>PANIC DISORDER Panic disorder is characterized by recurrent unexpected panic \
attacks. At least one of the attacks has been followed by 1 month or more of one or both of \
the following: persistent concern about having additional panic attacks or their \
consequences (e.g., losing control, having a heart attack, going crazy) or a significant \
change in behavior related to the attacks. \
\
Panic attacks and a diagnosis of panic disorder are related to higher rates of suicide, even \
when comorbidity and other risk factors are taken into account. Concordance rates for \
panic disorder are 20% - 30% among monozygotic twins and 0% - 10% for dizygotic twins. \
The prevalence of panic disorder is higher in individuals with other anxiety disorder \
\
\
\
                                       Section 9 - DSM-5: Anxiety Disorders \
\
(especially agoraphobia), major depression, bipolar disorder, and possible alcohol use \
disorder. Panic disorder is comorbid with a number of medical symptoms and conditions \
including dizziness, cardiac arrhythmias, hyperthyroidism, asthma, COPD, and irritable \
bowel syndrome. \
\
Cognitive behavioral therapy is considered the evidence-based treatment of choice for \
panic disorder. Treatment generally includes psychoeducation, cognitive restructuring, in- \
vivo exposure to situations that are avoided or give rise to panic, and interoceptive exposure \
to aversive physiological sensations. Relaxation training or breathing retraining is \
sometimes included as well. A particularly well-known package for treatment of panic \
disorder is Panic Control Treatment (PCT) developed by David Barlow. \
\
>AGORAPHOBIA Agoraphobia involves intense fear or anxiety about two or more \
situations: using public transportation, being in open spaces, being in enclosed spaces, \
standing in line or being in a crowd, or being outside the home. These situations are avoided \
because of thoughts that escape might be difficult (e.g., "can't get out of here") or that help \
might not be available when incapacitating or embarrassing symptoms (e.g., incontinence, \
vomiting, panic-like symptoms) occur. The fear, anxiety, or avoidance is persistent, \
typically lasting for 6 months or more. \
\
The majority of individuals with agoraphobia also have comorbid mental disorders. The \
most common co-occurring diagnoses include other anxiety disorders (e.g., specific \
phobias, panic disorder, social anxiety disorder), depressive disorders, PTSD, and alcohol \
use disorder. \
\
Agoraphobia is typically treated with cognitive behavioral therapy, in a manner largely \
similar to the treatment of panic disorder. \
\
>GENERALIZED ANXIETY DISORDER Generalized anxiety disorder is diagnosed \
when there is excessive anxiety and worry about a number of events or activities, occurring \
more days than not for at least 6 months. The anxiety is associated with three or more of \
the following six symptoms: restlessness, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, irritability, \
muscle tension, and sleep disturbance. Only one symptom is required in children. \
\
The median age of onset for generalized anxiety disorder is 30 years, which is later than \
for all the other anxiety disorders. This disorder is usually chronic, with a fluctuating course \
during which symptoms wax and wane. \
\
\
 \
\
                                       Section 9-DSM-5: Anxiety Disorders \
\
Both behavioral approaches (e.g., relaxation training, scheduled "worry time," pleasurable \
activities, controlled exposure) and cognitive approaches have been shown to be effective \
for generalized anxiety disorder. Some evidence suggests that the combination of both \
(e.g., CBT or Anxiety Management Training) may be superior to either by itself. Anxiety \
Management Training is a combination of relaxation and cognitive restructuring. \
\
>SUBSTANCE/MEDICATION-INDUCED ANXIETY DISORDER Substances that \
can induce an anxiety disorder include: alcohol, caffeine, cannabis, hallucinogens \
(including PCP), inhalants, opioids, sedatives, hypnotics or anxiolytics, and stimulants \
(including cocaine). \
\
>ANXIETY DISORDER DUE TO ANOTHER MEDICAL CONDITION Medical \
conditions that are known to manifest with symptoms of anxiety include endocrine \
disorders (e.g., hyperthyroidism, hypoglycemia), cardiovascular disorders (e.g., congestive \
heart failure, arrhythmia) respiratory illness (e.g., asthma, COPD), metabolic disturbances \
(e.g., vitamin B12 deficiency), and neurological illness (e.g., seizure disorders). \
\
>OTHER SPECIFIED/UNSPECIFIED ANXIETY DISORDER Examples include \
generalized anxiety not occurring more days than not, ataque de nervios (attack of nerves) \
or khyal cap (panic-like attacks, in which there is concern that a windlike substance may \
rise in the body causing damage). \
\
