                         Section 9 - DSM-5: Obsessive Compulsive and Related Disorders \
\
9.7 OBSESSIVE-COMPULSIVE AND RELATED \
                     DISORDERS \
\
The obsessive-compulsive and related disorders section begins with obsessive-compulsive \
disorder (OCD), characterized by obsessions and/or compulsions. It then covers related \
disorders of body dysmorphic disorder and hoarding disorder, characterized by cognitive \
symptoms (e.g., perceived defects in appearance, perceived need to save possessions), and \
trichotillomania and excoriation, characterized by recurrent body-focused repetitive \
behaviors (e.g., hair-pulling and skin-picking). \
\
>OBSESSIVE-COMPULSIVE DISORDER Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) \
involves either obsessions and/or compulsions. Obsessions are described as recurrent \
thoughts (e.g., of contamination), urges (e.g., to stab someone), or images (e.g., of violent \
scenes) that are experienced as intrusive and cause distress or anxiety. The person attempts \
to either ignore or suppress the thoughts or to neutralize them with some other thought or \
action. Compulsions are described as repetitive behaviors (e.g., checking, hand-washing) \
or mental acts (e.g., praying, counting) the person feels driven to perform to cope with an \
obsession or to comply with rigid rules. These behaviors or mental acts are an attempt to \
prevent or reduce distress or prevent some dreaded situation. The obsessions or \
compulsions are time-consuming (e.g., take more than 1 hour per day) or cause significant \
distress or impairment. \
\
Specifiers include: with good or fair insight, with poor insight, and with absent \
insight/delusional beliefs. Additionally, the specifier tic-related is coded if the individual \
has a current or past history of a tic disorder. \
\
Males have an earlier age of onset of OCD than females, with nearly 25% of males having \
