member, or experiencing repeated exposure to aversive details of traumatic events (e.g .. \
first responders, police officers repeatedly exposed to details of child abuse). The four \
characteristic symptoms include: intrusive symptoms (e.g., re-experiencing the trauma \
through dreams, recollections, dissociation/flashbacks), avoidance of stimuli associated \
with the trauma (e.g., avoiding memories, thoughts, or external reminders), negative \
alterations in cognitions and mood (e.g., inability to remember the event, distorted \
cognitions about the event, fear, guilt, shame), and increased arousal (e.g., irritability, \
reckless behavior, hypervigilance). In children 6 years and younger, the three characteristic \
symptoms include: intrusive symptoms, avoidance and/or negative alterations in cognitions \
and mood, and increased arousal. Symptoms must last for more than 1 month. The disorder \
may be specified as with dissociative symptoms (recurrent depersonalization or \
derealization), and with delayed expression if onset of symptoms was at least 6 months \
after the event. \
