         9.9 DISSOCIATIVE DISORDERS \
\
Dissociative disorders involve a disturbance or alteration in the normally integrative \
functions of consciousness, identity, memory, perception, emotion, body representation. \
motor control. and behavior. The disturbance may be experienced as intrusions into \
awareness and behavior (e.g., "positive" dissociative symptoms such as derealization). \
and/or as an inability to access information (e.g., "negative" dissociative symptoms such \
as amnesia). Dissociative disorders frequently occur following a trauma. \
\
>DISSOCIATIVE IDENTITY DISORDER This hallmark of dissociative identity \
disorder is the presence of two or more distinct identities or personalities (which may be \
viewed in some cultures as "possession"). The disruption in identity involves discontinuity \
in sense of self, frequently with accompanying alterations in affect, behavior, \
consciousness, memory, perception, cognition, and/or sensory-motor functioning. There is \
also an inability to recall everyday events, important personal information, and/or traumatic \
events that is too extensive to be explained by forgetfulness. \
\
