   9.11 FEEDING AND EATING DISORDERS \
\
Feeding and eating disorders are characterized by a persistent disturbance of eating \
behavior, leading to altered consumption or absorption of food that significantly impairs \
physical health and/or psychosocial functioning. \
\
>PICA The essential feature of pica is the persistent eating of nonnutritive, nonfood \
substances for a period of at least 1 month. This can include paint, plaster, insects, leaves, \
or soil. \
\
Pica is most commonly seen in young children and occasionally in pregnant women. \
Among individuals with intellectual disability, the prevalence of pica increases with the \
severity of the disorder. This disorder can potentially be fatal. \
\
>RUMINATION DISORDER Rumination disorder involves the repeated regurgitation \
of food for at least 1 month. The regurgitated food may be re-chewed, re-swallowed, or \
spit out. The eating disturbance is not attributable to a medical disorder (e.g., reflux). \
\
Complications may include weight loss, failure to make weight gains, or malnutrition. Age \
of onset is usually between 3 and 12 months. Neglect, stressful life situations, and parent- \
child problems may be predisposing factors for rumination disorder. \
\
>AVOIDANT/RESTRICTIVE FOOD INTAKE DISORDER    This disorder is \
characterized by a failure to eat adequately with one or more of the following: significant \
weight loss or failure to achieve expected weight gain, significant nutritional deficiency, \
dependence on a feeding tube or oral nutritional supplements, or marked interference with \
psychosocial functioning. This diagnosis is only made when there is no medical condition \
that accounts for the symptoms. Avoidant/restrictive food intake disorder is associated with \
the "failure-to-thrive" syndrome. \
\
>ANOREXIA NERVOSA Anorexia nervosa is characterized by a restriction of food \
intake, leading to a significantly low body weight. There is intense fear of gaining weight \
or behavior that interferes with weight gain. Additionally, there must be distortions in self- \
image, undue influence given to body weight or shape in self-evaluation, or a denial of the \
seriousness of the problem. \
\
\
