\
Two subtypes are specified: restricting type and binge-eating/purging type. Additional \
specifiers include: in partial remission or in full remission. Current severity is also \
specified as: mild (BMI of 17+), moderate (BMI 16 - 16.99), severe (BMI 15 - 15.99), or \
extreme (BMI < 15). \
\
Anorexia nervosa typically begins during adolescence or young adulthood. Earlier age of \
onset is associated with shorter duration of illness. Anorexia nervosa is far more common \
in females than males, with a female-to-male ratio of 10:1. Anorexia nervosa is associated \
with cultures, settings, occupations, and avocations that encourage thinness (e.g., \
modeling, elite athletics). Suicide risk is increased in individuals with anorexia nervosa. \
Bipolar, depressive, and anxiety disorders commonly co-occur with anorexia nervosa; \
alcohol use disorder and other substance use disorders may also be comorbid. \
\
Treatment for anorexia nervosa generally requires a multi-disciplinary approach, including \
physicians, nutritionists, and mental health professionals. Overall, family treatment is the \
most well-established treatment strategy. Although structural family therapy is possibly the \
most well-known approach, a variety of family therapies have been shown to be effective. \
Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) for anorexia nervosa also has modest research support. \
\
