 incontinence and without constipation and overflow incontinence. \
\
 Encopresis is characterized as either primary (in which the person has never established \
 continence) or secondary (in which the problem develops after a period of continence). \
\
 At this time, there are no evidence-based treatments for encopresis. Medical management \
 is often used successfully when constipation is the underlying problem. When encopresis \
 is clearly deliberate, features of oppositional-defiant and/or conduct disorder may also be \
 present. Treatment typically involves a behavioral approach in order to promote \
