                                     Section 9 - DSM-5: Sleep-Wake Disorders \
\
         9.13 SLEEP-WAKE DISORDERS \
\
Individuals with sleep-wake disorders typically complain of dissatisfaction with the \
quality, timing, and amount of sleep, resulting in daytime distress and impairment. Sleep- \
wake disorders include difficulties getting enough sleep, problems with excessive \
sleepiness in spite of sleeping adequate hours, sleep intrusion (e.g., narcolepsy), breathing- \
related sleep disorders, and parasomnias (e.g., abnormal behavior or physiological events \
occurring in association with sleep). \
\
>INSOMNIA DISORDER The hallmark of this disorder is a predominant complaint of \
dissatisfaction with sleep quality or quantity, associated with one or more of the following: \
difficulty initiating sleep, difficulty maintaining sleep (e.g., frequent awakening), or early- \
morning awakening with inability to go back to sleep. The difficulty occurs at least 3 nights \
each week for at least 3 months. \
\
Specifiers include: with non-sleep disorder mental comorbidity (e.g., depression, substance \
use disorder), with other medical comorbidity (e.g., COPD), and with other sleep disorder. \
\
Additional specifiers include: episodic (symptoms last at least 1 month but less than 3 \
months), persistent (symptoms last 3 months or longer), and recurrent (two or more \
episodes within 1 year). \
\
While CBT is regarded as one of the most effective treatments for insomnia, some of CBT's \
component techniques are also used independently to successfully treat insomnia. \
including sleep restriction therapy, stimulus control therapy, and relaxation training. \
\
>HYPERSOMNOLENCE DISORDER Hypersomnolence disorder is characterized by \
excessive sleepiness in spite of sleeping at least 7 hours, with at least one of the following: \
recurrent daytime sleep episodes, prolonged sleep for more than 9 hours that is \
nonrestorative, or difficulty being fully awake after abrupt awakening. The \
hypersomnolence occurs at least 3 times a week for at least 3 months. \
\
Specifiers include: with mental comorbidity, with medical condition, and with another \
sleep disorder. Additional specifiers include: acute, subacute, and persistent. Severity is \
also specified based on the frequency of difficulty maintaining daytime alertness: mild, \
moderate, and severe. \
\
\
\
                                     Section 9-DSM-5; Sleep-Wake Disorders \
\
>NARCOLEPSY The hallmark of narcolepsy is recurrent periods of an irresistible need \
to sleep, lapsing into sleep, or napping occurring within a given day, at least three times \
per week, for at least a 3-month duration. The disorder also involves at least one of the \
following: cataplexy (either brief episodes of sudden bilateral loss of muscle tone, typically \
precipitated by laughter or joking, or grimaces or jaw-opening with tongue thrusting, \
without obvious emotional triggers), hypocretin deficiency, or REM indicators (e.g., REM \
sleep latency less than or equal to 15 minutes). Severity is specified as: mild, moderate, or \
severe. \
\
Individuals with narcolepsy commonly experience recurrent intrusions of REM sleep into \
the transition between sleep and wakefulness. These intrusions manifest as hypnagogic \
hallucinations at the onset of sleep, as hypnopompic hallucinations on awakening, or as \
sleep paralysis at the beginning or end of sleep episodes. \
\
>BREATHING-RELATED SLEEP DISORDERS    The breathing-related sleep \
disorders include three distinct disorders: obstructive sleep apnea hypopnea (characterized \
by snoring, snorting/gasping, or breathing pauses during sleep), central sleep apnea (no \
evidence of obstruction), and sleep-related hypoventilation (decreased respiration \
associated with elevated CO2 levels). Obstructive sleep apnea hypopnea is the most \
common. Apnea refers to a temporary cessation of breathing, while hypopnea is \
abnormally slow or shallow breathing. \
\
>CIRCADIAN RHYTHM SLEEP-WAKE DISORDER This disorder is characterized \
by a recurrent pattern of sleep disruption caused by an alteration of the circadian system, \
or by a mismatch in the sleep-wake schedule required by the person's environment (e.g., \
work or social obligations) and the person's own circadian sleep-wake cycle. This \
mismatch results in insomnia or excessive sleepiness. \
\
Specifiers for this disorder include: delayed sleep phase type, advanced sleep phase type, \
irregular sleep-wake type, non-24-hour sleep-wake type, shift work type, and unspecified \
type. Additional specifiers include: episodic, persistent, or recurrent. \
\
