                                     Section 9-DSM-5: Sexual Dysfunctions \
\
          9.14 SEXUAL DYSFUNCTIONS \
\
Sexual dysfunctions are a heterogeneous group of disorders characterized by a disturbance \
in sexual response or sexual experience of pleasure. \
\
Specifiers include: lifelong (the disturbance has been present since the individual became \
sexually active) or acquired (the disturbance began after a period of normal sexual \
functioning); and generalized (occurs with all types of stimulation, situations, or partners) \
or situational (occurs only with certain types of stimulation, situations, or partners). \
Current severity is also coded based on distress over the symptoms: mild, moderate, or \
severe. \
\
>DELAYED EJACULATION Delayed ejaculation involves either marked delay in \
ejaculation or marked infrequency or absence of ejaculation, occurring on almost all or all \
occasions (75% - 100% of the time). The symptoms have persisted for a minimum of 6 \
months. \
\
>ERECTILE DISORDER Erectile disorder involves either the inability to achieve an \
erection, difficulty maintaining an erection, or decrease in erectile rigidity, occurring on \
almost all or all occasions (75% - 100% of the time). The symptoms have persisted for a \
minimum of 6 months. \
\
>FEMALE ORGASMIC DISORDER Female orgasmic disorder involves either marked \
delay, infrequency, or absence of orgasm, or reduced intensity of sensations of orgasm. \
occurring on almost all or all occasions (75% - 100% of the time). The symptoms have \
persisted for a minimum of 6 months. \
\
>FEMALE   SEXUAL INTEREST/AROUSAL   DISORDER   Female sexual \
interest/arousal disorder involves lack of or reduced sexual interest/arousal as evidenced \
by at least three of the following: absent/reduced sexual interest, absent/reduced sexual \
thoughts or fantasies, lack of or reduced initiation of sexual activity and lack of receptivity \
to partner's initiation, absent/reduced sexual pleasure (75% - 100% of the time), \
absent/reduced interest/arousal in response to internal or external sexual cues (e.g., verbal, \
visual), and absent/reduced sensations during sexual activity (75% - 100% of the time). \
The symptoms have persisted for a minimum of 6 months. \
\
\
\
                                      Section 9 - DSM-5: Sexual Dysfunctions \
\
>GENITO-PELVIC PAIN/PENETRATION DISORDER     This disorder is \
characterized by recurrent difficulties with one or more of the following: penetration during \
intercourse; pain during intercourse or penetration attempts; fear or anxiety about pain \
before, during, or after intercourse; tensing or tightening of the pelvis during attempted \
penetration. The symptoms have persisted for a minimum of 6 months. \
\
>MALE HYPOACTIVE SEXUAL DESIRE DISORDER   Male hypoactive sexual \
desire disorder is characterized by a deficiency or absence of sexual thoughts or fantasies \
and desire for sexual activity. The symptoms have persisted for a minimum of 6 months. \
\
>PREMATURE (EARLY) EJACULATION This disorder is characterized by recurrent \
ejaculation during partnered sexual activity within approximately 1 minute following \
penetration and before the person wishes it, occurring on almost all or all occasions (75% \
- 100% of the time). The symptoms have persisted for a minimum of 6 months. \
\
Treatment for premature ejaculation includes the squeeze and stop-start techniques, \
originally developed by Masters and Johnson. Additionally, the female superior position is \
recommended. Effective pharmacologic therapy includes SSRI antidepressants (e.g., \
sertraline, paroxetine, fluoxetine) and topical desensitizing agents (e.g., lidocaine). \
\
>SUBSTANCE/MEDICATION-INDUCED SEXUAL DYSFUNCTION Substances \
that can induce sexual dysfunction include alcohol, opioids, sedatives, hypnotics or \
anxiolytics, and stimulants (including cocaine). \
\
>OTHER SPECIFIED/UNSPECIFIED SEXUAL DYSFUNCTION An example is \
sexual aversion. \
