                                       Section 9 - DSM-5: Gender Dysphoria \
\
            9.15 GENDER DYSPHORIA \
\
This section includes one diagnosis for gender dysphoria, with separate criteria sets for \
children and for adolescents/adults. \
\
>GENDER DYSPHORIA   Gender dysphoria in children is characterized by a marked \
incongruence between one's assigned gender and the gender experienced or expressed, of \
at least 6 months duration, manifest by at least six of the following (the first criterion is \
required): a strong desire to be of the other gender or insistence that one is the other gender; \
a strong preference for cross-dressing; a strong preference for cross-gender roles in play; a \
strong preference for activities, toys, or games that are stereotypically of the other gender; \
a strong preference for playmates of the other gender; a rejection of toys, games, and \
activities that are stereotypically of the same gender; a strong dislike of one's sexual \
anatomy; and a strong desire for sex characteristics of the opposite gender. \
\
Gender dysphoria in adolescents and adults is characterized by a marked incongruence \
between one's assigned gender and the gender experienced or expressed, of at least 6 \
months duration, manifest by at least two of the following: a marked incongruence between \
one's experienced/expressed gender and one's sex characteristics; a strong desire to be rid \
of one's sex characteristics; a strong desire for the sex characteristics of the other gender; \
a strong desire to be of the other gender; a strong desire to be treated as the other gender; a \
strong conviction that one has the feelings and reactions that are typical of the other gender. \
\
The specifier posttransition is coded if the person is living as the other gender and has \
undergone (or is preparing to undergo) at least one cross-sex medical procedure or \
treatment regimen (e.g., surgery or cross-sex hormone treatment). \
\
Gender dysphoria is diagnosed more commonly in natal males (i.e., those assigned to the \
male gender at birth), with the male to female ratio being around 2:1 or 3:1. The onset of \
gender dysphoria among children is commonly between the ages of 2 and 4, and rates of \
persistence of gender dysphoria into adolescence or adulthood range from 2% to 50%. \
Late-onset gender dysphoria occurs around puberty or much later in life; while it occurs \
with natal males, late-onset gender dysphoria is extremely rare in natal females. \
\
