rules are violated. At least three criteria must be present in the past 12 months, and at least \
one criterion in the past 6 months from any of the four categories: aggression to people \
and animals as evidenced by bullying and threatening others, initiating physical fights, use \
of a weapon, physical cruelty to people, physical cruelty to animals, stealing while \
confronting a victim (e.g., mugging, armed robbery), forcing someone into sexual activity; \
destruction of property as evidenced by deliberate fire setting, deliberate destruction of \
property; deceitfulness or theft as evidenced by breaking into someone's house or car, lying \
to obtain favors, stealing without confronting a victim (e.g., shoplifting, forgery); or serious \
violation of rules as evidenced by staying out late, running away from home, or being truant \
from school. If the person is 18 or older, criteria are not met for antisocial personality \
disorder. \
\
Specifiers for conduct disorder include: childhood-onset type (prior to age 10), adolescent- \
onset type (after age 10), or unspecified type. Severity is specified as: mild, moderate, or \
severe. Additionally, the specifier with limited prosocial emotions is coded when two or \
more characteristics are persistent over 12 months: lack of guilt or remorse, callous (lack \
of empathy), unconcerned about performance, or shallow or deficient affect. \
\
Associated features of conduct disorder include the tendency to misperceive others" \
intentions as hostile or threatening and thereby feeling justified in responding aggressively. \
Poor frustration tolerance, irritability, temper outbursts, and recklessness are frequently \
seen. Conduct disorder is often associated with precocious sexual behavior, drinking, \
smoking, use of illegal substances, and risk-taking. Suicide attempts and completions occur \
at higher than average rates. ADHD and oppositional defiant disorder are both common in \
individuals with conduct disorder. Other concomitant diagnoses may include specific \
learning disorder, anxiety disorders, depressive or bipolar disorders, and substance-related \
disorders. \
\
Poor prognosis is associated with early onset. The symptoms of conduct disorder remit by \
adulthood in the majority of people with this diagnosis, although a substantial number of \
people with conduct disorder continue to exhibit symptoms that meet the criteria for \
antisocial personality disorder in adulthood. \
\
Predisposing factors to the development of conduct disorder include: difficult infant \
temperament, parental rejection and neglect, inconsistent child-rearing with harsh \
discipline, physical or sexual abuse, lack of supervision, change in caregivers or \
institutional living, large family size, and association with a delinquent peer group. \
\
\
