                          Section 9 - DSM-5: Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders \
\
        9.17 SUBSTANCE-RELATED AND \
             ADDICTIVE DISORDERS \
\
This section includes substance-related disorders as well as gambling disorder. Substance- \
related disorders include 10 classes of drugs: alcohol; caffeine; cannabis; hallucinogens \
(e.g., LSD, other hallucinogens); inhalants; opioids; sedatives, hypnotics, and anxiolytics; \
stimulants (e.g., amphetamine, cocaine); tobacco; and other/unknown substances. All \
drugs taken in excess activate the brain's reward system, which is involved in \
reinforcement of behaviors and production of memories. As a result, normal activities may \
be neglected. Individuals with lower levels of self-control, possibly reflecting impairment \
in the brain's inhibitory mechanisms, may be predisposed to develop substance use \
disorders. In addition to substance-related disorders, this section also includes gambling \
disorder, reflecting research that gambling behaviors activate reward systems similar to \
those activated by drugs of abuse. \
\
Substance-related disorders are divided into two groups: substance use disorders and \
substance-induced disorders. Substance-induced disorders include intoxication, \
withdrawal, and other substance/medication-induced mental disorders (e.g., psychotic \
disorders, bipolar and depressive disorders, anxiety disorders, sleep disorders, sexual \
disorders, etc.). The criteria for substance/medication-induced mental disorders are \
included in the relevant mental disorder section (e.g., psychotic disorders). \
\
Substance Use Disorders \
\
The essential feature of a substance use disorder is a cluster of cognitive, behavioral, and \
physiological symptoms that indicate continued use despite adverse substance-related \
consequences. A substance use disorder can occur with all substances except caffeine. \
\
Criteria for the substance use disorders include a problematic pattern of use leading to \
significant impairment or distress, as manifest by at least two of the following within a 12- \
month period: the substance is consumed in larger amounts or over a longer period of time \
than was intended; a persistent desire or unsuccessful attempts to cut down on the \
substance; a lot of time spent in activities trying to get the substance, use the substance, or \
recover from its effects; cravings for the substance; substance use results in failure to meet \
major role obligations at home, school, or work; continued use despite recurrent social or \
interpersonal problem: important recreational, social, or occupational activities are \
curtailed; recurrent use in situations that are physically dangerous; substance use is \
