\
continued in spite of awareness of physical or psychological problems caused or \
exacerbated by the substance; tolerance (either a need for increased amounts to achieve the \
desired effects or diminished effect with continued use of the same amount); or withdrawal \
(either characteristic withdrawal symptoms of the substance or the substance is taken to \
relieve or avoid withdrawal). These diagnostic criteria represent four groupings: impaired \
control with regard to the substance, social impairment, risky use, and pharmacological \
criteria. \
\
Current severity of any substance use disorder is specified based on the number of \
symptom criteria endorsed: mild (two or three symptoms), moderate (four or five \
symptoms), and severe (six or more symptoms). \
\
Specifiers for the substance use disorders also include: in early remission (none of the \
criteria, except cravings, have been met for at least 3 months but less than 12 months), in \
sustained remission (none of the criteria, except cravings, have been met for 12 months or \
longer), and in a controlled environment (the person is in an environment where access to \
the substance is restricted). \
\
Substance-Induced Disorders \
\
Substance Intoxication - The essential feature of substance intoxication is the development \
of a reversible, substance specific syndrome due to the recent ingestion of a substance. \
Substance intoxication typically involves disturbances in perception, wakefulness, \
attention, thinking, judgment, psychomotor behavior, and interpersonal behavior, \
attributable to the physiological effects of the substance on the central nervous system. \
Substance intoxication can occur with all substances except tobacco. \
\
Substance Withdrawal - The hallmark of substance withdrawal is the development of \
substance-specific behavioral change, with physical and cognitive elements, due to either \
stopping or reducing the use of a substance (typically use has been heavy and prolonged). \
The syndrome causes distress and/or impairment in social, work, or other areas of \
functioning. Substance withdrawal can occur with all substances except hallucinogens and \
inhalants. \
\
Substance/Medication-Induced Mental Disorders - These disorders may be induced by any \
of the 10 classes of substances that produce substance use disorders or by medications used \
in medical treatment. Each substance/medication induced mental disorder is described in \
the relevant section (e.g., depressive disorders, sleep-wake disorder). \
\
