I. ALCOHOL-RELATED DISORDERS \
\
>ALCOHOL USE DISORDER Alcohol use disorder occurs when the individual's use \
of alcohol meets the criteria for a substance use disorder. \
\
>ALCOHOL INTOXICATION Alcohol intoxication is characterized by behavioral or \
psychological changes (e.g., aggressive behavior, mood lability, and impaired judgment) \
and one or more of the following: slurred speech, incoordination, unsteady gait, nystagmus, \
impaired memory and concentration, as well as possible stupor or coma. \
\
>ALCOHOL WITHDRAWAL Alcohol withdrawal is characterized by two or more of \
the following: autonomic hyperactivity (e.g., sweating, pulse > 100), hand tremor, \
insomnia, nausea or vomiting, transient hallucinations or illusions, anxiety, psychomotor \
agitation, and seizures. Alcohol withdrawal can potentially be fatal. \
\
>OTHER ALCOHOL-INDUCED DISORDERS Other alcohol-induced disorders may \
include a psychotic disorder, bipolar disorder, depressive disorder, anxiety disorder, sleep- \
wake disorder, sexual dysfunction, neurocognitive disorder, as well as intoxication and \
withdrawal delirium. \
\
II. CAFFEINE-RELATED DISORDERS \
\
>CAFFEINE INTOXICATION Caffeine intoxication is characterized by five or more \
of the following: restlessness, nervousness, insomnia, flushed face, diuresis (excessive \
urination), gastrointestinal disturbance, muscle twitching, rambling speech, agitation. \
periods of inexhaustibility, and tachycardia. While symptoms of caffeine intoxication may \
mimic an anxiety disorder, caffeine intoxication can be differentiated by diuresis. \
\
>CAFFEINE WITHDRAWAL    Caffeine withdrawal involves three or more of the \
following: headache, fatigue/drowsiness, dysphoric mood or irritability, difficulty \
concentrating, and flu-like symptoms (nausea, vomiting, muscle pain). \
\
>OTHER CAFFEINE-INDUCED DISORDERS Other caffeine-induced disorders may \
include an anxiety disorder or a sleep-wake disorder. \
\
III. CANNABIS-RELATED DISORDERS \
\
>CANNABIS USE DISORDER Cannabis (or marijuana) use disorder occurs when the \
individual's use of cannabis meets the criteria for a substance use disorder. \
\
\
\
                          Section 9 - DSM-5: Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders \
\
>CANNABIS INTOXICATION Cannabis intoxication is characterized by behavioral or \
psychological changes (e.g., impaired motor coordination, euphoria, anxiety, sensation of \
slowed time, impaired judgment) and two or more of the following: conjunctival injection \
(redness in the white part of the eye), increased appetite, dry mouth, and tachycardia. \
\
>CANNABIS WITHDRAWAL Cannabis withdrawal is characterized by three or more \
of the following: irritability or aggression, nervousness or anxiety, sleep difficulty, \
decreased appetite or weight loss, restlessness, depressed mood, physical symptoms (e.g., \
abdominal pain, tremors, sweating, fever, chills, headache). \
\
>OTHER CANNABIS-INDUCED DISORDERS   Other cannabis-induced disorders \
may include a psychotic disorder, anxiety disorder, sleep-wake disorder, as well as an \
intoxication delirium. \
\
IV. HALLUCINOGEN-RELATED DISORDERS \
\
>PHENCYCLIDINE (PCP) USE DISORDER PCP use disorder occurs when the \
individual's use of phencyclidine meets the criteria for a substance use disorder. \
\
>OTHER HALLUCINOGEN USE DISORDER    Other hallucinogen use disorder \
occurs when the individual's use of a hallucinogen other than PCP (e.g., LSD, peyote, \
psilocybin) meets the criteria for a substance use disorder. \
\
>PHENCYCLIDINE (PCP) INTOXICATION PCP intoxication is characterized by \
behavior changes (e.g., belligerence, assaultiveness, impulsiveness, impaired judgment), \
and two or more of the following: nystagmus, hypertension or tachycardia, diminished \
response to pain, ataxia, dysarthria, muscle rigidity, seizures or coma, and hyperacusis \
(oversensitivity to sound). \
\
>OTHER HALLUCINOGEN INTOXICATION Other hallucinogen intoxication is \
characterized by behavioral or psychological changes (e.g., anxiety or depression, ideas of \
reference, paranoid ideation, impaired judgment, fear of losing one's mind) and perceptual \
changes (e.g., illusions, depersonalization, hallucinations), and two or more of the \
following: sweating, tachycardia, palpitations, pupillary dilation, tremors, blurred vision, \
