      9.18 NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDERS \
\
Neurocognitive disorders (NCDs) include delirium, as well as major NCDs, mild NCDs, \
and their subtypes (e.g., due to Alzheimer's disease, due to traumatic brain injury). The \
primary clinical deficit in NCDs is in cognitive function, and the disorders are acquired \
rather than developmental. The impaired cognition has not been present since birth nor in \
early life, and represents a decline from a prior level of functioning. \
\
For many of the NCDs the underlying pathology and etiology can be determined. The term \
dementia is subsumed under major neurocognitive disorder. While dementia is still used \
for disorders involving degenerative processes typically in older adults (e.g., Alzheimer's), \
neurocognitive disorder is preferred for conditions affecting younger persons (e.g., \
impairment secondary to brain injury or HIV infection). The major NCD definition is also \
broader in that individuals with a decline in a single domain can receive the diagnosis (e.g., \
what used to be an amnestic disorder is now a major NCD). Less severe levels of cognitive \
impairment are diagnosed as mild neurocognitive impairment. \
\
The criteria for the various NCDs are all based on six defined cognitive domains: complex \
attention (sustained attention, divided attention, processing speed); executive function \
(planning, decision-making, responding to feedback, mental flexibility); learning and \
memory (immediate memory, recent memory, remote memory); expressive and receptive \
language (naming, word finding, grammar, comprehension); perceptual-motor (visual \
perception, visuo-constructional, perceptual-motor, praxis, gnosis); and social cognition \
(recognition of emotions, theory of mind). \
\
The specifiers for both major and minor NCD include whether they are due to: Alzheimer's \
disease, frontotemporal lobar degeneration, Lewy body disease, vascular disease, \
traumatic brain injury, substance/medication use, HIV infection, prion disease (e.g., \
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease), Parkinson's disease, Huntington's disease, another medical \
condition, multiple etiologies, or unspecified. \
\
>DELIRIUM The hallmark of delirium is a disturbance in attention and awareness (e.g., \
reduced orientation to the environment). The onset is rapid (hours to days) and the course \
tends to be fluctuating. Additionally, delirium includes a cognitive disturbance (e.g., \
memory problems, disorientation, language difficulties, visuospatial abilities, or perceptual \
disturbance). Specifiers include: substance intoxication delirium, substance withdrawal \
\
\
\
                                   Section 9 - DSM-5: Neurocognitive Disorders \
\
delirium, medication-induced delirium, delirium due to another medical condition, and \
delirium due to multiple etiologies. \
\
Common causes of delirium include infections, metabolic disorders (e.g., hypoglycemia, \
renal disease), post-operative states, and substance intoxication or withdrawal. The \
majority of individuals with delirium recover fully, with or without treatment; nevertheless, \
early intervention shortens the duration of the delirium. Untreated, delirium may progress \
to coma, seizures, or death \
\
>MAJOR NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER Major neurocognitive disorder (NCD) is \
diagnosed when there is significant cognitive decline from a prior level of functioning in \
one or more domains (complex attention, executive function, learning and memory, \
language, perceptual-motor, or social cognition). The decline is noted by the individual, a \
knowledgeable person, or the clinician, and documented by standardized testing or \
quantified clinical assessment. The cognitive deficits interfere with independent \
functioning in everyday activities. \
\
>MILD NEUROCOGNITIVE DISORDER   Mild neurocognitive disorder (NCD) is \
diagnosed when there is modest cognitive decline from a prior level of functioning in one \
or more domains (complex attention, executive function, learning and memory, language, \
perceptual-motor, or social cognition). The decline is noted by the individual, a \
knowledgeable person, or the clinician, and documented by standardized testing or \
quantified clinical assessment. The cognitive deficits do not interfere with independent \
functioning in everyday activities. \
\
The DSM-5 includes some additional features for neurocognitive disorders due to specific \
etiologies. \
\
Due to Alzheimer's disease - insidious onset and gradual progression of impairment; either \
evidence of a causative Alzheimer's disease genetic mutation or clear evidence of a decline \
in memory, learning, and at least one other cognitive domain; no extended plateaus; no \
evidence of mixed etiology. \
\
Due to frontotemporal disorder - insidious onset and gradual progression of impairment; \
either behavioral variant (e.g., behavioral inhibition, apathy, perseverative behaviors, \
hyperorality) with decline in social cognition and/or executive functioning, or language \
variant (e.g., prominent decline in speech production, word finding, grammar, or \
comprehension); relative sparing of learning, memory and perceptual-motor function. \
\
\
 \
\
                                  Section 9- DSM-5: Neurocognitive Disorders \
\
With Lewy bodies - insidious onset and gradual progression of impairment; several of the \
following: fluctuating cognition with variations in attention/alertness, visual \
hallucinations, parkinsonism, REM sleep behavior disorder, and severe neuroleptic \
sensitivity. \
\
Due to vascular disease - a stepwise pattern of deterioration and a patchy distribution of \
deficits; evidence of cerebrovascular disease; decline is prominent in complex attention \
and frontal-executive functions. \
\
Due to traumatic brain injury - evidence of a traumatic brain injury; one or more of the \
following: loss of consciousness, posttraumatic amnesia, disorientation and confusion. \
neurological signs (e.g., seizures, hemiparesis); persists past the acute post-injury period. \
\
Substance/medication induced - the impairments persist beyond intoxication and \
withdrawal; the substance can produce neurocognitive impairment (e.g., alcohol, \
inhalants); for alcohol, the subtype amnestic-confabulatory is coded when appropriate \
[Korsakoff's syndrome, caused by a chronic thiamin deficiency secondary to alcohol use, \
results in anterograde amnesia and confabulation.] \
\
Due to HIV infection - criteria are met for major or minor NCD and there is documented \
infection with HIV; the NCD is not attributable to another medical condition. \
\
Due to prion disease - insidious onset and rapid progression of impairment; there are motor \
features of prion disease such as myoclonus (jerky muscle contractions) or ataxia, or \
biomarker evidence. [Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD), the most common prion disease, \
typically progresses very rapidly to major impairment over several months.] \
\
Due to Parkinson's disease - insidious onset and gradual progression of impairment: \
occurs in the context of a diagnosed Parkinson's disease. \
\
Due to Huntington's disease - insidious onset and gradual progression of impairment; \
occurs in the context of a diagnosed Huntington's disease, or risk for Huntington's disease \
(as cognitive abnormalities can predate motor symptoms by 15 years). \
