        9.19 PERSONALITY DISORDERS \
\
A personality disorder is defined in the DSM-5 as "an enduring pattern of inner experience \
and behavior that deviates markedly from the expectations of an individual's culture, is \
pervasive and inflexible, has an onset in adolescence or early adulthood, is stable over time, \
and leads to distress or impairment" (p. 645). Symptoms are evident in at least two areas: \
cognition (e.g., perceptions of self, others, events), affect (e.g., range, lability, \
appropriateness of emotional response), interpersonal functioning, or impulse control. A \
diagnosis of personality disorder can be made in persons under age 18 if the features of the \
personality disorder have been present for at least 1 year (with the exception of antisocial \
personality disorder, which cannot be diagnosed in persons under age 18). \
\
The DSM-5 delineates ten personality disorders and divides them into three clusters. \
Cluster A disorders involve odd or eccentric presentation, and include paranoid, schizoid, \
and schizotypal personality disorders. Cluster B disorders involve dramatic, emotional, and \
erratic behavior and include antisocial, borderline, histrionic, and narcissistic personality \
disorders. Cluster C disorders involve an anxious or fearful presentation and include \
avoidant, dependent, and obsessive-compulsive personality disorders. \
\
Cluster A Personality Disorders: Odd and Eccentric \
\
>PARANOID PERSONALITY DISORDER The hallmark of paranoid personality \
disorder is a pervasive distrust and suspiciousness of others and tendency to interpret \
actions of others as deliberately demeaning, threatening, and malevolent, as evidenced by \
four or more of the following: suspects that others are exploiting, harming, or deceiving \
him or her; is preoccupied with doubts about trustworthiness of others; is reluctant to \
confide in others because of concerns that the information will be used against him or her; \
interprets benign comments/events as demeaning or threatening; bears grudges; perceives \
attacks on his or her character, and responds with anger or counterattacks; believes his or \
her partner is unfaithful. \
\
>SCHIZOID PERSONALITY DISORDER    Schizoid personality disorder is \
characterized by a pattern of detachment from and indifference to social relationships and \
a restricted range of emotions, as evidenced by four or more of the following: neither \
desires nor enjoys close relationships (including familial); usually chooses solitary \
activities; has minimal interest in sexual experiences; experiences little pleasure in \
