          9.20 PARAPHILIC DISORDERS \
\
Paraphilias are intense and persistent sexual urges, fantasies, or behaviors that involve \
nonhuman objects, the suffering or humiliation of oneself or one's partner, or children or \
other non-consenting persons. A paraphilic disorder is a paraphilia that causes distress or \
impairment to the individual, or whose satisfaction involves personal harm or risk of harm \
to others. \
\
The specifier in a controlled environment is used when individuals are living in an \
institutional setting where opportunities to engage in the paraphilia is limited. The specifier \
in full remission applies to a situation in which the person has not acted on the urges and \
there has not been distress or impairment in functioning for at least 5 years, while in an \
uncontrolled environment. \
\
With the exception of sexual masochism, paraphilie disorders occur almost exclusively in \
men. \
\
>VOYEURISTIC DISORDER Diagnostic criteria for voyeuristic disorder include \
fantasies, urges, or behavior that involve observing an unsuspecting person who is naked. \
disrobing, or engaging in sexual activity, over a period of at least 6 months. The individual \
is at least 18 years of age. \
\
>EXHIBITIONISTIC DISORDER Exhibitionistic disorder involves fantasies, urges, or \
behavior that involve exposing one's genitals to a stranger, over a period of at least 6 \
months. \
\
>FROTTEURISTIC DISORDER Frotteuristic disorder involves fantasies, urges, or \
behavior that involve rubbing or touching a non-consenting person, over a period of at least \
6 months. \
\
>SEXUAL MASOCHISM DISORDER The hallmark of sexual masochism disorder is \
fantasies, urges, or behavior involving the act of being humiliated, beaten, bound, or made \
to suffer, over a period of at least 6 months. \
\
