            SECTION 10: MEMORY \
\
This section describes the stages of memory, a classification system for memory, the \
biology of memory, forgetting, and strategies for enhancing memory. \
\
            10.1 STAGES OF MEMORY \
\
Researchers have identified at least three distinct stages of memory: sensory memory, \
short-term memory, and long-term memory. \
\
I. SENSORY MEMORY \
\
Sensory memory involves transforming sensory input into the type of data that can be \
understood and storing the information as a visual or auditory image. The information in \
sensory memory is temporary, with visual images (iconic memory) lasting about a 1/2 \
second, and sounds (echoic memory) lasting up to four seconds. \
\
While we are frequently bombarded with much simultaneous visual and auditory \
information (e.g., at a party), only information that is attended to, by a process of selective \
attention, can pass into short-term memory (STM). Selective attention can be either \
deliberate or automatic, and in the absence of deliberately focused attention, our nervous \
systems automatically make some choices for us. Overall, stimuli that are more likely to \
be automatically attended to include those that are either novel or relate to satisfying basic \
needs. \
\
II. SHORT-TERM MEMORY (STM) \
\
Short-term memory works to process ongoing information and to store memories for a \
short duration of up to 30 seconds. Short-term memory is divided into two components, \
primary memory and working memory. \
\
>PRIMARY MEMORY Primary memory is a passive "holding tank" for small amounts \
of information requiring no manipulation (e.g., remember five digits in sequence). \
\
\
 \
\
                                     Section 10- Memory: Stages of Memory \
\
>WORKING MEMORY    Working memory not only holds information, but also \
manipulates it (e.g., repeating the five digits in reverse order). \
\
Rehearsing is the deliberate repetition, usually acoustic, of information to enhance our \
short-term memory for it, or to enhance its transfer into long-term memory. In fact, \
laboratory studies have shown that when interference tasks that prevent rehearsal are \
introduced, the contents of short-term memory are lost. \
\
The capacity for short-term memory is very limited, generally seven items, plus or minus \
two. Thus, the average person will remember 5 to 9 items from a list of unrelated items \
(e.g., digits, or names). Chunking involves transforming separate items into meaningful \
units and thereby increases the ability to remember the items. For example, whereas a \
random list of numbers 1-7-7-6-1-9-4-5-1-9-9-6 consists of twelve separate meaningful \
units (i.e., bits of information) and would tax most people's memory, the list 1776-1945- \
1996 is only three chunks and could be easily memorized. \
\
We appear to have a dual coding system for processing short-term memory information, \
including both verbal and visual channels. We use the visual system, for example, when \
we look at a flower, and later remember what the flower looked like in the form of a picture. \
We use a verbal system for processing words that are either seen or heard. The word \
"flower" thus enters short-term memory as a word pattern rather than picture. Research has \
shown that people remember words better if they also create a visual image of them. \
\
III. LONG-TERM MEMORY (LTM) \
\
Long-term memory is neither limited in capacity nor duration. Some theorists divide long- \
term memory into recent memory (intermediate memory), which lasts around two weeks, \
and remote memory (long-term memory), which lasts two years or more. For information \
to be useful, it must be stored so that it can be retrieved as well as updated by new \
information. \
\
Some research has supported the idea that during REM sleep, new information brought \
into long-term memory is reviewed, improved, and systematically catalogued. In addition, \
research has suggested that dream deprivation can result in impairment in memory \
formation. Research has also shown that learning from a tape cannot be done while \
sleeping, and that information is encoded and stored better when a person is alert, rather \
than drowsy. The ability to retain an image of what is seen for a long period of time is \
called eidetic (photographic) memory. \
\
\
\
                                     Section 10 - Memory: Stages of Memory \
\
A. KEY CONCEPTS \
\
Some important concepts associated with long-term memory include retrieval, priming, the \
Zeigarnik effect, redintegration, landmark events, flashbulb memories, prospective \
memory, and the effects of hypnosis. \
\
>RETRIEVAL Retrieval is the process of accessing information from long-term memory \
into short-term memory for analysis or awareness. Frequently, a cue will serve as a \
stimulus to begin the retrieval process from long-term memory. In general, tasks requiring \
recognition are easier than those requiring recall. This is because recognition involves \
matching a specific cue to items in long-term memory, while recall involves using a general \
stimulus cue to search the contents of long-term memory. A method for improving \
recognition is called priming. \
\
>PRIMING Priming involves exposure to a stimulus that makes it easier for a person to \
recognize the stimulus at a later point in time. For example, a person who is shown the \
following puzzle, "c_m_r_" and is asked to identify the word would be more likely to come \
up with "camera" if she has seen this puzzle before. \
\
>ZEIGARNIK EFFECT When a person is trying to solve a problem involving recall \
and comes to an impasse, it appears that the brain continues to work unconsciously until a \
solution is obtained. This is referred to as the Zeigarnik effect, the tendency to remember \
and work on incomplete tasks. \
\
>REDINTIGRATION   Redintigration occurs when something (e.g., a smell from \
childhood) rapidly unlocks a chain of memories. \
\
>LANDMARK EVENTS When we have difficulty with retrieval, we may also rely on \
landmark events to facilitate the process. Landmark events refer to events that are \
important to us, such as graduation, marriage, or the birth of our child, that serve as key \
markers for our memory. We can use these events to go backward or forward to locate \
details of other events that occurred around the same time. \
\
>FLASHBULB MEMORIES   Flashbulb memories involve memories of distinct, \
significant events, usually of a traumatic nature. Since flashbulb memories evoke strong \
emotional reactions at the time of encoding, they tend to involve vivid detail and are \
remembered for a long period of time. Typically, the person who experiences the event is \
most likely to remember later on what took place immediately before and during the \
traumatic event. For example, if a man witnesses a shooting spree at a local post office, he \
\
\
 \
\
                                     Section 10 - Memory: Stages of Memory \
\
is most likely to remember where he parked his car in the post office lot, being in line at \
the post office, and the shooting itself. \
\
>PROSPECTIVE MEMORY Prospective memory involves remembering that one had \
planned to do something at a particular time. Problems with prospective memory may \
involve failure to remember the purpose of a cue like a timer (e.g., not remembering why \
one had set a timer) or failure to remember what one had planned to do at a particular time \
(e.g., take a walk at four o'clock in the afternoon). \
\
>EFFECTS OF HYPNOSIS When a person is under hypnosis, he or she can usually \
provide more details about a memory. Research has indicated, however, that hypnosis tends \
to elicit more false memories than true ones. A hypnotized person is more likely to \
reconstruct memories, or use imagination to fill in gaps. Nevertheless, the person tends to \
have a great deal of confidence in the accuracy of the memory. In addition, leading \
questions by the therapist tend to alter memories. When given false information, the \
hypnotized person is likely to incorporate it into his or her memory. \
\
B. ACCURACY OF LONG-TERM MEMORY \
\
Our long-term memories can include additions, omissions and revisions of original events. \
While information in sensory memory and short-term memory is usually accurate, the \
process of transferring the information into long-term memory and retrieving it later \
frequently distorts the original information. It is thought that this distortion occurs because \
long-term memory relies heavily on semantic (meaning) features. For example, when \
subjects are asked to remember sentences, subjects are accurate if the delay is within 30 \
seconds, which requires access only to short-term memory. However, if the delay is longer \
than 30 seconds and the subjects therefore need to access long-term memory, they are more \
likely to identify a sentence with similar meaning but not the same wording. Other \
explanations for distortions of long-term memory include the fact that people frequently \
make inferences when hearing information or witnessing events (e.g., if someone says, \
"Fido was hit by a truck," we infer that Fido is a dog) and these inferences are filed into \
long-term memory. Furthermore, it seems that sources of information (where the \
information was heard) are less accurately filed than the information itself (what was \
heard). Areas in which the accuracy of long-term memory has significantly come into \
question include eyewitness reports and repressed memories. \
\
>EYEWITNESS REPORTS    Researchers have repeatedly cautioned against the \
reliability of eyewitnesses. In research, inaccurate memories commonly involve \
\
\
