\
      10.2 CLASSIFICATION OF MEMORY \
\
Many different classification schemas for memory exist. One classification schema divides \
memory into declarative or explicit memory, and procedural or implicit memory. \
\
>DECLARATIVE MEMORY Declarative or explicit memory involves conscious \
recollection of information or experience. Declarative memory is further divided into \
semantic and episodic memory. \
\
     SEMANTIC MEMORY   Semantic memory refers to our memory of meanings \
     of words, facts and how they relate to each other, for example, knowing that there \
     are twelve months in one year. Semantic memory depends upon our capacity to \
     recall abstract information or images. \
\
     EPISODIC MEMORY Episodic memory, by contrast, refers to the capacity to \
     recall autobiographical events, or when and where a specific event occurred, for \
     example, recalling your birthday party, or what you ate for breakfast today. \
     Retrieval from episodic memory involves reconstructing the original event in one's \
     mind. Overall, it is believed that determining the meaning of something requires \
     one type of memory, while knowing when or where it was learned involves a \
     different type of memory. \
\
>PROCEDURAL MEMORY Procedural, implicit, or nondeclarative memory involves \
the recollection of skills, physical operations, and procedures that are remembered \
automatically without conscious awareness. Procedural memories are not stored with \
respect to specific times or places. An example of procedural memory is remembering how \
to ride a bicycle even after not riding for ten years. \
\
\
\
                                     Section 10 - Memory: Biology of Memory \
\
        10.3 THE BIOLOGY OF MEMORY \
\
Many early studies of memory focused on attempting to identify neural locations of \
memory. Between 1915 and 1950 Karl Lashley completed hundreds of experiments \
involving either the removal of the cortex, or cutting of fiber pathways, and concluded that \
it was not possible to localize memory anywhere in the nervous system. Only three years \
later, however, William Scoville operated on H.M. in an attempt to stop uncontrollable \
seizure activity, and bilaterally removed H.M.'s temporal lobes. While H.M. was still very \
much able to remember things from the distant past, and had normal short-term memory \
capacity, H.M. developed complete anterograde amnesia (memory for events occurring \
after the surgery). This surgery highlighted the critical role of the hippocampus in the \
consolidation of long-term memory. At the same time, these findings also strengthened the \
belief that there is no single location for memory, because even though H.M. couldn't form \
new memories, his old ones remained intact. \
\
Further research has suggested that there are certain areas that are particularly involved in \
memory, including the frontal lobe (increased susceptibility to interference and problems \
with short-term memory), the temporal cortex, the hippocampus, thalamus, mamillary \
bodies, and the basal forebrain. Research has also pointed to the importance of the \
neurotransmitter acetylcholine (ACh), and problems with production of ACh in persons \
with Alzheimer's. \
\
The physiological process by which short-term memories become long-term memories has \
been described as long-term potentiation (LTP). It is believed that repeated stimulation \
of a synapse (e.g., through rehearsal) leads to chemical and structural changes in the \
dendrite of the receiving neuron, whereby this change results in increased sensitivity of the \
neuron to stimulation. Research also suggests that changes in the dendrites associated with \
LTP involve enzymes called kinases. \
\
\
