                 10.4 FORGETTING \
\
Ebbinghaus was one of the first researchers to study forgetting, as well as memory (largely \
using himself as his subject). When he plotted curves depicting memory of nonsense \
syllable lists that had been fully memorized, he found that the greatest amount of forgetting \
took place within the first hour. Fortunately, this forgetting does not apply to memory of \
material that is meaningful to us! \
\
On immediate recall of word lists, people remember those words at the beginning and at \
the end of the list better than those in the middle. This phenomenon is termed the serial \
position effect. On delayed recall, words at the beginning of the list are remembered best, \
while those in the middle and at the end of the list are remembered to an equivalent degree. \
\
I. TYPES OF AMNESIA \
\
>ANTEROGRADE AMNESIA Anterograde amnesia is impairment in acquiring new \
memories (e.g., after an accident, a brain-injured patient has difficulty remembering new \
people, what was done each day, etc.). \
\
>RETROGRADE AMNESIA Retrograde amnesia involves the loss of memories for \
events that occurred before an injury or disease (e.g., the day before a car accident). \
\
>POSTTRAUMATIC AMNESIA Posttraumatic amnesia involves the loss of memory \
for events occurring a short time after a trauma (e.g., the first few days after a course of \
ECT). \
\
>PARAMNESIA   Paramnesia is a distortion of memory and involves confabulation, or \
the type of errors made when someone is attempting to reconstruct the past. \
\
II. FACTORS INVOLVED IN FORGETTING \
\
A variety of theories have been proposed to explain forgetting. \
\
>RETRIEVAL FAILURE Retrieval failures occur when information that has been \
stored in long-term memory cannot be retrieved or recovered. An example is the "tip-of- \
\
\
\
