\
the-tongue" phenomenon in which we can't recall a word or name that we are sure we \
 know. \
\
>INTERFERENCE Interference theory proposes that we forget because other material \
interferes with the ability to learn or retrieve the target material. \
\
     RETROACTIVE INTERFERENCE    Retroactive interference (inhibition) \
     occurs when recently learned material interferes with the ability to recall material \
     learned in the past. For example, after reading the section on memory, you have \
     trouble remembering what you learned from the physiological psychology lecture \
     two months ago. \
\
     PROACTIVE INTERFERENCE   Proactive interference (inhibition) occurs \
     when previously learned material interferes with the ability to learn or recall current \
     material. For example, what you learned about physiological psychology two \
     months ago is interfering with remembering the memory section that you are \
     currently studying. \
\
>DECAY Decay theory proposes that memory deteriorates with the passage of time. \
Experimental support for this theory has been difficult to obtain because it is difficult to \
separate out the effects of decay from those of interference. \
\
>MOOD-CONGRUENT MEMORY Mood-congruent memory is the tendency for \
 people to remember material better when their emotional state matches the state they were \
in when they learned the material. This helps explains why people who are highly anxious \
when taking an exam may have difficulty retrieving material they learned while studying \
in a non-anxious or at least a less anxious state. This tendency also explains why depressed \
people typically remember best those times in their past when they have been depressed \
before, and have more difficulty remembering good times. \
\
>STATE-DEPENDENT MEMORY State-dependent memory is the tendency for people \
to remember material better when they are in a state similar to the state they were in when \
the learning took place. For example, if you studied for the exam under the influence of \
marijuana, you may perform better if you use marijuana just prior to taking the exam (but \
we don't recommend trying this out!). \
\
>MOTIVATED FORGETTING Motivated forgetting (repression), a concept developed \
by Freud, involves the unconscious active blocking of painful or disturbing memories. \
\
\
 \
\
