\
           10.5 ENHANCING MEMORY \
\
The following strategies and approaches can be used to enhance memory. \
\
>CHUNKING   Chunking involves combining separate items of information into \
meaningful units. Chunking improves short-term memory. \
\
>IMAGERY AND ASSOCIATION Imagery or association techniques can enhance \
memory. For example, when memorizing pairs of words, an image can be used to provide \
a meaningful link between the two words; for example, pen and ocean can be remembered \
by visualizing a pen floating in the ocean. \
\
>RECREATION OF CONTEXT Recreation of context involves mentally reviewing \
information associated with the material to be remembered. For example, if a subject were \
trying to remember the hair color of his first-grade teacher, he would be helped by \
remembering everything he could about the first-grade classroom, the teacher's tone of \
voice, etc. \
\
>STUDY STRATEGIES Study strategies to enhance memory include distributed \
practice (i.e., studying is spaced out) rather than massed practice (cramming). Also, \
material is less likely to be forgotten if it is rehearsed at regularly spaced intervals. \
\
>MNEMONICS Mnemonics are memory-enhancing strategies, and include the method \
of loci, the peg-word system, word associations, and the substitute word system. \
\
     THE METHOD OF LOCI The method of loci involves forming a visual image \
     of items on one's list and putting each in a specific place as one mentally walks \
     through a room. For example, a person trying to recall a list of grocery items may \
     initially picture bread on the front door, cereal in the kitchen, and milk on the dining \
     room table. \
\
     THE PEG-WORD SYSTEM The peg-word system first involves memorizing a \
     set of ten visual images that can be pegs on which to hang ideas, e.g., one is bun, \
     two is shoe, etc. Then the person associates each image with what is to be \
    remembered, for example, if the person is trying to remember a list of items to buy. \
     he may associate ketchup with hamburger buns, or socks with shoe, etc. \
\
\
\
                                    Section 10 - Memory: Enhancing Memory \
\
     WORD ASSOCIATIONS Word association involves forming words or sentences \
     with the first letter of the items being memorized, or making up stories that connect \
     the items together. Word associations can also be used to create verbal associations \
     for items to be learned, e.g., RIASEC for Holland's occupational themes. \
\
     THE SUBSTITUTE WORD TECHNIQUE In the substitute word technique, \
     the person breaks down the word to be remembered into parts, and substitutes \
     words that are more familiar and can be visualized. For example, a person who \
     wants to memorize the word "catabolize" would break it into "cat," "a ball," "eyes," \
     and then form a visual image of these words. \
