              11.1 BASIC CONCEPTS \
\
>NORM-REFERENCED VERSUS CRITERION-REFERENCED SCORES    A \
norm-referenced score provides information on how a person performed relative to others \
in the group (e.g., standard scores, z scores, T scores, and percentiles). A criterion- \
referenced score provides information on how much of the content the person has mastered \
(e.g., the number of correct items obtained on the test, or percentage correct). \
\
>OBJECTIVE VERSUS SUBJECTIVE TESTS Tests are considered either objective \
or subjective, based on the scoring procedures. An objective test does not rely on a rater's \
judgment for scoring, and it has a scoring key used to score the items. Examples of \
objectively scored tests include the MMPI-2 and the EPPP. Subjectively scored tests \
involve some element of the rater's judgment, such as the TAT and the Rorschach. \
\
>NORMATIVE VERSUS IPSATIVE SCORES A normative score tells us how \
someone performed relative to others (e.g., t-score, percentile rank). An ipsative score \
provides information on the relative strengths and weaknesses of the person only, and does \
not compare the person to others. Vocational preference tests (e.g., the Strong Campbell) \
most commonly yield ipsative scores. \
\
>EMPIRICAL-CRITERION KEYING Empirical-criterion keying is a process for \
selecting items to be used in a test. The items are keyed to an external criterion, and are \
intended to differentiate between groups of people who have a particular trait and those \
who do not. For example, the developers of the MMPI first generated a pool of items for \
possible use on Scale 8 (the Schizophrenia Scale). Only those items that were found to \
differentiate between normal individuals and individuals with Schizophrenia were \
ultimately included in the test. \
\
\
