  11.2 INTELLIGENCE AND INTELLIGENCE \
                        TESTING \
\
I. THEORIES OF INTELLIGENCE \
\
Most researchers agree that intelligence is a set of cognitive characteristics and abilities \
that cannot be directly observed. Over the years, psychologists have basically been of two \
camps: those who argue that intelligence is a single general ability, and those who believe \
there are several distinct kinds of intelligence. \
\
>SPEARMAN   Spearman (1927) proposed that intelligence is a single factor, which he \
termed "g factor." This came out of Spearman's observation that scores on various tests \
of mental abilities tend to correlate with each other. The most widely used tests of \
intelligence (e.g .. the Wechsler tests and the Stanford-Binet) measure the "g factor." \
\
>THURSTONE Thurstone (1938) argued that there are seven distinct primary mental \
abilities: verbal comprehension, word fluency, numerical fluency, spatial visualization, \
associative memory, perceptual speed, and reasoning. \
\
>CATTELL After reanalyzing Thurstone's data, Cattell proposed that a "g factor" does \
exist, with two subtypes, fluid intelligence and crystallized intelligence. \
\
     FLUID INTELLIGENCE Fluid intelligence is the capacity to acquire new \
     knowledge and solve new problems, and it is partially determined by biological and \
     genetic factors. \
\
     CRYSTALLIZED   INTELLIGENCE   Crystallized intelligence refers to \
     knowledge and learning gained over one's lifetime through an interaction between \
     fluid intelligence and environment (culture, education, etc.). \
\
>CATTELL-HORN-CARROLL The result of extensive factor analyses, this theory is \
considered by many to be the most empirically validated theory of human intelligence. \
According to this theory, intelligence can be understood in three levels: general intelligence \
or "g" (stratum III); about ten broad cognitive abilities, such as fluid reasoning, short-term \
memory, visual processing, reading and writing (stratum II); and finally, about 70 narrow \
cognitive abilities (stratum I). This theory, based on the original work of Cattell, has gone \
