through much development and there is some variance in the way it can be presented. For \
example, Horn and Carroll disagree over the validity of the general intelligence factor (g), \
and the number of broad cognitive abilities (stratum II) varies in different versions of the \
model. \
\
>GARDNER'S MULTIPLE INTELLIGENCES Gardner (1983, 1996) has identified \
eight distinct intelligences: linguistic, logical-mathematical, spatial, musical, bodily- \
kinesthetic, interpersonal, intrapersonal, and naturalistic. Gardner argues that people differ \
in their profile of intelligence, by which he means they have relative strengths and \
weaknesses among the eight areas. \
\
>STERNBERG'S TRIARCHIC THEORY    Sternberg's (1985) theory focuses on \
process rather than product, specifically the thinking processes used to arrive at answers to \
problems. Sternberg has proposed three aspects of intelligence: the internal components \
(e.g., those we use to acquire, store, perceive, and remember), the capacity to adapt to \
environmental changes, and the ability to apply past experience to current novel problems. \
\
II. THE WECHSLER ADULT INTELLIGENCE SCALE \
(WAIS-IV) \
\
The WAIS-IV (2008) is appropriate for persons from 16-0 to 90-11 years of age. The \
WAIS-IV consists of ten core subtests and five supplemental subtests. The WAIS-IV \
allows for the calculation of Full Scale IQ (FSIQ) score, four primary index scores, and an \
optional General Ability Index (GAI) score. IQ score and indexes have a mean of 100, and \
a standard deviation of 15. Subtests have a mean of 10 and a standard deviation of 3. \
\
>VERBAL COMPREHENSION INDEX (VCI)    The verbal comprehension index \
includes the subtests of similarities, vocabulary, and information. Comprehension is a \
supplemental subtest. \
\
>PERCEPTUAL REASONING INDEX (PRI) The perceptual reasoning index includes \
the subtests of block design, matrix reasoning, and visual puzzles. Picture completion and \
figure weights are supplemental subtests. \
\
>WORKING MEMORY INDEX (WMI) The working memory index consists of digit \
span and arithmetic. Letter-number sequencing is a supplemental subtest. \
\
\
 \
\
                            Section 11 - Assessment: Intelligence and Intelligence Testing \
\
>PROCESSING SPEED INDEX (PSI) The processing speed index consists of the \
subtests of symbol search and coding. Cancellation is a supplemental subtest. \
\
>GENERAL ABILITY INDEX (GAI) The optional general ability index consists of a \
composite of scores on the Verbal Comprehension and Perceptual Reasoning subtests. It is \
used when examiners want to calculate a summary score that minimizes the influence of \
Working Memory and Processing Speed. \
\
Although the WAIS-IV is clearly based on the Wechsler four-factor model, many of the \
subtests can be interpreted along the lines of the Cattell-Horn-Carroll three-strata model of \
intelligence (CHC model). The WAIS-IV subtests can be seen as representing various \
broad cognitive abilities of the CHC model (e.g., fluid reasoning, quantitative knowledge, \
crystallized knowledge, short term memory, visual perception). \
\
III. THE WECHSLER INTELLIGENCE SCALE FOR \
CHILDREN (WISC-V) \
\
The WISC-V (2014) measures intellectual ability and cognitive functioning in children \
from 6-0 to 16-11 years. The test consists of ten primary subtests and six secondary or \
optional subtests. The normative sample was stratified based on U.S. census data for age, \
sex, parent education level, geographic region, and race/ethnicity. A Spanish version is also \
available. \
\
In comparison to the WISC-IV, which it replaces, the WISC-V is quicker to administer, \
has new optional subtests, and has a greater variety of supplemental index scores. The \
perceptual reasoning index (PRI), found in the fourth edition of both the WAIS and the \
WISC, has been split into two separate indexes: the visual spatial index (VSI) and the fluid \
reasoning index (FRI). In addition to traditional paper-and-pencil administration and \
scoring, the WISC-V can be administered and scored digitally on tablets (the Q-interactive \
version). \
\
The WISC-V yields a Full Scale IQ (FSIQ) score along with five primary index scores. \
FSIQ and the indexes have a mean of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. Subtests have a \
mean of 10 and a standard deviation of 3. \
\
>VERBAL COMPREHENSION INDEX (VCI) The verbal comprehension index \
measures crystallized intelligence, including verbal concept formation, reasoning, and \
expression. The primary subtests are similarities and vocabulary. Secondary subtests \
include information and comprehension. \
\
\
\
                            Section 11 - Assessment: Intelligence and Intelligence Testing \
\
> VISUAL-SPATIAL INDEX (VSI) The visual-spatial index consists of the primary \
subtests of block design and visual puzzles. \
\
> FLUID REASONING INDEX (FRI) The fluid reasoning index measures induetive and \
quantitative reasoning. The primary subtests are matrix reasoning and figure weights. \
Secondary subtests include picture concepts and arithmetic. \
\
>WORKING MEMORY INDEX (WMI) The working memory index consists of the \
primary subtests of digit span and picture span. Letter-number sequencing is a secondary \
subtest. \
\
>PROCESSING SPEED INDEX (PSI) The processing speed index consists of the \
primary subtests of coding and symbol search. Cancellation is a secondary subtest. \
\
There are also several supplemental index scores that can be calculated by using different \
combinations of the primary subtests and/or the secondary subtests. Ancillary index scores \
include quantitative reasoning index, auditory working memory index, nonverbal index, \
general ability index, and cognitive proficiency index. In 2015, two more index scores were \
added: the verbal expanded crystallized index and the expanded fluid index. \
\
To aid in the assessment of specific learning disabilities, three complementary index scores \
can be calculated (naming speed index, symbol translation index, and storage and retrieval \
index). \
\
The WISC-V can be interpreted along the lines of the Cattell-Horn-Carroll model of \
intelligence, as well as other current structural models. Despite variation among different \
models, there is a general consensus that key underlying factors include verbal \
comprehension, visual spatial, fluid reasoning, working memory, and processing speed \
abilities. Each of these factors is represented by one of the five primary indexes of the \
WISC-V. \
\
Children with chronic middle ear infections (i.e., chronic otitis media) often demonstrate \
long-term deficits in language capacities. For this reason, when they are tested with the \
WISC-V, their scores on the verbal comprehension index will often be depressed. \
\
