IV. INTELLIGENCE TEST INTERPRETATION \
\
VCI is a measure of verbal comprehension abilities, which typically are considered to be a \
form of crystallized intelligence. PRI (on the WAIS-IV) and FRI (on the WISC-V) measure \
perceptual reasoning/fluid abilities. Crystallized abilities generally do not decrease with \
aging; they remain intact and may even improve. Fluid abilities tend to peak in adolescence \
and decline thereafter, in a gradual but steady manner. \
\
There are several sociocultural and psychological factors that can affect VCI and PRI/FRI. \
People who are more educated and of higher SES may obtain higher VCI scores than \
PRI/FRI scores. Those of lower SES and less education may show the reverse pattern. \
\
The VCI subtests also tend to be more culturally loaded than the PRI/FRI subtests. The \
VCI subtests may therefore not be appropriate for persons of a different cultural \
background or those who have limited facility with English because they might \
underestimate the person's intelligence. The PRI/FRI subtests, on the other hand, would \
not be appropriate for persons who have impaired motor functioning. \
\
In terms of psychological functioning, the PRI/FRI subtests are more susceptible to effects \
of anxiety and depression. Additionally, persons with a history of substance dependence or \
schizophrenia have a tendency for PRI/FRI to be lower than VCI. \
\
Vocabulary and information are considered to be the two best "hold tests," which means \
that if a person sustains brain damage or injury, performance on these subtests tends to \
hold steady and not decline. In other words, these subtests are good indicators of pre- \
morbid intellectual functioning. \
\
Aging affects some subtests more than others. Overall, scores on the WAIS on both the \
processing speed index (PSI) and the perceptual reasoning index (PRI) decline as people \
age but scores on the processing speed index (PSI) decline more significantly. Scores on \
the verbal comprehension index (VCI) do not tend to decline. Scores on the working \
memory index (WMI) decline slightly overall. \
\
Scatter analysis or pattern analysis looks at discrepancies between subtests. Such analysis \
has not been found to be valid for making diagnoses, and, in particular, can result in too \
many false positives. Measurement error alone may account for differences noted between \
subtests. \
\
