V. INTELLIGENCE TEST SELECTION \
\
>DIAGNOSING INTELLECTUAL DISABILITY AND GIFTEDNESS Intelligence \
is normally distributed in the population. Using the areas under the normal curve, it can be \
said that about 99% of the population have IQs between 55 and 145 (between +3 and -3 \
SDs); about 95% of the population have IQs between 70 and 130 (between +2 and -2 SDs); \
about 68% or two thirds of the population have IQs between 85 and 115 (between +1 and \
-1 SDs); and 50% of the population have IQs between 90 and 110. \
\
To be diagnosed with intellectual disability, a person's IQ is typically 70 or below, or two \
or more standard deviations below the mean. In addition, the person must show evidence \
of deficits in adaptive functioning in one or more areas (e.g., conceptual/academic domain, \
social domain, and practical domain) across multiple environments (e.g., school, home, \
work). Adaptive functioning frequently assessed by means of the Vineland Test of \
Adaptive Functioning. \
\
The term floor refers to the lowest possible score that a test can yield, and ceiling refers to \
the highest possible score. Intellectual disability is best assessed by an intelligence test with \
a fairly low floor. Similarly, giftedness is best assessed by a test with a fairly high ceiling. \
\
The WISC-IV has a high floor (IQ of 40) and a low ceiling (IQ of 160), which limits its \
usefulness for assessing someone with an IQ lower than 40 or higher than 160. The \
Stanford-Binet 5, in contrast, has a much lower floor (e.g., IQ score in the teens) and a \
much higher ceiling (IQ of 180), thus making it the test of choice for assessing both \
giftedness and intellectual disability. \
\
>NON-VERBAL TESTS OF INTELLIGENCE   Raven's Progressive Matrices is \
generally thought to be one of the best non-verbal tests of intelligence. In fact, Spearman \
himself considered it to be the best non-verbal measure of the "g factor." The test consists \
of a series of abstract patterns with one piece missing. The test-taker must select the missing \
piece using a multiple choice format. The test is appropriate for children as well as adults. \
\
>INFANT TESTS OF INTELLIGENCE   Infant tests of intelligence, such as the \
Bayley, tend to be poor predictors of intelligence in later years because these tests assess \
abilities (e.g., sensorimotor skills) different from those assessed by child or adult \
intelligence tests (e.g., verbal comprehension, perceptual organization). The one exception \
is that extremely low performance on an infant intelligence test tends to correlate with, or \
predict, lower intelligence in subsequent years. \
\
