    11.3 OBJECTIVE PERSONALITY TESTS \
\
I. MMPI-2/MMPI-2-RF \
\
The MMPI-2 is an objective self-report measure of personality functioning. It contains 567 \
true-false items. The MMPI-2 is scored with T scores, which have a mean of 50 and a \
standard deviation of 10. Scores at or above a T score of 65 (1.5 standard deviations above \
the mean) are considered significant. \
\
Empirical-criterion keying was used in developing the original MMPI, but it was not used \
with the MMPI-2. \
\
The MMPI-2 includes several validity scales. The most frequently cited validity scales are \
L. F, and K, which not only can help determine whether the profile is valid, but also can \
provide information on test-taking approach. \
\
       L SCALE L is the lie scale. A high score on this scale indicates that the person \
       is making a naive attempt to present him or herself in an overly favorable light. \
       The L scale is typically in the normal range. \
\
       F SCALE F is the infrequency ("fake bad") scale, and includes items that \
       were endorsed by less than 10% of people in the standardization sample. High \
       scores on the F scale suggest psychotic processes, a tremendous degree of \
       distress, or an attempt to appear in a negative light that could reflect a cry for \
       help. Extremely high scores (T of 100 or above) are suggestive of malingering \
       and would invalidate the profile. \
\
       K SCALE The K scale is the guardedness scale. High scores suggest that the \
       person is making a more sophisticated attempt to present him or herself in a \
       positive light ("fake good"). A low score on K is suggestive of someone who is \
       excessively open, has poor ego strength, and tends to openly reveal his or her \
       negative aspects. \
\
K is used to correct for guardedness based on a formula. The K correction uses the score \
on K to adjust some of the clinical scales for guardedness; the higher the person's score on \
K, the more points are added to several of the clinical scales. \
\
\
\
