\
        SCALE 8 -- SCHIZOPHRENIA (SC) High scores indicate feelings of social \
       and/or emotional alienation and misunderstanding, confusion and \
       disorganization, as well as lability and impulsivity. Extremely high scores are \
       consistent with poor contact with reality, unusual thinking, delusions, and \
       hallucinations. \
\
        SCALE 9 - HYPOMANIA (MA) High scores suggest overactivity, poor \
       impulse control, excessive speech, flight of ideas, agitation, grandiosity, \
       restlessness, and irritability. \
\
        SCALE 0 -- SOCIAL INTROVERSION (SI) High scorers are typically shy, \
       unassertive, lack confidence, and have limited social skills and interactions. \
\
The MMPI-2 also contains a number of supplementary scales including scales to measure \
actual or potential substance abuse (MAC-R, APS, AAS), PTSD (PK - Keane Post \
Traumatic Stress Disorder and PS - PTSD Schlenger), marital distress (MDS), \
overcontrolled hostility (O-H), anxiety (A), repression (R), ego strength (Es), dominance \
(Do), and social responsibility (Re). \
\
The MMPI-2-RF (Restructured Form) (2008) consists of 338 items linked to current \
models of psychopathology and personality. With the restructured clinical scales at its core \
the MMPI-2-RF consists of 8 Validity Scales, 12 Higher-Order (H-O) and Restructured \
Clinical (RC) Scales, 14 Somatic/Cognitive and Internalizing Scales, 11 Externalizing, \
Interpersonal, and Interest Scales, and 5 Personality Psychopathology Five (PSY-5) Scales. \
Test developers note that the MMPI-2-RF provides an alternative to the MMPI-2, not a \
replacement. \
\
II. MCMI-IV \
\
The Millon Clinical Multiaxial Inventory (MCMI-IV, 2015) is an objective measure of \
personality consisting of 195 true-false items. Aligned with the DSM-5, the MCMI-IV \
measures both more enduring personality characteristics/disorders, as well as more acute \
clinical symptoms/disorders. \
\
Because the test was normed on a clinical population, it should generally not be used with \
a normal population. When administered to a non-clinical population, the MCMI-IV tends \
to exaggerate pathology. \
\
