   11.4 PROJECTIVE PERSONALITY TESTS \
\
The premise underlying projective testing is the projective hypothesis. When persons are \
presented with unstructured stimuli to interpret or elaborate upon, it is believed that they \
project material from their unconscious onto the stimuli. Thus their interpretations and \
elaborations will reveal unconscious material from their psyche, such as repressed wishes, \
conflicts, and preoccupations. \
\
I. RORSCHACH \
\
The Rorschach is a projective personality test consisting of ten symmetrical inkblots. The \
overall goal of assessment with the Rorschach is to assess the client's personality structure: \
the emotional, behavioral, interpersonal, perceptual, and cognitive aspects of the person's \
functioning. Historically, Exner's Rorschach Comprehensive System (RCS) has been the \
most widely used system. In this scoring system, every Rorschach response is scored on a \
variety of dimensions. \
\
     CONTENT Content includes the specific category a response belongs to, e.g .. \
     Clothing, Science, Whole Human. \
\
     LOCATION Location refers to the area of the blot that the person used to develop \
     the response, e.g., whole blot (W), detail (D), small detail (Dd), or white space (S). \
\
     FORM QUALITY Form quality is determined by how accurately the response \
     relates to the form of the inkblot. \
\
     DEVELOPMENTAL QUALITY    Developmental quality is determined by \
     evaluating each response in terms of its degree of integration. \
\
In 2011, the R-PAS (Rorschach Performance Assessment System) was published. The R- \
PAS is a significant reformulation of the Rorschach. It is an internationally oriented \
approach, designed to decrease variability among examiners, align the test with an \
evidence base, and simplify procedures and presentation of data. \
\
