                  11.5 OTHER TESTS \
\
 I. NEUROPSYCHOLOGICAL TESTS AND BATTERIES \
\
 Neuropsychological tests measure perceptual, motor, verbal, memory, and cognitive \
 functioning. Neuropsychological testing measures the functional impact of brain damage \
 (e.g., stroke, head trauma) or disease processes (e.g .. Alzheimer's disease), as well as the \
 strengths and weaknesses of a patient. \
\
 Some tests are specifically designed to measure one area of functioning. For example, the \
 Wechsler Memory Scale (WMS-IV) measures memory (verbal and nonverbal); the \
 Wisconsin Card Sorting Test and the Stroop Test measure cognitive functioning \
 (problem solving and cognitive flexibility); and the Bender Visual-Motor Gestalt Test \
 measures perceptual/motor abilities. \
\
Neuropsychological test batteries (e.g., the Halstead Reitan and Luria Nebraska) are \
 designed to comprehensively sample the patient's neuropsychological functioning. \
\
 The Folstein Mini-Mental State Exam (MMSE) is a brief, easy to administer test used to \
 screen for cognitive impairment as well as to follow the course of cognitive changes over \
 time. \
\
 II. ACHIEVEMENT TESTS \
\
 Achievement tests, such as the Wide Range Achievement Test (WRAT) or Wechsler \
 Individual Achievement Test (WIAT), are used to assess academic achievement. A specific \
 learning disorder is diagnosed when the affected academic skills (e.g., reading, written \
 expression, mathematics) are substantially below those expected for the person's age, and \
 the learning problem interferes with academic/occupational performance or activities of \
 daily living. The criteria for substantially below are achievement test scores that are at least \
 1.5 standard deviations (SD) below the population mean for age (below the 7th percentile), \
 not better accounted for by intellectual disabilities. \
\
 \
\
                                        Section 11 - Assessment: Other Tests \
\
 III. THE VINELAND \
\
 The Vineland is a test of adaptive functioning often used as part of an assessment of \
 intellectual disability. A diagnosis of intellectual disability requires deficits in general \
 mental abilities (typically an IQ score of 70 or below) as well as deficits in adaptive \
 functioning in one or more areas (e.g., conceptual/academic domain, social domain, and \
 practical domain) across multiple environments (e.g., school, home, work). \
